INSERT INTO `areas` VALUES (1,'Makara Peak',1,'2008-12-23 09:19:36','Makara Peak has become [[region:1]]\'s premier mountain biking destination. A large network of tracks has been hand-made by the local community. The tracks cater for a wide range of abilities and there is plenty of honest hill to satisfy the hardiest of mountain goat types.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Makara Peak tracks can be very busy during weekends and public holidays. If you prefer to avoid the crowds then go early, late, or during the week. The tracks are also popular with runners but mostly during times when the number of bikers are lowest.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis is not a good place to bring your dog. There is a very active possum poisoning programme and there have been cases of dogs dying after eating dead possums.\r\n\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nA new intermediate track down from the summit is being developed â€“ currently called the [[track:613]]. The track starts next to the top of [[track:14]] and [[track:49]] and will eventually join [[track:50]] near the picnic tables. See the [[link:http://makarapeak.org/northface Northface Blog]] for a running commentary of build progress.\r\n\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee [[link:http://www.makarapeak.org Makara Peak Mountain Bike Park]] for further information, including: discussion forum, events, track maintenance schedules, and track building blogs.\r\n\r\n[[h1:Webcam]]\r\nOriginal source of webcam is [[link:http://www.makarapeak.org/webcam here]]. It says big thanks to Wendy and Pete for hosting the camera, ditto!\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://203.97.213.41/video.jpg:Makara Peak Webcam might be broken...:583:437]]','-41.292318','174.711714',14,'2010-01-13 09:03:24'),(2,'Hawkins Hill',1,'2008-12-23 09:15:07','Classic Wellington tiger country, big hills, great views, wind exposure, with generally dry and rocky tracks. Even though this area is on the fringe of the city you can feel a very long way from civilisation, and help should you require it.\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nBlazing of [[track:294]] is well advanced. Formal approval for the track will be sought once the pilot track is complete â€“ then track building will begin in earnest.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMeanwhile, the finishing touches are being put on [[track:67]].\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nThe [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz Feeling Great]] recreation guide has further information on the [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/walkways-and-tracks/190-explore-wellington-te-kopahou-reserve/52-tracks-and-walks Te Kopahou Reserve]] tracks, including [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/196-te-kopahou-reserve-red-rocks Red Rocks]] and [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/203-hawkins-hill-to-the-bunkers Hawkins Hill to the bunkers]] (otherwise known as [[track:61]]).','-41.335834','174.728451',13,'2009-09-05 08:23:44'),(3,'Polhill',1,'2008-12-23 10:08:16','Just out the back of Te Aro Polhill, like Mt Vic, is just minutes from the CBD.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the trails are very short (less than 700m) with a few exceptions that are between 1-2 km (like [[track:27]], the [[track:28]] and [[track:41]]). Polhill is not a fully continuous network of tracks but, if you plan ahead, your ride shouldn\'t be too disjointed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the Polhill trail network would suit riders with some experience (intermediate). There are easier links like [[track:47]], [[track:27]], [[track:36]], [[track:64]] or the Karori Sanctuary [[track:25]] (Wrights Hill).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are access issues.  WCC does not actually permit riding on [[area:3]] because you will have to cross privately owned land at some point.  Several of the land owners aren\'t happy chaps. Also, if you do choose to ride here quite a few single tracks can become overgrown and tree\'s that are felled may not be taken away.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe overall proximity of Polhill (10-15 mins) makes it a good candidate for a moonlit weeknight ride or a better place to spend your lunch hour than the office cafe.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are lots of access points. You could start from:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:the steps that lead up to the [[track:25]] in Waiapu Rd ([[link:http://www.sanctuary.org.nz/ Karori Wildlife Sanctuary]])]]\r\n[[bullet:Brosnahan Terrace in Mitchelltown]]\r\n[[bullet:the back of George Denton Park in Highbury Rd]]\r\n[[bullet:Ashton Fichett Drive in Brooklyn]]\r\n[[bullet:at the top of Mt Pleasant Rd.]]\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nWork is underway on two new multi-use tracks in this area. According to [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/services/resbelt/recreation/recreation.html Wellington City Council]] (as at 25 August 2009):\r\n[[para]]\r\n\"[[italic:With Council support, volunteers are building two new tracks. The tracks will link Ashton Fitchett Drive in Brooklyn to:]]\r\n[[bullet:Polhill Gully and Aro Street]]\r\n[[bullet:George Denton Park]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[italic:The new Polhill Gully track is designed for bike use, while walkers can use the current track (although walkers will be able to use the new bike track if they want to). The new track to George Denton Park will be for mountain bikers and walkers.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[italic:Work is expected to start on the Polhill Gully track at the end of August 2009. Work on the tracks is expected to take more than a year and until this work is finished the area is closed to bikers.]]\"\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Polhill Gully track is called [[track:839]], while the track from just above George Denton Park is called [[track:851]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEach week there is a [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/wednesday-work-parties-the-new-polhill-tracks-aro-valley-t100107.html Wednesday lunchtime work party]], from 12noon to 2pm. Tools and chocolate supplied. Make a post in the discussion, or contact [[link:http://www.kennett.co.nz/index.php/AboutUs/JonathanKennett Jonathan Kennett]] for further information.','-41.303861','174.754200',14,'2010-01-23 15:37:53'),(4,'Wrights Hill',1,'2008-12-23 09:30:34','Wrights Hill is the site of a fortress, built during World War II to protect Wellington city from naval attack.  The fortress, which is mostly underground, has open days several times a year when the public can explore the numerous tunnels, gun emplacements, magazines, etc.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs part of Wellington\'s outer green belt, Wrights Hill provides connections between the [[area:1]] mountain bike park and the [[area:3]] area.  The Wrights Hill tracks often form part of longer excursions, particularly via the [[track:29]], [[track:30]], and [[track:25]] tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nUnder the WCC [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/plans/policies/trackrec/pdfs/trackrec.pdf Track Recreation Activities Policy]], dated November 2008, all of the tracks on [[area:4]] are open to mountain bikes except for [[track:187]] and [[track:188]]. As at July 2009 the old \"no bikes\" signage is still in place, through there are plans to update the signage with new map boards and directional bollards.\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nMore information about the history and restoration of the fortress, plus a schedule of open day dates, can be found at the [[link:http://www.whfrs.org.nz Wrights Hill Fortress Restoration Society]] website.','-41.294769','174.739695',14,'2009-07-30 09:00:44'),(5,'Mt Victoria',1,'2009-05-17 10:17:58','Mt Victoria is a great place to ride close to the city. You can be in the midst of the action within 5 minutes of the CBD.  Mt Vic offers all year round riding options that are great for a lunchtime ride or for a quick night ride after work.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMt Vic is flush with wide walking paths (easy) and rooty single track (easy to intermediate).  To connect to both sides you\'re likely to have to ride up, or down, Alexandra Rd at some stage.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe paths are all dual use so they are likely to be used by walkers, runners and dog owners. Please ride a little conservatively if you are out there at peak times.\r\n[[h1:Overview of tracks]]\r\n[[h2:Cross-Country Riding]]\r\nMost of the good cross country rides run between the lookout at Oriental Bay and the Newtown end of the reserve (parallel to the main walkways).  Once you\'ve explored a bit, you\'ll easily put together a fun 6-8 km loop with lots of alternatives.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[h2:Down Hill]]\r\nThere are some decent downhill options running from the Hataitai Park side towards town. Many of these runs cut across the main walkways so down-hillers please take care at the points where runs cross main walkways.  Conflict between riders and walkers could cause the council to rethink their access policy.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[h2:Where to start]]\r\nThe single track networks aren\'t sign posted so they aren\'t very legible (they lack identity). This makes it a bit hard to describe rides to unfamiliar riders.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following is an easy Figure 8 circuit that gives a taste of the variety of tracks on Mount Victoria:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:Enter via Marjoribanks St.]]\r\n[[bullet:From the park at the top of Marjoribanks St take the Southern Walkway to the top.]]\r\n[[bullet:At the top cross the road and descend down the sealed path opposite the green fence.]]\r\n[[bullet:Once past the gate flow the main trail to the right until you come to a torn up clay section. There is another gate at the bottom.]]\r\n[[bullet:Once out of the gate turn right and follow the trail round behind the velodrome.]]\r\n[[bullet:Follow the main path that turns off to the right.]]\r\n[[bullet:At the end of this path turn right for a short climb back up to the bottom of Alexandra Rd.]]\r\n[[bullet:At the top of the short climb turn left and re-enter the path.]]\r\n[[bullet:You\'ll come out at an open field the path turns right up the hill, but head straight. You should see a single track cut across the small grass field.  Follow it into the tree line.]]\r\n[[bullet:There are a few roots here. Zip along until you get to a 90 right hand turn. At this point you should be able to see Campbell St.  If you keep going straight you\'d leave the area.]]\r\n[[bullet:The sharp right hand turn takes you back to a short piece of track.]]\r\n[[bullet:At the wooden track marker hang a hard right and head back up the short but steep climb back to Alexander Rd.]]\r\n[[bullet:Head up Alexandra Rd to the old hospital â€“ there are two paths take the one to the left. This will take you to the soccer field.]]\r\n[[bullet:Head around the gate to the field and back to Alexandra Rd.]] \r\n[[bullet:Climb up Alexandra Rd to the hub (of the figure 8). On your right is the sealed path leading back to the velodrome.]]\r\n[[bullet:Cross inside the green fence and turn right. There are two options. The higher trail (on the right) leads to a 4WD down hill.]]\r\n[[bullet:Take the lower trail on the left.]]\r\n[[bullet:As you enter the tree cover turn right down hill.  Follow the main trail until you come to a fork. The track to the left is a little more technical.]]\r\n[[bullet:Cross the main trail and take the right hander that heads slightly up hill.]]\r\n[[bullet:You should end up going through a tree tunnel where the bush completely encloses you.]]\r\n[[bullet:From here basically follow your nose and you\'ll end up back at Marjoribanks Park.]]\r\nNow that you have that basic run, start exploring by taking any of the many single tracks you passed along the way.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:A sampling of what Mt Victoria has to offer]][[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:f0CTAbEkk34]]\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nIn December 2008 the Wellington City Council [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/news/display-item.php?id=3403 announced]] an upgrade to the Mount Victoria track network. Improvements include:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:Smoother track surface, better stormwater run-off.]]\r\n[[bullet:Removal of unnecessary steps and upgrade of remaining steps.]]\r\n[[bullet:New track around the city side of Mt Alfred.]]\r\n[[bullet:Construction of the [[track:340]].]]\r\n[[bullet:Two circular mountain bike routes â€“ [[track:354]] and [[track:355]] â€“ highlighted with track markers and on map boards.]]\r\n\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nA simple map can be found at the [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz/uploads/images/199_vn_mtb_map_original.gif Feeling Great]] website.','-41.300381','174.791458',14,'2009-09-08 21:45:28'),(6,'Karori Park',1,'2009-05-25 16:40:02','This is a recreational area in a small block of forest above Karori Park. The area is situated between [[area:1]] and [[area:7]], so often forms part of a circuit through those areas â€“ particularly via the [[track:35]] and [[track:88]] tracks, plus entry/exit via [[track:315]].\r\n[[h1:Children\'s mountain bike circuit]]\r\nDuring 2008 and 2009 the [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/karori-park-beginners-trail-project-t86653.html Karori Park Beginners\' Trail Project]] worked to add and upgrade tracks in this area.  This work included clearing and realigning the [[track:88]] track (which had been blocked by fallen trees) and construction of [[track:316]] and [[track:320]] tracks for beginners.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Signage for the children\'s mountain bike circuit]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/KaroriPark-1.jpg:Karori Park sign:583:454]]\r\nThe sign says:\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe adjacent gently sloping track leads to a 15-minute circuit developed by Wellington City Council and volunteers to help children improve their mountain bike skills. Children should be accompanied by an adult and wear a helmet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe circuit starts and finishes at a picnic area and has several distinct sections of track to explore.\r\n[[bullet:UPHILL: From the picnic area, a 200-metre-long uphill track leads to a clearing.]]\r\n[[bullet:THE SNAKE: From the clearing, The Snake track weaves down through the forest to the picnic area.]]\r\n[[bullet:PUMP TRACK: In the clearing there is a pump track, which can be ridden on bikes with 20-inch (51cm) wheels or larger. BMX bikes and mountain bikes are ideal.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Pump Track is based on one in San Francisco, known as The Fix. It can be ridden in both directions, but is easier anti-clockwise. The challenge is to get around it without pedalling. By \'pumping\' the rollers and pushing off the berms (pushing and lifting over the bumps and pushing off the banked corners), it\'s possible to ride all day long without pedalling at all. It helps to lower your seat, and if you have suspension, it is best to lock it out.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce you\'ve mastered this circuit, it\'s time to tackle longer tracks at nearby Makara Peak Mountain Bike Park.','-41.283241','174.722893',16,'2009-09-15 21:52:49'),(7,'Western Hills',1,'2008-12-16 19:11:27','A range of mostly grassy hills from [[area:1]] in the south to Mt Kaukau in the north. Starting from [[area:1]] heading north the range takes in [[area:6]], [[area:4]], British Peak, Crow\'s Nest and finally Mt Kaukau.[[para]]Except for around [[area:6]] the ridge is open and exposed and [[region:1]]\'s predominant nor-west winds can certainly make themselves known. However all this exposure provides some great views over the South Island, [[region:1]] city and harbour, and on really clear days you can even see Mt Taranaki some 300kms to the North.\r\n[[br]][[br]]\r\nThere used to be various access issues to the farmland parts of this ridge. However in 2005 Meridian Energy (a major land owner in the area) opened it up to appeal to the public for it\'s then proposed wind farm in the Quartz Hill, Outlook Hill and Terawhiti area.','-41.264195','174.737377',14,'2008-12-16 19:11:27'),(8,'Wainuiomata trail project',1,'2008-12-23 09:27:55','The Wainuiomata Trail Project (WTP) is a mountain bike park under active development.  The project\'s objective is to create a range of mountain bike and walking tracks on the hills between Mount Towai and Wainuiomata. Hutt City Council intends to name this reserve area Waiu Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSeveral tracks have been completed, ranging in difficulty from a gentle two-way track ([[track:74]]), through to dedicated downhill tracks with challenging drops and other obstacles ([[track:77]] and [[track:78]]).  Further tracks are planned, including short, flat tracks suitable for family outings.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAccess to the tracks is via either the saddle of Wainuiomata Hill or from the end of Waui Street.  The land at the end of Waui Street is currently derelict.  Motorcross riders frequently make use of the area, including racing on a dirt track near the start of [[track:74]].  There are plans for re-development of this area, including construction of a car park and visitor information boards for users of the tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe WTP has secured funding from the Hutt City Council to assist with development of the project.  Even so, most of the tracks have been built by volunteers, led and coordinated by a local school teacher.\r\n\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nWork is currently underway on:\r\n[[bullet:A down hill track off [[track:75]], called [[track:739]].]]\r\n[[bullet:An extension to the bottom end of [[track:77]], called [[track:738]].]]\r\n[[bullet:A return leg for [[track:80]], called [[track:859]] though it may be merged with [[track:80]].]]\r\n[[bullet:A connection between the bottom of [[track:78]] and the [[track:176]], called the [[track:887]]. See [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/wtp-link-track-working-bees-t103390.html#p2221208 Wtp Link Track Working Bees]] for further information.]]\r\n[[bullet:A new track within the wetland area enclosed by [[track:176]], called [[track:911]].  See [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/post2262097.html?hilit=westside#p2262097 Wtp: New Trail Digs Westside]] for build details.]]\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the [[link:http://www.wtp.org.nz Wainuiomata Trail Project website]], [[link:http://blog.wtp.org.nz/ blog]], and [[link:http://www.facebook.com/pages/Wainuiomata/Wainuiomata-Trail-Project/211059460782 Facebook page]] for more information.\r\n[[para]]\r\nRefer to [[area:9]] for other tracks in this vicinity.','-41.245708','174.926677',15,'2010-05-08 14:06:25'),(9,'Wainuiomata',1,'2008-12-29 11:33:02','The Wainuiomata valley is surrounded by bush clad hills and valleys.  There are many tracks, fire breaks, and 4x4 roads in the area, providing a wide range of recreational possibilities.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that significant areas are off limits to mountain bikes, including the Orongorongo Valley and all of the tracks running down from Mount Lowry into [[area:134]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlso see [[area:8]] for tracks that are part of the mountain bike park under development.\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the Greater Wellington Regional Council for further information about the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/east-harbour-regional-park-3/ East Harbour Regional Park\'s Northern Forest block]] and the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/wainuiomata-recreation-area/ Wainuiomata Waterworks Recreation Area]].','-41.243869','174.957447',12,'2010-04-11 10:56:27'),(10,'Parangarahu Lakes',1,'2008-12-23 09:26:22','Parangarahu Lakes, which is part of the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/east-harbour-regional-park-3/ East Harbour Regional Park]], surrounds Lake Kohangapiripiri and Lake Kohangatera. These freshwater lakes, and their associated wetlands, are of national ecological importance â€“ being home to a wide variety of native plants and wildlife.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe area is popular with walkers and bikers, being especially busy on weekends. Entry to the area is via the large car park at the end of Muritai Road, Eastbourne.  Proceed through Burdans Gate and follow [[track:89]] along the rugged coastline of Wellington Harbour.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the Lower Pencarrow Lighthouse, a network of tracks provides several options including: continuing to [[track:90]], climbing to the [[track:97]], loops around lakes [[track:93]] and [[track:94]], or traversing [[track:92]] between the lakes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[track:97]] and other hill tops in the Parangarahu Lakes block provide panoramic views of the lakes, Cook Strait, and Wellington harbour.\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/parangarahu-lakes-area/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] and the [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/wellington/poneke/pencarrow-lakes/ Department of Conservation]] for further information.','-41.357613','174.865093',13,'2009-09-30 20:34:47'),(11,'Belmont Regional Park',1,'2009-04-04 09:16:21','Belmont Regional Park covers a total of 3500 hectares of hills and valleys between Porirua and the Hutt Valley, including the 1200 hectare Waitangirua Farm.  The land has multiple owners, including three city councils (Wellington, Porirua, and Hutt), the Greater Wellington Regional Council, and the Department of Conservation.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPoints of interest within the park include:  Korokoro Dam, World War II ammunition magazines, and part of the original Old Coach Road.  Spectacular views of the park and beyond are on offer from several peaks, including Boulder Hill, Round Knob, Cannons Head, and Belmont Trig.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a variety of tracks ranging from gentle bush clad strolls (such as [[track:99]]), technical tracks (such as [[track:150]]), though to sweet single track (such as [[track:105]]), connected by a network of 4x4 farm roads.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThanks to Jason (Hoz) Barclay, formerly Belmont Regional Park Ranger, for his assistance in compiling this information.\r\n[[h1:Closure of farm areas for lambing]]\r\nNote that tracks crossing the farm land are closed during lambing season, being the nine weeks prior to Labour Weekend.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor 2009, the [[bold:farm areas of the park were closed for lambing season from Saturday 22 August to Friday 23 October 2009 (inclusive)]]. As a guide to the farm areas, refer to the [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/stuff/2045_Belmontmaplambin_s3854%20lambing%202007.pdf map of lambing closures]].\r\n[[h1:Access]]\r\nThere are many entrances, enabling a variety of routes through the park.  The entrances that have car parking are:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.222988,174.860759&spn=0.011427,0.019312&t=h&z=16 Cornish Street]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.202415,174.87638&spn=0.005715,0.009656&z=17&iwloc=addr Oakleigh Street]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.180624,174.891443&spn=0.011434,0.019312&t=h&z=16 Stratton Street]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.177669,174.911807&spn=0.011435,0.019312&t=h&z=16 Hill Road]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.162623,174.945066&spn=0.005719,0.009656&t=h&z=17 Kaitangata Crescent]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?sll=-41.159129,174.970719&z=18 Dry Creek]] (intersection of State Highways 2 and 58)]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.141003,174.86661&spn=0.005721,0.009656&t=h&z=17 Warspite Avenue, Cannons Creek]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.156128,174.870719&spn=0.005525,0.009656&t=h&z=17 Takapu Road]]]]\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=belmont+road&sll=-41.177669,174.911807&sspn=0.011305,0.019076&ie=UTF8&ll=-41.133838,174.914736&spn=0.005656,0.009538&t=h&z=17 Belmont Road]], about 3km off State Highway 58.]]\r\n[[h1:Videos]]\r\nHere are a couple of videos from [[link:http://www.pnp.org.nz/mtb/events/2008/series08/rd408/?-session=pnpv4:CE30F0241405929B5DQNNi804C6E Round 4 of the 2008 PNP MTB Series]], held mostly in the forest block of the park â€“ including [[track:105]], [[track:153]], etc. Both videos were cut from the same, shared footage.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vorb:106106]]\r\n[[media:vorb:106087]]\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/belmont-regional-park-4/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] for more information about the park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere\'s a variety of interest groups associated with the park, including the Belmont Area Mountain Bike Association (BAMBA) which was established in late 2009.','-41.176328','174.903717',12,'2010-01-15 11:37:43'),(12,'Hutt River Trail',1,'2009-01-04 10:22:55','The Hutt River Trail is a popular recreational area that runs alongside the Hutt River from Hikoikoi Reserve in Petone to Birchville in Upper Hutt.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nUnlike most tracks in [[region:1]], the Hutt River Trail is virtually flat.  There are occasional bumps and an overall slight uphill trend as you head up the valley, but nothing of significance.  Along the entire 28.4km length of the eastern side of the river from Petone to Birchville, the track rises about 75m â€“ giving an average gradient of 0.25%, which is barely noticeable.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn addition to the continuous trail along the eastern bank of the Hutt River, there are parallel sections along most of the western bank.  However, there are gaps in the western tracks, one of which ([[track:130]]) is a dead-end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDue to the length of the Hutt River Trail, it is described in sections.  Each of the sections starts and/or ends at a bridge over the Hutt River, since the bridges provide natural break points along the trail and also offer opportunities to cross to the opposite bank.  The sections are named after a bridge, park, or other landmark associated with that section of the trail.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are plans to extend [[track:126]] as far as the Te Marua area of Kaitoke Regional Park, linking in with the Rimutaka Rail Trail and other tracks in the area.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[h1:Traversing the entire trail]]\r\nStarting from the eastern end of the Hutt Estuary Bridge (Waione Street) and heading north, one of many ways to traverse the entire Hutt River Trail is as follows: [[track:119]] - [[track:120]] - [[track:121]] - [[track:122]] - [[track:123]] - [[track:124]] - [[track:125]] - [[track:126]] - backtrack along [[track:126]] - [[track:127]] - [[track:128]] - south on [[track:123]] - [[track:129]] - south on [[track:121]] - [[track:130]] - backtrack on [[track:130]] - [[track:131]] - [[track:132]] - [[track:133]] - backtrack on [[track:133]] - cross Hutt Estuary Bridge to the start of [[track:119]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nTotal circuit distance (including bridges, backtracking, and repeated track sections): about 75km.\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nThere are plans to extend [[track:126]] to the east alongside State Highway 2. It will then connect with the Kaitoke water treatment area of [[area:16]], enabling access to the [[track:213]] and other tracks in that area.\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/hutt-river-trail/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] for further information about the Hutt River Trail.','-41.162114','174.984055',11,'2009-09-30 20:28:19'),(13,'Battle Hill',1,'2008-12-28 13:40:41','Battle Hill Farm Forest Park is a popular recreational area near Porirua.  The park is named after Battle Hill, which was the site of a battle between Maori and colonial forces in 1846.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCentred on a working farm, the park includes forestry areas and environmental restoration projects.  Activities in the park include walking, horse riding, mountain biking, camping and picnicking.  Most tracks in the park are short and fairly easy. For the more adventurous, the [[track:139]] provides access to the western side of the [[area:15]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBattle Hill is located on Paekakariki Hill Road about 6.5km north of Pauatahanui Inlet, off State Highway 58. Parking is available next to the ranger\'s office.\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/battle-hill-farm-forest-park-2/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] for further information about the park.','-41.057350','174.949465',14,'2009-09-30 20:40:59'),(14,'Northern Suburbs',1,'2008-11-30 09:03:40','[[region:1]]\'s northern suburbs, north of Ngauranga Gorge through to Porirua.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that some of these track descriptions might get moved, if there are enough tracks nearby to justify having their own area.\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nThere are plans for development of a mountain bike park on Colonial Knob, led by the [[link:http://www.colonialknob.org.nz/ Colonial Knob Supporters Incorporated]]. This development follows [[link:http://www.pcc.govt.nz/Theme/ModuleLayout/GetImage.aspx?imageid=8c983b4b-f576-490b-9bc8-1cb163533bc6&downloadnow=true Porirua City Council\'s purchase of land on Colonial Knob]] in mid 2009.','-41.144018','174.825439',11,'2009-10-16 10:32:52'),(15,'Akatarawa Forest',1,'2009-04-04 08:49:04','Akatarawa Forest covers an area of 15,000ha between Upper Hutt and the Kapiti coast.  It is the largest of the forests managed by the Greater Wellington Regional Council.  Encompassing three water catchments â€“ West Akatarawa river, Whakatikei river, and Maungokotukutuku Stream â€“ the forest is reserved as a potential future water collection area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the forest retains its native cover, though some area have been planted in exotics including pine and gum trees.  Parts of the exotic forest may be closed for time to time for forestry activities.  In particular, the south-eastern Valley View Forest (around [[track:193]] and [[track:195]]) is being progressively cleared and replanted from 2008 onwards, as are some areas off [[track:238]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn terms of terrain, the Akatarawa Forest consists mainly of rugged hill country.  Most of the hills reach an altitude of around 400-500m, though there are a couple of peaks that reach in excess of 700m.  In between the hills are many deep and steep-sided valleys covered in dense bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe area provides bountiful opportunities for a variety of recreational activities, including: mountain biking, walking, running, tramping, horse riding, trail bike riding, four wheel driving, quad biking, hunting, and fishing.  Note that the forest is one of the few areas of public land in the [[region:1]] region available for motorized recreation.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMountain biking is an especially popular activity in the forest, with a wide range of short and long tracks presenting a variety of challenges.  In particular, the Akatarawa Forest is the venue for the [[track:255]] mountain biking event, which has been held in the forest since 1985, along with the companion race the [[track:252]].\r\n[[h1:Access]]\r\nAkatarawa Forest is accessible via several entrances, including:\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Karapoti+Road,+new+zealand&sll=43.197167,-95.712891&sspn=45.136931,79.101563&ie=UTF8&ll=-41.061589,175.10087&spn=0.022133,0.038624&t=h&z=15&iwloc=addr Karapoti Road]], off Akatarawa Rd, Upper Hutt.]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps/mm?source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Maungakotukutuku+road,+new+zealand&g=Karapoti+Road,+new+zealand&ie=UTF8&t=h&ll=-40.965674,175.020018&spn=0.022943,0.038624&z=15 Maungakotukutuku Road]], via Waterfall Road 1km north of MacKays Crossing.]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[track:237]] via Moonshine Road and [[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Bulls+Run+Road,+new+zealand&sll=-40.965674,175.020018&sspn=0.022943,0.038624&ie=UTF8&t=h&z=15 Bulls Run Road]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[area:13]] Farm Forest Park, [[link:http://maps.google.com/maps/mm?source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Bulls+Run+Road,+new+zealand&ie=UTF8&t=h&ll=-41.060197,174.937277&spn=0.011455,0.019312&z=16 Paekakariki Hill Road]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:Valley View Road, off [[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Totara+Park+Road,+new+zealand&sll=-41.060197,174.937277&sspn=0.011455,0.019312&ie=UTF8&ll=-41.113124,175.080947&spn=0.005723,0.009656&t=h&z=17 Totara Park Road]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=tulsa+park,+new+zealand&sll=-41.113124,175.080947&sspn=0.005723,0.009656&g=Totara+Park+Road,+new+zealand&ie=UTF8&t=h&z=16 Tulsa Park]], in Totara Park.]]\r\n\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nThe forest is managed by the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/akatarawa-forest/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[area:15]] is a popular area for sporting events, including the [[track:255]] / [[track:252]] mountain bike races and the [[link:http://akattack.rhizome.net.nz/ Akatarawa Attack]] mountain bike orienteering adventure.','-41.017729','175.030060',11,'2009-09-30 20:23:47'),(16,'Pakuratahi Forest',1,'2009-03-29 09:21:56','The Pakuratahi Forest covers 8,000ha of rugged hill country on the western side of the Rimutaka ranges.  Tracks in this area include those in the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Tunnel-Gully/ Tunnel Gully Recreational Area]], [[track:278]], the old Rimutaka rail corridor through to the southern Wairarapa, plus a couple of tracks in the Kaitoke water collection area (which, strictly speaking, is part of the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Kaitoke-Regional-Park/ Kaitoke Regional Park]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the forest is native bush, though about 10% of the area is pine plantation.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPakuratahi Forest is a popular recreational area for walking, tramping, swimming, and mountain biking.  The two most popular areas are the historic 1870s [[track:213]]/[[track:212]] and the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Tunnel-Gully/ Tunnel Gully Recreational Area]] at the base of [[track:278]].\r\n[[h1:Access note]]\r\nParts of the forest are being logged in 2009. In particular, as of 3 January 2009 the entrances to [[track:208]] and [[track:209]] have notices that say: \"Authorised access only. Logging trucks operating weekdays from 5 January 2009\".\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the Greater Wellington Regional Council for more information on [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/pakuratahi-forest/ Pakuratahi Forest]] and [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Kaitoke-Regional-Park/ Kaitoke Regional Park]].','-41.118935','175.192795',12,'2009-09-30 20:27:17'),(17,'Hutt Valley',1,'2009-01-17 09:39:20','This is a large area encompassing all of the Hutt Valley from Petone to Upper Hutt.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[area:17]] is wedged between the surrounding areas of [[area:11]], [[area:15]], [[area:16]], and [[area:9]]. In addition, it is bordered by the [[area:8]] and has the [[area:12]] running through the middle of the valley.\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\n[[link:http://www.mountainbike.co.nz/clubs/hvmbc/ Hutt Valley Mountain Bike Club]] is planning to build a track between [[track:227]] and [[track:269]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[track:894]] track is being re-constructed, after the top section was messed up by logging.','-41.176070','174.971008',11,'2010-04-11 08:25:20'),(18,'Tinakori Hill',1,'2009-02-01 20:08:50','Tinakori Hill is part of Wellington\'s town belt, located only minutes from downtown on the northwestern side of the city.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is an extensive network of tracks on the hill, primarily on the southeastern side facing the harbour. Due to its proximity to downtown, and being surrounded on all sides by residential areas, the tracks are popular with walkers and runners at all times of the day.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPrior to 2009 only the [[track:240]] track was open to mountain bikes. In the new [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/plans/policies/trackrec/index.html Track Recreation Activities Policy]] (dated November 2008 and released in early 2009) four more tracks were opened to bikes â€“ that is, [[track:249]], [[track:241]], [[track:251]], and the [[track:250]].\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nAt some point mechanisms will be installed on the down hill part of the [[track:251]] and the [[track:250]] to slow down bikes. Given that these are shared-use tracks, it would be prudent to ride conservatively in the meantime.','-41.271420','174.770637',15,'2009-09-05 09:18:29'),(19,'Southern Suburbs',1,'2009-06-03 09:04:35','This is a general area covering suburban tracks in [[region:1]]\'s southern suburbs, excluding the areas that are described separately.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that some of these track descriptions might get moved, if there are enough tracks nearby to justify having their own area.','-41.327971','174.785528',14,'2009-06-03 09:04:35'),(20,'Whakarewarewa',2,'2009-02-02 03:45:02','Much hard work by locals and local clubs, and a continued good relationship with forest owners has resulted in many km\'s of fun singletrack. \r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can by a paper map at the park for $5, or have a look at the [[link:http://www.riderotorua.com/maps.php online version]].','-38.180315','176.285591',13,'2010-02-04 20:03:34'),(21,'Queen Elizabeth Park',1,'2009-03-13 17:35:10','Queen Elizabeth Park is a popular recreational area, with facilities for swimming, fishing, walking, mountain biking, horse riding, and picnicing. The 650 hectare park encompasses the last remaining area of natural sand dunes on the Kapiti Coast, adjacent to sandy beaches and views of Kapiti Island.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe highest point in the park is at an altitude of only 35m above sea level. Even so, there is a surprising amount of hill climbing - albeit in short bursts - as the tracks weave their way over and around the sand dunes. The tracks generally have a firm surface, but watch out for an occasional sand trap where a section of track has subsided or a dune has drifted onto the track. Also note that there is little shelter from the elements in the park, with the prevailing northwest wind dishing out a good sand blasting - especially on the coastal tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe park has a long history, including Maori pa sites at Whareroa and Wainui beaches. During World War II the largest [[link:http://pspt.wellington.net.nz/uss.htm United States Marine Corps camp]] in New Zealand was located in and around the park, housing 20,000 people. There is a World War II memorial next to Whareroa Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[link:http://www.wellingtontrams.org.nz/about.html Kapiti Coast Electric Tramway]] is located just inside the MacKays Crossing entrance. The tramway runs along a 2km line to Whareroa Beach and return.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[track:257]] and [[track:258]] tracks form part of the [[link:http://www.teararoa.org.nz/index.cfm/PageID/134/ViewPage/Waikanae+-+Paekakariki Te Araroa]] track network.\r\n[[h1:Access]]\r\nThere are three main entrance points:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:Southern:  Turn off SH1 into Paekakariki and turn right and continue to the end of Wellington Road.]]\r\n[[bullet:Centre:  The MacKays Crossing entrance off SH1 leads to Whareroa Road, which gives access to Whareroa Beach, surrounding dunes, picnic areas, walking, cycling and horseriding trails, the Tramway Museum, WWII memorial, a wetland and a kahikatea forest remnant. The Ranger\'s office is opposite to tramway station, just inside the main gate.]]\r\n[[bullet:Northern: Turn off SH1 at Poplar Ave and follow the road to its end at The Esplanade. Turn left and drive for about 1km to reach the park entrance.]]\r\nOpening hours: The park is open daily from 8am to dusk.\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/queen-elizabeth-park-4/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] for further information about the park.','-40.960586','174.976845',13,'2009-09-30 20:40:30'),(22,'Miramar',1,'2009-06-07 19:49:48','Miramar is a peninsular on the eastern fringe of [[region:1]] city.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[track:347]] is at the northern tip of the peninsular. Currently the land around the Massey Memorial is not readily accessible for recreational purposes, but there are calls for the area to be designated as [[link:http://masseyregionalpark.org.nz/index.htm Massey Regional Park]].  If a regional park is created, there is potential for the  Maupuia Reserve tracks to link into a wider track network around the northern end of the headland.\r\n\r\n[[h1:Track building]]\r\nSince late 2008 the [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/miramar-track-project-t91605.html Miramar Track Project]] has been working to create a recreational area for running, walking and mountain biking in the Maupuia Reserve. For further information see the [[link:http://www.facebook.com/pages/Miramar-Track-Project/220242049761#!/pages/Miramar-Track-Project/220242049761?v=wall project\'s Facebook page]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe reserve includes disused farmland south of [[link:http://corrections.govt.nz/utility-navigation/find-a-facility-or-site/find_a_corrections_facility/wellington_prison.html Wellington Prison]] (otherwise known as Mount Crawford Prison), which [[link:http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/506816 closed temporarily in 2008]] and [[link:http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/2489295/Demand-forces-Wellington-Prison-open-again reopened in July 2009]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nTracks currently being developed include [[track:346]], [[track:337]], and [[track:870]]. Note that the track names reflect the site\'s location immediately below Wellington Prison.','-41.312758','174.825439',13,'2010-02-24 20:05:29'),(23,'Queen Charlotte Sound',3,'2009-06-03 21:55:24','Home of the Queen Charlotte Track','-41.205533','174.032790',10,'2010-04-21 14:05:15'),(24,'National Park',4,'2009-06-22 22:00:01','There are a few tracks round here see also:\r\nhttp://nationalpark.co.nz/pages/activities/mountain-biking.php\r\n','-38.995707','175.827942',9,'2009-06-22 22:00:01'),(25,'Queenstown',6,'2009-06-30 20:08:07','At the heart of the Queenstown Lakes District is Queenstown, a resort town built around an inlet of Lake Wakatipu.  World renowned for its stunning scenery and adventure-based tourism, Queenstown is marketed as the \"adventure capital of the world\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom a mountain biking perspective, the [[link:http://www.qmtbc.co.nz/news.php Queenstown Mountain Bike Club]] actively supports the local mountain biking community through the maintenance and development of tracks.  Mountain biking tours and heli-bike trips are offered by several commercial operators, including [[link:http://www.fat-tyre.co.nz/ Fat Tyre Adventures]] and [[link:http://www.vertigobikes.co.nz/tours/ Vertigo Bikes]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor further information refer to [[link:http://www.queenstown-nz.co.nz/information/home/ Queenstown Tourism]].','-45.025495','168.646317',11,'2009-06-30 20:13:23'),(26,'Arrowtown',6,'2009-06-30 20:30:31','Arrowtown is a historic former gold mining town located on the banks of the Arrow River.\r\n[[para]]\r\nLike nearby [[area:25]], Arrowtown is surrounded by spectacular scenery.  Though in contrast to Queenstown, Arrowtown has a tranquil atmosphere focussed on arts and crafts along with quiet walks around its tree lined streets and historic buildings.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor the more adventurous, the area around Arrowtown offers plenty of walking and biking tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor more information, refer to [[link:http://www.arrowtown.com/ Discover Arrowtown]].','-44.938071','168.833427',12,'2009-06-30 20:34:05'),(27,'Victoria Park',5,'2009-07-08 15:59:23','A beautiful recreation area up on Christchurch\'s Port Hills, Victoria Park is a Hub of Activity, especially on the weekends, when you will see Dog Walkers, Hikers, Runners and Mountain Bikers all utilising the many tracks available here.\r\nFrom casual walks to downhill mountain biking tracks there is something for everyone.  \r\nYou can even see Native Kereru on the Bush Walks!','-43.589095','172.649031',14,'2009-08-13 15:15:10'),(28,'Kapiti Coast',1,'2009-07-12 14:22:48','Paraparaumu, Waikanae and Otaki areas north of Wellington.','-40.892753','175.089111',10,'2009-07-12 14:22:48'),(29,'Glenbervie Mountain Biking',7,'2009-07-18 01:59:00','Glenbervie Mountain Biking is a few kilometers east of Whangarei.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA detailed map and some photos can be found at [[link:http://www.glenberviemtbiking.zoomshare.com/2.shtml/Trail%20Maps Glenbervie Mountain Biking]]','-35.645230','174.348564',14,'2009-12-14 13:13:31'),(30,'Korokoro',1,'2009-07-23 20:08:39','This hill suburb of Petone has a history going back to the early 1900\'s.  Often bypassed on the way to/from Wellington, there is a variety of walking tracks through bush clad hills and breath-taking views from lookout points over Wellington harbour.  Indeed, these bush walks may be the most under-rated in Wellington.','-41.214627','174.866681',14,'2009-10-04 21:14:32'),(32,'South',8,'2009-07-29 01:05:08','Southern end of the Wairarapa valley and Cape Palliser area.','-41.390204','175.329437',10,'2010-02-14 19:34:59'),(33,'Ngaio',1,'2009-08-03 21:01:01','A quiet suburb a few kilometres north of Wellington city.  The compact village area has a few shops, cafe, library, school and is served by two railway stations on the Johnsonville line.  There are several sites of historical interest - a large sign outside the Ngaio library can provide directions.  The sunny, flat central Ngaio is surrounded by hills and bush clad valleys which makes for interesting exploration','-41.247999','174.782867',13,'2009-08-03 21:07:40'),(34,'Abel Tasman',9,'2009-08-04 15:57:43','Contains the famous \"Rameka\" Track, The \"Kaiteriteri MTB Park\", and the new \"Cannan Downs MTB Park\"','-40.908129','172.863436',10,'2009-08-12 11:48:31'),(35,'Waiwhero South',9,'2009-08-04 22:10:13','The Waiwhero Forest (Private land under AFM / Hancock\'s Management) Permit required for entry','-41.200356','172.959652',13,'2009-12-19 20:16:25'),(36,'Parihaka',7,'2009-08-05 16:00:32','Parihaka Mountain Bike Park. There is two entrances to this Park. Off Abbey Caves Rd or from the top of Memorial Drive. Abbey Caves Rd has the car park and park information. This park is a work in progress.','-35.709932','174.342084',15,'2009-08-07 19:24:46'),(37,'Whanui',7,'2009-08-05 16:02:29','Old Coach road running from Mangahua Rd through to Waiparera Rd, Parua Bay. Drive up Mangahua Rd to steel gate, the Coach Rd starts on left, and runs through to Waiparera Rd for approx 4.5 K\'s. Then turn around and retrace the journey. ','-35.697142','174.466624',15,'2009-08-07 19:22:18'),(38,'Sandy Bay ',7,'2009-08-05 16:03:59','Track from Sandy Bay to Whananaki.Park your car at McAuslin Rd, and ride on through the gate. Then follow the track through until you reach Whananaki bridge, go across and buy an Ice-cream at the store. Then about turn and head back.Approx 10-15k\'s ride.','-35.540712','174.463320',13,'2009-12-03 16:16:41'),(39,'Onerahi',7,'2009-08-05 16:05:01','The trails in the hills behind Onerahi are built and maintained by Brent Love of Missing Link cycles(missinglinkcycles@xtra.co.nz).','-35.736898','174.390793',14,'2009-12-04 14:00:48'),(40,'Western Hills Reserve',7,'2009-08-05 16:06:35','Trails in the Western Hills behind Whangarei. A sort of need to know place, there is no map for this area.','-35.721082','174.295778',15,'2009-08-07 19:30:47'),(41,'Central City',1,'2009-08-05 20:48:18','Central Wellington is a vibrant place with many sites of interest to walkers.  There are short routes suitable for a lunchtime stroll, or much longer walks in the botanic gardens, the cemetery, or along the waterfront.','-41.289803','174.769650',14,'2010-01-16 18:16:02'),(100,'Waiwhero North',9,'2009-08-11 11:09:53','Forestry Block requiring a permit to enter.\r\nVery good fitness area with a couple of excellent downhill runs.\r\nSuitable for most riders, Grade 2 or better, nothing technical.\r\nGood fitness required for the climb back up Short Cut Rd.\r\nSuggested ride as follows...\r\nPark at the bottom of Mill Rd.\r\nUp Mill Road, turn into Link Road, keep heading up to the top of the ridge and all the way along to do the Lookout Loop.\r\nOn the way back do the Loopback and Longsleive Lowdown, then return up the ridge to go down Gorse Gauntlet. Follow the Mot Highway up until you come to Waiwhero Road, turn in and ride short distance to Short Cut Road. Bike the steep climb back up to the ridge, and along to Shunt Road. Down Shunt Road (firebreak) and take all turns to the left until you come out at the bottom. Follow Waiwhero Road around to Mill Road, then back to carpark.','-41.166166','172.934966',13,'2009-08-11 13:08:13'),(101,'Hira Forest',9,'2009-08-11 12:32:34','large pine forest block close to Nelson containing several very good trails. Access to most trails requires a permit in this area.\r\nSuggested ride is to ride the 8.5km up Sharland road to the top of the R&R Rush, ride down the R&R and then up to the top of Scotwood Wiggles and down the Wiggles, then Down Lancewood Waggles. Ride up to the top of Suplejack and do either Rimu or Supplejack, finishing with a ride out on the sharland valley Trail.','-41.247741','173.350182',13,'2010-01-11 16:34:02'),(102,'Port Hills',5,'2009-08-12 18:07:30','The Port Hills are one of the best-loved landscapes of Christchurch. The tussock grasslands and rugged rock out-crops, contrast the flatness of the Canterbury Plains. Remnants of podacarp forest are reminders of the past.[[br]]\r\nPeople enjoy the Port Hills in many different ways, from scenic drives to picnic lookouts. Walking, running, mountain biking and road biking are all very popular. Botanists explore the crater rim forests, rock climbers dangle down the sheer volcanic bluffs, and paragliders soar high over the tussock slopes. There are permanent orienteering courses set up, great places from which to launch model planes, and many a photogenic view and rock.[[br]]\r\nThe Christchurch City Council manages 31 of the 39 reserves on the Port Hills. Other reserves are run by the Department of Conservation, privately or by trusts.\r\n[[h1:Track Status]]\r\n[[link:http://www.ccc.govt.nz/cityleisure/gettingaround/cycling/tracksrides/porthills.aspx Christchurch City Council Port Hills (and Victoria Park) track status]] is updated every few days, more often when weather is variable. Always check the status here before you head out. Some tracks (like Rapaki and Kennedys Bush) rarely ever close, others can suffer greatly in the rain and are damaged by riding on them when wet.','-43.583375','172.653580',11,'2010-01-15 10:15:49'),(103,'McLeans Island',5,'2009-08-13 09:13:05','McLeans Forest is part of the Waimakariri River Regional Park. The loop track travels through pine forest over a fast smooth track with fun corners and rises. Ideal for anyone with a off road bike â€“ it is easy riding suiting all abilities and all ages.','-43.455162','172.503204',12,'2009-09-11 16:42:21'),(104,'Bottle Lake Forest Park',5,'2009-08-13 14:40:44','Bottle Lake Forest Park is situated approximately 10km north east of central Christchurch, adjacent to the coast. Bottle Lake Forest is a production forest and trees are felled and logged in a 30 year rotation by the Selwyn Plantation Board.\r\n\r\nRecreational facilities include mountain-bike tracks, horse-trekking trails and walking tracks.\r\n\r\nDeveloped from a farm in the early 1900s the forest expanded from coastal protection plantings to its present size. It is planted with mostly pinus radiata and covers over 800 hectares of coastal sand dunes. The combined area of these forests is four times the size of Hagley Park, and as such, forms an important asset to metropolitan Christchurch.\r\nAccess\r\n\r\nThe main entrance and car park for Bottle Lake Forest is from Waitikiri Drive, off Burwood Road, via either Marshlands or Burwood. There is also access from Spencer Park, and from North Shore along the Southern Pegasus Bay Track.','-43.455910','172.700272',13,'2009-08-13 14:40:44'),(105,'Dun Mountain and Fringe',9,'2009-08-13 15:35:31','New Zealand\'s First Railway.\r\nThis area contains the famous recreational level Dun Mountain track along with the awesome technical Black Diamond, Sunshine and Peaking ridges. Also the large Coppermine Loop that has become an [[link:http://www.coppermine.co.nz/ annual event]].','-41.309447','173.337660',12,'2010-02-04 20:20:08'),(106,'Codgers MTB Park',9,'2009-08-14 15:13:14','This Recreational Level MTB Park has been developed by the Nelson City Council in conjunction with the Department of Corrections and the Nelson Mountain Bike Club.\r\nConsisting of a large number of tracks already, it is still expanding.\r\nThere are tracks here for all levels of rider, and plans for a pump track this summer.\r\nOpen all year round with easy access, this has fast become one of Nelson\'s most used and fun MTB parks.\r\n\r\n***** NOTE ******\r\n\r\nDUE TO LOGGING PIPALINI IS GOING TO GO AND A LARGE AREA IS CURRENTLY OUT OF BOUNDS','-41.290677','173.301635',16,'2010-02-14 22:42:27'),(107,'North',8,'2009-09-06 20:39:40','North Wairarapa from Featherston and northern end of Lake Ferry to Palmerston North and southern Hawke\'s Bay.','-41.017211','175.531311',9,'2009-09-06 22:02:02'),(108,'South Manawatu',12,'2009-09-20 20:49:05','The area north of Otaki but south of Palmerston North.  A coastal strip with the Tararua ranges on the East, snow capped in winter.','-40.400948','175.698853',8,'2009-09-20 20:49:39'),(109,'Woodhill',13,'2009-09-27 01:20:51','Auckland Mountain Bike club have built twisty tracks with jumps and banked corners, in this narrow strip of forest inland from Muriwai and Rangitira beaches.','-36.752364','174.414139',12,'2009-09-27 01:20:51'),(110,'Whitford Forest',13,'2009-09-27 01:33:12','Whiteford Forest is about 10km south-east of [[region:auckland]] city. Peter Cloustanâ€™s tracks are the best in Whitford. To get to them, start at the carpark at the top of the hill on the Whitford-Maraetai Road, 6km from Whitford. Then hop over the gate and head down the track. At the bottom, choose a track from the map board - most are named after Cloustanâ€™s relatives. Joshuaâ€™s track is a good starting point, whilst Peterâ€™s Track is the hardest. Be careful of jumps and drop-offs - especially after rain.','-36.939465','175.028000',12,'2009-09-27 01:33:12'),(111,'Hunua Ranges',13,'2009-09-27 03:16:27','To do','-37.085310','175.168762',11,'2009-09-27 03:16:27'),(112,'Kaiteriteri MTB Park',9,'2009-10-01 20:55:56','This is a Fantastic New MTB park that caters for all levels of rider.\r\nThe park includes a \"Pump Track\", a long easy trail, and several challenging ridge runs.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAccess is easy, less than 1km from Kaiteriteri beach!\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Introduction to Kaiteriteri MTB Park: [[track:615]], [[track:617]], [[track:618]] & [[track:616]]]]\r\n[[media:youtube:r4Caq2sE2iI]]\r\n\r\n[[h1:Further information]]\r\nSee [[link:http://www.kaiteriterimtbpark.org.nz/ Kaiteriteri Mountain Bike Park]] for further information.','-41.045163','173.003182',14,'2010-02-13 12:00:23'),(113,'Oamaru',14,'2009-10-05 13:20:47','Oamaru, North Otago','-45.098730','170.967865',11,'2009-10-05 13:20:47'),(114,'Central',15,'2009-10-26 20:39:04','Sunny Central Hawke\'s Bay contains the main towns and wineries.','-39.344918','176.717834',9,'2009-10-26 21:11:03'),(115,'Emano',9,'2009-11-03 22:09:45','A technical downhill section from Observatory Terrace to Upper Emano Street.  Has some great board walks making use of windfall trees and lots of tight turns.\r\nNot too big a walk back to the start to do it again!  \r\nRide up Princes Drive and take the left turn into Observatory Terrace, follow firebreak down to gate and the fun begins, alternatively ride to the top of Emano Street and enter through the park, walk up and ride down.','-41.287304','173.257806',12,'2010-04-21 10:13:15'),(116,'Blenheim',3,'2009-11-18 19:35:18','Situated on the Wairau plains Blenheim is about 30 minutes drive from Picton and the ferry terminal.  The area is famous for vineyards, and there are also many good mountain biking trails.','-41.398445','173.960266',10,'2009-11-18 19:45:48'),(117,'Ashley',11,'2009-11-18 19:52:37','A quiet village north of Christchurch with a large river mouth and nearby Waikuku Beach.','-43.272706','172.638474',11,'2009-11-18 20:02:39'),(118,'Christchurch City',5,'2009-11-18 20:40:54','City area.','-43.535109','172.632294',11,'2009-11-18 20:40:54'),(119,'Arthurs Pass',11,'2009-11-18 21:19:50','In the middle of the Southern Alps half way between Christchurch and the West Coast, this little town is high in the mountains and provides an excellent selection of walks for all types of people.','-42.925257','171.613312',10,'2009-11-18 21:27:51'),(120,'Okarito',10,'2009-11-18 21:42:33','Historic settlement on the west coast approximately mid-way between Haast and Hokitika (about 150 km from each).  A large lagoon borders the town.','-43.292350','170.370483',8,'2009-11-18 21:42:33'),(121,'Mosgiel',14,'2009-11-19 15:25:37','Mosgiel and surrounding tracks','-45.848891','170.359497',11,'2009-11-24 12:42:27'),(122,'Dunedin',14,'2009-11-19 15:33:46','Tracks around the Dunedin area','-45.831191','170.582657',11,'2009-11-19 15:33:46'),(123,'Ohakune',12,'2009-11-19 18:45:12','Region is popular in ski season, and the town of Ohakune is famous for its carrot.  Some excellent walking and cycling tracks.','-39.465885','175.704346',9,'2009-11-19 18:45:12'),(124,'North Waikato',16,'2009-11-19 19:05:35','The region immediately south of the Bombay hills.','-37.468319','175.361023',9,'2009-11-19 19:05:35'),(125,'Wellsford',7,'2009-11-19 19:20:50','Central Northland region.','-36.239843','174.578247',10,'2009-11-19 19:37:53'),(126,'Whirinaki Forest',4,'2009-12-01 20:42:59','The [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/bay-of-plenty/rangitaiki/whirinaki-forest-park/ Whirinaki forest]] is home to [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/bay-of-plenty/rangitaiki/whirinaki-forest-park/activities/whirinaki-forest-mountain-bike-track/ Whirinaki Forest Mountain Bike Track]] and the recent Moerangi Track.','-38.757231','176.006470',9,'2009-12-01 20:45:20'),(127,'Lake Guyon',17,'2010-01-02 22:59:13','This can be done as an out and back ride from the Rainbow Road. From Nelson it is about 2.5 hours drive to Pass Stream where the old pack track starts. You can do a loop either going in or coming out over Maling Pass. DoC is building a new section of track down the true left of the Waiau (late 2009) to avoid crossing the river. You could also make a loop riding down the Stanley and out via the Edwards, which is to be part of the St James cycleway. However an out and back gives the best riding with some pushing going back up Fowler Pass.\r\nThe total time for this out and back trip was 4.5 hours.\r\n','-42.956423','172.792969',6,'2010-01-02 22:59:13'),(128,'Hanmer Township',17,'2010-01-02 23:35:55','This is the area around the Hanmer Township and a bulk of the areas MTB tracks.\r\nThese tracks were mapped by me a little while back and I cannot guarantee their accuracy as I know a few of them were up for logging.\r\nThere is something for everyone here from the family friendly \"Forest Park MTB Area\" through to Yankee Tank Detox and red rock for a bit more of a challenge.\r\nIf you are an excersize freak, then the Jacks Pass / Jollies Pass loop will rock your sox.\r\nWith respect to the Hanmer MTB Club who\'s only source of income is Sales of their fantastic Trail Maps, There are no GPS file loaded for these tracks, just desriptions. Please purchase a map from the Bike Shop in Hanmer when you visit to support this worthy cause','-42.519945','172.829104',13,'2010-03-09 23:23:29'),(129,'Whanganui National Park',18,'2010-01-07 13:35:08','National Park around the upper reaches of the Whanganui River.','-39.303487','174.933929',10,'2010-01-07 13:35:08'),(130,'Nydia Bay',3,'2010-01-17 20:22:20','Stunning scenery and a mix of singletrack from fast flowing to steep and rooty. Plenty of technically challenging singletrack, and it takes about 6 hours for a fit group. Not recommended for beginners or unfit people!','-41.176823','173.784052',10,'2010-04-21 14:02:47'),(131,'Wairakei Forest',4,'2010-02-14 17:58:12','Also known as Craters of the Moon. A series of windy tracks mostly through pine forest.','-38.636316','176.071529',13,'2010-02-14 19:43:25'),(132,'Oban',19,'2010-02-28 21:10:19','The main area of the island.  Visitors will arrive in Oban and begin tramps from here.','-46.919317','168.068848',11,'2010-02-28 21:56:57'),(133,'Orewa Alice Eaves Reserve',13,'2010-03-23 09:23:16','The tracks are next to this reserve and are separate from the walking tracks.\r\nIt can be done as loop including the road, which gains elevation. Or you can use the numerous creek crossing bridges to make figure 8\'s so that you don\'t have to use the road.\r\nMost of the trail is single track, it\'s rooty and twisty and perfect for a trail bike, skinny tires at high pressure will be hard work in here!\r\n','-36.438961','174.704590',7,'2010-03-23 09:23:16'),(134,'Eastbourne',1,'2010-04-11 08:39:29','Eastbourne is a picturesque harbour-side suburb that stretches from Point Howard down to Burdans Gate.  To the north is [[area:17]] and to the south is the [[area:10]] area. To the east, over Mount Lowry, is [[area:9]] along with the [[area:8]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nClimbing steeply from the narrow built-up area, the hilly tracks soon offer spectacular views over the harbour.  Much of the area is covered in pristine native bush, which provides pleasant surroundings for the sometimes strenuous climbs.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAll of the tracks in this area are restricted to foot traffic only â€“ no bikes allowed.','-41.273162','174.904060',12,'2010-04-11 08:42:10'),(135,'Takaka',9,'2010-04-21 09:43:55','To do','-40.936340','172.805328',10,'2010-04-21 09:43:55');
