INSERT INTO `faqs` VALUES (1,'Can anyone edit the tracks?',1,'Yes anyone can edit tracks and areas. You need to be signed-in to make changes. If you want to create new tracks (or areas) please send an email to [[bold:info@tracks.org.nz]]','Editing','2008-12-15 06:42:55','2010-02-07 08:27:28'),(2,'How can I apply formatting and links when editing?',1,'The following simple formatting options are available in various free-text editing boxes:\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:New line:]] \\[\\[br\\]\\] â‡’ insert a newline/end of line]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:New paragraph:]] \\[\\[para\\]\\] â‡’ start a new paragraph (ie. putting a blank line in a text box doesn\'t create a new paragraph when displayed â€“ the \\[\\[para\\]\\] tag needs to be used).]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Heading level 1:]] \\[\\[h1:heading\\]\\] â‡’ create a heading - level 1]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Heading level 2:]] \\[\\[h2:heading\\]\\] â‡’ create a heading - level 2]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Bold text:]] \\[\\[bold:text\\]\\] â‡’ make \'text\' bold]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Italic text:]] \\[\\[italic:text\\]\\] â‡’ make \'text\' italic]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Bullet point:]] \\[\\[bullet:text\\]\\] â‡’ insert a bullet point containing \'text\']]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Link to Feature request:]] \\[\\[feature:n\\]\\] â‡’ link to feature or problem id \'n\', as listed on the [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/features Features]] page.]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Embed an image:]] \\[\\[image:ref:alt:width:height\\]\\] â‡’ display an image, which must already be available on the web, where: \'ref\' is a link to the image; \'alt\' is the alternate text to display if the image is not available; \'width\' is the image width in pixels (up to 492 pixels wide); \'height\' is the image height in pixels. Provide all colons even if not supplying the \'alt\', \'width\' or \'height\'. It might be necessary to precede the image with \\[\\[para\\]\\] or \\[\\[br\\]\\]. At present \'ref\' must include the full web address including the http:// part.[[br]]For example: \\[\\[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/Danger.png:Rifle range warning sign on Goat Rock:200:206\\]\\].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Hyperlink:]] \\[\\[link:ref name\\]\\] â‡’ create a hyperlink, where: \'ref\' is the link; \'name\' is the displayed link name. A space divides \'ref\' and \'name\'. Give the fully qualified address (ie. including the http:// part) for external links. To correctly identify an internal tracks.org.nz link give the full tracks.org.nz in front of the link.[[br]]For example: \\[\\[link:http://www.google.com Google\\]\\] becomes [[link:http://www.google.com Google]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Cross-reference to a track:]] \\[\\[track:region:name\\]\\] â‡’ internal link to track \'name\'. Track names must be unique within a region, though different regions may have tracks with the same name â€“ hence the need to include the \'region\' within the cross-reference. Note special use for when track name is all numbers: prepend the track name with a \'#\' (this is an edge case, but it has happened).[[br]]For example: \\[\\[track:Wellington:Aratihi\\]\\] becomes [[track:4]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Cross-reference to an area:]] \\[\\[area:name\\]\\] â‡’ internal link to area \'name\'.[[br]]For example: \\[\\[area:Makara Peak\\]\\] becomes [[area:1]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Cross-reference to a region:]] \\[\\[region:name\\]\\] â‡’ internal link to region \'name\'.[[br]]For example: \\[\\[region:Wellington\\]\\] becomes [[region:1]].]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Embed YouTube video:]] \\[\\[media:youtube:ref\\]\\] â‡’ embed [[link:http://www.youtube.com/ YouTube]] video.[[br]]Where: \'ref\' is the \'v=...\' part of the link.[[br]]For example: use the [[bold:6kxDxLAjkO8]] part of the following YouTube URL[[br]] http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=[[bold:6kxDxLAjkO8]]]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Embed Vorb video:]] \\[\\[media:vorb:ref\\]\\] â‡’ embed [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz Vorb]] video.[[br]]Where: \'ref\' is the \'id=...\' part of the Vorb URL. The easiest way to find this URL is to right-click the video link, copy location, and paste it somewhere temporary.[[br]]For example: use the [[bold:65226]] part of the following Vorb URL[[br]]http://www.vorb.org.nz/rez_viewattach.php?id=[[bold:65226]]&mode=&TB_iframe=false.]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Embed Vimeo video:]] \\[\\[media:vimeo:ref\\]\\] â‡’ embed [[link:http://www.vimeo.com Vimeo]] video.[[br]]Where: \'ref\' is the last part of the Vimeo URL.[[br]]For example: use the [[bold:6691202]] part of the following Vimeo URL[[br]]http://www.vimeo.com/[[bold:6691202]]]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Display left square bracket:]] \\\\[ â‡’ \\[]]\r\n\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Display right square bracket:]] \\\\] â‡’ \\] ]]','Editing','2008-12-15 06:43:33','2010-01-07 17:09:25'),(3,'How do I create and upload the Google Maps data for a track?',23,'The Google Maps use the [[link:http://code.google.com/apis/kml/ kml]] file format.  The easiest way to create a kml file is to use [[link:http://earth.google.com/ Google Earth]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are two options for creating the kml track data:\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:GPS log.]]  If you have a GPS log of the track, then open it in Google Earth. GPS is an inherently imprecise technology, so the GPS log may need editing to remove spurious data points or to adjust the recorded points to better match the aerial photo. Right-click on the track and select \"Properties\" to edit the track.]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:No GPS log.]] Don\'t worry if you don\'t have a GPS log of the track â€“ you can still create the map data by drawing the track manually in Google Earth. Use the \"Add Path\" tool to draw the track.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce you\'ve got the track looking good, give it a name (right-click and select \"Properties\"). The name will be displayed on the Google Map when the user points at the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThen save the track to a kml file as follows:\r\n[[bullet:Right-click on the track (either in the map view or in the \"Places\" bar).]]\r\n[[bullet:Select \"Save Place Asâ€¦\" and enter a file name.]]\r\n[[bullet:Select the kml file type (rather than the default kmz file type, which is a compressed kml file).]]\r\n[[bullet: Click the \"Save\" button to save the kml file somewhere convenient.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nTo upload the kml file to Tracks, [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/account/login Sign In]] and click the \"Upload GPS path file\" link under the track\'s map.','','2009-09-28 12:02:13','2009-09-30 07:18:25'),(4,'What does the track \'Grade\' mean?',23,'The grade indicates how difficult a track is, using the [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/parks-and-recreation/activity-finder/mtn-biking/mtb-grading-print.pdf track grading system]] developed by the [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/ Department of Conservation]] and [[link:http://www.bikenz.org.nz/Article.aspx?ID=759 Mountain Bike New Zealand]].  The same grading system is used for walking and mountain biking, though many tracks will be somewhat easier to walk than to ride.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track grades are defined as:\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Grade 1, Beginner]]: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Grade 2, Easy]]: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs on smooth track with easily avoidable obstacles such as rocks and potholes.]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Grade 3, Intermediate]]: Steep slopes and/or avoidable obstacles possibly on narrow track and/or with poor traction. There may be exposure at the track\'s outside edge.]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Grade 4, Advanced]]: A mixture of long, steep climbs, narrow track, poor traction and obstacles that are difficult to avoid or jump over. Generally exposed at the track\'s outside edge. Most riders will find some sections easier to walk.]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Grade 5, Expert]]: Technically challenging. Giant climbs, narrow track and numerous hazards including dangerous drop-offs, sharp corners and difficult obstacles. Expect walking and possibly bike carrying.]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Grade 6, Extreme]]: Downhill/free ride specific tracks. Extremely steep sections with large drop-offs and other unavoidable obstacles. May include man-made structures and jumps.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that most tracks will be more difficult when wet.','','2009-09-30 09:28:52','2010-02-07 08:28:24'),(5,'The maps don\'t work properly on my computer â€“ what can I do?',23,'If the map doesn\'t display, or the problem is with one of the Google Maps types (ie. the \"Map\", \"Satellite\", and \"Terrain\" buttons on the map), then have a look at the [[link:http://maps.google.com/support/bin/topic.py?topic=10781 Google Maps troubleshooting guide]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf the problem is with the Google Earth map type (ie. the \"Earth 3D\" button on the map), then have a look at the [[link:http://code.google.com/apis/earth/faq.html Google Earth API FAQ]]. Note that the first time you select the \"Earth\" map type, the Google Earth browser plugin will be downloaded and installed â€“ just follow the prompts to complete the installation.\r\n','','2009-10-07 13:44:39','2009-12-21 09:39:31'),(6,'How do I suggest a feature or report a problem?',23,'To suggest a new or modified feature, go to [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/features/new?kind=feature Suggest a feature]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nTo report a problem with the website, go to [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/features/new?kind=problem Report a problem]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can vote for the features and problems that you\'d like to receive higher priority. There\'s also a comment facility associated with each feature and problem, so you can contribute your views or provide additional information. You need to be signed-in to suggest a feature, report a problem, or comment on an existing feature or problem.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOpen feature requests and problem reports can be found in the [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/features Features and problems list]].','','2010-01-15 12:04:51','2010-01-15 15:03:33'),(7,'Is there somewhere I can discuss the Tracks website?',23,'Well yes, there is.  Have a look at [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/all-things-tracks-org-t103628.html All things tracks.org.nz]], where you can ask questions, discuss tracks, or chat about anything else relevant to the Tracks website.','','2010-01-15 12:20:12','2010-01-15 12:20:59'),(8,'Can I download the track data?',23,'Yes, there are two ways to download the track data:\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:Individual track:]] The data for each track is available for download by clicking the \"kml\" link under the track\'s map (labelled \"Download GPS path: kml\").]]\r\n[[bullet:[[bold:All tracks:]] The data for all tracks, including descriptions, in available in an [[link:http://www.gamma.net.nz/sites/default/files/all_nz_tracks.kml aggregate kml file]]. Note that this file, which is updated daily, is over 6MB.]]\r\nA kml file can be opened in a variety of applications, including [[link:http://earth.google.com/ Google Earth]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nTo upload an individual track kml to a GPS unit, the file may need to be converted to a different format â€“ the freeware application [[link:http://www.gpsbabel.org/ GPSBabel]] can probably help with the conversion.','','2010-02-10 12:54:43','2010-02-10 12:55:48');
