INSERT INTO `feature_comments` VALUES (1,3,1,'Ah that\'s because there\'s no Overview data for these old tracks. It\'s now required so won\'t show up on new ones. I will fix soon.','2009-03-17 08:53:31','2009-03-17 08:53:31'),(2,1,1,'This seems to work even though it\'s slightly clunky...','2009-03-17 08:56:30','2009-03-17 08:56:30'),(3,1,23,'The sort order of features with the same number of votes is not obvious. It doesn\'t appear to be a function of progress, Suggested/Updated time, or alphbetical order.','2009-03-17 21:38:13','2009-03-17 21:38:13'),(4,17,1,'Looks good. I like how it elegantly handles with links, nice.','2009-03-18 05:41:13','2009-03-18 05:41:13'),(6,10,1,'Good idea. I keep forgetting NZ has street view too.','2009-03-18 05:44:14','2009-03-18 05:44:14'),(7,12,1,'Good idea. I have had this in the back of my mind too.','2009-03-18 05:45:12','2009-03-18 05:45:12'),(8,19,1,'This is easy to do. I turned it off because Problems don\'t have votes and it was simpler that way.\n[[para]]\nI could add votes to the Problems too? Or release any associated votes if you move from Feature to Problem?','2009-03-18 05:48:27','2009-03-18 05:48:27'),(9,2,1,'I agree. This is probably the top \"missing\" feature for now.','2009-03-18 05:49:55','2009-03-18 05:49:55'),(10,11,1,'Yes showing the \'connecting\' tracks would be good.\n[[para]]\nI like the \'adjacent tracks\' idea. A long time ago there were 2 categories, \'connecting\' and \'nearby\' but I simplified it.','2009-03-18 05:53:43','2009-03-18 05:53:43'),(11,11,1,'I will investigate.','2009-03-18 05:54:22','2009-03-18 05:54:22'),(12,20,1,'Like so[[para]]:-(','2009-03-18 05:55:57','2009-03-18 05:55:57'),(13,18,1,'I will tidy that up. Was originally trying to make it concise but it only applies for the last comment so that is not an issue.','2009-03-18 05:57:08','2009-03-18 05:57:08'),(14,15,1,'I will look into this. I haven\'t done it yet because I need to have a good think about how it would interact with the simple text entry boxes. There are many ways to do it however and it would be good.','2009-03-18 05:58:58','2009-03-18 05:58:58'),(15,16,1,'Good idea.','2009-03-18 05:59:22','2009-03-18 05:59:22'),(16,1,1,'You\'re right, it\'s all over the place! I will need to play around with the sql.','2009-03-18 06:00:33','2009-03-18 06:00:33'),(17,14,1,'Good idea.','2009-03-18 06:01:19','2009-03-18 06:01:19'),(18,13,1,'Thanks, I will investigate. There are a couple of niggles related to this.','2009-03-18 06:04:23','2009-03-18 06:04:23'),(19,19,1,'When you view a Problem it shows 0 votes. I think I will add voting to Problems too. Much simpler code.','2009-03-18 06:05:47','2009-03-18 06:05:47'),(21,22,1,'Ok did a quick fix as this was really annoying. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. The rest of this comment is a test. ','2009-03-18 07:41:56','2009-03-18 07:41:56'),(22,22,1,':-)','2009-03-18 07:42:04','2009-03-18 07:42:04'),(23,2,1,'I have had various discussions via email on this. It is possibly a lot of work, however I could do a simple version first where the profiles are provided as images. Ultimately I would like to parse the supplied gps data (maybe with an option for \"don\'t parse this file, use my carefully tweaked data\") and produce graphs and generate basic stats from it.','2009-03-18 07:44:25','2009-03-18 07:44:25'),(24,1,1,'At next release the sort order will be by number of Votes then Updated','2009-03-18 08:25:39','2009-03-18 08:25:39'),(25,13,1,'That track link seems to be working for me?','2009-03-18 08:29:16','2009-03-18 08:29:16'),(26,13,1,'Ok have reproduced it. Fails on create, but if you edit then it fixes it. Which is why I couldn\'t see the problem you noted above.','2009-03-18 08:44:49','2009-03-18 08:44:49'),(27,5,23,'Nice.  Though as implemented why the labels light grey while the numbers are black?','2009-03-20 08:38:47','2009-03-20 08:38:47'),(28,5,1,'You\'re correct that is a bit odd. I was reusing some old css. I will change it soon.','2009-03-21 03:34:00','2009-03-21 03:34:00'),(29,20,1,'Now I can link to [[track:1]].','2009-03-21 05:54:47','2009-03-21 05:54:47'),(30,30,1,'I like this. I had a similar idea where you could choose/rank your top 3 or 5 tracks that would go into your settings/profile. This could then be used as the basis for rating tracks as you suggest.\n[[para]]\nA further idea on this which is probably getting way ahead of the current features of Tracks is users could use this info to find other riders with similar track preferences, kind social networky... maybe a future future thing!','2009-03-22 03:15:57','2009-03-22 03:15:57'),(31,27,1,'You can currently re-open a feature/problem if you were the original suggester. I will change it so anyone can re-open.','2009-03-22 03:30:53','2009-03-22 03:30:53'),(32,28,1,'The closed date will be the same as the last updated date. However I can explicitly show it on the Status line if closed, something like:[[br]]\n Closed, on 21 Mar 2009 08:36','2009-03-22 03:37:04','2009-03-22 03:37:04'),(34,29,1,'I have been having a play with this and next release will include it. However it is starting to look a bit messy. Maybe when I get the email sending thing setup ([[link:tracks.org.nz/features/21 #0021]]) it will be less necessary as you will get an email noting the change or comment?','2009-03-22 04:02:28','2009-03-22 04:02:28'),(35,27,1,'This is now working.[[para]]I think I will write a comment to indicate re-open to show a timestamp/history.','2009-03-22 05:33:43','2009-03-22 05:33:43'),(36,21,1,'See note on [[link:tracks.org.nz/features/29 #0029]].','2009-03-22 05:37:02','2009-03-22 05:37:02'),(37,30,23,'Good idea. I think it would be good if a user could rate any tracks they want to.  Their top rated tracks could then automatically be listed in their profile, if they were ever to have a public face.\n[[para]]\nI\'m a great fan of re-using existing code, and there are lots of code examples around for this sort of thing. For example, [[link:http://www.grafxsoftware.com/product.php?id=8 grafxsoftware]] offer a free star rating system. The [[link:http://rate.grafxsoftware.com/test_rate_ajax.php Ajax example]] is quite good.','2009-03-22 09:50:18','2009-03-22 09:50:18'),(38,31,23,'This feature would be good, since tracks like [[track:228]] and [[track:255]] don\'t really belong under the general track list.','2009-03-22 10:00:12','2009-03-22 10:00:12'),(40,11,59,'The problem with displaying with a lot of points on a map can be resolved by using the google maps api \"encoded polyline\". \nhttp://code.google.com/apis/maps/documentation/overlays.html#Encoded_Polylines\n\nThis allows the lines to be simplified when zoomed out which improves performance on maps with lots of lines.\n\nThis would involve parsing the kml to produce the encoded polyline.','2009-03-22 15:36:35','2009-03-22 15:36:35'),(41,23,1,'Yes this would be nice. I am just starting to use tinyMCE on another project so will investigate more. Hopefully I can add custom buttons for our track/area/region links.','2009-03-24 05:08:28','2009-03-24 05:08:28'),(43,32,23,'When logged in you should see an Edit and a Delete option for each report (for the first 7 days after a report is made). Something like this: \r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/Reports.png:Report example:201:349]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nDoes it look different in Chrome?','2009-03-24 19:26:02','2009-03-24 19:26:02'),(45,32,1,'I have tidied up the above on the Starfish page. But I will investigate if there is a problem... thanks for the feedback.','2009-03-25 04:01:50','2009-03-25 04:01:50'),(46,11,23,'I had a play with encoded polylines a few months ago. At that time they improved the map performance, but still often didn\'t work very well.\n[[para]]\nHowever, it seems that the API\'s performance has since been improved significantly. I\'ve mocked up [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/multiTracks/multiTrackTest.htm an example]] to show how multiple encoded polylines display on a map. This is just a test of a few ideas, rather than a firm proposal.\n[[para]]\nThe most important aspect is that it works, and hence drawing multiple tracks on a map looks to be feasible.','2009-03-26 19:25:47','2009-03-26 19:25:47'),(47,11,59,'Another approach to this problem could be to use the google earth browser plugin. I have not had a opportunity to test this but it may be worth investigating: http://code.google.com/apis/earth/','2009-03-27 10:10:55','2009-03-27 10:10:55'),(48,11,23,'Tracks already includes the Google Earth browser plugin - it is the \"Earth\" map type button at the top-right of each map. \n[[para]]\nUnfortunately, the Google Earth plugin is currently broken, as it won\'t display the track lines.  This seems to be a problem with Google\'s API rather than anything we\'ve done.','2009-03-27 11:14:37','2009-03-27 11:14:37'),(49,35,1,'I have turned off the rain charts because metservice has changed their page to use lots of javascript and it\'s not scraping the data correctly anymore. I haven\'t looked into it further but I think they are trying to protect their data as I think they also sell it and don\'t want people stealing it.','2009-04-05 07:38:28','2009-04-05 07:38:28'),(50,11,102,'Looks like the Google Earth API is fixed - I can see the tracks in \"Earth\" map type now, but you don\'t get the nice labelling when you scroll over them.\n\nNice encoding example Ian, did you drop each track into the HTML form encoder or download their Java encoder?','2009-04-19 09:44:44','2009-04-19 09:44:44'),(52,11,23,'Graham - yes, the Earth API has been fixed, so it shows the tracks again. However, it is slow to load the 37 tracks in my example and, as you say, the labels don\'t work.\n[[para]]\nAs for encoding, I used [[link:http://facstaff.unca.edu/mcmcclur/GoogleMaps/EncodePolyline/encodeForm.html this form]]. There are also scripts available at that site for automatically encoding tracks, which may be more useful than the manual approach I used for the example.','2009-04-19 21:30:00','2009-04-19 21:30:00'),(53,40,23,'Don wrote a script that collates the descriptions and gps data for each track into a single Google Earth kml file.  [[link:http://github.com/donovan/tracks/tree/master The code]] and the [[link:http://github.com/donovan/tracks/blob/2734a494d20ea11b3b5293898c104828bd817257/tracks.kml collated kml file]] are available if you want to have a look.\n[[para]]\nIs this the sort of thing you\'re thinking of?','2009-04-21 13:14:43','2009-04-21 13:14:43'),(54,33,23,'Yes please. I couple of times I\'ve messed up the content or formatting of a comment and had to delete it and then try again. Being able to edit a comment would be much better.','2009-04-21 13:16:44','2009-04-21 13:16:44'),(55,40,63,'Graham: check this out:\n\nhttp://www.gamma.net.nz/kml/tracks.kml\n\nfeel free to check the code out from github and contribute Its perl not php though.','2009-04-21 15:52:53','2009-04-21 15:52:53'),(59,40,102,'That\'s ideal! You\'re a legend. Will it run on the tracks.org.nz server? [[para]]If so (and I\'m guessing you may already be planning this) my suggestion would be: [[br]](a) implement to get it to check for new tracks at an interval and re-build if new tracks found, and (b) get the script to zip the file and rename to .kmz to save on traffic (actually this applies to all of your .kml files). [[para]]It could then be a link on the homepage, either as a downloadable .kmz, or better (if you\'re happy with the traffic implications) a .kml that calls the latest version of the .kmz from tracks.org.nz as a <Link> whenever it\'s been updated. Traffic in the latter case shouldn\'t be too bad as long as the .kml specifies the <refreshMode>onChange.[[para]]Is this feasible? Are you planning it? Happy to help, but you seem onto it! Nice.','2009-04-22 17:19:05','2009-04-22 17:19:05'),(60,12,23,'A couple of new videos have been added to [[track:78]]/[[track:79]] and [[track:77]].','2009-04-25 00:47:10','2009-04-25 00:47:10'),(61,11,1,'Ian, that\'s awesome! I will probably start work on this by using your examples and code. Is this ok by you?','2009-04-27 01:09:56','2009-04-27 01:09:56'),(62,40,1,'Hey Don, that\'s looking cool on Google Earth![[para]]\nA feature I would like to add one day is to have an xml interface to some (most?) data, particularly the track paths. I would need to look into this further but it should allow for getting the data in a friendlier and more standard way.','2009-04-27 01:25:44','2009-04-27 01:25:44'),(63,26,1,'Good idea. I will create an entirely separate website that can be a staging environment (mostly live now http://stage.tracks.org.nz). This will be almost like production and will use the production data. I will put a banner across the top so you get regular reminders that this is not production...\n[[para]]\nBefore I do a prod release I will copy the prod data across to stage.tracks.org.nz. This will also give me a nice release test area too.','2009-04-27 16:09:22','2009-04-27 16:09:22'),(64,36,1,'Good idea. This is reasonably easy to do. Could also output PDFs maybe.','2009-04-28 01:05:35','2009-04-28 01:05:35'),(66,11,23,'Jonny, feel free to use the code from my example â€“ that\'s what it is for.\n[[para]]\nI\'ve been working on a [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/multitracks3/multiTrackTest.htm further example]] that adds/changes some features, specifically:[[br]]\n- uses xml data files, extended to include more data.[[br]]\n- the xml could easily be extended further â€“ perhaps consistent with your 27 Apr comment on [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/features/40 Issue 40]]?[[br]]\n- the lines on the map are formatted to reflect the track condition and grade.  That is, the track colour is a function of grade and the track line width is a function of condition (narrow for single track, wide for roads).[[br]]\n- Earth map type interaction is possible, but it is currently incomplete.','2009-04-28 01:51:42','2009-04-28 01:51:42'),(68,11,1,'I have put up the first cut onto Stage (stage.tracks.org.nz)\n[[para]]\nCurrent functionality:[[br]]\n- multiple tracks shown per page[[br]]\n- encoded data held in db[[br]]\n- current prod kml files will get parsed at prod release time[[br]]\n- uploading a new kml file will encode new path[[br]]\n- multiple paths per kml file supported (sub-path names are currently lost, I will fix this)','2009-04-28 04:08:57','2009-04-28 04:08:57'),(69,37,1,'This seems to be a bug in Google Maps. I have disabled it for now as the work-a-rounds are hacky. I will leave this report open so I revisit in the future.','2009-04-28 05:11:52','2009-04-28 05:11:52'),(70,32,1,'Hmm something strange on Chrome. Maybe script.aculo.us or some other javascript thing?','2009-04-28 06:13:32','2009-04-28 06:13:32'),(71,11,23,'I had a quick play with the stage.tracks.org.nz version.  Looks good so far.  A couple of observations:[[br]]\n- it doesn\'t cope well with tracks that have markers, as neither the track nor the map controls are shown.  eg. [[link:http://stage.tracks.org.nz/track/show/78 Spoonhill]].[[br]]\n- I\'m concerned that my [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/multitracks3/multiTrackTest.htm further example]] is trying to show too much information at once. ie. the proliferation of colours is a bit ugly.  One possibility would be to only have two colours (main and adjacent tracks - like example 1), and have the line widths vary by track type.  Then on mouseover show a line colour for the selected track that relates to its difficulty.  Or something like that.','2009-04-28 13:26:10','2009-04-28 13:26:10'),(72,11,1,'Some more (slow) progress on Stage:\n[[para]]\nFirst of all thanks for the cool examples Ian, they rock!\n[[para]]\n- I have used a little of v3 in the current iteration (mostly mouse-over of tracks, with bug: each sub-line has the main track length).[[br]]\n- I might leave adding multiple colours/line widths to a future version[[br]]\n- sub-path names are included[[br]]\n- markers are still being lost. Are these just the youtube videos? I can add an optional media section that has video and picture links[[br]]\n- I want to move to a system where a \"track\" can be made up of multiple smaller tracks, nearly there now. Each of these smaller tracks would have their own length and profile.[[br]]\n- The xml output idea would not use files but an api type system, seems to be the way these days. Input files for track paths should be via kml or gpx I think...[[br]]','2009-05-17 05:35:37','2009-05-17 05:35:37'),(73,25,1,'I would like to add sub-section (tab?) to each track that allows for optional collections of media; pictures, videos, other?[[para]]\nIdea: you can flag one of the images as \"key\" and this 1 image would also display on the main track page','2009-05-17 05:41:18','2009-05-17 05:41:18'),(74,11,23,'I\'ve added some more pieces of the puzzle in [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/multitracks4/overlay.htm another example]]. This one uses image overlays and a few other tricks to get around the limitations of the Google Earth map type. The result is that the 2D and 3D map types interact in more-or-less the same way. There are some quirks though, as noted in the bullet points.\n[[para]]\nAs for markers, there are a few variations scattered around, eg. [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/track/show/278 Mt Climie]] has a couple of peak markers.','2009-05-18 21:28:55','2009-05-18 21:28:55'),(75,25,23,'The HighSlide tool that I used in my example is very flexible, with lots of options.  There are [[link:http://highslide.com/index.htm many possible variations]] - such as [[link:http://highslide.com/examples/gallery-in-page.html gallery in page]] and [[link:http://highslide.com/examples/gallery-thumbstrip-above.html image that becomes a gallery]].','2009-05-18 21:41:37','2009-05-18 21:41:37'),(76,11,23,'Another issue to consider: in a few places I\'ve used different colours to indicate different track access types - for example, \'Foot only\' for the middle section of [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/track/show/158 Duck Creek]], or track sections under construction for [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/track/show/67 Car Parts Extension]]. It would be good to retain this sort of distinction and apply it consistently (not that I always have).','2009-05-19 07:37:44','2009-05-19 07:37:44'),(78,25,23,'For the \"key\" image idea, do you mean something like [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/gallerySingle/gallery/gallery.html this example]]?  This is almost identical to my previous example, with the following changes:[[br]]\n- CSS:  changed style for slideshowcontainer[[br]]\n- CSS:  changed style for slide[[br]]\n- HTML: put z-index on first image so it is on top of the others.','2009-05-19 09:50:08','2009-05-19 09:50:08'),(79,25,23,'I was just wondering if it is possible to combine images and videos in the same slideshow.  Turns out to be quite straightforward, as shown in this [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/galleryMulti/gallery.html multimedia example]].\n[[para]]\nThis might be a way of organising multiple YouTube videos, rather than embedding them directly in the webpage.','2009-05-27 21:35:24','2009-05-27 21:35:24'),(80,31,74,'Great idea. Thinking about longer connecting rides e.g. from Polhill to Wrights to Makara, or Mt Albert loop.','2009-05-28 19:18:02','2009-05-28 19:18:02'),(81,8,1,'Track AKAs are clunky so I have created a new bug for this, #0041','2009-06-03 11:34:32','2009-06-03 11:34:32'),(82,33,1,'This is a test comment that I edited.','2009-06-03 12:00:26','2009-06-03 12:00:40'),(83,11,1,'I have implemented some of this. To make sure it is continued refer to [[link:tracks.org.nz/feature/45 feature 0045]].','2009-06-03 12:06:31','2009-06-03 12:06:31'),(84,45,1,'(From #0011, Ian)[[br]]\nI\'ve added some more pieces of the puzzle in [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/multitracks4/overlay.htm another example]]. This one uses image overlays and a few other tricks to get around the limitations of the Google Earth map type. The result is that the 2D and 3D map types interact in more-or-less the same way. There are some quirks though, as noted in the bullet points.\n[[para]]\nAs for markers, there are a few variations scattered around, eg. [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/track/show/278 Mt Climie]] has a couple of peak markers.','2009-06-03 12:37:01','2009-06-03 12:37:01'),(85,45,1,'(from #0011, Ian)[[br]]\nAnother issue to consider: in a few places I\'ve used different colours to indicate different track access types - for example, \'Foot only\' for the middle section of [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/track/show/158 Duck Creek]], or track sections under construction for [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/track/show/67 Car Parts Extension]]. It would be good to retain this sort of distinction and apply it consistently (not that I always have).','2009-06-03 12:37:25','2009-06-03 12:37:25'),(86,43,1,'I have some ideas around this. It will tie into the News feature idea. See [[link:tracks.org.nz/features/38 News feature]].','2009-06-03 12:41:33','2009-06-03 12:42:12'),(87,38,1,'Some ideas on this, \"news\" items would be:[[para]]\no Site update[[br]]\no Track report[[br]]\no New track[[br]]\no New area[[br]]\no New feature/bug\n[[para]]\nMain (home) page would have aggregate of all news from each region plus site stuff. Each region page would have news section. These news sections would replace/enhance the current \"Track Reports\" section.','2009-06-03 12:45:21','2009-06-03 12:45:57'),(88,45,23,'v2.160 of the Google Maps API has substantially improved the integration of 2D and 3D map types, as discussed in the [[link:http://googlegeodevelopers.blogspot.com/2009/05/hey-maps-api-and-earth-api-developers.html Google Geo Developers Blog]].  This should greatly simplify the coding needed for interactive multi-track maps that are consistent across the 2D and 3D map types.\n[[para]]\nHowever, API v2.160 has a bug that prevents it from working properly, so we\'ll have to wait for Google to fix it before the 3D track interaction can progress.\n[[para]]\nIn the meantime, any thoughts on whether to display the mouseover track information using HTML (as currently implemented) or using image overlays (which are probably easier for the 3D map type)?','2009-06-05 11:52:40','2009-06-05 11:52:40'),(89,12,23,'The ability to embed YouTube videos is great.  The feature seems to allow the possibility of adding other media types, so I suggest Vorb videos as a potential addition to the list. A popup menu at the bottom-right of each video provides the code.  For example, see [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/makara-peak-skills-area-grand-opening-t58453.html Makara Skills Area Grand Opening]].','2009-06-09 20:36:32','2009-06-09 20:37:01'),(90,52,23,'If the Regional Council boundaries are a bit coarse, then perhaps the [[link:http://www.metservice.co.nz/public/aboutThisSite/regional-area-map.html regions used by the MetService]] would be better?  There are more regions, each of which is a more manageable size.','2009-06-30 20:41:16','2009-06-30 20:41:16'),(91,54,1,'Nice. I have seen this calculation before. I like the \"adjustment factor\" idea too.','2009-08-06 16:26:40','2009-08-06 16:26:40'),(92,56,1,'This is a good idea and is similar to [[link:tracks.org.nz/features/31 Feature 0031]], but different enough that it sould be reviewed with [[link:tracks.org.nz/features/31 Feature 0031]] when it is developed.','2009-08-06 16:28:45','2009-08-06 16:30:20'),(93,31,1,'See also [[link:tracks.org.nz/features/56 Feature 0056]].','2009-08-06 16:29:40','2009-08-06 16:30:00'),(94,52,1,'This is absolutely required. The home page is becoming a bit of a mess. The order of the Regions needs some attention too. Alphabetical doesn\'t seem right for that level.','2009-08-06 16:32:43','2009-08-06 16:32:43'),(95,57,1,'You are right, broken!','2009-08-06 16:50:22','2009-08-06 16:50:22'),(96,32,1,'Seems to work now on Chrome, on my Mac anyway. Not sure if I updated since, oh er 28 April...','2009-08-06 16:54:47','2009-08-06 16:54:47'),(97,51,1,'Thanks, I will look into this.','2009-08-06 16:57:32','2009-08-06 16:57:32'),(98,52,23,'Ording the list of regions from north to south would seem reasonable, and would tie in well with a map of NZ.','2009-08-06 20:13:14','2009-08-06 20:13:14'),(99,58,23,'The Google Maps API includes functionality to draw and edit polylines â€“ see [[link:http://gmaps-samples.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/poly/mymapstoolbar.html Google\'s example]].','2009-08-06 20:15:51','2009-08-06 20:15:51'),(100,59,23,'Sorry, that\'s my fault.  When I upgraded the multi-track example code to the new Google Maps interface I simply applied the default user interface behavior, which includes scroll wheel zoom.  It can be disabled by adding one line of code to mapMain.js, between getting the default options and setting the interface, like so:\n[[para]]\nvar uiOptions = map.getDefaultUI();  // Get default options[[br]]\nuiOptions.zoom.scrollwheel = false;  // Disable scroll wheel zoom[[br]]\nmap.setUI(uiOptions);  // Set the map\'s interface','2009-08-06 20:18:16','2009-08-06 20:18:47'),(101,59,1,'Awesome thanks!','2009-08-07 03:05:23','2009-08-07 03:05:23'),(102,50,1,'Yuck, this is still happening.','2009-08-07 03:16:39','2009-08-07 03:16:39'),(103,50,1,'Got it behaving better, next release.','2009-08-07 04:55:20','2009-08-07 04:55:20'),(104,44,1,'Cool thanks.','2009-08-07 05:02:04','2009-08-07 05:02:04'),(105,32,1,'Also works on Chrome on PC, will close.','2009-08-07 07:25:09','2009-08-07 07:25:09'),(106,50,1,'Seems good now, best to confirm tho...','2009-08-07 07:27:15','2009-08-07 07:27:15'),(107,12,1,'How is this?\n\n[[para]]\n[[h2:YouTube]]\n[[media:youtube:6kxDxLAjkO8]]\n\n[[para]]\n[[h2:Vorb]]\n[[media:vorb:65226]]\n\n[[br]]','2009-08-10 04:19:25','2009-08-10 04:19:34'),(108,12,1,'See the FAQ for \"how to\".','2009-08-10 04:20:48','2009-08-10 04:20:48'),(109,61,1,'Hmm, strange. I see them on Firefox 3.5 on Mac which makes me suspect a Google issue with your setup. Which browser (and version) and what OS? Also is it when viewing, editing, or both?','2009-08-12 15:40:39','2009-08-12 15:40:39'),(110,62,1,'Oops, cheers! Tweaked column width slightly, will be fixed in next release.','2009-08-14 02:35:37','2009-08-14 02:35:37'),(111,63,1,'I have a fix for #2 above.[[br]]\nBut I can\'t reproduce #1... seems to work for me.','2009-08-14 04:18:12','2009-08-14 04:18:24'),(112,63,23,'I just added Jungle Scout as an \'Adjacent Track\' for [[track:75]], yet the \'Last modified\' date is still 7 December 2008.','2009-08-14 08:56:00','2009-08-14 08:56:00'),(113,45,23,'An information box is displayed upon the mouseover event for a track line on a map. The box includes a \"Length\" field, which shows the total length of the track. However, this is misleading for tracks that consist of multiple segments. It would be better if the length of the specific track segment were displayed instead of the total length. \n[[para]]\nGiven that the server now calculates the track length automatically (thanks to [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/features/54 Feature #0054]]), some of the functionality required to implement this feature already exists.','2009-08-16 08:57:19','2009-08-16 08:58:30'),(114,52,1,'I have done an implementation of this, now live. On the issue of defining regions I think I will just let it run for a while and see what happens.','2009-08-18 09:33:52','2009-08-18 09:33:52'),(115,52,23,'Nice. The ability to zoom in/out might be useful if there are several fairly small regions closely packed, but it isn\'t needed at the moment.','2009-08-18 10:30:05','2009-08-18 10:30:05'),(116,52,1,'Can do. Do you think the Areas of a Region should be represented like this too? Easy to re-use the polygons thing.','2009-08-18 14:30:36','2009-08-18 14:30:36'),(117,45,1,'Good point. This should be easy to do.','2009-08-18 14:31:53','2009-08-18 14:31:53'),(118,52,23,'It would be nice to have the Region maps show Areas as polygons, just like on the home page map.\n[[para]]\nThat raises the question of how to create the polygons? Ideally they would be drawn/edited directly on the Region map â€“ like drawing tracks directly, as in [[feature:58]]. However, that might be a lot of work and possibly not worth it. An alternative would be to upload a polygon drawn in Google Earth.\n[[para]]\nOne issue that might arise is where an area is entirely within another area â€“ for example, [[area:27]] might be contained within [[area:102]].\n[[para]]\nAlso, some areas are very small â€“ for example, [[area:6]] â€“ so may not display well when zoomed out to show a whole Region.\n[[para]]\nAs a refinement of the home page map (and possibly Region maps), it would be good to display the Region name on mouseover. The Google Maps API doesn\'t seem to have that functionality natively, but various extensions provide it â€“ such as [[link:http://www.svennerberg.com/2009/03/announcing-maptooltip/ Map Tooltip]].','2009-08-18 20:39:46','2009-08-18 20:41:29'),(119,52,1,'Thanks for the Map Tooltip reference, I looked at the gpolygon API and there didn\'t seem a way to do it. This is obviously a problem others have had.\n[[para]]\nHave a play on stage.tracks.org.nz around adding new region polygons - try adding a new region and editing an existing one (you should now be able to add regions too BTW). Is this drawing similar to what you would do in Google Earth?\n[[para]]\nYes some areas are small, maybe they could be merged later? It might be more obvious if we have this visual view of areas.\n[[para]]\nI would think that areas wouldn\'t be inside other areas, maybe this is wrong?','2009-08-19 05:30:56','2009-08-19 05:31:42'),(120,52,23,'Cool. I had a play with editing the Area polygons on stage.tracks.org.nz. Seems to work well.\n[[para]]\nThe \'Auto-fit region\' function looks intriguing, but what does it do?\n[[para]]\nI tried to add an area, but it failed with the error message: \'NoMethodError in Region#new\'.\n[[para]]\nI agree that having an area inside another area wouldn\'t usually make sense, but there might be some circumstances where it does. If so, then the Google Maps polygons can contain holes â€“ as in [[link:http://facstaff.unca.edu/mcmcclur/GoogleMaps/EncodePolyline/examplePolygons.html this example]].','2009-08-19 07:43:58','2009-08-19 07:43:58'),(121,52,1,'The auto-fit just changes the zoom and lat/lng to centre and fit the shape in the window.\n[[para]]\nOops that error is a real bug! I will fix asap.\n[[para]]\nAt present my polygons can only have one \"path\". That pentagon example uses two. If you draw a complicated polygon shape that overlaps itself you get holes. It\'s a sort of exclusive-or for what\'s in the shape. Also regions can overlap or be contained right now, however I\'m not sure which one would be clickable, possibly the last one that was mouse-over event enabled?','2009-08-20 03:47:30','2009-08-20 03:47:30'),(122,52,1,'Should be good now. Stage fixed too.','2009-08-20 04:57:51','2009-08-20 04:57:51'),(123,52,23,'That all seems to work well, subject to some tweaks:\n[[bullet:In the Stage environment creating a region failed because I gave it the name \'Taranaki (test)\' - it didn\'t like the brackets, I suppose.]]\n[[bullet:When creating a (more reasonably named) region it would help if the other regions\' polygons are shown, like they are when editing a region\'s polygon.]]\n[[bullet:It would be helpful to have a \'Cancel\' option in the \'Edit region order\' function, in case the user changes their mind or messes it up and wants to try again.]]\n[[para]]\nIt would also be good to have a \'snap-to\' type behaviour so that the vertices of adjacent polygons are nicely aligned. - though that\'s very much in the nice-to-have category.','2009-08-20 13:38:21','2009-08-20 13:38:21'),(124,52,1,'Good ideas above. I will investigate the brackets, probably a bug.[[para]]\nI\'m not sure how much work for the snap-to feature. The polygon drawing/editing is simple gmap polygon feature. Do you know of an example where snap-to is used?[[para]]\nI had a play with the tooltips. It only works on older versions of the gmap2 spec (2.149), currently 2.172 and 3.11... I am using the mouseOutTolerance feature from a more recent version to make the polygon hover more snappy. I am also looking at one from [[link:http://www.bdcc.co.uk/Gmaps/BdccGmapBits.htm Bill Chadwick]] but it\'s also not so straight forward.','2009-08-28 02:35:53','2009-08-28 02:35:53'),(125,52,23,'Yes, tooltips seem to be problematic.\n[[para]]\nMeanwhile, here\'s an example of [[link:http://www.rfocus.com/ex/Snap.aspx snap-to]].  The code is obscured and it uses a custom method for drawing polygons which has been superceded by the natice API functionality.  In any case, the method seems fairly straightforward, albeit probably involving a fair bit of bruteforce processing.','2009-08-28 07:46:49','2009-08-28 07:46:49'),(126,2,1,'Been playing a little with the [[link:http://code.google.com/apis/visualization/documentation/gallery/areachart.html Google Visualization API area charts]]. Looks promising and works in several browsers - tried FF, Safari, Chrome, IE 7&8.\n[[para]]\nNow I just need to figure out nicely parsing the data from the GPX files (that I mostly don\'t have...) using some of the tools I have found online. However I am getting some weird crashes using the amazing [[link:http://www.gpsbabel.org/ gpsbabel]], probably user error or a poorly formed example data file.','2009-09-03 07:49:04','2009-09-03 07:49:44'),(127,2,23,'Google Visualization looks to have the same limitation as the various Flash-based graphics packages - ie. the x-axis data for area charts must be in uniformly increments. This is awkward, but not impossible, to work with. Apart from that, it looks good.\n[[para]]\nFor the chart source data, it would be good to allow kml format as well as gpx. This would enable editing of the gpx, for example in Google Earth, to remove spurious data from the GPS log before uploading.','2009-09-03 21:44:08','2009-09-03 21:44:08'),(128,2,23,'When I say kml format, I don\'t necessarily mean the kml file that contains the track data - I mean a separate kml file containing data for the profile chart. This is because the coordinate data required to make an accurate map isn\'t necessarily the same as the GPS data that can be used to create a profile chart, since the raw GPS log almost always requires editing to make it look good.\n[[para]]\nThe distinction between track coordinates for the map and altitude data for the elevation profile chart will become more stark when the hand drawn track feature is implemented (feature [[feature:0058]]).','2009-09-04 07:30:38','2009-09-04 07:30:38'),(129,52,1,'I think this feature is mostly done. I have created two new features to track the extra items above:[[br]]\n[[bullet:[[feature:66]] for tooltips]]\n[[bullet:[[feature:67]] for snap-to]]','2009-09-06 03:42:24','2009-09-06 03:42:43'),(130,65,1,'Oh, thanks. I\'ve been starting to rationalise the various js files and I\'ve broken it, will fix soon.','2009-09-06 03:49:24','2009-09-06 03:51:28'),(131,68,1,'Hmm good idea. This might take Tracks back to its MTB roots.[[para]]\nIt would be a logged-in only feature with a user selectable default. I will have to think about just how it would work in terms of hiding stuff.','2009-09-07 11:32:48','2009-09-07 11:32:48'),(132,64,1,'Yes can do that.','2009-09-08 13:02:18','2009-09-08 13:02:18'),(133,36,1,'From Jay\'s suggested feature [[feature:55]] (which I have closed as a duplicate):[[para]]\nHi guys I often use the description and map to help navigate to riding spots in the Welly region that I haven\'t been to. I think it would be a valuable feature if you were able to print out the track description textbox and the map. At the moment the print command will print out about 5-7 pages per track. It starts out with the navigator bar, then the updates then the track description. The map doesn\'t print at all. I think a simple 1-2 page print set up would be awesome. Hey thanks for this site. It is brilliant!','2009-09-13 08:16:43','2009-09-13 08:16:43'),(134,55,1,'I will close this as a duplicate of [[feature:36]]. I have copied this description as a comment into it.','2009-09-13 08:19:40','2009-09-13 08:19:40'),(135,36,1,'Bum. It seems that you cannot print the Google satellite maps at all, street view only. I can still make a much nicer printable version of the other stuff.','2009-09-13 08:22:23','2009-09-13 08:22:42'),(136,36,1,'Ah but it looks like I can with V3 of Google maps. Now need to investigate if I can use all the other map features with V3, it\'s still kinda new. They are focusing on speed over features initially for V3.','2009-09-13 08:32:17','2009-09-13 08:32:17'),(137,36,23,'In what sense do you mean that \"you cannot print the Google satellite maps at all\" â€“ as a technical issue or a licence issue?\n[[para]]\nThe simplest way of solving the technical issue is to change the CSS link to be something like: media=\"screen, print\".  It ain\'t pretty (eg. a map that crosses a page break will only partially print), but it does print the satellite images.\n[[para]]\nMy reading of the [[link:http://www.google.com/permissions/geoguidelines.html#print Google Permissions]] is that printing of the type contempated here is OK, so there shouldn\'t be any licence issues.\n[[para]]\nAs for API v3, my impression is that it is targetted at displaying maps on mobile devices, so doesn\'t have most of the functionality of v2 (yet). In particular, polylines haven\'t been implemented â€“ which makes it useless for the Tracks maps.','2009-09-13 12:55:13','2009-09-13 12:55:52'),(138,39,162,'The Canterbury Mountain Bike Club has a simple table of tracks. Clicking on the column headers resorts the information.\r\n\r\nThat way people can sort via track grade, ride distance, and region...\r\n\r\nAllows seasoned mountain bikers to select the longest, hardest ride... and beginners to avoid the same death traps.','2009-09-26 13:19:30','2009-09-26 13:19:30'),(139,70,1,'I will add new media types as they are needed.','2009-09-27 03:42:12','2009-09-27 03:42:12'),(140,69,1,'Yes, easy change.','2009-09-27 03:42:56','2009-09-27 03:43:20'),(141,72,162,'And if this site is also being used for walking and running tracks as well - Do the tracks need a seperate gradings for each activity.... As I can imagine that an intermediate walking track is going to be a difficult biking track....','2009-09-28 22:41:53','2009-09-28 22:41:53'),(142,72,23,'As far as I know, the grades aren\'t defined anywhere on Tracks. My interpretation is that they align with Mountain Bike New Zealand\'s [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/parks-and-recreation/activity-finder/mtn-biking/mtb-grading-print.pdf grading system]].\n[[para]]\nI agree that track grades for walking and biking aren\'t necessarily the same, though it isn\'t clear how to deal with that.\n[[para]]\nPerhaps a new [[link:http://tracks.org.nz/faq FAQ]] would be in order.','2009-09-29 09:41:13','2009-09-29 09:41:13'),(143,72,23,'I\'ve added a new [[link:http://www.tracks.org.nz/faq FAQ]] Q&A that replicates the Mountain Bike NZ grading system.','2009-09-30 09:51:33','2009-09-30 09:51:33'),(144,71,1,'Oops, I broke that. I will remove the user-settable video size as it\'s causing this problem and is not so simple to fix. Videos will remain at the larger setting.','2009-10-01 06:17:12','2009-10-01 06:17:32'),(145,2,59,'I just saw the height graphs on this site.\nhttp://www.journeyplanner.org.nz/\n\nVery nice that they are interactive, mouse over heightmap shows location on map.\n\nAny idea what they are using to do this?\n\nSeems that the height graph uses canvas tag I am guessing it is SVG.\n\nIt would be great if this was done with some library that we could just \'plugin\' to tracks.org\n\nAlso they must be getting the height data from somewhere...','2009-10-04 18:29:13','2009-10-04 18:29:13'),(146,34,1,'Easy to fix. Can\'t beat reading the API...','2009-10-14 17:01:41','2009-10-14 17:01:52'),(147,36,1,'Ok that was my mistake. The maps do print. I have a simple printable version in dev that I am playing with, wont be long...','2009-10-14 19:27:12','2009-10-14 19:27:12'),(148,76,23,'This is very similar to [[feature:0068]].  Perhaps the two feature requests could be merged?','2010-01-13 19:35:36','2010-01-13 19:35:36'),(149,40,59,'Don\'s script no longer works as site rearrangement broke the screen scraping he was doing. \n[[para]]\nI agree that ideally there should be a standardized interface to pull info out of the tracks site.\n[[para]]\nI\'d be happy to help out with this feature. If I could check tracks.org code out from somewhere I could work on a local development copy and submit a patch for you to test.\n[[para]]\nJonny, does that sound ok to you?','2010-01-14 14:50:52','2010-01-15 20:42:27'),(150,68,59,'Merging 0076 with this request.\n[[para]]\nThinking about it some more, would be nice if the filter was generic, so could filter on all fields.\n[[para]]\neg. Say I am only interested in MTB single track of intermediate difficulty. I\'d like to be able to filter on those criteria. ','2010-01-14 14:57:16','2010-01-14 14:57:16'),(151,76,59,'oops didn\'t see 0068, canceling this one.','2010-01-14 14:57:28','2010-01-14 14:57:28'),(152,74,1,'Nice. This will not be hard to do. Cheers!','2010-01-15 10:26:52','2010-01-15 10:26:52'),(153,80,23,'That\'s a good idea.  I\'ll have a look at stringing together the component tracks into an aggregate Puke Ariki track.','2010-01-19 22:23:10','2010-01-19 22:23:10'),(154,80,23,'Done.  See [[track:849]].','2010-01-20 19:37:47','2010-01-20 19:37:47'),(155,80,193,'Hi Thank u for doing that. Are there plans to do similar with other tracks that may form a long route. Have noticed there are some in the Eastbourne region.','2010-01-24 17:33:35','2010-01-24 17:33:35'),(156,82,59,'I\'d also like to see this feature. |It would make navigating maps easier especially now that there are several tracks per map often covering a large area.','2010-01-24 18:38:10','2010-01-24 18:38:10'),(157,80,23,'There are a couple of feature requests around that functionality â€“ see [[feature:0031]] and [[feature:0056]].\n[[para]]\nIf you\'re happy that this feature request is complete, then please close it (Edit, then change the Status to Closed).\n[[para]]\nMeanwhile, there\'s a [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/all-things-tracks-org-t103628.html thread on Vorb]] for discussion of stuff relating to the Track website that\'s outside specific feature requests.','2010-01-24 19:45:49','2010-01-24 19:46:10'),(158,82,23,'Small tweak: [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/fullscreen-v2/fullscreen.html version 2]] uses an icon instead of a button for toggling between full screen and normal size.','2010-01-25 16:25:57','2010-01-25 16:25:57'),(159,74,23,'As an experiment to see how many tracks the Google Maps API can handle, I\'ve put together a [[link:http://iod.freehostia.com/tracks/howmanytracks/overview.html set of test cases]].\n[[para]]\nAs the number of simultaneously displayed tracks increases, the browser can become sluggish â€“ especially when zooming in/out. Firefox generally performs much better than Internet Explorer. The speed of the computer also matters. For example:\n[[bullet:On a fast PC, running Firefox 3.5.6, 800+ tracks is a bit slow to redraw when zooming, but otherwise performs well.]]\n[[bullet:On a slower laptop PC running Firefox 3.5.6, the limit for reasonable performance is around 100 tracks.]]\n[[bullet:On the same laptop but using IE 7, 50 tracks would be about the limit of acceptable performance.]]','2010-01-30 13:57:02','2010-01-30 13:57:46'),(160,40,59,'Script updated and on github. KML is now here: [[link:http://www.gamma.net.nz/sites/default/files/all_nz_tracks.kml all tracks in one KML file]]','2010-02-10 20:53:11','2010-02-10 20:55:23'),(161,84,1,'Maybe a \"history\" section?','2010-03-23 09:41:13','2010-03-23 09:41:13'),(162,2,23,'Google have just introduced an elevation profiling service that integrates with the maps.  See [[link:http://googlegeodevelopers.blogspot.com/2010/03/aint-no-mountain-high-enough.html Google\'s blog]] and the [[link:http://code.google.com/apis/maps/documentation/elevation/ Elevation Web Service Developer\'s Guide]].\n[[para]]\nGoogle\'s examples use their own charting API, though that doesn\'t appear to be a requirement.  A useful bit of functionality, shown in the blog\'s example, is that the elevation chart and the map interact so that the location of an elevation point is shown on the map using a marker.','2010-03-26 13:01:07','2010-03-26 13:01:07'),(163,87,1,'If it\'s within a week you should be able to delete a report you created. Otherwise simply add a new update with the new details.','2010-05-06 13:44:19','2010-05-06 13:44:19'),(164,87,1,'If it\'s a specific report that you really want removed send me a note at [[link:mailto:info@tracks.org.nz info@tracks.org.nz]]','2010-05-11 16:02:50','2010-05-11 16:03:26');
