INSERT INTO `tracks` VALUES (1,'Koru',1,'','Main track into the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park.','This is the main entry to the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park, from the main car park on South Karori Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe preferred entry is across a bridge (added in March 2009) accessible from the southern end of the car park (head past the toilet block). The bridge at the northern end of the car park (past the shelter) is an exit for [[track:53]] and [[track:22]].  Alternative entries include \"Koru wet feet\", which crosses the stream without the aid of a bridge, or by dropping down from [[track:53]] where it emerges from the bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is a relatively gentle climb up a series of switchbacks and rolling bush-clad hills.  Several of the switchbacks can be bypassed by climbing the very steep [[track:117]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the 2.0km point, on a sweeping left-hand corner, there is a short connecting track to [[track:8]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nA further 0.5km along, at about the 2.5km point, there is a marked intersection with a short connecting track to [[track:21]] and the [[track:54]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6691202]]','Starts at the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park\'s main car park on South Karori Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:2]] and several other tracks.','Strictly speaking this track is called \"The Koru\", though it is generally known simply as \"Koru\".','3.026',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-10 18:24:49',23,'-41.298687','174.718430',16,2,1,1,1,'2010-01-12 15:03:08','calc',5),(2,'Sally Alley',1,'','Sweet single track between [[track:1]] and [[track:3]].','There are a couple of short connectors from [[track:2]] to [[track:51]], as shown on the map (zoom in to see them clearly). The second connector, which is sign-posted at the [[track:51]] end, is only 50m from the western end of the [[track:19]].\r\n[[media:youtube:8oXeMZXw_18]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6730799]]','Starts from the top of [[track:1]], at an intersection with several other tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on [[track:20]], directly opposite the eastern end of [[track:3]].','One-way only, from the top of [[track:1]] to the eastern end of [[track:3]].','1.377',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-26 12:33:47',23,'-41.295444','174.713470',16,3,1,1,1,'2009-11-08 22:14:46','calc',5),(3,'Missing Link',1,'','Connection between [[track:2]] and [[track:4]].','This is an especially important track in the [[area:1]] network, as it links the lower tracks (particularly [[track:1]] and [[track:2]]) to [[track:4]], [[track:9]], [[track:65]], and [[track:10]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nHeading west from [[track:20]], at the end of [[track:2]], the track drops down into a deep and dark valley. At the first hairpin bend there is a bench seat perfectly positioned to admire the inspiring view.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter descending for a while, you\'ll pass the top of [[track:10]] which is between two bridged creek crossings. Then there\'s a zigzag climb up to the bottom of [[track:18]], with the bottom of [[track:4]] nearby.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is narrow all the way, with a rocky surface in many places â€“ including a mean rock cutting that has a steep and off-camber exit. In several places there are nasty drop-offs that you probably don\'t want to explore under the direct influence of gravity.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Downhill section of Missing link, to top of [[track:10]]]]\r\n[[media:youtube:_AJjJucafSk]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6765294]]','Western end is on the [[track:20]], opposite the end of [[track:2]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end is at the bottom of the [[track:18]]. There\'s a bench seat at the end of the track, with a lovely view of the pylon.','This is a two-way track, though most traffic is east to west.  There are many blind corners, so watch out for other track users at all times.','1.577',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 21:30:30',23,'-41.295599','174.708323',17,3,1,1,1,'2010-01-09 09:11:47','calc',5),(4,'Aratihi',1,'','Main track up to the summit of [[area:1]].','With a moderate grade, this is a popular way to reach the summit of [[area:1]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom 0.5km is the steepest, after which the gradient becomes a bit more mellow.  Much of the track surface has worn down to rough bare rock, just to make the climb a little more challenging.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost traffic is up hill, but this is a two-way track so watch out for people travelling in the other direction.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAratihi (Ah-rah-tee-hee) is a New Zealand MÄori word that means:\r\n[[para]]\r\n- ara (noun) way, path, lane, passageway, track, course. \r\n[[para]]\r\n- tihi (noun) summit, top, peak, point.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6774379]]','Starts just above Tower 16, at the western end of [[track:3]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on the [[track:18]] just below the summit of [[area:1]].','','2.088',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-11 09:09:37',177,'-41.292737','174.704740',16,3,1,1,1,'2010-05-07 11:44:14','calc',5),(5,'Ridgeline',1,'','Steep and rocky descent from the summit of [[area:1]].','This is one of the more difficult tracks in the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt starts with a rolling piece of singletrack along a ridgeline. It then weaves its way down a series of steep sections with some tight corners, plus a couple of sweeping corners thrown in for fun.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are spectacular views over Karori and the harbour beyond. However, if you want to admire the views then stop off the track to do so, as the track requires full concentration.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome of the more difficult drops and steps have easier alternative lines, though not all of them do. There is plenty of exposed rock along the way, which is challenging when dry and tricky when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter dropping down a set of steep, tight switchbacks, the track ends abruptly at an intersection with [[track:19]]. Directly opposite is the start of [[track:50]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Ridgeline then to picnic tables on [[track:50]]]]\r\n[[media:youtube:nVCojrJtvh0]]','Starts from the summit of [[area:1]]. Head along the ridgeline to the southeast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:19]].','','1.325',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-10 19:43:04',23,'-41.291496','174.710144',16,4,1,1,1,'2010-02-21 08:51:40','calc',5),(6,'Big Tom\'s Wheelie',1,'','Short and gentle connection between [[track:50]] and [[track:7]].','This short connecting track is a natural progression off the end of [[track:50]].  The surface is firm, with just enough bumps to make it interesting, while the surrounding bush is pleasant.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter cruising along this gentle track, there are several options including:\r\n[[bullet:continue down [[track:7]]  & [[track:22]] to the main car park.]]\r\n[[bullet:take [[track:53]] down to the main car park.]]\r\n[[bullet:head back into the depths of the park via [[track:2]].]]\r\n[[bullet:cruise on down to the [[track:54]] via [[track:21]] or [[track:16]].]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nBe careful crossing [[track:51]] as you enter the start of this track â€“ there can be vehicle traffic heading up/down the road.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:6]] (0:00-0:30) / [[track:7]] (0:31-2:05) / [[track:22]] (2:06-end)]]\r\n[[media:youtube:YhSLc0_ks0Y]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:6]] (0:00-0:46) / [[track:7]] (0:47-2:13) / [[track:22]] (2:14-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6764775]]','Continues from directly opposite the end of [[track:50]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with several other tracks, including [[track:7]], [[track:53]], and [[track:2]].','Strictly speaking [[track:6]] is part of [[track:7]], though it is often referred to as if it were a seperate track.','0.186',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-14 10:07:09',23,'-41.295132','174.716736',17,2,1,1,1,'2009-09-27 09:55:45','calc',5),(7,'Swigg',1,'','Short but sweet single track from the top of [[track:1]] down to the top of [[track:22]].','The \"Swirly Whirly Green Goat\" track, otherwise known as SWIGG, is a sensuously sweet flowing descent. It has high-bermed corners, a steep wooden ramp, and interesting little wriggles and bumps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSWIGG, in association with [[track:22]], is one of the main routes back to the main car park.  Consequently it is a very popular track, as is the adjacent easier option of [[track:53]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nStrictly speaking [[track:6]] is part of SWIGG, though they are usually treated as separate tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:6]] (0:00-0:30) / [[track:7]] (0:31-2:05) / [[track:22]] (2:06-end)]]\r\n[[media:youtube:YhSLc0_ks0Y]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:6]] (0:00-0:46) / [[track:7]] (0:47-2:13) / [[track:22]] (2:14-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6764775]]','Starts on [[track:21]] at the nexus of several tracks, including [[track:1]], [[track:6]], and [[track:53]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on [[track:66]], next to the communications tower and directly opposite the start of [[track:22]].','','0.541',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-10 21:26:59',23,'-41.295712','174.718924',17,3,1,1,1,'2009-10-18 14:28:01','calc',5),(8,'Live Wires',1,'','An interesting little track connecting the [[track:54]] with the lower part of [[track:1]].','This is a gnarly, downhill-only track that includes some wooden structures (near the top, just below the [[track:54]]), tight corners, rough surface, and a generally steep and technical descent. The track surface is a mixture of bare dirt and rocks, which is especially interesting when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 350m from the top, the track splits into advanced (left) and intermediate (right) alternatives. The advanced option has an especially steep and usually deeply rutted drop down to rejoin the main track 200m down the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is also a connection to/from [[track:1]], about 0.15km from the top on the apex of a tight switchback. This connection is only 50m long, meeting [[track:1]] at a sweeping left-hand corner.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Through the [[track:54]] and down Live Wires (including advanced section)]]\r\n[[media:youtube:TL_yux_66LQ]]','The top of the track is on the south-eastern side of the [[track:54]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom end of the track is on [[track:1]], just above where the \'Wet feet\' alternative joins the main track.','The track length counts the main track and the difficult alternative.','0.944',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-26 12:23:58',23,'-41.299347','174.719818',16,3,1,1,1,'2009-09-08 21:04:27','calc',5),(9,'Leaping Lizard',1,'','Swoopy ridge romp with plenty of jumps.','The first third of this track is smooth and fast, heading straight down a ridge, with plenty of jumps for the thrill seekers. All of the jumps can be rolled over, if you prefer.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track changes as you leave the ridge, carving through manuka and then down to a grassy valley. Parts of this section are steep, rocky, and generally gnarly.  At the base of the valley you\'ll cross a small stream.  There\'s no bridge over the stream, but it is easy to cross without getting wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe official exit is via a tough climb and then steep descent over a ridge. This route includes fording Karori Stream, which will likely involve getting wet feet.  Less than 0.1km after Karori Stream you\'ll reach South Karori Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, just past the small stream crossing turn left up the initially mellow valley.  Then climb up [[track:65]] and along [[track:10]] to meet [[track:3]] â€“ though this is by no means an easier option.\r\n[[media:youtube:yKWFtMjySO4]]','Starts on [[track:18]], opposite the bottom of [[track:48]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on South Karori Road, about 2km from [[area:1]]\'s main car park.','','2.730',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-06-01 00:00:00',23,'-41.302216','174.703857',15,4,1,1,1,'2009-09-13 19:09:45','calc',5),(10,'Nikau Valley',1,'','Narrow and technically challenging single track from [[track:9]] to [[track:3]].','This track drops off the [[track:9]] ridge down into a deep valley, providing an interesting loop up to [[track:3]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track is narrow, with various technical challenges along the way, including: steep rutted sections, rocky bits, and off-camber corners. In several places there are sheer drop-offs to the side, some of which are obscured by the dense regenerating bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter dropping down into the valley, the track then climbs quite steeply up to meet [[track:3]].  Although [[track:3]] is a two-way track, the usual exit strategy from [[track:10]] is to the left up to the bottom of [[track:4]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeing in a deep, dark valley much of the track is prone to being quite wet. The climbing section, in particular, more-or-less follows a creek that drains a large catchment between [[track:4]] and [[track:51]]. Consequently, the lower parts of the track can be very wet and slippery for long periods of time.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Downhill section of Nikau Valley]]\r\n[[media:youtube:fdMNjjeWIgA]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Full trail video]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:11546367]]','The start of [[track:10]] is to the left at an obvious intersection near the end of [[track:9]]\'s straight section.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:65]] joins from the south, 250m from the [[track:9]] end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end joins the middle of [[track:3]].','One-way only, from the [[track:9]] end.','1.574',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (or Advanced when wet)','2008-12-19 21:32:39',177,'-41.297622','174.705791',16,3,1,1,1,'2010-05-07 20:05:52','calc',5),(11,'Varley\'s',1,'','Northern entry to the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park, via a series of switchbacks.','This is a popular route into and out of the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park, particularly in combination with [[track:12]] and [[track:35]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Makara Road end of this track zig zags along a 100m high ridge via 14 switchbacks. Many of the switchbacks are rocky and tight, making them a challenge â€“ especially when climbing. Above the top switchback there is a short, usually overgrown, track that detours up to a trig station.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.1km from the top, at a hairpin bend, the track meets [[track:49]] and [[track:13]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust above the second from bottom switchback there are a couple of wooden posts in the track, so if descending you\'ll need to slow down for that. The bottom switchback is on a short asphalt section that runs from a steel gate at the bottom up to the water tank that is clearly visible in the map.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6863489]]','The top meets [[track:51]] directly opposite the end of [[track:12]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom is on Makara Road, just 0.1km from the southern end of [[track:32]] with the top of [[track:35]] less than 0.2km further along.','This track is named after Gareth Varley, a young mountain biker who was killed crossing a road while representing New Zealand at the 1998 World Mountain Bike Championships in Quebec. Also see the [[track:298]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a memorial to Gareth on a prominant rock above the intersection of [[track:11]], [[track:12]], and [[track:51]]. The plaque says \"In memory of Gareth Varley. Tragically killed while representing New Zealand at the 1998 World Mountain Bike Championships. Ride in peace. Erected by the Victoria University Mountain Bike Club and Friends on behalf of the Mountain Bike community\".\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/Varley-memorial.png:Gareth Varley Memorial:492:385]]','1.042',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-15 19:12:35',23,'-41.284015','174.715265',17,3,1,1,1,'2009-10-04 09:28:48','calc',5),(12,'Zac\'s Track',1,'','Tight and twisty singletrack from the summit of [[area:1]].','This is narrow track that sashays around the northern side of [[area:1]].  It provides either an interesting exit from the summit, or an alternative climb up to the summit.  A route in either direction that includes [[track:11]] and [[track:35]] is a popular combination.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several rocky sections to provide a bit of technical challenge when travelling in either direction. \r\n[[para]]\r\nAt around the 1.0km point, when heading down, there is a 1m+ step down.  The drop is straight ahead so if you want to avoid it, then deviate sharply to the right for an easier path.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6763392]]','Drops down from the summit of [[area:1]], heading towards the north past the summit shelter.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe other end is at the point where [[track:11]] meets [[track:51]].','This track is two-way, so watch out for people ascending.','1.406',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-10 18:27:13',23,'-41.286564','174.708908',16,3,1,1,1,'2009-09-27 09:59:42','calc',5),(13,'Vertigo',1,'','Twisty technical descent. Features various optional wooden obstacles, including a spiral bridge that you go over then under.','This is a twisty technical descent, with plenty of challenging (mostly optional) features including wooden obstacles. Near the bottom there is a spiral bridge that you go over then under. There isn\'t much room under the bridge, so remember to duck!\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track starts in open low scrub and ends in low dense bush. The lower reaches, in particular, provide a very pleasant environment â€“ not that there is much opportunity to admire the scenery, as the track demands full attention.\r\n[[para]]\r\nUnlike most of [[area:1]], the lower parts of this track are slow to dry out after wet weather. This really is a dry weather track, as the difficult sections get much more arduous when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Top half of Vertigo]][[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:_i7iiGtzsKk]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Bottom half of Vertigo]][[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:a86aeaZwVz0]]','Starts near the top of [[track:11]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds near the bottom of [[track:14]]. Continue along [[track:14]] to exit on to Allington Road.','One-way only, downhill.','0.967',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 21:36:38',23,'-41.287368','174.715362',16,5,1,1,1,'2009-10-18 14:14:27','calc',5),(14,'Trickle Falls',1,'','Honest technical downhill with some drops and jumps. Can all be rolled over with care. When ridden at modest speed provides a good flowing single track.','This is probably the most technical track in the park (sometimes that honour goes to [[track:13]] when it\'s been wet). It descends for most of the height of the Peak. A nice mixture of flowing single track with natural rock jumps, and squiggly bush shenanigans. Some rocky sections and some clay.','From the summit head down [[track:51]] to the north. The entrance is well marked on the right about 100 metres from the summit. You can also exit [[track:12]] about 1/4 of the way down via a 10 metre grassy slope â€“ near a section of flax.','Built by Ricky \"Slackboy\" Pincott and friends 2002-2003.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track has changed a lot over the years. In the early days the final rocky drop into the stream was the crux of the track but now it\'s pretty straight forward. Then up until May 08 the very top left-hander was a gotcha, especially when dry. Now that has been tidied nicely. Currently the most technical section is provided as an option (marked with triple-x sign, about 0.5km from the top) with a decent rocky exit drop that has next to no run-out before you make a sharp right hander. One for the experts methinks.','1.348',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-20 21:24:22',23,'-41.288239','174.713130',16,5,1,1,1,'2009-09-27 13:41:49','calc',5),(16,'Magic Carpet',1,'','Interesting and flatish amble parallel to [[track:21]], ending at the [[track:54]].','This is a seemingly seldom used, but interesting, little track that provides a nice alternative to the [[track:21]] 4wd road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track undulates up and down a few metres, with enough of a gradient to provide a test of skill in wet conditions, yet without being a strenuous workout.  As such, this is a good track for practicing a bit of bike control while on your way to the [[track:54]] for more extensive training.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen heading from north to south, the first exit will place you at the top of the [[track:54]]\'s jumps. If you\'d prefer a more sedate entry to the [[track:54]], then continue along the track down a twisty chute and turn left when you reach the 4wd [[track:21]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Along Magic Carpet and into the [[track:54]]]]\r\n[[media:youtube:OOsqbX-9-5M]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6760573]]','Northern end is on [[track:21]], next to the top of [[track:66]] and about 80m south of the intersection of [[track:1]], [[track:53]], and other tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end has two exits â€“ the first is to the top of the [[track:54]], while the other rejoins [[track:21]] a few metres north of a link from [[track:1]] to the [[track:54]].','This track is one-way only, towards the [[track:54]].','0.546',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-06-01 00:00:00',23,'-41.297752','174.718414',16,2,1,1,1,'2009-09-27 10:04:00','calc',5),(17,'Quintessential',7,'',' ','','','','0.612',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2006-09-17 00:00:00',1,'-41.274422','174.744003',16,3,2,1,1,'2006-09-17 00:00:00','calc',5),(18,'Tower 16 Connector',1,'','4wd road providing access to electricity transmission pylon 16.','This 4wd road marks the northwestern boundary of the [[area:1]] mountain bike park. Much of it is seldom used by recreational visitors to the park. Most people use only the top and bottom few percent of this track, from the end of [[track:3]] to the start of [[track:4]] and then from the top of [[track:4]] to the summit of [[area:1]] â€“ though a few hardy souls ride up the 0.6km to the top of [[track:9]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nParts of the road are quite steep, so it can be a grind going up.  When going down it is easy to gain plenty of speed, but there are occasional service vehicles using the road so watch out for them.','Top is at the summit of [[area:1]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is at pylon 16, where it meets [[track:3]] and the bottom of [[track:4]].','','1.737',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-06-01 00:00:00',23,'-41.292737','174.704719',15,2,1,3,1,'2010-01-13 12:16:59','calc',5),(19,'Allington Connector',1,'','Steep access road into [[area:1]] via a locked gate.','This steep 4wd access road provides an alternative entry to, or exit from, the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park. The gate on Allington Road is tall and has cross-beams, though it is possible to squeeze a bike through with some effort.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is a reasonable climb up from Allington Road, gaining about 90m before dropping down 20m to meet [[track:51]].  Just before meeting [[track:51]] you\'ll cross the intersection where the end of [[track:5]] leads on to the start of [[track:50]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n','Starts from a metal gate near the top of Allington Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:51]].','At the very end of Allington Road, just 60m from the metal gate where this track starts, you\'ll find the end of [[track:68]].','0.736',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-06-01 00:00:00',23,'-41.292511','174.715057',17,3,1,3,1,'2010-04-05 21:04:09','calc',5),(20,'Tower 18 Connector',1,'','4wd road providing access to electricity transmission pylons 17 and 18.','Usually only the northern one-third of this road is frequented by recreational users, as that\'s where there is an intersection with [[track:2]] and [[track:3]].  People typically emerge from the western end of [[track:2]], have a short rest at the intersection, and then continue on to either [[track:3]] (directly opposite [[track:2]]) or up the road to [[track:51]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe climb up to [[track:51]] is moderately steep, and can be tricky when wet due to the slick rock and clay surface of the road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout two-thirds of the way along, towards the southern end of the road, there is a short branch that goes to pylon 17.  This branch, and the southern end of the road in general, is a dead-end, so return the same way.','Northern end descends from [[track:51]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is at pylon 18, having passed pylon 17 along the way.','','0.623',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-06-01 00:00:00',23,'-41.297108','174.709976',16,2,1,3,1,'2010-01-13 12:26:44','calc',5),(21,'Tower 19 Connector',1,'','4wd road providing access to electricity transmission pylon 19, which is in the [[track:54]].','This is a 4wd access road for pylon 19, though more importantly (from the perspective of the [[area:1]] mountain bike park) it provides access to the [[track:54]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of this road runs parallel to [[track:1]] and [[track:16]]. Towards the northern end, about 0.12km from [[track:51]], is a major intersection of the park\'s lower tracks.  That is: on the western side you\'ll find the top of [[track:1]] and the start of [[track:2]], while on the eastern side is the nexus of [[track:6]], [[track:7]], and [[track:53]].','Northern end meets [[track:51]] just above the intersection with [[track:50]] and [[track:6]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is in the [[track:54]].','','0.690',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-06-01 00:00:00',23,'-41.298023','174.717621',16,2,1,3,1,'2010-01-13 12:45:49','calc',5),(22,'Starfish',1,'','Short exit to the main car park.','This is one of the main exits from [[area:1]]. It follows on from [[track:7]], ending at the main car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several large berms, making for great corners that can be taken at almost any speed, though other corners are rocky and require the application of more skill. Other interesting features include a sharp step down in a section that is already sloping downwards, and a very steep concrete ramp immediately after a tight squeeze between two massive tree stumps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTake care on the final run towards the car park, as this track merges with the end of [[track:53]] immediately before the car park\'s north bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:6]] (0:00-0:30) / [[track:7]] (0:31-2:05) / [[track:22]] (2:06-end)]]\r\n[[media:youtube:YhSLc0_ks0Y]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:6]] (0:00-0:46) / [[track:7]] (0:47-2:13) / [[track:22]] (2:14-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6764775]]','Top is next to the communications tower at the intersection of [[track:7]] and [[track:66]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is on the northern side of the main car park, immediately before the north bridge.','','0.557',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-10 21:21:15',23,'-41.296211','174.721741',17,3,1,1,1,'2010-01-12 14:49:41','calc',5),(23,'Tip Track',2,'','A classic Wellington track with an honest altitude change. Mostly packed rock and gravel with patches of clay on the bottom half and patches of loose gravel on the top half. The council blades this 4wd track about once a year so it is usually in good condition, however serious ruts do form after heavy rain. The surrounding hills are mostly covered in gorse which is slowly regenerating. Plenty of wild goats and rabbits for company. In late spring the lower slopes turn purple with a weed daisy that has taken hold. This track can be ridden in either direction, and is quite exposed to the northerly which can add extra challenge on the upper half. The views from the top are excellent, and on a clear day you can see all of Wellington and harbour, the Tararua mountains and the top of the South Island.','Going up. The climb is in two main sections with a brief descent/rest in the middle. The climbing starts immediately at the big metal gate at the bottom. You climb up the right flank of the ridge for about 1.5k with gorse on either side of you. About 1/4 of the way up you go around a sharp left-hand bend where you can see all the way up to the old cattle yards at the half way point. The bottom third is probably the steepest but usually has the least loose gravel. There are several large water-bars to roll through. After this the gradient slowly levels off as you approach the cattle yards. The next kilometre rolls up then down as you traverse across to the next part of the climb. As you come around a large right-hand bend with the bank on your right, there is a track off to your left that goes to [[track:56]] (marked with a new signage). Stay on the main trail. Once through the saddle the climb starts again sidling to the right with more gorse. There are a few tough left-hand corners here with plenty of loose gravel which can be a real challenge to ride. There is a major intersection to Red Rocks about 400m from the top (you can see the top for the last 3rd of the ride). The turn-off is well marked and the Tip Track continues on to the right. This last section is not quite so steep as the track takes you up to a metal pole-gate at the top. If the northerly is really blowing and you want a sit down then you can usually find some shelter just below the sealed road where the Tip Track joins. Views to the South Island are best from the summit about 300m further up the sealed road.[[para]]Coming down. This is a very fast descent. Going down you really don\'t notice the loose gravel patches and the main difficulty is keeping your speed down so you can make the bends comfortably. Beware the water-bars on the bottom third which can be quite deep and rutty after big rain. There are also some clay patches here which can be greasy if it has been wet.','The bottom of the Tip Track starts at the big metal gates immediately to the left of the road to the rubbish dump off Happy Valley road (about 5km south of Brooklyn). There is signage at the gate for Te Kopuhou Reserve, and another on the gate saying \"Emergency Vehicle Access\".[[para]]The top can be reached by continuing on up the sealed road from the Brooklyn wind turbine. The track starts on the left, just up from the orange concrete-block castle - beware of the dragons (dogs). Or if you are coming from the summit of Hawkins Hill it is about 300m down from the \"golf ball\" (Airways Corporation aircraft monitoring station) on the outside of a right-hand bend. If you pass the castle you have gone too far.','','3.545',432,16,34,450,' (when going up)','','2008-02-07 12:05:02',7,'-41.334225','174.741562',14,4,1,3,1,'2008-02-07 12:05:02','calc',5),(24,'Car Parts',2,'','A flowing twisty single track through a tunnel of regenerating scrub below the Brooklyn wind turbine.','From the wind turbine you drop down a short rutty slope to the start of the single track. This is the steepest part, and probably the most difficult. Immediately below the car park, heading off towards Hawkins Hill, is [[track:67]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:24]] then enters the bush and is narrow and nearly all downhill with one short uphill section that cannot be coasted up. At the top of this there is a blue refrigerator, but no time for refreshments as it\'s all downhill from here to the end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track suddenly emerges from the bush at a grassy area next to the sealed road. Cross here to join the [[track:25]] track. Or there is a short zig zag across the grass to the next corner on the sealed road if you want to carry on to Brooklyn.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track has a base of gravel and rock with a rich dark dirt cover can get very messy when wet. Due to the close bush cover and south-east aspect this track takes a long time to dry out and can stay wet for most of the winter. It can be ridden in either direction but is most popular as a descent. There are good views over Wellington and harbour from the top, and even some glimpses of the Kaikoura mountains.','The top entrance/exit is directly across the carpark at the Brooklyn wind turbine and adjacent to the eastern end of [[track:67]] which continues southwest towards Hawkins Hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom entrance/exit pops out of the bush where the sealed road meets the [[track:25]] track for the first time when coming up. There is a bike-friendly style between the [[track:25]] and the sealed road, and [[track:24]] is directly across from this.','Be wary of vehicles when exiting the lower end, it can be particularly busy on weekends.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track is popular with the shuttle crowd as you can drive to the top.','0.978',7,84,376,299,' (when going down)','','2008-05-09 23:39:22',23,'-41.308472','174.746201',16,3,1,1,1,'2010-03-24 14:32:00','calc',5),(25,'Fenceline',4,'','This 4wd track follows the predator-proof fence around the Karori Bird Sanctuary. The bird sanctuary covers a large valley and the adjoining flanks of [[area:4]] and [[area:3]], so the track includes two good climbs if done as a loop (to complete the loop add [[track:34]] and [[track:31]]).','From George Denton Park go through the metal gate and follow the track up. Very soon you will meet the bird sanctuary fence. You can follow the fence in either direction, however heading up (left) from here is the most popular way to go.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe 4wd track continues up in short steep rises up to the wind turbine. From here the gradient is generally more rolling until you reach the highest point, also known as the tapu sign. The views east from here are excellent.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter a short descent you will pass a gap in the regular fence on your left - this is the last exit if you wish to go up towards [[area:2]]. From here the track traverses for about 300 metres before diving down to the area that used to be known as \'The Glade\', which is the lowest point at the southwest end. Beware of this descent if wet as the gradient increases going down culminating in a rutty clay section before levelling off again.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom The Glade you can access [[area:4]]. To continue around the [[track:25]] keep the fence on your right and head up. The track climbs for about 500 metres before levelling off again. Just past a transmission tower there is an intersection on your left that will take you to the [[area:4]] parade ground.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:25]] continues for another 0.6km before it meets the [[track:31]] track. You can go down the steep hill beside the fence but it is extremely steep with loose gravel and rocks, beware. It is easier to go down [[track:31]] and then rejoin [[track:25]] at the bottom - possibly via [[track:174]].','There are many places to access this track. The most popular would be via the [[track:28]] from George Denton Park at the end of Highbury Road in Highbury.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother popular access is from the Parade Ground at the top of [[area:4]]. From the sealed access road, go around the metal pole gate on to a gravel 4wd road. Take the next right over another metal pole gate. After about 500m you will come to a large grassy area, this is the Parade Ground. Head east towards the wind turbine, and when you meet the predator-proof fence turn right.','This track is popular with walkers/runners and their dogs. Also after a good storm the fence is checked by the bird sanctuary people, so watch out for vehicles. I have also met horses, trail bikers and the odd stray livestock on this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[link:http://www.coolrunning.co.nz/races/karori/index.html The Meridian Gutbuster]] running race is held on this track each year â€“ the sponsorship connection being that the track goes past Meridian Energy\'s [[link:http://www.meridianenergy.co.nz/NR/rdonlyres/B496C006-3F64-4F0E-8305-C22CAE732A4E/24695/0187MEDBrooklynwebBro_FAaj.pdf Brooklyn wind turbine]].','8.303',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:37:04',23,'-41.301991','174.742527',14,3,1,3,1,'2010-02-21 14:18:19','calc',5),(26,'Maori Gully',2,', exit is through T&T Landfills Ltd','Ridgeback roller coaster. In the early 90s the landfill people were ok about riders coming through. But it changed hands and the new owners closed access and now the gorse has taken over. The track is still under there somewhere, but currently not passable. There were rumblings of the local downhill club opening it back up, and there is a possible return up the valley to connect back into [[track:24]], but that is a long way off.','','','','1.000',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',', but completely overgrown with gorse','2008-05-09 23:49:27',23,'-41.317463','174.748444',14,3,4,1,1,'2010-03-24 14:23:24','user',0),(27,'Planet Ride',3,'','2km single track on Polhill','Little steep in some places - few roots. Some quite narrow sections.','Top is on the lower end of [[track:36]], with an alternative connection to Ashton Fitchett Drive via a set of steps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is on Aro Street, 20m down from Holloway Road.','Slippery when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere\'s a Wellington City Council sign at the top, on [[track:36]], that says \"NO BIKES\".','2.034',11,224,263,51,' (when going down)','','2009-04-11 16:27:47',23,'-41.299282','174.757462',15,2,2,1,1,'2010-02-14 09:40:03','calc',5),(28,'Roller Coaster',3,'','Downhill alternative to the fenceline with lots of jumps from near [[track:36]] to George Denton Park.','','','','0.807',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-21 19:46:46',1,'-41.299250','174.750295',15,3,1,1,1,'2010-04-27 10:28:25','calc',5),(29,'Salvation',4,'','A meandering single track through mixed light and dense regenerating bush. The gentle gradient of this track is by design, and it never gets steeper than 6%. This track is the best connector if going from [[area:1]] to [[area:4]].','As you leave the road end you are immediately plunged into the bush and confronted with probably the tightest switch-back on the entire track. After this things settle down as the track winds through the bush over various small wooden bridges and corners. The first intersection to [[track:189]] is on a sharpish right-hand switch-back. It is clearly marked with a large sign that says \"no bikes\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter this the track levels off for about 700 metres. Continue climbing. There are a couple of brief downhill bits but it\'s pretty much up hill all the way to the next intersection to [[track:43]]. Continuing straight on the track climbs for only another 250 metres before levelling off. The last 500 metres is level and then slightly down. As you sweep around a downhill bend out of the bush past the turn-off to [[track:30]], the top carpark straight ahead about 30 metres on.','The top can be reached from the first carpark on [[area:4]], which is on your right coming up Wrights Hill road just where the gradient levels off on a sharp left-hand bend. The bottom can be reached from the end of Fitzgerald Place, it is the most obvious trail on the north side of the parking area. The less obvious track is the exit to [[track:30]].','This track has been designed with decreasing radius corners (from downhill pov) which is an attempt to reduce the speed of riders coming down. This makes for a \'power climb\' as you can accellerate out of the corners.[[para]]This track was originally (officially) called Skyline and is a part of the \'Skyline Trail\'. But a lot of people including me think this name is really confusing (other [[track:32]]) so the unofficial name [[track:29]] is used here, as it is used informally by local riders.\r\n\r\n[[para]] \r\n[[image:http://i721.photobucket.com/albums/ww214/capuchin09/salvation-bigtext-250w.png:Salvation Height Graph::]]\r\n[[para]]','2.889',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-08 12:40:31',23,'-41.295219','174.729691',16,2,1,1,1,'2009-09-01 18:03:40','calc',5),(30,'Deliverance',4,'','A rogue downhill through dense native scrub with fast traverses and short steep drops. A few short ups and stream crossings add to this excellent flowing single track.','Technically challenging rumble down a deep, dark valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track follows a creek, crossing it several times.  During or after wet weather, the distinction between the track and creek becomes somewhat unclear in places, adding to the fun/torture (depending on one\'s point of view).\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top of the track is a sign warning about the \"dappled lighting conditions\". Just along from the warning sign, on the righthand side of the track, is a headless Jesus statue.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe dappled lighting conditions are the least of your problems as you soon encounter a steep boulder strewn rock garden that has only a passing resemblence to a track. If this is too intimidating, then proceed no further.  There are numerous other obstacles as you drop down the valley, including sudden drops, rocks in awkward places, and lots of slippery tree roots across the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor those still keen, ascending [[track:29]] and descending [[track:30]] makes for a great circuit.','The original entry to [[track:30]] (also known as Normal) can be reached from the first car park on [[area:4]], which is on your right coming up Wrights Hill road just where the gradient levels off on a sharp left-hand bend. There is a sign post for Skyline ([[track:29]]) and [[track:43]]. Follow [[track:29]] for about 30 metres and you will come to a large sign for [[track:30]] which dives off to the left just before [[track:29]] ascends slightly.','There are now three different entrances to [[track:30]], one of which divides again before they all rejoin [[track:30]] proper. The easiest entry to find is Normal, which is described above. Another popular entry is [[track:52]]. For a more challenging start try the entry known as [[track:69]], from which [[track:70]] makes a hard left-hand turn away from the natural flow of the track just before the section known as Pure Evil. Beware!\r\n\r\n[[para]] \r\n[[image:http://i721.photobucket.com/albums/ww214/capuchin09/deliverence-final.png:Deliverance Height Graph::]]\r\n[[para]]','1.463',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-08 13:08:15',23,'-41.296510','174.730296',16,4,1,1,1,'2009-09-13 13:12:53','calc',5),(31,'Scout Hall',4,'','Twisty alternative to an especially gnarly section of [[track:25]], from the summit of [[area:4]] to the Williams Hall scout den in Campbell Street.','This is a neat piece of singletrack through a pleasant bush setting. While it isn\'t technical, some of the switchbacks can be a little tricky - especially when climbing in the wet. \r\n[[para]]\r\nCombine this track with [[track:34]] and [[track:25]] to form a complete circuit of the Karori Wildlife Sanctuary.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn a couple of places there are detours, where the track briefly splits into alternative paths - one slightly easier than the other.  These detours are only a few metres long.\r\n','From the [[area:4]] viewing platform, follow the sealed path that drops down below the platform and then into the bush. Alternatively, follow [[track:25]] to just below the summit of Wrights Hill.  At the point where [[track:25]] dives down an extremely steep section, this track branches off into the bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom of the track is at the southeastern corner of the scout hall.','This is a popular walking track, so modest descent speeds would be prudent.','1.013',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-26 21:08:25',23,'-41.295478','174.742194',17,3,1,1,1,'2009-12-21 09:28:54','calc',5),(32,'Skyline',7,', leave gates as you find them.','Exposed ridge-top romp across [[region:1]]\'s [[area:7]]. This track redefines \"Windy [[region:1]]\" when the nor-wester is pumping.','By traversing the ridges from Makara Hill to Mount Kau Kau, this track offers spectacular views both over Wellington and the western hills towards Makara Beach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWith a combination of farm roads, single track, and open grass areas, there is plenty of variety along this relatively long track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf travelling from the southern ([[area:1]]) end, then the inclination is generally upwards.  In addition, there are several significant valley/peak combinations to be negotiated, making for a decent bit of climbing overall.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Skyline track from the top of ]][[track:178]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/Skyline-Oli-1.jpg:Skyline track:492:478]] \r\n[[bold:Transmission towers to the west of [[track:32]]]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/TxSkyline.jpg:Transmission towers to the west of Skyline:492:388]]','Either start at the summit of Makara Hill Road, where there is a small car park, or head southwest from the summit of [[track:159]].','Track building in 2009 replaced some sections of farm road with single track and replaced many gates and stiles with foot and bike friendly [[link:http://www.kennett.co.nz/index.php/Tracks/SkylineCattleStops cattle stops]] â€“ nice.','9.987',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:32:55',23,'-41.257033','174.747505',13,3,1,1,1,'2010-01-31 12:54:32','calc',5),(33,'Parkvale Access',7,'','Grassy farm track access between Karori and [[track:32]].','This track starts climbing immediately from the gate at the end of the sealed road. Following the orange discs on white poles the track climbs at a steady and comfortable gradient to the main intersection at a wooden gate just below the ridge. There is one gate to negotiate at about halfway up, and be sure to turn right at the intersection just after this. Enjoy the relative calm of this little valley because when you hit the ridge you will certainly feel any Northerly wind. ','The lower end of this track starts at the end of Parkvale Road (off main Karori road at Karori Mall). The track starts just past the block wall where there is a sign, gate and style. The top end is also well sign-posted at a gate and a style just below the main ridge.','This is a good access to the newest single track section of [[track:32]]. This is an active sheep and cattle farming area so leave all gates as you find them. There are styles at all the major gate crossings.','0.561',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2005-11-24 00:00:00',1,'-41.274921','174.734131',17,2,1,3,1,'2005-11-24 00:00:00','calc',5),(34,'S Bend',4,'','Narrow trail with super tight switchbacks and dense bush.','','','At the bottom of the valley the track crosses Kaiwharawhara stream.  A small dam across the stream forms St John\'s Pool, which was used for swimming prior to the Karori pool being constructed in the 1930s.','0.723',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-29 22:07:14',23,'-41.289352','174.752462',17,3,1,1,1,'2009-06-21 20:51:13','calc',5),(35,'Wahine',6,'','A short connector between [[track:32]] and [[track:315]].','A short, steep track through mature pine forest from [[track:32]] to the back of the [[track:315]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe combination of steep hills, mature pine trees, and typical [[region:1]] greywacke rock makes this area particularly prone to slips and tree falls.  In August 2008 two large trees fell during a storm, blocking the track and making a large hole in the bank above the track. One tree was cleared and a bypass emerged around the other\'s stump â€“ eventually becoming a ridable chicane.','This track is often ridden as part of a circuit to/from the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park.','The track has existed for many years, but was closed due to damage inflicted during the Wahine storm of 1968 â€“ hence the name.  It was reopened in 2003 following restoration work by the [[area:1]] supporters.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is popular with a variety of uers, which occasionally leads to conflict.  In early 2009 the WCC placed a sign at the point where [[track:35]] deviates from the [[track:323]] which says something like: \"This is a multi-purpose track used by walkers, runners and mountain bikers. For safety reasons, please do not place branches across the track\".','0.688',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:33:13',23,'-41.282926','174.721016',16,3,1,1,1,'2009-09-01 18:01:16','calc',5),(36,'Sawmill',3,'','Single track access between the top of Brooklyn and the [[track:28]]/[[track:25]]. Also the only access to the top of [[track:27]].','This handy connector from Ashton Fitchett Drive to [[track:25]] makes a nice alternative to climbing the sealed access road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a steel barrier at the bottom that you\'ll have to lift the bike over, and a pole-gate through the fence at the top.','The bottom of this track starts just to the right of the gate on the road access to the wind turbine, off Ashton Fitchett Drive.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTo access the top, turn off the [[track:25]] track just north of the large modern blocky house behind the wooden fence (it\'s the only house on the track; if you reach the transmission tower then turn back because you went 130m too far north).','','0.394',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-07 21:31:02',23,'-41.304256','174.751709',17,2,1,1,1,'2010-01-23 15:43:17','calc',5),(37,'Superconductor',7,', new owner has installed \'keep out\' signs.','Electric descent from open tops to dense forest via transmission towers in the mist.','','','This track does not really exist yet. There is evidence of an old 4wd but it is overgrown with gorse for the first part. After that it is dense pine forest similar to [[track:44]], in fact it\'s on a parallel ridge slightly to the north.','1.637',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' due to no track!','2006-11-25 00:00:00',1,'-41.274193','174.726151',16,5,6,1,1,'2006-11-25 00:00:00','calc',5),(38,'Long Gully',2,', contact Long Gully Station (04) 4765296 for permission',' ','','','','0.000',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' to 6','2006-02-08 00:00:00',1,'-41.329262','174.714203',13,2,4,3,1,'2006-02-08 00:00:00',NULL,0),(39,'Red Rocks',2,'','Rocky downhill along cliff tops with huge sea views.','','','','4.582',106,511,412,5,' (when going down)','','2008-12-19 20:32:53',23,'-41.343502','174.733000',14,4,1,3,1,'2008-12-19 20:32:53','calc',5),(40,'Emedee',7,'','Gentle 4wd traverse from the Wilton electricity sub-station to the [[area:7]] ridge. This is an official access to the [[track:32]] track, in fact it\'s even sign-posted as [[track:32]] which continues the confusing theme of naming several tracks with that name.','From the carpark at the sub-station follow the 4wd road as it traverses along under a small hill with a transmission tower on it. Ignore the right-hand 4wd track that goes up to the tower.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter crossing a few rustic gates you will come to an information board on your left with some local history about the are