16',17,2,1,2,1,'2009-08-30 11:07:13','calc',5),(67,'Car Parts Extension',2,'','Single track from the Brooklyn wind turbine to the entry to Long Gully Station.','This track is Stage One of a plan to build track from the [[area:3]] wind turbine to just below the summit of [[area:2]].  See [[track:294]] for the development of Stage Two.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBy sidling around the hills and valleys just below the Hawkins Hill Road, this track follows a meandering path with plenty of corners. The track surface is undulating, providing lots of variety. The track has an overall altitude loss of about 30 metres (when heading south).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a set of steep switchbacks at the northern end which will be replaced by a short connection with the section around the knob, as shown on the map.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA 0.35km long alternative route goes around the knob/ridge at the northern end and connects with [[track:24]].','Northern end is just below the [[area:3]] wind turbine car park, at the top of [[track:24]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is at a saddle point opposite the entry to Long Gully Station, where [[track:294]] will continue up towards Hawkins Hill.','','2.010',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-25 16:41:59',23,'-41.314241','174.739459',16,3,1,1,1,'2009-10-05 19:07:35','calc',5),(68,'Rimu Trail',1,'','Gentle connector between Allington Road and St. Albans Avenue.','This track was built as a gentle connection between Allington Road and St. Albans Avenue. The track is generally smooth and firm, though some of the corners are fairly tight.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust 60m from the Allington Road end is the [[track:73]], which goes up to the picnic tables on [[track:50]]. Otherwise, the track cruises along mostly under a pleasant bush canopy. Towards the St. Albans Avenue end there is a series of zigzags as the track winds down a hill, though the gradient is gentle so the track works well in either direction.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the St. Albans Avenue end it is a bit of a grind up [[track:51]], but only for 0.3km to where you\'ll find the end of [[track:6]].','Northwest end is at the end of Allington Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSoutheast end meets [[track:51]] 0.13km from the end of St. Albans Avenue.','','0.794',30,4,173,197,'when going up','','2008-10-13 20:36:15',23,'-41.292794','174.717926',17,2,1,1,1,'2010-01-13 09:49:21','calc',5),(69,'Downpipe',4,'','Wild connector to [[track:30]].','Going down the track there is a series of increasingly steep and technical drops.  The final drop, immediately after [[track:70]] branches off to the left, is ridiculously steep.','At the intersection of [[track:180]] and [[track:181]], look into the bush behind a small mound of grass-covered dirt. A few metres into the bush is a rusty road sign that says \"Extreme caution\".  They\'re not kidding.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJoins [[track:52]] 20m before connecting with [[track:30]].','Just before the steep straight chute there is a sneaky left-hander to [[track:70]].','0.267',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' and Extreme for one 10 metre section.','2008-12-24 09:51:53',23,'-41.295591','174.736326',17,5,1,1,1,'2008-12-24 09:51:53','calc',5),(70,'Evil',4,'','Squiggly \"bus stop\" alternative to the scary part of [[track:69]].','Branches off [[track:69]] at the top of its most heinous drop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNot that [[track:70]] is that much better.  The drop down to join [[track:52]] is also rather steep and sketchy - it just looks tame in comparison to [[track:69]]\'s last section.','About 230m from the top of [[track:69]], branch off to the left. If you fall down a near-vertical cliff, then you went a couple of metres too far.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJoins [[track:52]] about 120m before it connects with [[track:30]].','','0.082',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-30 20:59:01',23,'-41.295663','174.735682',17,4,1,1,1,'2008-11-30 20:59:01','calc',5),(71,'Pringles',4,'','Narrow bush connector from the top of  [[area:4]] to [[track:25]].','','To access the top head due south from the gun pit at the summit of  [[area:4]], towards the sign-post saying \"no bikes\" (referring to the track from the summit down to the top of [[track:31]]). Just 1m to the left of the sign is a tiny opening in the bush, this is it!\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track emerges from the bush to join [[track:25]] 0.25km from the top of [[track:31]].','','0.105',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-29 21:42:34',23,'-41.296647','174.739491',18,3,1,1,1,'2009-11-01 22:07:31','calc',5),(72,'Gun Pit 3',4,'','Overgrown road that was once the main above-ground access to gun pit 3.','Gun pit 3 is actually 20m off the track, hidden somewhat in the bush to the northwest. The gun pit has been almost filled in with dirt.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf going around the pit, watch out for the northeast side of the pit, as there are a couple of access holes that need to be stepped over â€“ they could act as effective traps for the unwary.','Branches off [[track:181]] and meets [[track:180]] 80m west of [[track:25]].','','0.484',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-24 10:02:54',23,'-41.298049','174.738160',17,3,1,1,1,'2009-11-01 22:16:45','calc',5),(73,'AMP Connector',1,'','Narrow connection from the top of [[track:68]] to the middle of [[track:50]].','This is a short connection between [[track:68]] and [[track:50]].  The track is narrow and has quite tight corners, which makes for an interesting time in either direction.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you\'re entering the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park via Allington Road, then this track provides a convenient way to access a variety of subsequent alternative routes.  Drop down [[track:50]] and [[track:6]] to a major intersection, from which you can head either up or down various tracks.','From the top of Allington Road follow [[track:68]] for 50m to where this track branches up to your right.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you come up [[track:68]] from the east, then you should see the sharp left-hander just before you pop out on the Allington Road (backtrack if you miss it).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of the track meets [[track:50]] at the picnic tables. From [[track:50]] look for the narrow track in the flax heading north.','','0.189',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-13 20:34:38',23,'-41.292882','174.717400',18,3,1,1,1,'2009-08-30 11:05:44','calc',5),(74,'Jungle Gym',8,'','Jungle Gym is the main track up into the Wainuiomata Trail Project.  With a gentle grade and no tricky technical obstacles, the track is suitable for a wide range of users.','[[track:74]] starts near the bottom of the valley and gently climbs to near the Wainuiomata Hill saddle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome parts of the climb are quite steep, though they\'re interspersed with sections that are flatter or even slightly downhill. There are a couple of sets of switchbacks, which account for a fair proportion of the altitude gained. An interesting feature is a chicane, where the track drops down and around an S-bend for no apparent reason other than because it can.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track has had heaps of gravel embedded in it, making for a generally firm and robust track surface, designed to withstand all weather.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top of [[track:74]], there are several alternatives.  You can proceed up or down the [[track:81]], which traverses the length of the Eastern Hutt Hills.  [[track:75]] starts from the top of [[track:74]], continuing up the hill more-or-less parallel to the [[track:81]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, turn left and travel 30m down the [[track:81]] to find the start of the downhill-only [[track:77]] track.  Climbing [[track:74]] and descending [[track:77]] makes a good combination.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:74]] (Start-3:05), then [[track:80]] (3:06-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6876522]]','Officially the track starts from the \"Wainuiomata\" sign on Wainuiomata Road.  If you need somewhere to park a vehicle, then a more convenient entrance is from the end of Waiu Street.  Take [[track:80]] from Waiu Street to [[track:74]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, the top of the track is 20m up the [[track:81]] from the Wainuiomata Road saddle car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf traveling over the Wainuiomata hill, turn left at the first roundabout in Wainuiomata and then left again into Waiu Street.  At the end of Waiu Street, follow [[track:80]] until you meet a T-intersection.  The left-hand branch is a short section that goes to the official start of [[track:74]], the right-hand branch is [[track:74]] continuing up the hill.','[[track:74]] crosses the downhill-only [[track:77]] track at about 1.0km up from the official start.  Users of [[track:74]] should give way to those on [[track:77]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:74]] is a multi-use track, though cyclists have the right of way.','1.796',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-13 12:24:45',23,'-41.246902','174.923887',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-02-06 11:05:04','calc',5),(75,'Labyrinth',8,'','Labyrinth is a twisting single-track through classic regenerating bush.  It connects the top of [[track:74]] with [[track:78]]/[[track:79]].','Labyrinth climbs from the top of [[track:74]] to the top of [[track:78]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs a purpose designed and built mountain bike track, Labyrinth has a nice flow â€“ especially when descending.  The track is quite narrow in places, and although not technically demanding it is more difficult than [[track:74]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 200m from the top of Labyrinth, you\'ll reach a short road that provides access to a power pylon.  This used to be the end of Labyrinth.  In mid-2008 the track was extended to reach [[track:78]] â€“ just continue along the track into the bush directly opposite.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Wainuiomata in the early morning mist]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/WainuiLabyrinth.jpg:Wainuiomata in the early morning mist:492:358]]\r\nThe following video is taken going in the uphill direction:\r\n[[media:vimeo:10821009]]','The bottom of the track is at the top of [[track:74]], 40m up the [[track:81]] from the Wainuiomata Road saddle car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, the top of the track is to the right of the power pylon when entering the top of [[track:78]].\r\n','Labyrinth is a multi-use track, though cyclists have the right of way.','1.008',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-07 10:29:28',177,'-41.242175','174.925132',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-11 08:58:10','calc',5),(76,'Konini Firebreak',9,'','As the name suggests, this is more of a firebreak than a track.  Nonetheless, it provides a useful and interesting connection between the [[track:81]] and the Wainuiomata valley.','The firebreak runs along a ridge from Parkway, past a water reservoir on Round Hill, then up to the [[track:81]] above Mount Towai.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough the track can be ridden in either direction, it is easier as a descent.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf heading up hill, the initial climb from Parkway is up a steep 4x4 road.  After that, the track gets progressively rougher, and occasionally steeper.  There are a few rolling hills along the way, but the inclination is generally upwards.  Most riders will need to walk/push up some of the way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf heading down from the top, there are a few sharp uphill sections, through they are short. Almost half way down there is a fire-fighting pond off to the side of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is mostly clay and bare rock.  Some of the steeper sections are deeply rutted and littered with crumbling rock, providing a challenge â€“ especially when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn several places the track splits briefly into the firebreak proper and narrower detours. The detours are easier, with some of the more direct routes being extremely steep.','The bottom of the track is accessed via a metal gate, about half way along the eastern section of Parkway.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top is reached via the [[track:81]].  There are no markings to indicate the top of the track.  If approaching from the south, look for a track to your right on a lefthand corner, about 2.3 km from the Wainuiomata Road saddle car park or 1.5 km from the top of Spoonhill.  The track goes past pylon 26.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDon\'t be fooled by a 4x4 track 0.8 km up from the top of Spoonhill â€“ it is a dead-end access track that goes to pylon 27.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf approaching from the north, along [[track:81]], then don\'t be confused by a similar looking track about 0.25km south of the bottom of [[track:162]].  That track ends at the back of a private farm off the end of Stockdale Street.','Despite signs on Parkway prohibiting motorised recreation, the area is popular with motocross riders â€“ so watch out for them.','2.964',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-07 21:25:15',23,'-41.242901','174.937277',14,4,1,3,23,'2009-10-03 20:44:02','calc',5),(77,'Beeline',8,'','Beeline is a downhill-only track with several technical challenges.','Beeline is a fast, downhill-only track from Wainuiomata Road saddle to meet [[track:176]] on the valley floor.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWith several jumps and steep drop-offs designed to test a rider\'s skill and confidence, the track presents a challenge. The top section includes a series of little bump-jumps, including doubles. Further along, there are a couple of seriously steep drops â€“ neither of which have a \"nana line\". The track ends with a pair of side-by-side wooden ramp jumps, though they can be by-passed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn the flat area around the bottom of the track there are several dirt jumps of various sizes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is actively maintained, so may change from time to time without notice.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Helmet camera video of a run down Beeline]][[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:Let4lC8WPDk]]\r\n\r\n','From the Wainuiomata Road saddle car park, jump over the metal gate.  The top of Beeline is on the right hand side, 5m past the metal gate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, from the end of Waiu Street ascend [[track:74]], then cruise 30m down the [[track:81]] to just before the metal gate.','Beeline crosses [[track:74]] about 0.2km from the bottom, so watch out for traffic at the intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeeline is a multi-use track, though cyclists have the right of way.\r\n[[para]]','0.688',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-25 00:15:15',23,'-41.245579','174.924102',16,4,1,1,23,'2010-01-01 10:39:25','calc',5),(78,'Spoonhill',8,'','Spoonhill is a downhill-only track that follows a ridge from high on Wainuiomata Hill down to the valley floor.','The track starts at the top of [[track:75]] and ends at the back of the playground on Parkway.  The [[track:81]] also passes the top of Spoonhill â€“ look out for power pylon 28 which is 30m downhill from the road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the track consists of a clay surface that is especially tricky when wet.  Not much of the track has a solid base, so deep ruts are common.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 150m down from power pylon 28, the track branches in two directions. Take [[track:79]] to the left for the moderate, all-weather track or continue on Spoonhill to the right for the difficult, dry weather track. The two tracks rejoin about 0.3km further down Spoonhill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom there is a choice between a very steep clay chute that drops straight down the hill versus an alternative line that weaves off to the left. The alternative line used to be easier, but has become deeply rutted, so the clay chute might be a better option (though not if it is wet!).','Either climb the [[track:81]] - Spoonhill starts about 0.8km from the steel entry gate - or turn right down Spoonhill from the top of [[track:75]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter exiting the track, return to Waiu Street by turning right on Parkway.  Alternatively, turn left on Parkway and follow the road around to the bottom of the [[track:76]].','Walkers have the right-of-way on this track.\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\nHelmet camera video of a run down Spoonhill[[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:5os_yZGAHGY]]\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother helmet camera video of a run down Spoonhill/[[track:79]][[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:OlEjcrMkqtQ]]','1.644',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-25 00:23:37',23,'-41.245385','174.929123',15,4,1,1,23,'2010-01-15 07:57:19','calc',5),(79,'491',8,'','491 is the easier, though still tricky, all-weather alternative to the top section of [[track:78]].','491 deviates off [[track:78]], about 150m down from power pylon 28. Take 491 to the left for the moderate, all-weather track or continue on [[track:78]] to the right for the difficult, dry weather track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEven though 491 is an easier alternative, there are still some tricky sections of track. Parts of the track are riddled with tree roots, which are especially slippery when wet. There are also small, and not-so-small, step down bits to test your skill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA particularly interesting feature is a wooden ramp on a hair-pin bend. It looks intimidating, but rides really well if you have just the right speed â€“ just watch out for the step down off the end of it. ','Take the left hand branch off [[track:78]], about 150m from pylon 28.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter 491 rejoins [[track:78]], continue down to the back of the Parkway playground.','Walkers have the right-of-way on this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track\'s name comes from the length of the track, which is apparently 491m.\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\nHelmet camera video of a run down [[track:78]] and 491[[br]]\r\nThe 491 section is from 0:41 to 2:12.[[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:5os_yZGAHGY]]\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother helmet camera video of a run down [[track:78]]/491[[br]]\r\n[[media:youtube:OlEjcrMkqtQ]]','0.456',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-25 00:26:59',23,'-41.241586','174.928823',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-10-03 21:48:42','calc',5),(80,'Jungle Scout',8,'','This track connects the open area at end of Waiu Street with [[track:74]].','[[track:80]] provides an entry to the [[area:8]].  A roughly parallel track, [[track:859]], provides the return leg of a short loop through the bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is initially almost flat, and then climbs gently to meet [[track:74]]. There is a firm hard-packed gravel surface, which makes for easy riding or walking.  Much of the track is under tree cover, which is rather pleasant.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:74]] (Start-3:05), then [[track:80]] (3:06-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6876522]]','From the end of Waiu Street, jump over the metal barrier.  Proceed across the open area, heading a little to the left. The track starts 40m southwest of where the two ends of the [[track:176]] meet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track used to go through the dirt race track (\"The Bowl\"), but since December 2008 winds its way through the bush to meet [[track:74]] at a T-intersection.','The dirt area around the end of Waiu Street is popular with motocross riders, so listen out for them when entering and leaving the area.  Re-development of this area is underway, including a car park for recreational users of the tracks, formal track signage, etc.\r\n[[para]]\r\nRenamed from \'Carpark Link\' to \'Jungle Scout\' in January 2009.','0.439',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-12 22:05:03',23,'-41.250363','174.925486',17,2,1,3,23,'2010-03-27 20:43:01','calc',5),(81,'ECNZ pylon road',9,'','This is a 4x4 road that runs the length of the Wainuiomata hills through to the hills above Stokes Valley, apart from a section in the middle which crosses private property (which can be bypassed via [[track:269]]).','This road is a popular route for a variety of recreational users.  It is primarily of interest because it provides access to a variety of tracks that branch off it, including tracks in the [[area:8]], [[area:9]], and [[area:17]] areas.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome parts of the road are quite steep, but the surface is maintained in good condition which makes the climbs a bit easier than they would be on a single track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHeading north from Mount Fitzherbert (where there is a cluster of communications towers) the road drops down a narrow 4wd track. After about 0.5km the road forks. The western fork is [[track:269]], which continues along the rolling ridgeline. The eastern fork drops down into Moores Valley, crossing private property along the way. To rejoin the northern part of this track, take the [[track:269]] track rather than dropping into the valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSimilarly, heading south there is a fork in the road about 0.8km before reaching the summit of Mount Ken. Take the northwestern road, which is the other end of the [[track:269]] track, rather than dropping into Moores Valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road was built to provide access to the high voltage transmission line that runs along the ridge â€“ originally owned by the [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electricity_Corporation_of_New_Zealand Electricity Corporation of New Zealand]], hence the track\'s name. A couple of prominent communications towers on the peaks also attract some service vehicle traffic.','The southwestern end is a steel barrier at the top of the Wainuiomata Road saddle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northeastern end is at an intersection with [[track:363]], about 0.6km south of a large clearing at the top of [[track:224]] and [[track:226]].','The road has a fair bit of traffic, being regularly used by service vehicles, horse riders, walkers, runners, and mountain bikers.','11.531',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-16 21:06:21',23,'-41.215337','174.970322',12,3,1,3,23,'2010-01-01 13:16:43','calc',5),(82,'Mount Lowry',9,'','A gnarly, root-infested climb from the Wainuiomata saddle to the summit of Mount Lowry.','Following a ridge from the Wainuiomata saddle to the summit of Mount Lowry, this is a difficult climb through classic bush-covered hills.  Much of the track is narrow and twisting, with a surface consisting of root-infested leaf detritus.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe initial short, sharp climb is followed by rolling hills for about 1km.  Then the real work begins - an altitude gain of 135m over a distance of 0.9km, at an average grade of 15%, made all the more difficult by the uneven track surface. There are a few steps and several sections where there would be steps if not for the tree roots.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe climbing effort is worthwhile, though, with a great technical descent either returning the same way or continuing on to [[track:83]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a lookout near the start of the track, plus several other lookouts along the way, providing spectacular views over Wellington harbour and the Wainuiomata valley.','The track starts on the western side of the Wainuiomata Road saddle, opposite the start of the [[track:81]] (100m along the sealed road towards Wainuiomata).','Most of the tracks that descend from this track into either Eastbourne or Wainuiomata are closed to mountain bikes.','2.862',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-08-27 07:25:52',23,'-41.255614','174.923458',14,4,1,1,23,'2008-08-27 07:25:52','calc',5),(83,'Rata Ridge',9,'','A steep descent from the summit of Mount Lowry to Wainuiomata valley.','As the name suggests, this track traverses Rata Ridge from near the summit of Mount Lowry down to the Wainuiomata valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nApart from one short climb, it is downhill essentially all the way.  Most of the descent is slow, with a narrow and uneven track surface to contend with.  Towards the Stanley Street end there is a section of wide and very steep firebreak, with a clay and bare rock surface that is extremely slippery when wet.','Continue from the [[track:82]] track or, if you like carrying your bike uphill, climb up from the end of Stanley Street, Wainuiomata.','Most of the tracks that descend from this track into either Eastbourne or Wainuiomata are closed to mountain bikes.','3.062',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-01 22:01:44',23,'-41.269872','174.934530',14,4,1,1,23,'2008-09-01 22:01:44','calc',5),(84,'Gums Loop',9,'','An pleasant entry into the Wainuiomata Waterworks Recreation Area. ','A gentle amble through gums trees and regenerating native bush, this track provides a pleasant entry to the Wainuiomata Waterworks Recreation Area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPoints of interest include picnic spots along the river and the ruins of houses used by workers during construction of the reservoir dam.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe â€œloopâ€ part of the track name refers to the option of crossing the Wainuiomata River via a pair of bridges â€“ a truss bridge near the start of the track, and a swing bridge at the end of the track â€“ and wandering along the sealed Reservoir Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTrack conditions are a mix of mostly 4x4 plus single track and open grass.\r\n','There is a car park at the end of Hine Street, next to the Memorial Garden.  Head east across the grass area to the proper start of the track.','Much of the Wainuiomata waterworks catchment area is closed to the public â€“ the Recreation Area is the main exception.','1.555',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-01 22:14:02',23,'-41.274033','174.976888',15,2,1,3,23,'2008-09-01 22:14:02','calc',5),(85,'Sledge',9,'','A combination of regenerating wetland and classic New Zealand bush.','This track starts at the end of [[track:84]].  After crossing a wetland area, the track heads up the Sledge Creek valley â€“ take the left hand branch to travel clockwise around the loop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPassing through dense native bush, the track gently climbs up the valley, following the creek for about 0.5km.  It then turns more sharply up hill for 0.2km, before descending to meet itself near the boundary of the wetland and the bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.2km from the start, there is a â€œSwimming Holeâ€ sign pointing towards the river.','Wander up [[track:84]] to an open field, where the dam construction workersâ€™ houses used to be.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a short alternative path around the southern side of the wetland, rejoining the main track just before it heads into the bush.\r\n','Much of the Wainuiomata waterworks catchment area is closed to the public â€“ the Recreation Area is the main exception.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce in the bush section of the track, typical examples of native flora are described by small information signs.\r\n','1.407',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-01 21:41:45',23,'-41.272420','174.987059',16,3,1,1,23,'2008-09-01 21:41:45','calc',5),(86,'Tana Umaga',9,'','A steep track providing great views over the Wainuiomata Waterworks Recreation Area.','Originally built in the 1970s as part of a proposed dam development for the valley, this track had become overgrown but was restored in 2007.  It branches off [[track:85]] and heads up hill for 0.4km before dropping very steeply down to [[track:84]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhile it can be traversed in either direction, the easiest direction is from [[track:85]] to [[track:84]].','The eastern end starts about 80% of the way around the [[track:85]] loop (when traveling clockwise), while the western end drops down to join [[track:84]].','Much of the Wainuiomata Waterworks catchment area is closed to the public â€“ the Recreation Area is the main exception.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is named after former All Blacks captain Tana Umuga, who was born and raised in Wainuiomata.\r\n','1.095',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-01 22:13:10',23,'-41.273597','174.983969',16,3,1,1,23,'2008-09-01 22:13:10','calc',5),(87,'Zigzag',9,' (Opened to mountain bikes in 2007)','A steep connector from [[track:83]] to Fraser Street.','This track provides an alternative exit from [[track:83]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe upper part of the track is more like a fire break.  As you descend, the track gets narrower, ending with a very steep gravel path consisting of several zigzags - which give the track its name.\r\n','If descending [[track:83]], then youâ€™ll encounter a T-intersection about three quarters of the way down.  The Zigzag track is clearly marked where it heads off to the left.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Fraser Street end of the track is clearly marked.  The sign by the street indicates no mountain bikes, but a newer sign just up the path shows that mountain bikes are permitted.','Be aware that there are two very steep, smooth clay and bare rock sections which are extremely slippery when wet.','0.895',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:41:12',23,'-41.266227','174.945087',16,3,1,2,23,'2008-12-19 20:41:12','calc',5),(88,'98 Downhill',6,'','Course used for the Wellington round of the 1998 national mountain biking championships.','This track was used as the downhill course of the 1998 national mountain biking championships.  It is a steep track through mature pine forest, consisting of short, fast sections and technical challenges such as rock obstacles, tree roots, and a 1m drop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHalf of the way down there is a set of steps which have a bypass to the left. At the bottom of the steps, turn sharply to the left, rather than following the more obvious track straight down the hill (ie. [[track:318]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nWith construction of [[track:316]] in 2008/09, the bottom end of [[track:88]] was realigned and extended further south, so that it now exits near the bottom of [[track:35]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track had fallen into a state of disrepair.  There were several large trees across the track, making it unridable without dismounting.  With work from volunteers and the Wellington City Council, the track was cleared in late 2008.','From the top of [[track:35]], proceed about 75m to an intersection â€“ [[track:35]] is marked by signs pointing to the right, while the 98 downhill track goes straight ahead then turns right another 75m further along.','The Google map shows a track that approximates the [[link:http://www.downhill.co.nz/events/nzchamps/1998/info/wgtn-dh-course.gif actual 1998 downhill course]].','0.630',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-24 15:09:00',23,'-41.282588','174.722185',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-07-26 19:18:23','calc',5),(89,'Pencarrow',10,'','A gravel road that provides access to the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/parangarahu-lakes-area/ Parangarahu Lakes]] block of the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/east-harbour-regional-park-3/ East Harbour Regional Park]].','A gentle, though fairly long, gravel road from Eastbourne to the lower lighthouse on Pencarrow Head.\r\n[[para]]\r\nUnlike most parts of Wellington, the road is flat â€“ it follows the rocky beach and deviates no more that a couple of metres in elevation.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis road is very popular with walkers and bikers, being especially busy on fine, calm days.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the Lower Lighthouse, continue towards [[track:90]] for access to the [[track:97]].  Alternatively, wander inland for loops around Lake [[track:93]] or Lake [[track:94]], including [[track:92]] and [[track:98]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Seagulls seen against the setting sun, just north of the Lower Lighthouse]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/SeagullsAtSunsetPencarrow.jpg:Seagulls seen against the setting sun:492:328]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Lower Lighthouse during late afternoon]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/PencarrowLighthouse.jpg:Lower Lighthouse during late afternoon:492:328]]','Start at the large car park at the end of Muritai Road, Eastbourne. Proceed through Burdans Gate and follow the gravel road along the Wellington Harbour coastline.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a locked steel gate 250m from Burdens Gate, but some vehicles have access so watch out for them.','Being an exposed coastal road, it is probably best to avoid this area when there is a strong northerly wind, otherwise the return trip to Eastbourne can be a hard slog.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDogs are prohibited along the coastal road during the lambing season, from 1 August to 31 October each year. At all other times dogs must be kept on a leash.','6.808',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:37:36',23,'-41.334158','174.862175',13,2,1,4,23,'2009-09-30 20:37:06','calc',5),(90,'Baring Head',10,'','Gravel road from Pencarrow Head to Baring Head.','Traversing Fitzroy Bay this road provides access to the popular rock climbing area around Baring Head.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road gets progressively rougher, eventually degenerating into little more than a rough 4x4 track.  For the last 200m the road almost disappears entirely, with a soft sand surface that is extremely difficult to ride when dry.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt least 40 shipwrecks have been recorded along the coastline between Eastbourne and Baring Head. The small, steel-hulled steamer Paiaka, which was wrecked in 1906, is beside the road 450m past the outlet of Lake Kohangatera.','Start from the end of [[track:89]] at Pencarrow Head. Return the same way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe total return distance from Eastbourne to Baring Head is about 29km.','Much of the road passes through private land, so stay on the road.','7.078',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-06 10:25:29',23,'-41.384279','174.875221',13,2,1,4,23,'2008-09-06 10:25:29','calc',5),(91,'Bluff Point',10,'','Short grassy track to Bluff Point lookout over Lake Kohangapiripiri.','A short detour from the [[track:97]] track, providing a lookout over Lake Kohangapiripiri.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe grassy track is a bit indistinct in places - just keep heading towards the Bluff Point sign that is visible from almost all of the track.','Branches off [[track:97]], at the last flat area near the top.  Return the same way.','','0.555',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:34:13',23,'-41.361027','174.851832',16,3,1,1,23,'2008-12-19 20:34:13','calc',5),(92,'Cameron Ridge',10,'','Traverses the ridge between Lake Kohangapiripiri and Lake Kohangatera.','A grassy track that climbs through farmland to the ridge between Lake Kohangapiripiri and Lake Kohangatera.  With great views of the lakes, and beyond, this is a very picturesque area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track can be ridden either as a diversion from [[track:90]], or as part of loops around either or both of the lakes.  At a clearly sign posted major intersection, head north along [[track:93]] or drop down to the right for [[track:95]].','This track can be ridden in either direction, though it is easiest to go along [[track:90]] past Lake Kohanapiripiri to immediately before the Lake Kohangatera outlet, where the track is initially a 4x4 road that goes up the hill.  Follow that road, which soon becomes grassy, to the ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt a sign posted intersection, turn left to go up a bit and then down a very steep descent to the eastern shore of Lake Kohanapiripiri and then back to [[track:90]] 1.1 km from where you started.','','3.034',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:34:59',23,'-41.367244','174.861102',15,3,1,1,23,'2009-10-17 13:21:04','calc',5),(93,'Kohangapiripiri',10,'','Interesting single track around the shores of Lake Kohangapiripiri.','Lake Kohangapiripiri is an important ecological area, consisting of a freshwater lake and associated wetland area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track continues along the ridge from the point where [[track:92]] drops down to the lake. Having rumbled along the ridge for a while, this track drops down to the Cameron Creek wetland, crossing it via a 70m long boardwalk (marked with signs warning about the deep water). The boardwalk includes a sheep-stop grill towards the western end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThereafter the track skirts the western lake shore except for a short, sharp climb and then descent over a ridge that juts out into the lake.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is generally smooth and wide, with boggy bits either bridged or filled with gravel to create a firm surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA short detour is available up to the Lake Kohangapiripiri lookout, as shown on the map. [[track:295]] continues up hill from the lookout sign.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is possible â€“ on foot only â€“ to bypass the short, sharp climb/descent near the western end. A sheep track that goes around the shoreline can be walked fairly easily, except for the rocky point which requires a bit of scrambling.','The western end can be found by travelling 0.8km past the Lower Pencarrow Lighthouse, along [[track:90]]. If you cross the outlet of Lake Kohangapiripiri then you\'ve gone too far. At that point [[track:97]] is a gravel road that veers off to the left, so follow that for 0.7km to where this track crosses the wetland and heads around the lake.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, to find the eastern end, climb to the top of [[track:92]] and keep going north until you find the sign posted end of this track.','','3.087',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-12 21:34:23',23,'-41.359707','174.857798',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-02-28 09:13:27','calc',5),(94,'Kohangatera',10,'','Gentle and picturesque meander around the eastern shore of Lake Kohangatera.','A picturesque cruise around the eastern shore of Lake Kohangatera and its inland wetland.  About 0.3km past the boardwalk that crosses the wetland, the track ends suddenly with a Private Property sign.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEither return to [[track:90]] the same way, or go back to the boardwalk and go up to the [[track:95]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor a demanding detour, climb [[track:98]] for great views over Lake Kohangatera and the surrounding hills.\r\n','2.5km along [[track:90]], 50m past the Lake Kohangatera outlet, turn left through a gate.  If you get to a driveway that comes down the hill past Lake Kohangatera, then youâ€™ve gone 250m too far.\r\nAfter going 150m past the entry gate, cross the paddock towards the right.  Then turn left through another gate and follow the track around the lake shore.\r\n','Although still considered to be a freshwater water lake, Lake Kohangatera is slightly more brackish than Lake [[track:93]].  ','3.340',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-09 19:45:48',23,'-41.365601','174.868269',14,2,1,1,23,'2008-09-09 19:45:48','calc',5),(95,'Kohangatera Lookout',10,'','Steep climb to a lookout over Lake Kohangatera.','Short but demanding climb to the summit of a prominent hill overlooking Lake Kohangatera.  Although it is hard work, the effort is worthwhile because the lookout offers great views of Lake Kohangatera and its wetland.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track connects Lake Kohanapiripiri and Lake Kohangatera, providing opportunities for doing a loop around both lakes.','From the [[track:92]] end of Lake [[track:93]] drop down to lake level and then climb up a steep, grassy track to the lookout over Lake Kohangatera.  From there, backtrack 40m and follow the recently added connection towards Lake Kohangatera via a very steep descent.  Cross the wetland via a 100m long boardwalk.','This used to be a dead-end track, from [[track:93]] and back.  With the addition in late 2007 of a short section of track and boardwalk across the wetland, it is now possible to circumnavigate Lake Kohangatera.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf traveling anti-clockwise around the Lake Kohangatera, youâ€™ll have two steep climbs to complete, so probably best to go from the [[track:92]] end.\r\n','2.074',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-09-09 19:52:06',23,'-41.358579','174.870844',15,3,1,2,23,'2008-09-09 19:52:06','calc',5),(96,'Lighthouse Shortcut',10,'','Dicey cliff face shortcut to/from the [[track:97]].','This steep and narrow track slides diagonally across a cliff face, with the adjacent near vertical drop helping to focus the mind.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBikers usually take this route on the way down from the [[track:97]].  You might encounter walkers going up, which can be interesting in places because there is no room to pass.','On [[track:89]], about 750m before the Lower Lighthouse, you\'ll see a narrow track heading up the cliff â€“ that\'s it.  If you get to a cattle stop in the road, you\'ve gone about 100m too far south.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen descending [[track:97]], climb over the stile at the saddle point about half way down [[track:97]].','','0.221',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:36:27',23,'-41.354818','174.852133',17,3,1,1,23,'2010-02-28 09:17:59','calc',5),(97,'Light house track',10,'','Climb up to the Upper Lighthouse for spectacular views over Wellington Harbour and Cook Strait.','Climbing up to the Upper Lighthouse adds a bit of spice to the relatively sedate [[track:89]] journey.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe first half of the climb from the [[track:90]] 4wd road is easy, while the second half is steeper (though in bite-size sections).  The effort is worthwhile, as the lighthouse offers stunning views of Wellington harbour and Cook Strait.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere used to be deep scouring around the base of the lighthouse, giving an indication of the wild weather sometimes seen in this area.  This was repaired in early 2010, with the placement of large natural paving stones.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the last flat area before the summit, you can take a detour to [[track:91]] lookout.','Either ascend [[track:96]] from [[track:89]] or proceed 0.8km along [[track:90]] then turn left and follow the western shore of the lake.  After about 0.7km [[track:93]] crosses the wetland to the right, while continuing up the valley will take you to the saddle point which is also the top of [[track:96]]. From there, head up towards the upper lighthouse.','The Pencarrow lighthouses were opened in 1859, in response to the frequent shipwrecks along this coastal region.  They were New Zealand\'s first permanent lighthouses.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThree-quarters of the way up the hill, and overlooking the harbour, there is a small white fenced area that marks the grave of a lighthouse keeper\'s daughter.','1.822',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:37:26',23,'-41.360351','174.852626',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-02-28 09:17:42','calc',5),(98,'Valley View Hill',10,'','Very steep climb to Valley View Hill lookout, which provides great views over Lake Kohangatera and the surrounding hills.','Demanding climb to the summit of Valley View Hill via a rough 4x4 track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe lookout provides great views over Lake Kohangatera and the surrounding hills to the north and east.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe climb is slightly less difficult from the southern end, so usually done from that direction.  Either return the same way, or continue down the other side of the hill to rejoin Lake Kohangatera 0.8km from where it meets the [[track:95]] boardwalk.\r\n','About 0.6km from [[track:94]]\'s entry gate on [[track:90]], take the steep track up the hill to the right.','','1.663',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:38:12',23,'-41.367501','174.873333',15,3,1,2,23,'2008-12-19 20:38:12','calc',5),(99,'Cornish Street',11,'','Gentle stroll from Petone to the Korokoro Dam.','A pleasant and gentle single track that follows the Korokoro stream from Petone up to the disused Korokoro Dam.  The track more-or-less follows, and is often directly built upon, the pipe that used to deliver water from the dam to Petone and beyond.  There is a smaller dam along the way to the upper dam.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome sections of track are narrow with a near-vertical drop to the stream, so some caution is advised.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is popular with walkers, though in many places there is no room to pass and there are many blind corners, so a sedate pace would be in order.','The track starts at the end of Cornish Street, Petone.  Either return the same way, or take one of the more difficult climbs that will take you further into the Belmont Regional Park â€“ such as [[track:150]], [[track:110]], or [[track:552]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track is also used as an exit from the Belmont Regional Park, usually via [[track:151]] and [[track:150]].','The upper dam is almost completely filled with soft, deep silt such that there is only about 0.5m of water behind the dam.','4.049',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 20:02:44',122,'-41.209074','174.863462',14,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-17 17:54:29','calc',5),(100,'Belmont Trig',11,'','Gravel road from Stratton Street to the summit of Belmont Trig.','Belmont Trig provides spectacular views over the [[area:11]] and beyond, including the South Island on a good day.  The climb is hard work, but the views are worthwhile.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is a steep gravel road which forms part of a loop that includes [[track:152]], [[track:112]], and [[track:111]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the summit, exit options include:\r\n[[bullet:A fast descent down [[track:100]] to Stratton Street.]]\r\n[[bullet:Descend into the Horokiwi Valley via [[track:151]], [[track:148]], or [[track:190]].]]\r\n[[bullet: Continue around the hill tops via [[track:152]].]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust for fun, there is also a short â€“ though extremely steep â€“ shortcut from the summit that runs north almost straight down the hill from the trig to the main track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.8km from the bottom the walking-only [[track:552]] track heads off to the south.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Sunset as seen from the Belmont Trig, looking towards the South Island]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/SunsetBelmontTrig.jpg:Sunset as seen from the Belmont Trig, looking towards the South Island:492:380]]','Go through the gate next to the cattle stop on Stratton Street.  Cross the small bridge, then look to the left, where there is a 4x4 road up the hill - that\'s it.  The start is very steep, but the rest isn\'t quite so bad.','','2.833',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 19:52:36',23,'-41.184145','174.881101',15,3,1,3,23,'2009-10-24 21:53:12','calc',5),(101,'Boulder Hill',11,'','Climb from the Hutt Valley to the summit of Boulder Hill.','A 400m climb from the floor of the Hutt Valley to the summit of Boulder Hill.  Parts of the track are steep, especially towards the summit, though there is a flatish section in the middle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is plenty of variety in terms of track surface â€“ ranging from a well-formed gravel road on the lower sections, through to a grassy 4x4 track in the middle, and ending with a barely defined single track for the final section to the summit.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe summit of Boulder Hill is littered with exposed boulders â€“ hence the name.  A heap of small rocks have been collected to mark the summit with a sizable cairn.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:A cairn marking the summit of Boulder Hill]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/CairnBoulderHill.jpg:A cairn marking the summit of Boulder Hill:492:349]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Thistle encased in a spider nest on Boulder Hill]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/ThistleBoulderHill.jpg:Transmission towers to the west of Skyline:492:453]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following video starts at the car park\'s information board, heads out to Hebden Crescent, then up the 4x4 access road, past the top of the zig-zag track, then up the track towards Boulder Hill.  At 3:12 the video deviates onto the [[track:106]] track.\r\n[[media:vimeo:7410408]]','The track starts from [[area:11]]\'s Dry Creek entrance, off State Highway 2.  From the car park climb up the short zig-zag track next to the information board, and then turn right up the 4x4 road.  Alternatively, the 4x4 road provides a less steep access off Hebden Crescent (parallel with State Highway 2), meeting a metal gate just below the top of the zig-zag track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of this track is at the summit of Boulder Hill.','Where the transmission line crosses the track there is a steep, 250m long alternative track that takes a short-cut down the hill â€“ probably best taken as a descent.','4.566',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-01 09:37:12',23,'-41.156492','174.954271',14,3,1,3,23,'2010-01-05 13:12:31','calc',5),(102,'Bridleway',11,'','A gentle meander along the valley floor following a steep descent from [[track:111]].','This is a track of two halves.  The northern half is a steep 210m descent from [[track:111]].  Conversely, the southern half of the track is a gentle meander along the valley floor to the base of the [[track:100]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern section is a very steep descent, with a gradient typically around 25%. The track surface is mostly grass, with rock and clay patches adding some technical spice. To provide a bit of variety, there are a couple of short, though very steep, up hill sections. The first ascent climbs up from a deep, dark valley that looks like it gets little or no direct sunlight during winter.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn some parts of the southern section the track is not well defined, being more open field than track as such.  A couple of the creek crossings are not bridged, so can have quite deep mud at times.\r\n','The northern end of this track is next to the farm gate across [[track:111]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end heads up the valley from the paddock next to the Stratton Street cattle stop, at the bottom of the [[track:100]] track.','','2.312',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','/Advanced','2008-11-09 21:28:02',23,'-41.177750','174.890757',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-10-26 12:25:19','calc',5),(103,'Cannons Creek',11,'','Steep climb from Cannons Creek Shopping Centre to Takapu Road substation.','Starting from the Cannons Creek Shopping Centre, the track is initially a smooth and flat path next to the lakes in the Cannons Creek Lake Reserve.  There is then a short, sharp climb to a grassy clearing.  The track continues down to the right, crossing a walk bridge over Cannons Creek before again climbing steeply for almost 0.6km to a gate.  Climb over the stile, then head left and follow the track to the end of Takapu Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the end of Takapu Road, you can make your way further into the [[area:11]] - eventually making a traverse from Porirua to Petone, if you\'re really keen.','Make your way to the back of the Cannons Creek Shopping Centre - the track starts in the southeast corner of the car park.  You can wander along the paths either side of the Cannons Creek Lake Reserve, since the paths converge just before heading up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, the top of the track is at the end of Takapu Road, just north of the substation, at the western end of [[track:158]].','','2.101',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 19:55:12',23,'-41.148220','174.868526',14,3,1,1,23,'2009-10-26 19:44:14','calc',5),(104,'Cottle',11,'','Shortcut from Cottle Park Drive to Stratton Street.','Steep short-cut from Cottle Park Drive to Stratton Street, or vice versa.  It is about half the length of taking the sealed road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nParts of the track are very steep, so may require some walking if ascending.  Conversely, the steep bits are great fun when descending.\r\n','The top of the track is through a small wooden gate (marked with a horse shoe) on a corner near the top of Cottle Park Drive.  The bottom of the track is about half way along Stratton Street, and also has a small wooden gate.','If descending from Cottle Park Drive, watch out for the gate about half way down.  Also note that the track appears to be frequented by pony-trekkers, so try to not scare the horses.','1.014',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-27 16:40:06',23,'-41.190362','174.893932',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-03-27 16:40:06','calc',5),(105,'Danzig',11,'','Classic tight single track through mature hillside forest.','A great piece of classic single track which winds its way through a block of mature forest on a steep hillside.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDanzig provides a good way to ascend to the Park\'s hilltop tracks - such as [[track:111]], [[track:112]], [[track:152]], and [[track:100]] - as part of a circuit that starts and ends at Stratton Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is a combination of soft clay, tree roots, and pine needles, with a few rocks thrown in for variety. By the end of winter the track surface is usually deeply rutted, especially on the switchbacks.  By that stage, climbing is difficult and descending quickly is technically challenging.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHalf way along the track is a green hut, which also marks the start of [[track:142]].','The bottom of the track is 250m past the Ranger Station at the end of Stratton Road, past some farm buildings and 50m beyond the gate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of the track is 1.5 km along [[track:111]], measured from the end of Normandale Road - or less than 100m past the entry to [[track:114]].','Danzig crosses [[track:116]] about 350m from the bottom, so watch out for riders descending in a barely controlled free fall.','1.692',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-22 22:25:30',23,'-41.177394','174.895198',16,3,1,1,23,'2008-11-22 22:25:30','calc',5),(106,'Dry Creek',11,'','Mixed single track and steep 4x4 road, providing a loop around the Dry Creek valley.','This track is divided into six distinct stages, travelling clockwise from the [[track:101]] (western) end:\r\n[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:Gentle single track meanders through bush and open country.]]\r\n[[bullet:A change in character sees the track get narrower, more technical, and steeper â€“ abruptly dropping almost 100m to a small bridge over Dry Creek.]]\r\n[[bullet:Steep climb to meet a 4x4 farm road, which is about 2.0km from [[track:101]]. Continue heading clockwise â€“ the road in the other direction ends after 0.4km at a locked gate marked with a \"Private property - keep out\" sign.]]\r\n[[bullet:The 4x4 road drops a little and then continues climbing up Haywards Hill (though not to the summit) at an intially rather steep average gradient of 18%.]]\r\n[[bullet:From the highest point, the 4x4 road drops 250m down to the valley floor.  Soon after the descent starts you\'ll pass the western end of [[track:560]], next to a pylon. Beware that the last 0.5km of the descent is particularly brake-sizzling â€“ watch out for ruts and loose gravel.]]\r\n[[bullet:Finally, there is a gentle path on which to unwind as you cruise back to the car park.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following video includes the climb from the car park towards Boulder Hill before joining the Dry Creek Loop.\r\n[[media:vimeo:7410408]]','Western end is 3.0km up the [[track:101]] track.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end starts from the car park, follows a gentle path for 350m into the valley, then heads up a steep 4x4 road to the right.','Easiest done in a clockwise direction, in association with the first part of [[track:101]].','5.200',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 19:57:59',177,'-41.152097','174.957533',14,3,1,3,23,'2009-11-04 15:45:10','calc',5),(107,'Hill Road',11,'','Farm track from Hill Road into the heart of the [[area:11]].','This is an easy climb from the end of Hill Road to an intersection with [[track:134]] and [[track:158]], thereby providing access to other parts of the [[area:11]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several potential loops that include [[track:107]], such as:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:107]] â€“ right into [[track:134]] â€“ first section of [[track:135]] â€“ [[track:109]] (which ends just above the Hill Road car park).]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:107]] â€“ left into [[track:158]] â€“ [[track:111]] â€“ [[track:114]] (which ends 1.5km downhill from the Hill Road car park).]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:107]] â€“ left into [[track:158]] â€“ [[track:111]] â€“ then back to [[track:107]] via either [[track:179]] or [[track:155]].]]','At the top of the sealed part of Hill Road is an automatic gate, followed by a short gravel section that ends in a car parking area.  The track is the obvious gravel road that heads up the valley from the car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of the track is at an intersection with [[track:158]] (to the west) and [[track:134]] (to the east).  Only 50m west of the intersection there is a gas pumping station â€“ apparently it is normal to smell gas in that vicinity.','It is easy to gain a lot of speed when descending the straight parts of [[track:107]], so watch out for farm vehicles and other track users.','2.395',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 19:48:52',23,'-41.167800','174.905777',15,2,1,4,23,'2009-08-09 08:50:20','calc',5),(108,'Kaitangata',11,'','Connector from [[track:101]] to Kaitangata Crescent.','This is a narrow and, in places, rough piece of track that provides an alternative exit from [[track:101]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nKaitangata Crescent, at the end of Kelson, is the subject of active housing development. What impact, if any, that development has on this track remains to be seen.','About 0.6km from the top of [[track:101]] this track branches off down hill towards Kaitangata Crescent.','','1.885',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-23 20:35:41',23,'-41.158560','174.940710',15,3,1,1,23,'2008-10-23 20:35:41','calc',5),(109,'Kilmister',11,'','Traverse across the Kilmister Block of the [[area:11]].','From the northern end, this track more-or-less follows a creek down the valley at the heart of the Kilmister Block of [[area:11]].  There are places where the track is not well defined, but the valley is quite narrow so you can\'t go too far wrong.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter crossing the creek or its tributaries ten times, there is an obvious intersection:\r\n[[bullet:The eastern branch, across the creek, is the bottom of [[track:136]] â€“ a very steep track that drops down from near the summit of Boulder Hill (probably best done as a descent).]]\r\n[[bullet:The western branch is the continuation of [[track:109]].]]\r\nHead up the steep hill to the west and then down a long and winding farm road to a Y-intersection at the first of another series of stream crossings. Cross the concrete ford and turn right.  There are another five stream crossings as you head up a narrow gully that climbs steeply to eventually emerge next to the [[track:107]] car park. This is a tough climb â€“ expect to do some bike pushing/carrying in this section, whichever direction you\'re travelling in.','The northern end is just off [[track:134]], on the way up to Boulder Hill via [[track:135]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthwestern end is at the bottom of the [[track:107]] track, a few metres from the car park (on the right-hand side as you head up hill).','','4.998',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 20:02:05',23,'-41.163729','174.919939',14,4,1,2,23,'2009-10-26 11:53:49','calc',5),(110,'Oakleigh West',11,'','Connector from [[track:99]] Dam to Oakleigh Street.','After a leisurely climb to the upper [[track:99]] Dam, there are only two options - return the same way or climb this steep path to Oakleigh Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough there are a few steps along the way, and no concessions such as switchbacks to ease the grade, the incline is mercifully short.\r\n[[para]]\r\nGiven its pleasant bush surroundings, this track is understandably popular with walkers and runners, so watch out for them.','This track starts at the highest point of [[track:99]], just above the upper dam, and ends at the western side of [[area:11]]\'s Oakleigh Street car park.','','0.889',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-22 21:48:16',23,'-41.199937','174.873161',16,3,1,2,23,'2009-08-16 09:40:03','calc',5),(111,'OCR Belmont',11,'','Continuation of the Old Coach Road through [[area:11]].','A cruisy and mostly gentle entry to the [[area:11]], providing access to a variety of other tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround the highest point of the track there are a couple of grassy rolling hills.  The track goes straight up the hills, which are rather steep. So, as shown on the map, there are two alternative routes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe easier alternative is to follow a 0.75km long enhanced sheep track that sidles around the eastern side of the hills.  When heading north, follow the sheep track about 40m past the sign that says \"Please use poled track\". The sheep track is narrow, but more-or-less flat so much easier than the hills it bypasses. The sheep track rejoins the main track between a bunker and an green electrical transformer box at the intersection with [[track:112]] â€“ so if heading south then veer off to the left along the sheep track at that point rather than going up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOn the other hand, the views from the hill tops are spectacular and the descents are great fun. The climbs are hard work though.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end of the track crosses an airstrip.','Start from Normandale Road, which ends with a small parking area. The northern end intersects with the [[track:158]] track.','This track follows part of the original coach route into Wellington. Another section of the original [[track:160]] exists as a link between Johnsonville and Ohariu.','4.772',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-29 19:47:01',23,'-41.172710','174.899426',14,2,1,3,23,'2009-10-22 21:00:37','calc',5),(112,'Round Knob',11,'','Short, steep climb to the summit of Round Knob.','Round Knob, as the name suggests, is an approximately circular hill top that affords great views over the [[area:11]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nTechnically the track doesn\'t actually go up to the summit of Round Knob, but rather just skirts around the side.  Ignore the lack of a track and go to the summit anyway. Then enjoy the challenge of riding down the very steep rippled hillside surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the [[track:111]] intersection there is an short though intimidating looking initial section that runs straight up the hill. Instead of taking the direct route, follow the easier sheep trails that zig-zig up the hill - those sheep ain\'t dumb.','This track branches off [[track:111]], at a clearly marked major intersection on a saddle point below Round Knob.','','1.042',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-29 19:49:28',23,'-41.161484','174.893396',16,3,1,3,23,'2009-03-29 19:49:28','calc',5),(113,'Stratton',11,'','Very steep connector from [[track:111]] to Stratton Street.','More of a firebreak than anything else, this track skirts around the northern edge of the forest block.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is very steep, due to its direct route down the hill.  But unlike [[track:116]], there is plenty of traction due to the rocky surface - so the track is surprisingly ridable.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHalf way down there is a gap in the trees. [[track:153]] ends just inside the tree line, and [[track:154]] leads to the centre of the forest at the nexus of [[track:116]], [[track:105]] and [[track:142]].','Where [[track:111]] emerges from the forest, under the transmission lines, take a hard left down the hill at the \"Stratton Street\" sign.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the bottom of the hill the track joins [[track:102]].','','0.510',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-29 20:08:21',23,'-41.176377','174.895928',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-03-29 20:08:21','calc',5),(114,'Sweetacres',11,'','Steep connector from [[track:111]] to Hill Road.','After a short, steep, climb from [[track:111]], this track winds its way down through Sweetacres reserve.  There are a couple of particularly steep parts - near the summit, and the initial section just above Hill Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the upper grassy section there are great views over the Hutt Valley and towards Wellington Harbour.  But keep an eye on the track, as it is quite rough in places.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe lower sections pass through regenerating bush, with a few tight switchbacks to slow down your descent.\r\n','One end of the track is signposted on [[track:111]] as \"Hill Road\", about 1.5km from the end of Normandale Road - just before the top of [[track:105]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe other end of the track is on Hill Road, opposite the school and up hill a few metres.','','1.898',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-01 09:43:06',23,'-41.181303','174.906592',15,3,1,1,23,'2008-11-01 09:43:06','calc',5),(115,'Takapu Ridge',11,'','Very steep climb straight up Takapu Ridge towards [[track:100]].','Officially this is a tramping track, meaning that it is very steep and for most of the way it crosses open paddock where there isn\'t actually a track.  Just keep pointing up/down the ridge and you can\'t go too wrong.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough it is a difficult climb, it can be made easier by zig-zagging between the fences.  Riding down can also be difficult, due to the rough surface, but tremendous fun.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf descending, watch out for the chicane under the trees.  Going straight instead of turning will take you behind a farm building - if so, just back-track a bit and drop onto the farm road through a gate under the trees, then carry on.','If starting from the end of Takapu Road, go past the substation and follow the farm road around to the right.  About 400m past the substation, on a sharp right-hand corner, follow the sign pointing up the ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top intersects with [[track:152]].','','1.356',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-27 16:58:01',23,'-41.164279','174.873161',15,3,1,6,23,'2009-03-27 16:58:01','calc',5),(116,'The Slide',11,'','Hard, smooth clay chute straight down a steep hillside.','For those who like flying uncontrollably down a ridiculously steep track towards mature pine trees, [[track:116]] is the place to be.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThrow in a track surface that â€“ particularly on the bottom half â€“ consists mostly of smooth, hard-packed clay, with a layer of pine needles providing the only traction, and what more could you ask for?\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough [[track:116]] and [[track:105]] start and end at the same altitude, [[track:116]] is much, much steeper because it goes essentially straight down the hill.  Excluding a couple of flattish bits, the chutes are at a grade of 30%+.  Overall, the track drops almost 200m over a length of less that 900m.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBut seriously â€“ this is a track for dry weather only.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vorb:116472]]','[[track:116]] runs roughly parallel to [[track:105]], typically being 30-50m north except where they cross towards the bottom.  Entrance is 10m north of [[track:105]] on [[track:111]]. Exit is 60m south of [[track:105]] on [[track:102]].','Down hill only.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:116]] crosses [[track:105]] about 100m from the bottom.  You\'ll probably not even notice the intersection, due to your adrenalin-induced tunnel vision as you hurtle towards the inevitable.','0.817',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-29 20:22:56',23,'-41.176813','174.895070',16,4,1,1,23,'2009-08-12 22:34:05','calc',5),(117,'Koru Shortcut',1,'','Shortcut up the hill off [[track:1]].','Steep shortcut that skips several of the switchbacks on the lower part of [[track:1]].','When heading up [[track:1]], the shortcut is marked on the right hand side before the first set of switchbacks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of the shortcut rejoins [[track:1]] just before the chainring tree.','Back when [[track:1]] was a two-way track, this shortcut provided a quicker route back to the car park.  Now it is only slightly quicker than climbing the switchbacks.','0.140',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-04 13:00:10',23,'-41.300870','174.721091',17,3,1,1,23,'2008-10-04 13:00:10','calc',5),(118,'Waitangirua Ridge',11,'','Grassy ridgeline alternative to the top part of [[track:107]].','For most of its length this track has a grassy surface.  Combining the occasional herd of cattle with a bit of rain makes for a challenging mix of deep mud and \"landmines\".  At a saddle point there\'s a gate that is especially prone to extreme muckiness â€“ best to jump the fence to avoid that area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough this track can be ridden in either direction, it is easier as a descent from [[track:134]], providing an alternative to the upper parts of [[track:107]].  If climbing from [[track:107]], the initial climb isn\'t as steep as it looks, though some parts further up are a bit steeper.','The northern (top) end of the track heads up between the radio masts from the intersection of [[track:107]], [[track:134]], and [[track:158]]. An alternative entry is down [[track:134]], almost 0.3km east of the intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern (bottom) end of the track is about 0.8km from the bottom of [[track:107]], at a sign-posted track on the eastern side of the road.\r\n[[para]]','At the top of the hill is a collection of radio masts, each of which has its own fenced-off area. Further up there is a trig marker, though the track goes around the hill rather than up to the summit.','2.546',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 20:13:18',23,'-41.166445','174.908144',15,3,1,2,23,'2009-10-23 07:40:31','calc',5),(119,'Strand Park',12,'','East bank: Hutt Estuary Bridge to Melling Bridge.','Paved cycleway that passes under the Ewen Bridge and the Ava Rail Bridge on its way from Petone to Melling.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:120]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:132]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:133]] on the opposite bank to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:131]] on the opposite bank to the north]]\r\n','Southern end is at the Hutt Estuary Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Melling Bridge.','','3.697',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 20:24:44',23,'-41.220761','174.900627',13,1,1,5,23,'2009-09-20 22:02:46','calc',5),(120,'Kennedy Good',12,'','East bank: Melling Bridge to Kennedy Good Bridge.','Mostly a gravel path with a short section of gravel road towards the northern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAccess to the Kennedy Good Bridge is via a short track through the bush on the north-eastern side of the bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:121]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:119]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:131]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:132]] on the opposite bank to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:130]] on the opposite bank to the north]]','Southern end is at the Melling Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Kennedy Good Bridge.','','2.484',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 20:24:31',23,'-41.199452','174.917622',14,1,1,2,23,'2009-09-20 21:35:08','calc',5),(121,'Silverstream',12,'','East bank: Kennedy Good Bridge to Silverstream Bridge.','Relatively long section of track, with a variety of surface conditions. Most of the track has a gravel surface, with some gravel road, and a short section is asphalt paving.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOpposite the Manor Park golf course there is an interesting piece of track that swoops along below the Eastern Hutt Road. After 0.5km you\'ll have the choice of a short climb back up to the Eastern Hutt Road or drifting off to the river\'s edge (the map shows the latter option).\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:122]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:129]] on the opposite bank to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:120]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:131]] on the opposite bank to the south]]','Southern end is at the Kennedy Good Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Silverstream Bridge.','','8.037',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 21:38:46',23,'-41.168188','174.963284',13,1,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 14:24:52','calc',5),(122,'Moonshine',12,'','East bank: Silverstream Bridge to Moonshine Bridge.','A mix of gravel track and gravel road, with some paved road at the northern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 50m south of the Moonshine Bridge there is a deep and wide dip in the track that provides a bit of a whoop when hit at speed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:123]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:121]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:129]] on the opposite bank]]','Southern end is at the Silverstream Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Moonshine Bridge.','','4.240',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 20:23:55',23,'-41.133547','175.018902',14,1,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 14:25:09','calc',5),(123,'Totara Park',12,'','East bank: Moonshine Bridge to Totara Park Bridge.','Mostly gravel road but with a short section of single track and 0.7km of open grassed area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:124]] to the northeast]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:122]] to the southwest]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:129]] on the opposite bank to the southwest]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:128]] on the opposite bank to the northeast]]','Southern end is at the Moonshine Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Totara Park Bridge.','','3.976',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 21:19:00',23,'-41.116219','175.059071',14,1,1,4,23,'2010-04-04 08:16:28','calc',5),(124,'Maoribank',12,'','East bank: Totara Park Bridge to Maoribank footbridge.','Initially the southern part of the track is a gravel road.  It then turns into a paved path before crossing a large wooden structure on a bend in the Hutt River.  Finally, you\'ll follow a sealed road to the suspension footbridge that crosses the river.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:125]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:123]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:128]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:127]] on the opposite bank to the north]]','Southern end is at the Totara Park Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Maoribank footbridge.','','2.226',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:48:09',23,'-41.110238','175.091987',15,1,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 14:25:43','calc',5),(125,'Harcourt Park',12,'','East bank: Maoribank footbridge to Birchville Bridge.','Immediately north of the suspension footbridge is Harcourt Park, which includes a motorcamp and signage pointing out the earthquake escarpments. There are a couple of alternative paths through the park, both of which meet Akatarawa Road by the sub-station.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can head north along Akatarawa Road or, as shown on the map, turn left into Pokaka Street then across Hoggard Park to find an obscure piece of single track. This section of track rumbles along next to the river, behind several houses, before rejoining Akatarawa Road.  There\'s a pair of tight and steep switchbacks along the way, just to provide a bit of interest.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust before this section of track ends, there is a rotunda shelter 0.1km south of the Birchville Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:124]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:126]] or [[track:588]] to the northeast]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:127]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:128]] on the opposite bank and to the south]]','Southern end is at the Maoribank footbridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Birchville Bridge.','','2.034',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:20:10',23,'-41.096915','175.093789',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-04 08:16:05','calc',5),(126,'Gemstone',12,'','East bank: Spur from Birchville Bridge towards Kaitoke.','From the shelter to the end of [[track:125]], go down the gravel road towards the river.  Veer off through the bridge underpass then up to the stopbank.  Then follow the grassy spur that heads in the general direction of Kaitoke, but doesn\'t quite get there.  Instead, it simply stops next to State Highway 2, 1.3km short of the Twin Lakes Road entry to the water treatment area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWatch out for a set of steps in one of the bush sections, somewhere around the middle of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt a small bridge, just before meeting State Highway 2, the track forks left and right. The righthand branch goes straight to State Highway 2, while the lefthand branch takes a slightly longer scenic route to meet State Highway 2 a little further along.\r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way then cross the Birchville and Bridge Road bridges to continue on the [[area:12]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:125]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:588]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:127]] to the southwest across the river]]','Western end is at the Birchville Bridge. Access directly from the eastern side of the road, or drop down towards the river on the western side of the road and go under the bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end is on State Highway 2. Either return the same way or continue along State Highway 2 to the Kaitoke water treatment area.','There are plans to extend this track to the east alongside State Highway 2. It will then connect with tracks in the Kaitoke water treatment area and hence enabling access to the [[track:213]].','2.232',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-05 13:46:22',23,'-41.093131','175.107951',15,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-01 14:26:19','calc',5),(127,'California Park',12,'','West bank: Birchville Bridge to Maoribank footbridge.','Proceed along the sealed Bridge Road until it ends with a steep corner up to the [[track:199]] car park.  Instead of going up to the car park, take the single track that is straight ahead.  You\'ll soon encounter a couple of large concrete blocks across the track, letting you know that you\'re going the right way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter climbing gently for a while, there is a short but quite steep descent through bush. Watch out for the wooden drainage channels, which are at acute angles across the track.  The descent ends abruptly when the track emerges into an open grassed area just before the Maoribank footbridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:128]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:125]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:124]] on the opposite bank to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:126]] and [[track:588]] to the east]]','Northern end is at the Birchville Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is at the Maoribank footbridge.','','2.147',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-28 14:53:31',23,'-41.097076','175.090742',14,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-01 14:26:53','calc',5),(128,'Awakairangi Park',12,'','West bank: Maoribank footbridge to Totara Park Bridge.','Gentle cruise along the river stop banks, past the playing fields of Awakairangi Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter crossing the Totara Park Bridge, drop down the steep chute to the gravel road that passes under the bridge. Heading south the gravel road is [[track:123]], while heading north it is [[track:124]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:123]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:127]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:124]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:125]] on the opposite bank to the north]]','Northern end is at the Maoribank footbridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is at the Totara Park Bridge.','[[track:193]] starts opposite Awakairangi Park, on the northern side of the Totara Park Bridge.','2.142',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-05 13:50:57',23,'-41.109817','175.088811',15,1,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 14:27:17','calc',5),(129,'River Road',12,'','West bank: Moonshine Bridge to Silverstream Bridge.','Riverside gravel road, apart from a brief excursion over a rocky outcrop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCross the Moonshine bridge using the path on its south side.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:121]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:123]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:122]] on the opposite bank]]','Southern end is at the Silverstream Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Moonshine Bridge.','','4.608',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 21:37:15',23,'-41.133805','175.017271',14,2,1,4,23,'2010-01-01 14:27:33','calc',5),(130,'Manor Park',12,'','West bank: Spur from Kennedy Good Bridge to Manor Park.','This spur heads north on the west bank towards the Silverstream Bridge, but doesn\'t reach it due to a golf course being in the way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you follow the Manor Park Road stopbank to the south, under the rail bridge, there is a track along the river bank that eventually rejoins this section of the [[area:12]]. Take care to not head inland too soon, or you\'ll find yourself literally in the middle of a paint ball fight!\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Dry Creek entry to [[area:11]] is just north of Manor Park, so this track could be a potential entry/exit point for Belmont.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:131]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:120]] on the opposite bank to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:121]] on the opposite bank]]','Southern end is at the Kennedy Good Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at Manor Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is possible to continue through Manor Park and across to the other side of State Highway 2 via the railway underpass, then along State Highway 2 to the Silverstream Bridge. However, this is not recommended.','','4.906',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 21:57:01',23,'-41.179558','174.945602',13,1,1,2,23,'2009-09-20 21:48:47','calc',5),(131,'Melling',12,'','West bank: Kennedy Good Bridge to Melling Bridge.','At each end there are short sections of single track under the respective bridges.  Inbetween the track is a mix of gravel path and paved road, though an alternative paved road runs parallel for almost the whole length.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:132]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:130]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:120]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:119]] on the opposite bank to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:121]] on the opposite bank to the north]]','Southern end is at the Melling Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Kennedy Good Bridge.','','2.615',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-26 21:57:38',23,'-41.197967','174.917278',14,1,1,2,23,'2009-09-20 21:55:25','calc',5),(132,'Ava',12,'','West bank: Melling Bridge to Hutt Estuary Bridge.','From the Melling Bridge to the Ava Rail Bridge there are two alternative routes: the upper track is on the flood stop bank and has a grass/asphalt surface; the lower track is closer to the river and has a grass/gravel surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter ducking under the Ava Rail Bridge, cross the cricket ground (or go round if in use) to the flood stop bank which then continues through the golf course.\r\n[[para]]\r\nRather than crossing Waione Street, there is a tunnel under the Hutt Estuary Bridge.  This leads to a tight and twisty little board walk around the estuary then up to the the footpath on the southern side of Waione Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:133]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:131]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:119]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:120]] on the opposite bank and to the north]]','Northern end at the Melling Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end just past the Hutt Estuary Bridge.','','3.983',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-27 11:04:27',122,'-41.219082','174.898052',13,2,1,2,23,'2009-10-04 20:20:29','calc',5),(133,'Hikoikoi',12,'','West bank: Hutt Estuary Bridge to Hikoikoi Reserve.','From the Waione Street footpath, drop down a narrow track that skirts around the edge of the estuary.  Continue along a gravel road then up a small hill to the Hikoikoi Reserve, where there is a wooden platform and information board.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:132]] to the north]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:119]] across the river and to the north]]\r\n[[track:583]] continues along the foreshore to the southwest.','Northern end is 0.15km west of the Hutt Estuary Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is on the wooden platform in the Hikoikoi Reserve.','','0.536',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:47:01',23,'-41.234736','174.897666',16,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-20 21:31:54','calc',5),(134,'Belmont Road',11,'','Farm road from the top of the sealed part of Belmont Road to the top of [[track:107]].','This is the main northern entrance to the [[area:11]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a 200m altitude difference between the ends of this track.  Parts of the track are quite steep, with a grade of up to 12%, though the overall grade is much less.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor most of its length the track surface is gravel and hard-packed clay, with the occasional grassy section.','For the northern end, turn off State Highway 58 (Haywards Hill Road) and go up Belmont Road to where the seal ends. This is a narrow road - barely one lane - so watch out for traffic in the other direction. [[track:134]] continues up the hill in the form of a farm road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end of [[track:134]] is at an intersection with [[track:107]] and [[track:158]], by the gas station.','Along the way the track passes several World War II bunkers that were used for storing ammunition.','4.788',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-27 21:42:42',23,'-41.146733','174.914017',14,3,1,3,23,'2009-03-27 21:42:42','calc',5),(135,'Murphys',11,'','Link between [[track:134]] and [[track:101]].','This is a steep 200m+ climb to the summit of [[track:101]], along a rough farm track and across open paddock.  For much of its length the track is ill-defined, though the orange markers provide sufficient guidance.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn case the climb isn\'t hard enough, after a particularly steep section that goes straight up a grassy hill, the track drops down a bit before the final ascent to the summit.\r\n[[para]]\r\nApproaching the summit of [[track:101]] you will encounter a boulder field that will probably require a bit of walking, but it isn\'t far.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA challenging loop off [[track:134]] is: climb up [[track:135]] to the summit of [[track:101]], backtrack a bit then drop down [[track:136]], climb up the northern half of [[track:109]] to the saddle point near the start of [[track:135]], and then back up to [[track:134]].','The track starts about half way along [[track:134]], drops down to a saddle point that is also the northern end of [[track:109]], then climbs up to the summit of [[track:101]].','The lower section of this track approximately follows a paper section of Murphys Road - hence the name.','2.449',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 20:04:15',23,'-41.152194','174.926891',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-20 19:46:40','calc',5),(136,'Speedys',11,'','Steep connector from [[track:135]] to [[track:109]].','Much of this track is a cross-country trek across paddocks, following the occasional marker pole.  The final section down to [[track:109]], starting at a power pylon, is on a rough 4x4 track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOverall this is a very steep track, which drops 290m from top to bottom, so probably best done in the downhill direction from [[track:135]] to [[track:109]].  The main descent has an average grade of 21%, with some parts being even steeper.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the intersection with [[track:109]] the track crosses a creek at a log weir.  Provided the water level is low, the weir can be ridden across.','From the summit of [[track:101]], proceed about 0.3km down [[track:135]] to a sign posted intersection.  Head down a ridge towards the right (the middle ridge ends with a gully), following the markers.  The bottom of the track meets the lowest point of [[track:109]].','','2.599',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-10-28 11:20:32',23,'-41.162114','174.929895',14,4,1,6,23,'2008-10-28 11:20:32','calc',5),(137,'Transmission Gully',13,'','Short connection from The Dell to Transmission Gully.','A short and gentle connection from the carpark to Transmission Valley.  The track surface is a mix of gravel farm road and open paddock.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn the middle of the track is a brief climb over Gas Line Ridge, the track drops into Transmission Gully.  From the gate on the eastern side of Gas Line Ridge head diagonally across Transmission Gully, under the transmission line to a small creek crossing which is the end of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:141]] and [[track:138]] start from a sign-posted intersection opposite the deer enclosure. [[track:140]] joins near the tops of Gas Line Ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:137]] (0:00-2:00) / [[track:139]] (2:01-14:25) / [[track:137]] (14:26-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6758237]]','Starts from the car park side of The Dell (the circular horse training circuit), then heads around the southern side of the buildings towards Gas Line Ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on the eastern side of Transmission Gully, at the start of the [[track:139]].','There are [[link:http://www.transit.govt.nz/projects/transmission-gully/ plans]] to build a 4 lane highway up this quiet and pleasant valley, though no construction start date has been decided.','1.426',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:15:22',23,'-41.057722','174.943757',16,2,1,4,23,'2009-09-27 10:32:27','calc',5),(138,'Farm Loop',13,'','Loop around the northern part of the farm, including a climb to the summit of Battle Hill.','After sharing the first 0.1km of track with the [[track:141]], head up the steep hill to the left.  The tracks shares another short section with the [[track:141]] before continuing up to the summit of Battle Hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou\'ll have to find you own way up the last 0.1-0.2km to the summit, as the track isn\'t well defined. The summit of Battle Hill provides nice views over Transmission Gully and the surrounding hills.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the summit, drop back down to the track then along a ridge that drops quite steeply towards the farm buildings.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom of the hill, either follow the track around to the right, through the bush and onto a gravel road, or go directly across Abbott\'s Field to the farm buildings and car park.','Follow [[track:137]] to the track start at a sign-posted intersection part way up Gas Line Ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at the northern side of the car park.','','3.389',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-09 11:46:22',23,'-41.053693','174.939852',15,3,1,2,23,'2008-11-09 11:46:22','calc',5),(139,'Puketiro Loop',13,'','Steep loop from [[track:137]] up Puketiro Road then down an adjacent ridge .','This track is completely different to the others in the [[area:13]] Farm Forest Park.  It follows a steep 4x4 road through the forest, climbing almost 400m then dropping back down to where it started.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top of the road, where this track meets [[track:238]], there is a sign-post that says \"Puketiro loop track from Battle Hill\" pointing up towards the right.  Climb up the steep single track to almost the summit, then drop down towards the right along a narrow ridge which eventually drops down to meet a double track that returns down the hill to the end of [[track:137]].  The video takes this route at time 7:45. Alternatively, there is a road that goes around the summit and rejoins this track at time 10:40 in the video.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you\'re still keen after the steep climb from [[area:13]], there are several forestry roads in the vicinity of the summit that continue deeper into the [[area:15]] for the more adventurous. The main road heading east, more-or-less along the ridge initially, is [[track:238]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:137]] (0:00-2:00) / [[track:139]] (2:01-14:25) / [[track:137]] (14:26-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6758237]]','Follow [[track:137]] to just past the creek crossing after entering the tree line. Take the left-hand track up the hill at the start (ie. not through the gate on the right - that is the end of the track).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe loop ends less than 20 metres from where it starts, so return to the car park via [[track:137]].','The track is one-way only, in a clockwise direction.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track is on 4x4 forestry roads, though there is a short section of narrow and technical singletrack down from the summit before rejoining the road.','5.784',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-25 09:53:20',23,'-41.060747','174.959078',15,3,1,3,23,'2009-09-27 10:36:35','calc',5),(140,'Restoration Trail',13,'','Short wander around the farm and over Gas Line Ridge.','The climb up Gas Line Ridge is fairly steep, but it isn\'t high and a bit of zig-zagging across the paddock will make it easier.','Start from The Dell (the circular horse training circuit) and go through a gate on the southern side then into a short bush section. Follow the markers across the paddock and over Gas Line Ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe tracks ends at an intersection with [[track:137]]  near the top of Gas Line Ridge.','','1.358',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-09 11:31:36',23,'-41.060311','174.941611',16,2,1,6,23,'2008-11-09 11:31:36','calc',5),(141,'Wetlands Walk',13,'','Easy wander around restored wetlands and over a small hill.','A mostly gentle wander around some wetlands in the process of being restored. There is a hill in the middle, which is fairly steep but it isn\'t high.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.5km from the start there is a worthwhile option of jumping across to the other side of the wetland.  Otherwise just continue along the western track - the two alternatives rejoin just before climbing up the hill.\r\n','Start from a sign-posted intersection with [[track:137]], sharing the first 0.1km with [[track:138]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at another intersection with [[track:137]], though nearer the farm buildings.','The further 0.25km section of track across the hill is shared with [[track:138]].','2.469',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-09 11:55:48',23,'-41.054728','174.941740',15,2,1,1,23,'2008-11-09 11:55:48','calc',5),(142,'Big Weta',11,'','Interesting and challenging downhill alternative to the bottom half of [[track:105]].','This track is designed as a downhill-only complement to the bottom half of [[track:105]] (which it is intended will eventually become uphill-only). It is complemented by [[track:153]], which is at a similar level of difficulty.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe surface consists mostly of smooth clay and tangled tree roots, with only pine needles for grip.  There are several very steep clay slides, tight corners, and undulations.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt about the halfway point, a few metres after crossing the bridge, the track forks into two parts. The fork to the left (constructed in early 2010) is somewhat easier, while the fork to the right is especially steep.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAll up, this is a challenging track that makes an interesting alternative to [[track:105]].','The track starts little more than 10m up hill from the green hut, where it diverges from [[track:105]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends by the gate on [[track:102]], between the wool shed and the bottom of [[track:105]].','[[track:142]] made its official debut during the [[area:11]] round of [[link:http://pnp.org.nz/mtb/events/2008/series08/rd408/?-session=pnpv4:DE99F8B702dbe299DBUoO1358D33 PNP\'s mountain bike racing series on 2 November 2008]].','0.649',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 19:53:23',23,'-41.177475','174.893149',17,4,1,1,23,'2010-01-17 19:17:36','calc',5),(143,'Middle Ridge',11,'','Steep farm track from Cannons Head to the valley floor.','This is a steep and rough 4x4 descent from the summit of Cannons Head. Some sections of track are very steep, though the rocky surface generally provides plenty of grip.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWith a typical grade of 20%, and some steeper sections, this is a quick way to get from the hill tops down to the Stratton Street valley.  But it isn\'t all downhill - in addition to the occasional flatish bit, there\'s a steep, though short, climb about a third of the way down.','From the Cannons Head sign on [[track:152]], go through/over the gate that is 50m away towards the southeast.  Then follow the most obvious track all the way to the valley floor, finishing with a small bridge to join [[track:102]].','Best done as a descent, unless you like walking up steep hills.','2.157',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-29 20:19:06',23,'-41.176974','174.886894',14,3,1,3,23,'2009-03-29 20:19:06','calc',5),(144,'Southern Mt Victoria',5,'','Mount Victoria section of the Southern Walkway.','Starting from the southern end, at the intersection of Wellington Road and Crawford Road, the track immediately branches into two alternatives: the upper alternative goes through the trees; while the lower alternative sweeps across the open grassed area parallel with Wellington Road.  The alternatives merge after 0.1km.\r\n[[para]]\r\nProceed a further 0.25km up to Alexandra Road.  The track shares 0.1km in common with [[track:146]] before diverging and following Alexandra Road for 0.3km.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCross Alexandra Road at a car park outside the old Fever Hospital.  Climb the track on the northern side of the car park to the north-eastern corner of Alexandra Park.  At that point there are steps that go straight up the steep hill.  Instead of going that way, cruise over to the north-western corner of Alexandra Park and up a piece of track (constructed in early 2009) that bypasses the steps.  After an initial zigzag this bypass heads east up the hill, before doubling back to join the main track near the ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom there, continue climbing at a gentle gradient to just before the Mount Alfred survey mark (red and white pole). Veer off to the east and follow the section of track added in June 2009 that bypasses the steps down to a map display at the saddle point where [[track:147]] crosses Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue 0.5km along the verge of Alexandra Road (on the western side), then go into the trees and follow the marked track for 0.6km. Around 0.1km along this section the track crosses, and briefly coincides with, [[track:231]]. The last 0.2km of this section coincides with [[track:229]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top of a steep drop down to an open grass area, instead of going down the hill turn sharply to the right along a wide unmarked track.  This section of track gets progressively more technical, with lots of exposed tree roots and narrow parts.  There is a set of steps just before the track ends on Palliser Road.','Starts from the intersection of Wellington Road and Crawford Road.  Ends on Palliser Road, about 0.5km up hill from the northern end of [[track:145]] (which also ends on Palliser Road).','This track is the Mount Victoria section of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]].  All of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','3.080',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (apart from the last 0.2km at the northern end)','2009-06-07 22:02:55',23,'-41.303474','174.789906',14,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:32:21','calc',5),(145,'Charles Plimmer',5,'','Palliser Road to Charles Plimmer Park.','At the top of the sealed path, skim along the upper edge of the park on a flat track.  Briefly dive into the trees, down a tight hairpin bend, and then out across flat, open ground to the top of the Majoribanks Street steps.','The northern end starts with a sealed path straight up the hill off Palliser Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end is just above the steps leading down to the top of Majoribanks Street, which is also the start of [[track:147]].','','0.439',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-19 20:44:40',23,'-41.294495','174.790549',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:23:04','calc',5),(146,'Newtown to Hataitai',5,'','Connector from Mein Street in Newtown to the velodrome in Hataitai.','From the top of Mein Street, ascend a paved path up past the table tennis club.  Cross Alexandra Road then immediately turn north along a 0.1km section of track that is shared with [[track:144]].  At the car park, dive down through the trees to the velodrome.','Starts from the top of Mein Street in Newtown.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a metal barrier on the south-eastern side of the Hataitai velodrome.','','0.778',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-22 09:30:25',23,'-41.308277','174.788661',16,2,1,2,23,'2009-09-10 20:30:29','calc',5),(147,'Hataitai to City',5,'','Connector from velodrome in Hataitai to Majoribanks Street in the City.','From the velodrome exit road, ascend a gravel path that passes directly over the Mount Victoria Tunnel (marked by the exhaust of a large ventilation shaft).  Cross Alexandra Road to where this track intersects with [[track:144]].  Then drop down through the trees and head north.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.6km from Alexandra Road you\'ll cross the [[track:231]] track coming up from Pirie Street. A further 0.2km along, just above Charles Plimmer Park, [[track:229]] heads up the hill to the right.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen the track opens out into Charles Plimmer Park, skirt around to the left, down a ramp to Lawson Place, and finally to the top of Majoribanks Street.','The start is near the northern end of the velodrome in Hataitai.  An alternative entry is up a set of sealed footpath switchbacks and steps at the end of Hinau Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends in the city, at the top of Majoribanks Street where a flight of steps ascends to Charles Plimmer Park.  The steps also mark the southern end of [[track:145]].','','1.506',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-25 16:55:02',23,'-41.300282','174.789777',15,2,1,2,23,'2009-09-10 20:26:06','calc',5),(148,'Horokiwi Bridleway',11,'','Extremely steep track from Horokiwi Road to near the summit of Belmont Trig.','This is a track of two halves.  From Horokiwi Road, the western half drops down a steep 4x4 track to the floor of Horokiwi Valley.  The eastern half is an extremely steep climb to near the summit of [[track:100]] (though probably best done as a challenging descent).\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn terms of track surface, the halves are also quite different.  The western half used to be narrow almost to the point of resembling singletrack, but has been opened up to be more of a 4x4 track. Substantial realignment work was done in late 2008 to bypass the steepest parts.  Apart from a short bush section at the top, the eastern half is either rocky singletrack or concealed by long grass.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeware of the extremely steep grassy sections on the eastern half.  The average slope down that part of the track is in excess of 30%, with some sections being even steeper.  The surface under the long grass is uneven with hidden holes, bumps, and rocks.','The western end drops off the side of Horokiwi Road about 0.2km before it turns around under the transmission line. The top of the track is clearly sign posted, about 0.2km along the unsealed part of Horokiwi Road. The top of the [[track:166]] track is about 0.9km south on Horokiwi Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end of this track meets [[track:100]] just below the summit, about 50m south-west of [[track:152]]\'s southern end.','About 40% of the eastern half coincides with [[track:190]] track, which was constructed to bypass the steepest parts of this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track finally deviates from [[track:190]] at an S-bend in [[track:190]] just after it has passed through the fence a few times.  [[track:148]] continues as a barely discernable track down a ridge towards a grassy knoll that has an orange track marker on it.  [[track:190]] follows a different ridge to the south.','2.573',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-22 13:41:34',23,'-41.187052','174.865136',15,4,1,1,23,'2009-07-30 13:06:59','calc',5),(149,'Horokiwi Valley',11,'','Valley floor connector from [[track:150]] to [[track:148]].','Venturing beyond [[track:150]], this track will take you further up the Horokiwi Valley.  Along the way, about 0.5km north of [[track:150]], the [[track:190]] track heads up the eastern hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter following the creek (and crossing it several times), you\'ll emerge from the bush into a grassy clearing. Looking to both the left and the right you\'ll see [[track:148]] climbing up both sides of the valley - apart from returning the way you came that\'s the only way out of the valley.','From [[track:150]] go up [[track:151]] for almost 50m to a signposted intersection just before a wooden gate.  [[track:149]] is the track heading down towards the north.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track ends in a clearing at a T-intersection with [[track:148]].','','1.225',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-22 13:45:55',23,'-41.192316','174.865007',15,3,1,1,23,'2008-12-22 13:45:55','calc',5),(150,'Baked Beans Bend',11,'','Wet and wild connector from [[track:99]] to the clearing known as Baked Beans Bend.','This track follows a creek up the Horokiwi Valley to the clearing known as Baked Beans Bend. There isn\'t a lot of flow to this track, given its technical sections and many creek crossings.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDepending on how they are counted, there are about nine unbridged creek crossings on this short track, some of which are only a few metres apart.  Provided that the water level is low, it is possible to ride or use stepping stones across the creek crossings without getting wet feet - but don\'t count on it.  One of the crossings is via a log which has been shaved to provide a flat top, which is rather tricky if carrying a bike.','Turn off [[track:99]] at a T-intersection marked by a large log with \"Trig\" carved into it.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe end of the track is at Baked Beans Bend, where it meets [[track:151]] and [[track:149]].','Camping is permitted at Baked Beans Bend.  See the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Picnics-and-camping/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] for details.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Log Bridge]], Tricky\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/sites/default/files/brindge_on_baked_beans_bend.jpg:Log Bridge:350:400]]\r\n','0.742',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-14 09:45:04',59,'-41.199694','174.863141',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-02-07 06:27:34','calc',5),(151,'Belmont Trig South',11,'','Very steep drop down the southern side of Belmont Trig.','This is a difficult track that winds its way along a ridge to the south of [[track:100]].  The surface mostly consists of either smooth clay or rough rocks except for a pleasant, though short, forest section.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe most common approach to this track is to start from the summit of [[track:100]].  From there, the track quickly drops 390m in altitude down to the floor of Horokiwi Valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nLike many hills in the area, this one gets progressively steeper as it approaches the valley.  In this case, that means an average grade of 15% for the upper sections and more like 25% for the lower sections.  Consequently, with a rough rock and clay surface, the last 0.4km section just above [[track:150]] is either a challenging descent or a demanding climb depending on which way you\'re going.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:151]] is most commonly used as part of a loop that may include [[track:100]] or [[track:152]], leading to an exit from the [[area:11]]  via [[track:150]] and [[track:99]].\r\n','From the summit of [[track:100]], go through the wooden gate 20m south of the trig marker.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the base of the hill, the track meets [[track:150]] and [[track:149]].','','2.561',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-22 12:28:46',23,'-41.190862','174.870415',14,4,1,1,23,'2008-11-22 12:28:46','calc',5),(152,'Dress Circle',11,'','Hilltop romp from [[track:112]] to [[track:100]] via Cannons Head.','This track more-or-less traverses the ridgeline all the way from [[track:112]] through to [[track:100]], summiting several hills including Cannons Head.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough there are no big climbs or descents on this track, there is a series of small hills.  When travelling from north to south the cumulative altitude gain is about 200m - even though the two track ends differ in altitude by less than 40m.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track surface consists of hard-packed dirt and rock, with a fair amount of grass covering in many places.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several exits from this track.  At the northern end is [[track:112]].  At or near the southern end is: [[track:100]], [[track:151]], and [[track:148]].  Along the way you could also take: [[track:157]], [[track:143]], or [[track:115]].','Northern end is at the western side of [[track:112]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is just below the summit of [[track:100]].','Much of this track is fully exposed to the wind from every direction, so prepare accordingly.','4.337',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-23 20:26:42',23,'-41.170901','174.878311',14,3,1,1,23,'2009-10-24 21:49:21','calc',5),(153,'Choppers',11,'','Convoluted downhill-only track parallel to and inbetween [[track:116]] and [[track:113]].','Short and steep downhill-only track with lots of switchbacks and drifting corners.  The track is seldom far from [[track:113]], though there is a fence inbetween along the treeline.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is mostly bare clay slides, with a few tree roots thrown in for variety.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn dry conditions there is sufficient grip, plus handy berms on key corners, to give this track a nice flow.  But combine the steep clay slides with a bit of moisture and this becomes a very challenging track in the wet.','Follow [[track:111]] for almost 0.2km past the top of [[track:105]] and [[track:116]].  If you emerge from the trees at the top of [[track:113]], then backtrack 40m.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at a T-intersection with [[track:154]].','','0.509',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-22 21:25:19',23,'-41.176554','174.896894',17,4,1,1,23,'2009-08-09 21:32:48','calc',5),(154,'Green Hut',11,'','Short connector from [[track:113]] to the green hut on [[track:105]].','From the gap in the [[track:113]] treeline fence, it is only a short distance to the green hut where this track ends - hence the name.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHalfway along there is a culvert over a small creek. Just before reaching the green hut this track crosses an open area traversed by [[track:116]], so watch out for people coming down the hill.  At this intersection there is an official looking, though not particularly helpful, sign that simply says \"Track\". Cross the open area and into the trees opposite to the start of [[track:142]], off [[track:105]].[[para]]\r\nUnlike other tracks in the forest block, which generally go up/down the hill, [[track:154]] cuts across the hill.  This creates opportunties for loops that intersect at the Green Hut, for example: climb [[track:105]], head north along a short section of [[track:111]], drop down [[track:153]], take [[track:154]] to the centre of the forest, then down [[track:142]] to near the bottom of [[track:105]].','Starts halfway down [[track:113]] where there is a gap in the treeline fence, marked with a large orange-topped fencepost.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds a few metres uphill of the green hut, in the centre of the forest block, at an intersection with [[track:105]] and [[track:142]].','','0.121',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-29 20:04:04',23,'-41.177184','174.895434',17,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-17 19:19:10','calc',5),(155,'Hill Road Views',11,'','Grassy connector from [[track:111]] to [[track:107]].','This is a useful connection between [[track:111]] and [[track:107]] â€“ useful because it provides additional options for loops within the [[area:11]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track is across open paddock or grassy farm road.  On the way down towards [[track:107]], watch out for an abrupt change in direction part way down the hill â€“ go around to the left on a flatish road instead of continuing down the steep hill to the trees.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEasiest if starting from the [[track:111]] end, due to the quite steep 110m drop in altitude across the paddocks.','If heading north on [[track:111]], 400m after emerging from the trees, follow the \"Hill Road\" signpost that points up a hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe other end of this track is on [[track:107]], just over 1km from the car park.  It is marked with a sign that says, amongst other things, \"Old Coach Road\".','0.2km from the [[track:111]] end there is the option of climbing up to a lookout next to a power transmission pylon.  This diversion is marked with a sign that says \"View Point\".','1.476',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-22 22:33:53',23,'-41.170449','174.902172',15,3,1,1,23,'2009-08-22 21:20:26','calc',5),(156,'Maara Roa',11,'','Branch off [[track:103]] that goes around the north-eastern side of the Maara Roa restoration project to [[track:158]].','From the [[track:103]] plateau, drop down the track indicated by a sign that says \"Hill Road\" (though getting to [[track:107]] by bike requires traversing several tracks, specifically: [[track:156]], [[track:157]], [[track:152]], [[track:112]], and [[track:111]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern half of the track climbs quite steeply up a farm track.  At the top of the climb, go through a gate and proceed straight ahead  across open pasture and through the gap in the hills. Then tend around towards the right and follow the fence line to a white post in the distance.  From there, the track drops down to [[track:158]], just south of a small stand of trees.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the summit, where the track crosses a ridge via a saddle point, [[track:843]] branches off heading northeast, initially running almost parallel with the transmission pylons that run along the ridge line.','The northern end branches off [[track:103]] where it briefly reaches a plateau.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end forms an intersection with [[track:158]] and [[track:157]].','See the [[link:http://gw.govt.nz/Friends-of-Maara-Roa/ Friends of Maara Roa]] for more information.','1.621',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-14 09:45:51',23,'-41.150546','174.876723',15,3,1,2,23,'2010-01-17 18:14:40','calc',5),(157,'Cannons Head',11,'','Farm track connection from [[track:152]] to [[track:158]].','This is a quick way to drop from the [[area:11]] hill tops down towards Porirua.  Alternatively, this is a demanding climb.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the intersection with [[track:152]], the first section is a gentle cruise along a grassy farm track.  After abruptly dropping down a very steep (28%) grassy slope to a gate, the track continues down the hill along a sheep track before opening out to a rocky farm road under the transmission lines.  This road will take you down to an intersection, where you have a choice of continuing along the gravel road (which is [[track:158]]) or head up the hill opposite via [[track:156]].','Top end branches off [[track:152]] about 0.9km from the Cannons Head summit, or about 0.6km from [[track:112]], at a sign that says \"Cannons Creek\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom end is on [[track:158]], almost opposite the end of [[track:156]].','','1.376',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-23 21:29:30',23,'-41.158204','174.882989',15,3,1,2,23,'2010-01-17 09:55:00','calc',5),(158,'Duck Creek',11,' (No bikes in the middle section)','Gravel road from Takapu sub-station to intersection with [[track:134]] and [[track:107]].','From the Takapu Road information board, follow the gravel road around the sub-station to an intersection.  [[track:158]] goes down the hill, while the track on the right will take you to the bottom of [[track:115]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue down and then up the gravel road until you encounter a small stand of trees at an intersection with [[track:156]] and [[track:157]].  There is a sign on the left indicating that bikes may proceed no further, so if you\'re on a bike then either return the same way or head up one of the adjoining tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOtherwise, continue down the hill then turn up the main farm road to the airstrip - which marks the end of [[track:111]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue along the road to just past the gas station where there is a major intersection with [[track:134]] and [[track:107]]. Bikes are permitted on this final section from the airstrip.','Starts at the information shelter 0.1km north of Takapu sub-station, at the end of Takapu Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the intersection with [[track:134]] and [[track:107]].','The map shows the track divided into three sections: bikes may be ridden on the western (Takapu) and eastern (airstrip) sections. Bikes are prohibited on the middle section as it is the main farm access road for vehicles and livestock.','5.231',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-24 18:44:31',23,'-41.151710','174.887838',14,2,1,4,23,'2010-01-15 15:48:31','calc',5),(159,'Kau Kau',14,'','Demanding climb from Johnsonville to the summit of Mount Kau Kau.','Starting from the [[track:160]] saddle point, head up the grassy slope in the general direction of Mount Kau Kau.  The track looks like little more than a sheep track in places, but it is defined well enough to follow OK. A switchback has been added at the first (small) saddle to allow one to ride the steep uphill heading south.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter crossing a ridge, the track drops down into a shallow valley.  Thanks to the [[link:http://www.kennett.co.nz/ Kennett Bros]] and [[link:http://wellington.govt.nz/ WCC]] the rocky scramble is now a sweet series of two beginner level switchbacks up to the top of [[track:779]]. Take note of the loving care that the lower switchback has been chiselled and benched out from the rock â€“ it is a piece of art... From here the track becomes more clearly defined â€“ being a rocky trail for most of the remaining climb to the summit.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a couple of very steep tracks heading off to the east â€“ [[track:779]] and [[track:780]] â€“ these drop down to the park at the end of Truscott Avenue and are not suitable for bikes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDirectly opposite the intersection with [[track:779]] is the old water supply dam and pump for the defunct Onslow County Borough. There is a short and rather precarious track down to the reservoir. Just 40m down the [[track:779]] track is the entrance to a tunnel that provided an outlet for the water pipe.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA bit further along is an intersection with [[track:161]] â€“ either down a short, steep track or after a narrow piece of rocky singletrack.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.35km past the [[track:161]] intersection, the track splits into two parts: the narrower track on the left is easier, whereas the other track is great fun on the way down.  The alternatives rejoin next to a gate and stile.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe remaining 0.4km to the summit is very steep.  However, the effort is rewarded with spectacular views over large parts of the Wellington region.  The views are absolutely gorgeous on a fine, calm day â€“ especially from the viewing platform â€“ but the summit is horrendously exposed to the wind from all directions so prepare accordingly.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the summit, head to the west along [[track:32]], or return back the way you came.  The track that heads down towards Khandallah is closed to bikes.','The northern end branches off the highest point on [[track:160]], about 0.5km from the end of Carmichael Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe other end is at the summit of Mount Kau Kau.  There are only two legitimate ways to get there by bike:  this track, or via [[track:32]].','','2.857',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-01 20:40:10',122,'-41.226280','174.786344',14,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-10 14:35:35','calc',5),(160,'Old Coach Road',14,'','Historic connection between Ohariu Valley and Johnsonville.','At the end of Old Coach Road, follow the double track that goes up to a small park at the end of Carmichael Street.  From there, follow the track up and around the head of the valley to a saddle point overlooking Ohariu Valley.  It is from this point that [[track:159]] heads up the grassy slope.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you start the descent into Ohariu Valley the track becomes a 4x4 road.  After winding its way down the hill, at an easy grade of around 5%, the track ends when it meets Rifle Range Road.','The eastern end continues on from the end of the sealed part of Old Coach Road.  Alternatively, join the track from the end of Carmichael Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe western end adjoins Rifle Range Road.','From the end of Rifle Range Road there is a sealed road that goes to the summit of Mount Kau Kau.  This road is on private property and is not open to the public.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track follows part of the original coach route into Wellington. Another section still exists through the [[area:11]], called [[track:111]].','2.632',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-29 15:10:33',23,'-41.220373','174.786687',15,2,1,3,23,'2010-01-03 09:24:22','calc',5),(161,'Sirsi',14,'','Short and steep connection to [[track:159]].','This track provides an alternative entry/exit from [[track:159]], via the streets of Broadmeadows, and Sirsi Terrace in particular.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe first 0.3km from Sirsi Terrace is rather steep, so requires some effort to climb.  The remainder of the track is much more moderate.','If climbing up, then start from Sirsi Terrace.  The track heads up a steep, sealed section that goes to a water reservoir - though branch off further uphill instead of following the sealed road to the reservoir.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe north-western end joins [[track:159]] 0.75km from the summit.','','0.773',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-29 13:40:27',122,'-41.234188','174.788704',16,3,1,2,23,'2010-01-10 14:22:56','calc',5),(162,'Outer Loop',9,'','Precipitous firebreak that runs parallel to [[track:81]], near [[track:76]].','At the southern end go up a short and fairly steep side road off [[track:81]].  Turn right between two communication towers and wander along a bit between two more buildings to where the fun begins.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSoon you\'ll drop down the first of three outrageously steep descents. There is a narrow singletrack on the left which bypasses the steepest section of the first descent.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom there continue down the second steep descent and along to a Y-intersection. The left-hand branch (towards the Hutt) is [[track:254]], while the right-hand (northeastern) branch is the third and final steep descent on this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter the third descent you\'ll rejoin [[track:81]] having dropped a total of 115m, including the short ascents inbetween. With grades of 25-40% â€“ along with drops, ruts, and loose rock â€“ this is a challenging descent even in the best of conditions.  If the surface is wet, then forget about it.','Proceed along [[track:81]] and you\'ll find a turnoff to the southern end of [[track:162]] 1.1km north of [[track:78]] (or 0.3km south of [[track:76]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom of the precipitous drop rejoins [[track:81]], 1.2km north of the top of [[track:76]].','Presumably this track is called a loop because a loop can be formed by using part of [[track:81]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there is a signposted track to Hayward Scenic Reserve. That track is apparently very steep, with lots of steps, so not suitable for bikes.','1.029',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:31:50',23,'-41.229314','174.933543',16,5,1,2,23,'2009-04-29 23:31:50','calc',5),(163,'Broken Hill',14,'','Climb up to the Spicer Forest from the Broken Hill landfill.','This track climbs up a ridge into the Spicer Forst. Along the way it passess the northern end of [[track:169]], which branches off into the forest from a dip in the track just before the last small hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you continue to the end of this track you\'ll meet the [[track:168]] track, which continues through to the end of Ohariu Road.','There are two alternative entries to the eastern end of this track, on either side of a sharp ridge.  One entry is opposite [[link:http://www.trashpalace.co.nz/ Trash Palace]] on Broken Hill Road.  This entry is through a broken steel gate to the left of a recycling centre, leading to a steep gravel road that ascents to a plateau. The other entry climbs up to the plateau via a steep grass covered gas pipeline right-of-way from the end of Chastudon Place.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe western end of this track meets [[track:168]] in an open field in the middle of nowhere.','Parts of the track are surrounded by rubbish that has blown into the area from the adjacent landfill. Not the most pleasant of environments.','1.617',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-30 16:07:43',122,'-41.162179','174.816856',15,3,1,1,23,'2009-12-31 20:17:20','calc',5),(164,'Colonial Knob',14,'','Gravel road climb to the summit of Colonial Knob.','This is a demanding climb, gaining 400m in altitude up a gravel road that is quite steep in places. The effort is rewarded with spectacular views over Porirua and the surrounding areas.','Start from a steel barrier halfway along Raiha Street, at a sign that describes the area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom a biking perspective the track ends just after reaching the summit of Colonial Knob.  The track continues across farmland, but it is closed to bikes - see [[track:165]].','There are plans for development of a mountain bike park on Colonial Knob, led by the [[link:http://www.colonialknob.org.nz/ Colonial Knob Supporters Incorporated]]. This development follows [[link:http://www.pcc.govt.nz/Theme/ModuleLayout/GetImage.aspx?imageid=8c983b4b-f576-490b-9bc8-1cb163533bc6&downloadnow=true Porirua City Council\'s purchase of land on Colonial Knob]] in mid 2009.','4.440',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-07 12:12:05',23,'-41.145247','174.815826',14,3,1,4,23,'2009-10-16 10:33:54','calc',5),(165,'Colonial Knob South',14,' (No bikes across farmland)','Southern side of Colonial Knob.','From the summit of [[track:164]] this tracks swoops down a section of open farm land. The track then enters a steep descent through bush, including quite a few steps.','The western end continues from [[track:164]], crossing private farmland.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end is at a car park next to the Broken Hill landfill gate.','There is a sign at the top that says something like \"No dogs or bikes. Dogs will be shot\".  The sign is silent on what will happen to bikes, but probably best to avoid if you\'re on a bike.','2.806',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-07 12:18:27',122,'-41.156815','174.812994',15,3,2,1,23,'2009-12-31 20:16:46','calc',5),(166,'Grenada North',14,'','Goat track from Caribbean Drive to Horokiwi Road through the Grenada North Recreational Reserve.','The top and bottom sections of this track are deceptively inviting.  Although moderately steep, there is nothing intimidating.  That is, until you reach the middle section - where the track is extremely steep, overgrown, and mostly unformed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhether ascending or descending, expect a bit of bike pushing/carrying.  The middle section is too steep and rough to ride up or, for most people, down.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDespite the difficult middle section, this track is one of the few connections across the Horokiwi hills. From the top it is possible to link with [[track:148]] for entry into, or exit from, the [[area:11]].','The bottom end continues up the hill from the end of Caribbean Drive.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough not especially obvious from the road, the top end meets Horokiwi Road.  Around 0.9km further north on Horokiwi Road you\'ll find the top of [[track:148]].','','2.441',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-04 20:01:29',23,'-41.189022','174.847541',15,4,1,1,23,'2008-12-04 20:01:29','calc',5),(167,'Lawson\'s Track',14,'','Cruisy, though occasionally steep, path from Colchester Cresent to the heart of Seton Nossiter Park.','This track through the bush-clad part of Seton Nossiter Park has a well formed gravel base.  There are several bridges, some of which are at awkward angles to the adjoining track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nParts of the track are quite steep, especially towards the Colchester Crescent end, so the track is easier to traverse when heading in the generally downhill direction from southeast to northwest.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.45km from the picnic area a tramping track crosses a bridge towards the north heads up a very steep valley.','To go in a generally downhill direction, start from Colchester Cresent opposite Pimlico Place (which is the southeastern end of the track).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northwestern end meets [[track:856]] in the picnic area.','See [[link:http://www.grenadavillage.org.nz/The%20Grenada%20Village%20Community/Seton%20Nossiter%20Park/seton_nossiter_park.aspx Grenada Village]] for more information about Seton Nossiter Park.','1.216',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-07 12:04:53',23,'-41.216403','174.826941',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-25 13:31:22','calc',5),(168,'Spicer Forest',14,'','Ridgeline wander through the Spicer Forest.','From the Ohariu Valley Road end this track starts with a steep climb straight up the hill.  The rest of the track is relatively gentle, following a rolling ridgeline along a continuous clearly through the forest.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough the Te Araroa Walkway continues up the hill towards [[track:165]], that section of track is unridable.  Therefore, either return the same way or turn into [[track:163]] and perhaps then dive off down [[track:169]].','A few metres before the end of Ohariu Valley Road there is a gate on the eastern side of the road, just on the edge of the forest.  If you look carefully, you\'ll see the Te Araroa markers - follow them up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:163]].','This track is part of the [[link:http://www.teararoa.org.nz Te Araroa Walkway]].','1.587',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-14 09:50:00',122,'-41.169512','174.807115',15,3,1,1,23,'2009-12-31 20:16:32','calc',5),(169,'Tawa Singletrack',14,'','Swooping singletrack along the paper road portion of Ohariu Road.','Although this track is never much more than 300m from houses, there is quite a sense of being in the middle of nowhere as you swoop down through the forest.  From the ridge there are glimpses of Tawa through the trees towards the east, but just ignore them and enjoy the ride.  This sense of isolation is heightened as you drop into a seemingly secluded valley - until you suddenly emerge into a suburban street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome sections of track are fairly steep and lack a firm surface.  Of greater concern is the rickety old gate and couple of large trees across the track at head height.  Beware.\r\n[[para]]\r\nUPDATE: The section of track from the rickety gate down to Kiwi Crescent is on private land.  The landowners have said we are not allowed to ride there.  However, the forest before that is council land which we are allowed on.  See our website for more information.','Branch off [[track:163]] in a dip just before the final small hill on that track.  The entry point is becoming more obvious with use, but if you miss it and instead meet the intersection with [[track:168]], then backtrack 0.2km and have another go.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter a romp through the forest wilderness, the track stops at a rickety gate on a downhill.  Do not go past the gate - it is private land.','Tawa Off Road Riding Club\r\nhttp://torrcing.ning.com','1.476',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-22 09:56:04',31,'-41.169448','174.812050',15,3,1,1,31,'2009-04-22 09:56:04','calc',5),(170,'Wakely',14,'','Commuter connection between Wakely Road in Newlands and the bottom of Ngauranga Gorge.','By connecting Ngauranga Gorge with Newlands, this track is mostly used by bike commuters heading into or from the city or the Hutt.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is a decent climb, gaining 160m in altitude at a constant grade of just over 10%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe surface is firm and fairly even, with a hard-packed gravel and clay base.  However, watch out for the four deep concrete drains that cut across the track.  Sometimes they are filled with gravel, making them shallow and easy to cross.  But at other times they are clear and can be awkward if descending at speed.','Head down an accessway off Wakely Road, which turns into a gravel track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOr climb up from the bottom of Ngauranga Gorge.  It is not possible the cross Centennial Highway in that vicinty, so you\'re stuck with being on the northern side of the road whichever way you\'re going.','','1.447',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-04 20:13:19',23,'-41.236673','174.814711',15,2,1,2,23,'2008-12-04 20:13:19','calc',5),(171,'Whitireia Coastline',14,'','Gentle meander around the coastline of Porirua Harbour to Whitireia Park.','This is a very pleasant and gentle track with a nice outlook over the harbour.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough the track is narrow in places, there\'s nothing at all technical along the way - except, perhaps, the cattle that are sometimes present.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWatch out for the low wire rope barriers across the track - easy to step over, but tricky to ride over.  There are also a couple of fences/stiles to contain the cattle.','Continue off the end of Onepoto Road, past the boat sheds, and the road turns into a singletrack that meanders around the coastline all the way to the main car park in Whitireia Park.','This is one of the very rare mountain bike tracks in [[region:1]] that doesn\'t involve a hill.  No point on this track is more than 5m above sea level.','3.902',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-02 20:44:33',23,'-41.103803','174.860630',14,1,1,1,23,'2008-12-02 20:44:33','calc',5),(172,'Whitireia Inland',14,'','Inland track through Whitireia Park.','This tracks starts with a gentle climb through the centre of Whitireia Park, approaching from the south to reach a saddle point overlooking Onehunga Bay.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the saddle point, the wide and well groomed track stops and is replaced with a narrow track that is more like a trench in places.  The descent down to the bay is quite difficult, especially if the track has been cut up by the cattle that frequent the area.','Just after [[track:171]] crosses a wetland, head inland up a gentle valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at the main Whitireia Park car park.','The southern half of this track used to be narrow and tricky, just like the northern half still is.  It seems that funding for upgrading the track ran out before they finished the job.','1.866',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' / Intermediate (northern half)','2008-12-04 19:33:01',23,'-41.100504','174.853334',14,2,1,1,23,'2008-12-04 19:33:01','calc',5),(173,'Kaitawa',14,'','Short, dead-end excursion around Kaitawa Head.','A short trip around to a secluded bay below Kaitawa Head.  It is possible to walk further around the bays to the southwest, but there is no track beyond the first bay.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the track is on sealed road, except for a short section of singletrack that climbs over the headland and then down into the adjoining bay.','From the main car park, take the sealed road around the coastline heading north. The road becomes a narrow track as it heads over a small bluff and then dropping back down to the beach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way.','Kaitawa Head was the site of a Maori Pa.  The remains of the Pa can be seen high on the headland, reached via the sealed road up the hill from the main Whitireia Park car park.','0.916',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-04 19:39:52',23,'-41.091384','174.852476',15,2,1,5,23,'2010-01-15 15:50:01','calc',5),(174,'Croydon',4,'','Short connector from Croydon Park to [[track:25]].','From the bottom of [[track:31]] you could take a 40m long grass track to join [[track:25]] at the bottom of a steep climb (heading clockwise, which is the most popular direction).\r\n[[para]]\r\nInstead of going that way, cross Croydon Park to its eastern edge (directly opposite the scout den) and follow this narrow singletrack up the hill at an easier grade. Halfway up the hill, this track meets [[track:25]], so you could exit there or take a sharp left and continue up the singletrack to finally join [[track:25]] a little further along.','Start from the end of [[track:31]], outside the Williams scout den in Croydon Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe end of this track joins [[track:25]] less than 0.1km from its start.','','0.137',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-11-29 21:56:02',23,'-41.295752','174.745279',18,3,1,1,23,'2009-12-21 09:20:42','calc',5),(175,'Karori Rock',2,'','Sand and pebble tour around the southern coastline beyond Sinclair Head to the Karori Rock lighthouse.','From Sinclair Head the track gets increasingly rough and ill-defined.  By the time you\'re a couple of kilometres from Karori Rock, the track has degenerated into a (large) pebble rumble with sections of unridable deep, soft sand.  At low tide it might be possible to ride on the compacted wet sand along the water line, but don\'t count on it.  Most likely there will be a bit of walking involved.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 1.7km from Sinclair Head there is a track diverging up the cliff face.  This initially goes to a memorial overlooking Cook Strait and then heads inland to Long Gully.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Interisland Ferry passing Karori Rock Light]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/KaroriRock.jpg:Interisland Ferry passing Karori Rock Light:492:297]]','Continue around the coastline from the end of [[track:63]] at Sinclair Head.\r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way.','Watch out for the 4x4 drivers. They don\'t like stopping on the soft parts of the track, in case their vehicles get stuck. Consequently most of them will charge on through and expect everyone else to get out of the way.','6.395',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-07 11:08:50',122,'-41.346531','174.688454',13,3,1,3,23,'2010-02-20 19:15:40','calc',5),(176,'Wetland Loop',8,'','Gentle loop around the wetlands at the end of Waiu Street.','This is an easy, two-way loop around the wetlands at the end of Waiu Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTravelling clockwise around the loop, you\'ll start with a fairly gentle climb along a wide and smooth gravel path. About 0.3km from the start you\'ll pass the bottom of the downhill-only [[track:77]] track. Continue along the wide path for another 0.7km, to the head of the valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern half of the loop is a reasonably wide single track that generally descends, again at a gentle gradient. Cruise through the bush for 0.4km to a 120m long boardwalk â€“ which includes three passing bays to allow for two-way traffic. After a bit more single track, including a little double-back loop (with a shortcut alternative) and a wooden bridge over a small creek, the track heads across open territory back to where it started.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following video was taken while riding in the anti-clockwise direction around the loop.\r\n[[media:vimeo:7303564]]','Branch off [[track:80]] and follow the wide track towards the head of the valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs the track\'s name suggests this really is a loop, so you\'ll end up back where you started.','Much of the track appears to follow an old benched track that had become overgrown.','2.144',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-12 14:05:42',23,'-41.246644','174.926956',16,1,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 10:23:29','calc',5),(177,'Chartwell',7,'','Connection from Chartwell to [[track:32]].','There\'s nothing technical on this track, though a bit of climbing is required to reach the ridgeline that [[track:32]] follows.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the Chartwell Drive end of the track there is a double gate - that is, a steel barrier and a farm gate about a metre apart. There are three other gates along the way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the Chartwell Drive end the track is a gravel road that progressively turns into a grassy double track up the hill to [[track:32]].\r\n','Top end is 1.0km north of the top of [[track:178]], at a clearly sign-posted exit from [[track:32]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is near the top of Chartwell Drive, just at the point where it narrows to 1.5 lanes. [[track:40]] starts 0.35km further up Chartwell Drive, where the road ends outside the substation.','Around the buildings there is somewhat of a menagerie, with several horses, ducks, some feral cats, and a lot of chickens.\r\n[[para]] \r\n[[image:http://i721.photobucket.com/albums/ww214/capuchin09/chartwell-small5.png:Chartwell Height Graph::]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nHeights in meters, Distance in Ks\r\n','2.194',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-04 21:42:35',23,'-41.259678','174.752505',16,2,1,2,59,'2010-01-31 12:55:26','calc',5),(178,'Skyline Cemetery Link',7,'','Connection from [[track:32]] to Karori Cemetery.','This is a sinuous track with nice flowing curves when descending.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWatch out for a few low hanging trees over the track, though they are easy to avoid.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a couple of tracks along the way that head off to the east into Otari-Wilton\'s Bush - no bikes allowed in there.','The top is on [[track:32]], around 1.3km north of [[track:33]] or 1.0km south of [[track:177]], at the northern end of the Johnson Hill Reserve. There is a track name marker at the top of a wide, grassy track that drops gently off [[track:32]] down towards the southeast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom of the track emerges on to Karori Cemetery\'s sealed perimeter road, near the northwestern corner.  Follow the signs to exit via Standen Street.','Opened in December 2008.','1.563',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:32:35',122,'-41.270807','174.744759',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-08-30 14:36:34','calc',5),(179,'Hill Road Shortcut',11,'','Shortcut from [[track:107]] to [[track:111]].','This track provides a shortcut between [[track:107]] and [[track:111]].  The shortcut is useful in either direction, avoiding the less direct route via the airstrip and the top of [[track:158]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track has a 5% grade and an only slightly bumpy grass and rock surface, so there is nothing too challenging.\r\n','About 2/3 of the way up [[track:107]], as you approach a small stand of trees, look towards the left (south) and there is a gate and a farm track heading around the hill â€“ that\'s the bottom of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHeading north on [[track:111]] there is a sign that says \"Please use poled track\", referring to [[track:111]]\'s first significant hill climb. Immediately to the east of the sign is the top of this track.','','0.700',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-16 19:44:39',23,'-41.167542','174.900198',16,2,1,2,23,'2009-08-09 20:18:12','calc',5),(180,'Parade Ground',4,'','Gravel road from Wrights Hill Road to [[track:25]], running past the parade ground.','A useful connecting road that provides access to several other tracks including the tops of [[track:69]] and [[track:52]], plus [[track:25]].  [[track:181]] and [[track:72]] also branch off this road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road has a slight slope at each end, but nothing dramatic.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe most prominent feature of this track is the large, flat grassy area that it passes.  This was a parade ground used by the military during construction of the Wrights Hill Fortress in the 1940s.\r\n','Starts at a steel barrier in a small alcove 0.3km from the lower car park or 0.2km from the upper car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:25]].\r\n','The parade ground is a designated [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/services/dogs/exercise/dogmaps.html dog exercise area]], within which dogs are allowed to be off the leash.','0.772',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:39:24',23,'-41.297010','174.737227',16,1,1,4,23,'2009-04-29 23:39:24','calc',5),(181,'Gun Pit 2',4,'','Sealed path connecting [[track:180]] to the summit of [[area:4]], running past the remnants of gun pit 2.','This sealed path provides the quickest connection between [[track:180]] and the summit.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several tracks at or near either end of this track, plus [[track:181]] branches off to the south along the way.','The eastern end is the sealed path just 25m from the summit viewing platform.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe western end intersects [[track:180]], opposite the top of [[track:69]].','','0.372',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-24 09:49:12',23,'-41.296324','174.738547',18,1,1,5,23,'2009-09-01 18:02:49','calc',5),(182,'Landsdowne',4,'','Cruisy connector from Landsdowne Terrace to the lower car park of [[area:4]].','Nice piece of single track that provides a handy connection between Landsdowne Terrace and other tracks in the [[area:4]] area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.25km from the Landsdowne Terrace end the track just brushes [[track:29]], with a 5m connection between the two tracks, before diverging away again.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA further 0.2km along, [[track:43]] branches off down the valley.','The western end continues off the end of the Landsdowne Terrace cul-de-sac.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end is at the [[area:4]] lower car park, a couple of metres to the north of [[track:29]].','','0.641',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:43:10',23,'-41.293302','174.731948',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-04-29 23:43:10','calc',5),(183,'Lynmouth',4,'','Very short connection from [[track:43]] to a set of steps off Lynmouth Avenue.','When descending [[track:43]], less than 0.2km from the end, the track divides into two branches at an unmarked intersection. The upper branch is [[track:183]], while the lower branch is the continuation of [[track:43]]. ','Starts as a diversion off [[track:43]], gently curving around the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a set of steps off Lynmouth Avenue.  That is, it literally just ends - there is no entry to the steps, so you\'ll have to climb over the hand rail onto the steps.','','0.114',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:42:32',23,'-41.290609','174.731530',18,2,1,1,23,'2009-04-29 23:42:32','calc',5),(184,'Lower Car Park',4,'','Bush track connection between the lower car park to [[track:185]] near the upper car park.','Gentle piece of single track that wanders along a finger of bush between two parts of Wrights Hill Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTo reach the lookout from this track there are a few options. In an open stretch of track 0.4km from the lower car park, take the unmarked [[track:186]] track that angles back up the hill. If you miss that turnoff, then take the short, sharp, sign-posted alternative [[track:186]] route up through the bush. If you reach the [[track:185]] intersection, then backtrack 30m and have another go - or turn right and follow [[track:185]] for 0.2km then climb up the top part of [[track:31]] to the summit.','Starts on a hairpin bend on Wrights Hill Road, opposite the lower car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:185]].','','0.449',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:42:49',23,'-41.294051','174.736959',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-04-29 23:42:49','calc',5),(185,'Wrights Hill Shortcut',4,'','Shortcut from Wrights Hill Road up to [[track:31]] near the summit of Wrights Hill.','Useful shortcut that avoids the last section of seal on Wrights Hill Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is fairly steep, gaining around 60m in altitude in short order, but the surface mostly provides good grip so the climb isn\'t too difficult.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the bottom there are two alternative entries - one with lots of steps, and the other has no steps but it does have an excessively tight switchback. There are still some steps just above the alternative entry, but only a few.','At a small parking area on Wrights Hill Road there is an information board and track signs indicating the start of this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of this track joins [[track:31]] just below the summit of [[area:4]].','The bottom section, next to the information board, starts with a bunch of steps.  In late 2008 a more bike-friendly alternative entry was cut a few metres to the east.','0.535',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:40:56',23,'-41.294632','174.739394',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-11-01 22:03:10','calc',5),(186,'Wrights Hill Lookout',4,'','Deviation off [[track:184]] up to the Wrights Hill lookout platform.','From either the upper car park or from [[track:184]] this track will take you to the lookout platform at the summit of [[area:4]].  From the platform there are spectacular views over [[region:1]] harbour and the surrounding hills.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn an open part of [[track:184]], this track branches off from an unmarked intersection at an acute angle back up the hill. The map also shows a short alternative connection from [[track:184]], which is steeper but at least it has a sign.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe zig-zag section from the upper car park is paved, though it has several unpaved shortcuts through the bushes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCrossing the grassy area towards the lookout platform you\'ll pass gun pit 1, which was the main defensive weapon of the Wrights Hill Fortress.','','Branches off [[track:184]] in a couple of places.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on the lookout platform at the summit of [[area:4]].','0.499',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:41:28',23,'-41.295405','174.739008',18,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 18:05:21','calc',5),(187,'Paparata',4,'','Foot-only track from Paparata Street to [[track:43]].','This is a short and fairly steep track connecting Paparata Street with [[track:43]]. It isn\'t suitable for bikes due to some steps 50m from the Paparata Street end and a tight and very steep set of zig-zag switchbacks in the middle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 50m from the intersection with [[track:43]], there is a track marked with a \"Dead end\" sign.  In fact it isn\'t a dead end, but rather it is a short track that goes up to [[track:188]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the [[track:43]] intersection, the natural flow when descending [[track:43]] is to continue along [[track:187]].  A hard left turn is required to continue down [[track:43]] instead.','Start from the end of Paparata Street, where it meets Caughley Grove and Mewburn Rise.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at an intersection with [[track:43]].','','0.349',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-24 09:36:15',23,'-41.290778','174.733955',17,3,2,1,23,'2008-12-24 09:36:15','calc',5),(188,'Mewburn Rise',4,'','Short connection from [[track:187]] to a cul-de-sac off Mewburn Rise.','This track appears to be in the middle of a deep, dark forest.  That is, until it emerges on to the end of a newly constructed cul-de-sac.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough the area around the cul-de-sac has sections marked out, there hasn\'t been any construction as yet. Once construction begins, the fate of this track is unclear.  Perhaps it will become a dead end track, as the sign on [[track:187]] states.','Branches off [[track:187]] at a sign that says \"Dead end\" - though it isn\'t, because the track emerges at a new, though so far empty, little cul-de-sac off Mewburn Rise.','','0.097',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-24 09:31:49',23,'-41.291359','174.734395',17,3,2,1,23,'2008-12-24 09:31:49','calc',5),(189,'Woodhouse',4,'','Short connection between the end of Woodhouse Avenue and [[track:29]].','This track provides an alternative entry point to the [[area:4]] area.  It joins [[track:29]] about 0.8km from Fitzgerald Place.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is fairly narrow with an occasionally rocky surface and some slightly off-camber parts, but nothing difficult.','Starts at the end of Woodhouse Avenue, off the end of a short road extension.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a sign-posted intersection with [[track:29]].','','0.140',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:41:49',23,'-41.293898','174.727045',18,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 18:04:56','calc',5),(190,'Honeysuckle Ridge',11,'','Quad bike access to the Horokiwi valley from [[track:100]].','This track was constructed in late 2008 to provide the Ranger and contractors with quad bike access to the Horokiwi valley by avoiding the steepest parts of [[track:148]].  It is a two-way track so expect traffic in either direction - though ascending cyclists are likely to be walking.\r\n[[para]]\r\nLike other tracks in this part of [[area:11]], this track is very steep.  The total altitude change is 330m, with a typical grade of 15%-20%, a couple of short uphill bits, and an especially steep final section at the [[track:148]] end that has a grade approaching 30%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the upper section coincides with [[track:148]].  The two tracks have separate entrances and they diverge along different ridges about half way down the hill.','About 50m north from the intersection of [[track:100]] and [[track:152]], just below the summit of the trig, there is a grassy track heading north over a low ridge.  This track continues under the transmission line, through a gate marked with a \"Private property\" sign. Forty metres before getting to that gate, veer left (west) towards the treeline and through another gate that is at the bottom of a small gully.  Thereafter the track is clearly defined.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends when it meets [[track:149]], around 0.5km north of the intersection of [[track:151]] and [[track:150]].','','1.992',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (or Advanced if ascending)','2008-12-22 17:38:52',23,'-41.187052','174.869471',15,3,1,2,23,'2008-12-22 17:38:52','calc',5),(191,'Karapoti Gorge',15,'','Wide and relatively gentle introduction to the [[area:15]], heading up the Karapoti Gorge.','From the Karapoti Road car park, head along a gentle path up the valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou\'ll soon need to cross the unbridged Little Akatarawa River.  It is rocky, cold, and can also be deep and fast flowing after heavy rain, so probably best avoided if there has been a lot of rain in the previous couple of days.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce past the river crossing the track meanders up the valley, climbing progressively alongside the Akatarawa River West.  The valley itself is deep, surrounded by steep hillsides covered with dense native bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is rocky in places, though nothing too difficult.  During and immediately after heavy rain, parts of the track can have a fair amount of water flowing down/across them, which can make things interesting.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top of this track is [[track:192]], which starts at an obvious concrete bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6791345]]','Starts from the car park at the end of Karapoti Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at McGhies Bridge.','This track forms part of both the [[track:252]] and [[track:255]] courses.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe [[track:191]] is commonly used by motorbikes to access the [[area:15]], so listen out for them in either direction.','4.206',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-08 12:56:27',23,'-41.060780','175.079412',14,2,1,2,23,'2009-10-04 09:38:29','calc',5),(192,'McGhies',15,'','Forestry road from McGhies Bridge to the northern edge of the Valley View Forest block.','Starting from McGhies Bridge, this track climbs up a moderately steep gravel road and then saunters down to a large clearing. There are several short patches of old seal emerging through the mostly gravel surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the cleraing, either return the same way or ascend a very steep section of [[track:193]] (aka \'Three Skulls Road\') to the ridgeline. [[track:194]] also ends at the clearing, though that track is best done as a downhill.','Starts at the top of [[track:191]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a three-way intersection with [[track:193]] and [[track:194]].','This track forms part of the [[track:252]] course.','1.954',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-03 20:36:07',23,'-41.065213','175.065036',15,2,1,4,23,'2009-09-05 16:38:16','calc',5),(193,'Valley View Road',15,'','Forestry Road from suburban Upper Hutt into the heart of the [[area:15]].','[[track:193]] is one of the several official entrances to the [[area:15]] â€“ though it is unclear if the Totara Park entrance is currently open (see the note below). In any case, several other tracks lead to [[track:193]], including [[track:198]], [[track:199]], and [[track:192]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe initial climb up from Totara Park is quite steep.  From there, the road traverses a narrow ridge that connects Cannon Point with the northern (and larger) part of the Valley View Forest Block. There the road heads northeast along another ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt a T-intersection with [[track:195]] (which continues straight ahead), the road turns left and drops down a steep section to end in a large clearing where it meets [[track:192]] and the bottom of [[track:194]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several singletracks and small access track branching off [[track:193]]. However, the Valley View Forest Block is reaching maturity and is progressively being cleared. Therefore, those tracks are unlikely to survive much longer.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following video was taken following the road from North to South.\r\n[[media:vimeo:7495957]]','Starts off Totara Park Road. The [[track:128]] track, which is part of the [[area:12]], runs past the Totara Park Road end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a three-way intersection with [[track:192]] and [[track:194]].','From time to time there are logging trucks operating in the plantation areas of the [[area:15]]. The trucks may use the Totara Park Road entrance of [[track:193]], so watch out for the trucks and other machinery.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern section of this track forms part of the [[track:252]] course.','9.894',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-03 19:43:23',23,'-41.091643','175.067997',13,3,1,4,23,'2010-02-21 10:00:10','calc',5),(194,'Woolshed Road',15,'','Steep clay road through the middle of the Valley View Forest block.','After a hard climb to reach the [[track:193]] ridge, this neat piece of clay road provides a fun reward. The descent is steep and fast, with a bit of rutted cornering to add some technical challenge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTowards the bottom of the hill there is a mud puddle that appears to be semi-permanent.  After prolonged rain, the mud can be rather deep, so best to go around.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is possible to gather a fair bit of speed going down the straights, but beware that the clay surface offers little in the way of grip other than a thin layer of pine needles.','Southern end drops down from [[track:196]] to meet [[track:192]] and the northern end of [[track:193]] at a three-way intersection.','This track forms part of the [[track:252]] course.','2.277',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-03 20:36:39',23,'-41.078963','175.061646',14,3,1,2,23,'2009-09-05 16:58:05','calc',5),(195,'Lindsay\'s Road',15,'','Dead-end forestry road into a recently cleared and replanted Lindsay Block of the Valley View Forest.','If you\'ve just completed the the steep ascent from the intersection of [[track:192]], [[track:194]], and [[track:193]] then you\'ll encounter a T-intersection. The righthand (southern) branch is the continuation of [[track:193]] along the ridge.  The lefthand (northern) branch is this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere used to be several tracks branching off this one, though they seem to have been destroyed or obscured by logging of the Lindsay Block in 2008.','Branches off [[track:193]] at the north-eastern end of the ridge, just before [[track:193]] heads down to meet [[track:192]] and [[track:194]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the top of a ridge that was clear felled and replanted in late 2008.','','2.421',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-03 13:48:08',23,'-41.071522','175.078769',15,3,1,4,23,'2009-01-03 13:48:08','calc',5),(196,'Airstrip Drive',15,'','Secondary forestry road through part of the Valley View Forest block.','This is a gently curving forestry road that branches off [[track:193]] at a prominent T-intersection.  After wandering along for a while, it descends towards a locked gate where it crosses a block of private land.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there is another T-intersection where [[track:194]] heads off downhill towards the north.','Branches off [[track:193]] near the south-western end of the central ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end is at a gate that marks an entrance to the Rallywoods block of private land. Permission is required from the owner to proceed past the gate and cross their land.','The eastern end of this track forms part of the [[track:252]] course.','1.579',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-03 19:41:42',23,'-41.089638','175.059328',15,2,1,3,23,'2009-09-05 17:11:17','calc',5),(197,'Cannon Zig Zag',15,'','Zig zag shortcut track from the Tulsa Park entrance.','This track provides an interesting alternative to [[track:198]]. It can be ridden either up or down, though down is much more fun.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs the name suggests, this track zig-zags its way up the hill, in a series of quite steep sections punctuated by tight hairpin turns.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the top of this track, turn left (southwest) up the [[track:199]] to reach the Cannon Point Trig.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the bottom of the track, next to a farm gate, there is a gentle shortcut that connects with [[track:198]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following video was taken going downhill towards Upper Hutt.\r\n[[media:vimeo:10931878]]','Starts from a small plateau 0.5km up the [[track:198]] track. The start is clearly sign-posted.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds with a T-intersection with [[track:199]], less than 0.2km northeast of the Cannon Point Trig.','','1.606',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-03 10:37:15',177,'-41.104288','175.075486',16,3,1,2,23,'2010-04-15 07:36:18','calc',5),(198,'Cannon Point Road',15,'','Easier alternative to the [[track:197]], from Tulsa Park to [[track:193]].','After starting with a short piece of singletrack, cross the stile and continue up the 4wd road that goes up the hill from the plateau.  Alternatively, you could go up the steep [[track:197]] track that also starts from the plateau, though it is more difficult than taking the less steep road up to [[track:193]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nUpon reaching the top of this track, turn right (east) and almost 0.3km up [[track:193]] you\'ll find the start of the [[track:199]].','Starts from the car park in Tulsa Park, at the intersection of Totara Park Road and California Drive.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:193]].','The first section, up to a plateau at the bottom of [[track:197]] is singletrack, while the remainder is a narrow 4wd track.','2.715',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-03 10:21:11',23,'-41.107780','175.071859',15,3,1,3,23,'2010-02-21 09:59:27','calc',5),(199,'Cannon Point Walkway',15,'','Demanding track up to the Cannon Trig then down an extremely steep track past the Birchville Dam.','Cannon Trig provides awesome views over the Hutt Valley.  The trig is just over 0.7km from the western end of this track, or less than 0.2km from the top of [[track:197]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Birchville Dam entrance starts with a narrow swing bridge at a car park off the end of Bridge Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the car park at the Birchville Dam entrance drop down to Bridge Road, which is part of the [[track:127]] section of the [[area:12]].','Starts from [[track:193]] almost 0.3km east of the top of [[track:198]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a car park off the end of Bridge Road, Birchville.','The Birchville Dam section of this track is closed to bikes.  The biking section ends with a lookout over the catchment valley of the dam - return the same way.','4.236',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-28 15:37:21',23,'-41.099146','175.079327',14,3,1,1,23,'2009-12-06 21:28:49','calc',5),(200,'Upper Fitzherbert',9,'','Steep access road from the end of Upper Fitzherbert Road to [[track:81]].','From the end of Upper Fitzherbert Road jump over the rusted steel gate next to the \"No motorised recreation\" sign.  Proceed along the flat, narrow paddock towards the hills where the gravel road starts.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe ascent starts gently but soon becomes steep - after the initial section the slope averages around 20% right up to the top.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis can be a quick track to descend, but watch out for other users on the blind corners. Judging by the shoe prints, this is a popular track with horse riders.','Starts from the end of Upper Fitzherbert Road, past all the speed bumps designed to deter the boy-racers.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:81]], just under 0.3km east of the top of the [[track:253]] firebreak.','','1.042',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-08 09:15:48',23,'-41.223827','174.948006',15,3,1,4,23,'2009-03-08 09:15:48','calc',5),(201,'Wainui Centre',9,'','Firebreak along the ridge between Wainuiomata and Moores Valley.','This track is a firebreak along the rolling ridge between Wainuiomata and Moores Valley.  Like many firebreaks, it rigorously follows the ridgeline, making no compromises for the sake of comfort or ease.  Consequently, there are many short, sharp climbs followed immediately by short, often technically challenging, descents.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the first major high point there are two things of interest:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:The first is the spectacular views over the Wainuiomata Valley and, in the distance, Wellington Harbour.]]\r\n[[bullet:The second is another firebreak that drops down a ridge towards Wainuiomata. At the base of the initial extremely steep (45%+) section is a sign that says \"Private property. Keep out. No exit\".  Instead of descending the steep upper section, continue along this track to about 0.25km past the high point, where there is an easy shortcut to the base of the other firebreak\'s extremely steep section.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several more steep up/down sections as the track reaches its highest point, at the summit of Mount Mowlem, and then continues down hill for a while. Just past the summit is a trig, which is a useful landmark.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEventually the track just peters out, about 1km beyond the summit of Mount Mowlem, becoming too overgrown to proceed any further (if, in fact, it ever did).','Branches off [[track:81]] towards the south, at an intersection that also includes the access road to a prominent communications tower.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is a dead-end, so return the same way. The return journey is slightly easier, since it has more down hill than up hill.','','4.909',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-29 14:26:05',23,'-41.238189','174.962769',13,4,1,2,23,'2009-08-06 21:07:09','calc',5),(202,'Harry Todd',9,'','Tricky singletrack from Willis Grove to Hine Road.','This track traverses the Harry Todd Reserve off Hine Road. Although this track is clearly sign posted at both ends, it doesn\'t appear to get much traffic, which is a shame because it is a challenging track set in pleasant bush surroundings.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe tricky parts of this track are the very tight hairpin bends and the occasional steps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMany of the hairpin bends are very difficult to ride up/down, particularly those with exposed tree roots. In several places there are back-to-back hairpin bends.\r\n[[para]]\r\nClimbing from the eastern end (Willis Grove) is easier because most of the steps are towards the western end. The steps tend to be small boards stuck in the ground, rather than formal structures, so most can be either ridden down or bypassed. A few of the steps are more difficult - especially those off the lower end of a bridge that is about half way between the [[track:203]] intersection and the Hine Road end (ie. about 0.45km from Hine Road).\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you want to get to the top of [[track:203]], then climbing this track (from the Willis Grove end) is the easiest way.','From the turning circle at the end of Willis Grove cul-de-sac ([[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=willis+grove,+wainuiomata&sll=-41.276605,174.956084&sspn=0.002854,0.009656&g=hine+road,+wainuiomata&ie=UTF8&ll=-41.27696,174.96706&spn=0.002854,0.009656&z=17&layer=c&cbll=-41.276958,174.967065&panoid=LBELzI0o1XBMPAXyPaFD3Q&cbp=11,226.78774871075228,,0,-5.589509860790361 Street View]]), head between two concrete driveways up a track that immediately plunges into the bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe other end of the track is up a short gravel driveway marked with a \"Harry Todd Reserve\" sign, on Hine Road ([[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=hine+road,+wainuiomata&sll=37.0625,-95.677068&sspn=48.909425,79.101563&ie=UTF8&ll=-41.276604,174.956082&spn=0.002854,0.009656&z=17&layer=c&cbll=-41.276604,174.956082&panoid=2_0YqP60t63jukVPbOoSsQ&cbp=11,183.10800866705756,,0,13.067983367111108 Street View]]), less than 0.2km from the Main Road intersection.','The sign at the intersection with [[track:203]] refers to \"Kiwanis Track\", though the Hutt City Council call this the Harry Todd track.','2.094',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-30 16:36:46',23,'-41.278839','174.960966',16,3,1,1,23,'2008-12-30 16:36:46','calc',5),(203,'Mount Crowther',9,'','Combination of sweet singletrack and extremely steep 4wd track.','From the T-intersection with [[track:202]], there is a 0.3km long piece of singletrack up to a small plateau. There you\'ll find a communications tower and a couple of buildings. The rest of the track is a steep 4wd road to the end of Sunny Grove.\r\n[[para]] \r\nAfter rolling up and down some small hills, there is a very steep (25-30%) section up to the summit.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThen the fun begins. The track drops straight down a ridge - losing 250m in altitude in just over a kilometre.  Parts of this drop are extremely steep, having a gradient in the range 30-35%. Excellent brakes, or more than a touch of madness, are called for on this descent as there is no where to bail out and little respite from the relentless pull of gravity.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom of the hill is a chicane followed by a tame exit to Sunny Grove.','Starts at a T-intersection in the middle of [[track:202]].  Ascending from the Willis Grove end of [[track:202]] is by far the easiest approach to this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the top end of Sunny Grove, off Hine Road.','','2.531',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-31 19:14:36',23,'-41.285063','174.964356',15,4,1,3,23,'2008-12-31 19:14:36','calc',5),(204,'Kiwanis Lookout',9,'','Short connector from [[track:202]] to [[track:203]], near the lookout plateau.','This track is more-or-less parallel to the singletrack section of [[track:203]] and never more than about 50m to the southeast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough it is marked at the [[track:202]] end with a sign that says \"Lookout\", this track doesn\'t actually go up to the lookout - though it does take you in that general direction. To reach the lookout you need to continue up [[track:203]] just a little bit.','Branches off [[track:202]] at a sign that says \"Lookout\", about 30m from its intersection with [[track:203]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an unmarked T-intersection with [[track:203]], about 70m below the communications tower plateau (which could be called a lookout, of sorts).','','0.252',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2008-12-30 16:20:39',23,'-41.281112','174.960226',17,3,1,1,23,'2008-12-30 16:20:39','calc',5),(205,'Poole Crescent',9,'','Gentle wander along the banks of the Wainuiomata River.','This is a gentle wander through the pleasant gardens and trees of Poole Crescent Reserve, which is adjacent to the Wainuiomata River.\r\n[[para]]\r\nInitially the track is a smooth gravel path.  At the end of the Reserve cruise down the long car park outside the Wainuiomata AFC clubroom and grounds. At the end of the car park jump over the low barrier and follow the fenceline towards the bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bridge, instead of crossing the river veer into the bush just upstream of the large pipe.  Follow this short piece of singletrack to either a metal barrier at the end of Hine Road, or ford the creek and head towards the start of [[track:84]].','Starts on Main Road, at the south-eastern corner of a bridge over the Wainuiomata River.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the eastern end of Hine Road.','','1.407',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-16 19:12:39',23,'-41.274871','174.961996',15,1,1,2,23,'2009-01-16 19:12:39','calc',5),(206,'Pylon Loop',16,'','4wd access road for a transmission line that runs through the Kaitoke Regional Park.','This is an easy climb or docile descent along a gentle road through mature pine forest. The road surface is a mix of gravel and soft mud reinforced with deep pine needle detritus.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDespite its name, this isn\'t actually a loop. However, a loop can be formed by adding [[track:207]]. In fact, if you\'re starting from the Kaitoke Regional Park, then climbing [[track:206]] and descending [[track:207]] is much easier than taking the reverse route.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor the more adventurous, take the [[track:214]] as an alternative to some of this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA short detour is also available from the eastern-most apex, where [[track:215]] is a spur.','Around 0.75km from the water treatment plant end of [[track:207]] you\'ll encounter a Y-intersection. [[track:207]] heads up the hill while [[track:206]] continues along at a more gentle grade.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:207]] and [[track:206]] meet at the northwestern end of the State Highway 2 underpass.','','2.121',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-08 10:13:53',23,'-41.081130','175.164256',15,2,1,3,23,'2009-01-08 10:13:53','calc',5),(207,'Kaitoke Hill',16,'','Rugged 4wd track from the Kaitoke water treatment plant up to State Highway 2.','The northern half of this track is a typical 4wd road, with nothing out of the ordinary. However, the other half is an undulating - and in some places quite rough - track that goes straight down the hill along the edge of a pine forest. It seems more like a fire break than a track, so perhaps its primary purpose is actually as a fire break for the forest.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn any case, there are several short, sharp rollercoaster style undulations along the generally downhill trend when travelling from south to north. Some of the short ascents will likely require a bit of walking.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf starting from the water treatment plant end, then [[track:206]] veers off towards the east after about 0.75km. Ascending [[track:206]] and the descending [[track:207]] is a much easier option than climbing [[track:207]].','Starts next to the water treatment plant, at the eastern end of the sealed road past the twin water reservior lakes.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:207]] and [[track:206]] meet at the northwestern end of the State Highway 2 underpass.','','2.067',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-08 10:31:24',23,'-41.081227','175.158763',15,3,1,3,23,'2009-01-08 10:31:24','calc',5),(208,'Station Connection',16,'','Short gravel road connection from Kaitoke Loop Road through to the intersection of [[track:209]] and [[track:210]].','This track provides a connection from the Kaitoke Regional Park through to either the Tunnel Gully Recreational Area (via [[track:209]]) or the [[track:213]] (via [[track:210]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that the area looks quite different to that shown in the Google map.  State Highway 2 was being reconstructed when that aerial photo was taken, but is now long since completed.  In particular, State Highway 2 has an underpass from the Kaitoke Regional Park through to the Kaitoke Loop Road. Also, much of the pine forest on the southern side of State Highway 2 has been cleared and replanted.','The northern end is on Kaitoke Loop Road about 0.1km northeast of the State Highway 2 underpass (which starts at the southern intersection of [[track:207]] and [[track:206]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end is at the intersection of [[track:209]] and [[track:210]].','As of 3 January 2008 the entrance has a notice that says: \"Authorised access only. Logging trucks operating weekdays from 5 January 2009\". ','0.534',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-08 09:27:15',23,'-41.088619','175.161939',16,2,1,4,23,'2009-01-08 09:27:15','calc',5),(209,'Station Drive',16,'','Forestry road that follows part of the old railway line.','This track was part of the old railway line from Wellington to the Wairarapa. Other parts of the line can be seen in the Tunnel Gully Recreation Area (especially in the Maymorn area) and, of course, in the [[track:213]] which starts almost 2km to the east of this track\'s northern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track itself is smooth, with a gentle grade, and large radius corners - as would be expected from an old railway line. In the middle is a short diversion across an old railway bridge, whereas the road goes around and rejoins 0.1km further along.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFollow this track from the Tunnel Gully Recreational Area to the intersection of [[track:208]] and [[track:210]]. From there either take [[track:208]] to the State Highway 2 underpass and then into the Kaitoke Regional Park, or follow [[track:210]] to join up with the [[track:213]].','Northern end is at the intersection of [[track:208]] and [[track:210]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end meets Plateau Road 0.5km from the upper car park (which is the start of the Mount Climie track).','As of 3 January 2009 the entrance has a notice that says: \"Authorised access only. Logging trucks operating weekdays from 5 January 2009\".','2.172',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-08 09:43:31',23,'-41.099081','175.160780',14,2,1,4,23,'2009-09-22 19:51:15','calc',5),(210,'Goat Rock',16,'','Forestry road that goes up Goat Rock and then down to the [[track:213]].','This is a fairly typical winding forestry road that climbs part way up Goat Rock. Its most redeeming feature is that it provides a connection between either the Tunnel Gully Recreation Area or the Kaitoke Regional Park through to the [[track:213]] and subsequent tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe final drop down to meet the [[track:213]] is steep and twisty, making for a fun descent (or a difficult climb).','Starts from the intersection of [[track:209]] and [[track:208]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:213]], 2.7km from the car park.','Warning: This track passes about 0.7km behind the business end of the deerstalkers rifle range.  At around the halfway mark of this track, near an intersection with a road that looks like it goes down to the airstrip, there is a sign that says \"DANGER! Rifle range safety zone. Do not leave the road & go downhill\".\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/Danger.png:Rifle range warning sign on Goat Rock track:200:206]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt looks like there will be some forestry action in this area during 2009, so watch out for logging trucks and closure signs.','5.148',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-29 07:58:26',23,'-41.096494','175.175414',14,3,1,4,1,'2009-09-22 19:31:01','calc',5),(211,'Cross Creek',16,'','Easy track from the end of Cross Creek Road to the start of the [[track:212]].','This track provides access to the famous [[track:212]]. \r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the car park, the track climbs up a mostly gentle (apart from a couple of short, sharp bits) hill through the bush, alongside Cross Creek. At the upper end there is a bridge over Cross Creek immediately before emerging from the scrub into the old rail yards.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce you reach the rail yards, the [[track:212]] heads up the hill to your left (west).  The old rail yards end 0.3km to your right (east), which might be worth exploring before heading up the hill.','If travelling over the Rimutaka Hill from Wellington, take a right turn at the first intersection off State Highway 2 just after entering Featherston.  If you reach the railway line crossing State Highway 2 in the middle of Featherston, then you missed the turnoff.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFollow the mostly straight road for about 9km until Cross Creek Road branches off to the right.  The gravel Cross Creek Road continues for another 1km before ending at a car park, which is the start of the track.','','2.067',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-11 11:21:16',23,'-41.167057','175.225925',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-01-11 11:21:16','calc',5),(212,'Rimutaka Incline',16,'','The famous Rimutaka Incline converted to a walking and biking track.','This track follows the famous Rimutaka Incline railway line. From part way through the Summit Tunnel down to the rail yards the slope is typically 1 in 15 - a modest gradient for a mountain bike, but extremely steep for a railway line.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are three tunnels to pass through (in order, from the top): Summit Tunnel (576m long), Siberia Tunnel (108m long), and Prices Tunnel (98m long). It is advisable to take a light of some form for the Summit Tunnel.  Although the Summit Tunnel is straight - so the other end is always visible - it can be quite a disorienting experience with only the light at the far end of the tunnel for guidence. The other tunnels are curved but are sufficiently short that they don\'t really require a light (though having a light wouldn\'t hurt).\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.4km down hill from the Summit Tunnel there is a lookout (down a spur) that provides sweeping views of the valley.  The views are worth the short diversion.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust below the Siberia Tunnel is Horseshoe Gully - otherwise known as \"Siberia\" due to the local micro-climate. There was a curved earth embankment across the gully until, in 1967, it was washed away. Now there is a deep gully that has signs stating \"Steep, slippery approach to creek bed. Cyclists are advised to dismount and walk\". Chances are you\'ll have to dismount to cross the creek and ascend the other side anyway. Note that the track on the summit side of the gully is about 25m upstream of the track on the Cross Creek side.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs would be expected from an old railway line, the track itself is fairly smooth and evenly graded with gentle curves. Nonetheless, watch out for the occasional rut and stone on the track - especially if descending at speed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom of the track is at the old rail yards that formed the Cross Creek Station and settlement. From there, either return back up the incline or continue along the [[track:211]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Rimutaka Incline, viewed from the lookout near the top]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/RimutakaIncline.jpg:Rimutaka Incline, viewed from the lookout near the top:492:330]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Warning sign at the top of Siberia gorge]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/SiberiaSign.jpg:Warning sign at the top of Siberia gorge:492:419]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:213]] (start-5:00) and [[track:212]] (5:01-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:7244466]]','Top end ajoins the [[track:213]], starting from the summit plateau.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom end is at the old rail yards, from which [[track:211]] provides access to the exit road.','See [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/rimutaka-incline/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] and [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rimutaka_Incline Wikipedia]] for further information.','5.335',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-11 13:45:22',23,'-41.157461','175.201807',14,3,1,2,23,'2009-10-26 10:42:59','calc',5),(213,'Rimutaka Rail Trail',16,'','Northern, and easier, complement to the [[track:212]].','This track is built on the old Wellington-Wairarapa railway line, leading to the summit of the famous [[track:212]]. The track is a popular area for recreation, due to its easy grade, rugged scenery, historical significance, and easy accessibility.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeing an old railway line, the track\'s gradient is easy and consistent, averaging around 1% (uphill from the car park). The track surface is generally smooth and well-maintained.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround 0.6km from the car park you\'ll pass the deerstalkers rifle range - but don\'t worry, they should be shooting away from the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way you\'ll pass through the Pakuratahi Tunnel (91m long, and curved - so a light would be helpful but isn\'t necessary) plus cross several bridges. \r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the summit, either return the same way or continue through the 576m long Summit Tunnel along the [[track:212]] to [[track:211]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf doing a there-and-back trip on the [[track:213]], then an interesting alternative to the first part of the return trip might be to go (initially up and then mostly down) via the [[track:218]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are camping facilities on the summit plateau and at the [[track:216]]. See [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/tracks-and-walks/wellington/wairarapa/rimutaka-rail-trail/ DOC]] for more information.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:[[track:213]] (start-5:00) and [[track:212]] (5:01-end)]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:7244466]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Ghost train in one of the tunnels]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:6854866]]','Starts from a car park about 1.5km down a gravel road off a well signposted exit from State Highway 2. An alternative entry is to take [[track:210]], which joins 2.7km from the car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the summit rail yards.','See [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Rimutaka-Rail-Trail/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] for further information.','10.145',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-11 13:43:40',23,'-41.115185','175.186100',13,2,1,2,23,'2009-10-26 10:41:54','calc',5),(214,'Powerline Shortcut',16,'','Gnarly shortcut between sections of the [[track:206]], following a power line through the forest.','This is a sneaky shortcut between the lower and upper sections of [[track:206]], following the path of a wooden pole power line through a gap in the forest.  The track is barely formed, and hence rather rough in places, but makes for an interested diversion from the forest road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOn the Google Map it appears that this track continues on the southern side of [[track:206]] towards State Highway 2. Perhaps it once did, though on the ground things are much more overgrown than they were when that aerial photo was taken so such an extension doesn\'t really exist any more.','At a corner 0.15km from the northern end of [[track:206]] there is a set of power poles heading up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the upper ridge section of [[track:206]] the power line emerges through a gap in the trees.','','0.430',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-08 10:46:09',23,'-41.079513','175.163162',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-01-08 10:46:09','calc',5),(215,'Pylon Loop Extension',16,'','Spur off [[track:206]] to a power pylon.','This is a short spur off [[track:206]] that goes to the last pylon that is accessible from Kaitoke Hill.','Deviates off the western-most apex of [[track:206]]. \r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way.','The Google map suggests that there is a track heading down to the paddocks below Kaitoke Hill.  However, on the ground there is little evidence of such a track. It is likely to head into private land anyway.','0.304',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-11 10:40:38',23,'-41.077293','175.168859',17,2,1,3,23,'2009-01-11 10:40:38','calc',5),(216,'Pakuratahi River Camp',16,'','Camp site off the [[track:213]].','This is a short access road from the [[track:213]] down to a camping area next to the Pakuratahi River.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCamping facilities are rather spartan, consisting of a flat patch of land and a makeshift camp fire. That\'s it.  See [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/tracks-and-walks/wellington/wairarapa/rimutaka-rail-trail/ DOC]] for further information.','Drops down to the Pakuratahi River about 3km from the summit plateau, or about 0.5km up hill from Ladle Bend (which is also the northern end of the [[track:218]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way.','','0.348',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-11 10:14:21',23,'-41.128359','175.195461',17,2,1,3,23,'2009-01-11 10:14:21','calc',5),(217,'Dela Rosa',16,'','Smooth gravel road from the Rimutaka Hill Road (State Highway 2) to [[track:218]] near the [[track:213]].','The track initially ascends about 40m from the Rimutaka Hill Road.  Then, apart from a couple of short ascents, the track descends 235m at a near constant 9-11% gradient to meet [[track:218]] less than 0.5km from the [[track:213]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are intermittent patches of tarseal. Given the well formed nature of the otherwise gravel road, it is possible that the road was once sealed throughout its entire length.  In any case, the road surface is smooth and firm - making for a fast descent and relatively easy ascent.','The eastern end of the track is at a small parking area about 1.2km from the summit of Rimutaka Hill, on the Wellington side.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe western end meets [[track:218]] just up hill from where [[track:218]] deviates from [[track:213]] and heads up a parallel valley.','The name for this track comes from the signpost at the intersection with [[track:218]], which says \"Via Dela Rosa to SH2 Rimutaka Hill\".  In Spanish \"de la rosa\" means \"the rose\", though what relevance that has to this track is unclear.','4.001',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-05 12:20:02',23,'-41.117383','175.212364',15,3,1,4,23,'2009-01-05 12:20:02','calc',5),(218,'Back Road',16,'','Alternative to a section of the [[track:213]], running along and up a parallel valley.','From Ladle Bend, the track climbs up to meet [[track:217]].  It then turns into a valley that runs parallel to the [[track:213]], drops down a little to [[track:221]] and then climbs more-or-less steadily to a saddle point where [[track:219]] branches off to the local summit.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust 40m after the [[track:219]] corner, the track splits into two branches.  The lower branch is [[track:220]], while [[track:218]] continues on the upper branch to climb a bit further and then drop down to rejoin [[track:213]] at the summit plateau.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a reasonable amount of climbing when heading from north to south - around 200m altitude gain in total, at a typical gradient of 10% and occasionally up to 15%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf doing a there-and-back trip on the [[track:213]], then an interesting alternative to the first part of the return trip might be to go (mostly down) via the [[track:218]].','The northern end heads up the hill off the [[track:213]] a few metres south of the Ladle Bend bridge, around 0.5km north of the [[track:216]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end branches off [[track:213]] just as it reaches the summit plateau, about 0.25km from the summit shelter.','','3.457',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-07 09:43:03',23,'-41.132771','175.204554',14,3,1,4,23,'2009-01-07 09:43:03','calc',5),(219,'Centre Ridge',16,'','Short excursion from [[track:218]] offering inspiring views of the surrounding mountains.','The summit of Centre Ridge is the location of one of Greater Wellington Regional Council\'s automatic hydrological monitoring stations. Although the monitoring station isn\'t much to look at, the views certainly are. \r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the summit of this peak there are spectacular views of the surrounding mountains - which are mostly 200-300m higher with deep valleys inbetween, giving the impression of standing on the raised centre of a huge bowl. The summit is only 60m higher that the turnoff from [[track:218]], so the short climb is well worth the effort.\r\n\r\n','Branch off [[track:218]] at a hairpin bend immediately before the top of [[track:220]] and just north of [[track:218]]\'s highest point.\r\n[[para]]\r\nDeadend, so return the same way.','Google\'s aerial photo shows a track heading north along the ridge.  While this track is discernable on the ground, as of 4 January 2009 it was so overgrown as to essentially not exist.','0.609',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-07 10:15:11',23,'-41.134565','175.201356',16,3,1,3,23,'2009-08-06 20:55:04','calc',5),(220,'Pig Gully',16,'','Deadend forestry access road that branches off [[track:218]].','This track looks like it should go somewhere.  However, it just provides access to recent pine planting areas so it now has no other exit (if it ever did).\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.25km from the start there is a fork in the road - the upper branch goes around the hill immediately in front, while the lower branch is the continuation of [[track:220]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nA spur roughly in the middle of the track heads down towards the [[track:213]].  Although the Google aerial photo suggests that the track almost reaches the [[track:213]], in fact it stops well short - actually only about 75m at the closest point, but with 2-3m tall pine trees (as at 4 January 2009) and dense gorse and scrub inbetween, there is no obvious way to reach the [[track:213]].  Perhaps a connection will be possible when the trees have grown sufficiently to thin the scrub, but not yet.','Take the lower road off [[track:218]] 40m past the intersection with [[track:219]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nDeadend so return the same way.','','2.285',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-07 11:57:40',23,'-41.132512','175.196700',15,3,1,3,23,'2009-01-07 11:57:40','calc',5),(221,'Miro Creek',16,'','Deadend forestry access road that branches off [[track:218]].','This is a short forestry road that wanders up a valley next to Miro Creek.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe forest area around the end of this track looks like it was cleared and then replanted in 2007/08.  There are tracks up the hill from the clearing at the end, but they will be gone in a year or two as the seedlings have been planted on those tracks.','Branches off [[track:218]] about 0.5km from its intersection with [[track:217]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nDeadend so return the same way.','','0.701',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-07 10:53:38',23,'-41.123898','175.210111',16,2,1,4,23,'2009-01-07 10:53:38','calc',5),(222,'Black Creek',9,'','Almost flat north-south connector through Wainuiomata.','This track runs alongside the eastern bank of Black Creek, traversing much of the length of Wainuiomata in a north-south direction.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNot that there is actually a track, as such, for most of the way.  It is more of an open grassy area that is accessible to bikers, walkers, and runners.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough the track runs for over 3km through a surburban area, it crosses only one road (Nelson Crescent).  Along the way there are several foot bridges over the creek, a couple of ditches to negotiate, and a bunch of deadend roads that ajoin the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nUnusually for the [[region:1]] area, this track is essentially flat.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you continue north for 1.7km along Upper Fitzherbert Road you\'ll find the bottom of [[track:200]]. At the Nelson Crescent intersection, if you head 0.75km west you\'ll find the bottom of [[track:76]].','The southern end is next to the Wainuiomata Bowling Club, at a steel gate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end is at the intersection of Norfolk Street and Upper Fitzherbert Road.','Much of the western bank of Black Creek is also ridable, with a couple of exceptions:\r\n[[bullet:Halfway along there is a deep drain next to playing fields at the intersection of Fitzherbert Road and The Strand â€“ go around the drain via the Girl Guides car park.]]\r\n[[bullet:About 0.25km south of Best Street the track along the western bank of Black Creek is blocked by the back yards of houses so that you can proceed no further south.]]','3.040',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-16 17:25:27',23,'-41.255549','174.949207',14,1,1,2,23,'2009-08-07 20:38:52','calc',5),(223,'Rotary Park',9,'','Gentle path through Rotary Park.','This is an easy meander along a track that follows Black Creek to its confluence with the Wainuiomata River, then turns into the more open part of Rotary Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the northern section the track surface is a smooth, though narrow, gravel path.  After crossing a small wooden bridge the track follows the Wainuiomata River through a wide grassy area where you\'re free to choose your own route.','The northern end is on Main Street, opposite Moohan Street, and about 0.15m from the southern end of [[track:222]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end is under the \"Rotary Park\" archway on the northwestern end of a bridge on Main Street - diagonally opposite the western end of [[track:205]].','','1.097',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-16 19:21:25',23,'-41.272598','174.950838',16,1,1,1,23,'2009-01-16 19:21:25','calc',5),(224,'Kingsley',17,'','Fairly easy entry to the northern sector of the eastern Hutt hills, from the top of Kingsley Street.','From the steel gate at the top of Kingsley Street follow the gravel road around to the south.  After just 60m there is another pair of steel gates - jump over the lower gate (the other goes up to a water reservoir) and continue along the gravel road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlmost 1km from the start there is a Y-intersection which has a very wide gravel road heading down the hill and a narrower 4wd track heading up the hill. As of July 2009 the wide road was blocked by a deliberately placed log. Take the narrower track up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track gets progressively narrower, eventually turning into single track around 0.4km from the top. At that point there is an overgrown track that heads down the hill towards the southwest (on your right when ascending) - it is a deadend pylon access road, so take the singletrack on your left.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top 50m of this track was destroyed by logging operations which created a clearing at the intersection of [[track:363]] and [[track:226]]. In making the clearing, a large amount of tree debris and dirt was pushed into what used to be the top of this track, forming an insurmountable wall.  For a while there was a rope tied to a large tree to assist with climbing up the 2m high bank. However, that access was covered by further forestry work and now (as at July 2009), you\'ll need to climb up a 3m high near-vertical dirt bank â€“ which is quite a difficult scramble with a bike.','Starts from the end of Kingsley Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds in a large clearing at the intersection of several other tracks, including [[track:363]] and [[track:226]]. If you\'re in the clearing, then to find where the track enters the treeline look towards the west and there is a small dip in the dirt edge next to a couple of possum control posters stapled to a tree.','','3.543',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-17 10:24:22',23,'-41.165603','174.997187',14,3,1,3,23,'2009-07-11 14:00:06','calc',5),(225,'Kiln',17,'','Difficult entry to the northern end of the eastern Hutt hills, from Kiln Street.','From Kiln Street head along a flat path as shown on the map. Turn to the left of a shed and cross a rather unpleasent little creek.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThen head up a steep and deeply rutted clay track. The climb is short, but will probably require a bit of walking and bike carrying.  Descending down this section is challenging even under the best of conditions - when wet, parts of the steep section are very slippery and difficult.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe rest of the climb is relatively tame, apart from a few axle-deep  mud puddles (though it is easy enough to go around them).\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top is a T-intersection. The track going up to the left is [[track:226]], while the track going down to the right is [[track:232]] (which is a much easier way to reach or exit from that point).','Starts on Kiln Street in Silverstream.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:232]] and [[track:226]].','','1.401',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-19 12:27:27',23,'-41.151451','175.001907',16,4,1,1,23,'2010-01-01 13:18:27','calc',5),(226,'Pinehaven Ridge',17,'','Bush clad climb along a ridge overlooking Pinehaven.','Heading up from the intersection with [[track:232]] and [[track:225]], the track is initially steep with a deeply rutted clay surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs shown on the map, after just 0.15km you\'ll encounter a Y-intersection. The left-hand branch is flatish and looks inviting, while the right-hand branch heads up a steep and rutted track. Take your pick: the left-hand branch is initially easy but at the apex turns into a steep and deeply rutted climb; the right-hand branch is initially a steep and deeply rutted climb and then gets flatter. The right-hand branch is probably slightly easier. The alternatives rejoin 0.25km up the right-hand branch.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround 1.1km from the start you\'ll meet a T-intersection. Turn right uphill, since the left-hand branch ends 0.1km downhill (as shown on the map). From this intersection to the large clearing at the top the track surface is more of a forestry road, being generally much firmer and smoother.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf heading down from the large forestry clearing, it might be easier to get confused by the several tracks that branch off this one. In most cases the way to go is fairly obvious - just stick to the main road. However, there are a couple of intersections to note:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:About 0.3km from the top there is a Y-intersection. Take the right-hand road that heads slightly down (rather than heading up to the left).]]\r\n[[bullet:About 1.7km from the top there is a track that branches off at 90 degrees to the left while what appears to be the main track continues straight ahead and slightly down (this is the T-intersection 1.1km from the bottom, as mentioned above). The straight ahead track actually ends 0.1km further along in a circular clearing. If you end up there, then backtrack and take the other branch.]]','Starts at an intersection with [[track:232]] and [[track:225]], above the [[link:http://www.silverstreamrailway.org.nz/ Silverstream railway museum]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a large forestry clearing, where it meets [[track:81]], [[track:224]], and several other tracks.','The stated track length includes the alternative path and the deadend section. If you stick to the main track then the length is 2.8km. ','3.163',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-19 10:35:54',23,'-41.163665','175.005255',14,3,1,3,23,'2009-08-06 20:51:41','calc',5),(227,'Old Soil Bureau',17,'','Steep circuit around the Old Soil Bureau.','From Shaftesbury Grove head along an initially rolling track until, at around the 0.8km mark, you encounter a large water tank. On the western side of the tank there is a closed track that goes down towards the actual old soil bureau.\r\n[[para]]\r\nInstead of going that way, head up the hill on the southern side of the water tank and continue to the summit (which is very near the southern-most point of the track). Some parts of the climb are quite steep, though only for short bursts at a time.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the summit, the track drops 200m down to the Eastern Hutt Road at an almost constant 18% gradient.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe section of track from the water tank to the summit is a narrow sealed road, though the seal is getting a bit rough around the edges.','Starts at the end of Shaftesbury Grove, off Holborn Drive.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on the Eastern Hutt Road.','','2.727',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-17 09:38:07',23,'-41.178654','174.969635',15,3,1,5,23,'2010-01-09 19:28:24','calc',5),(228,'NI XC Cup 2009',5,'','This is the course for the North Island Cross Country Cup, held on 18 January 2009. Competitors in the Cup did from 2 to 5 laps, depending on the class. The course provides a sample of the track variety that Mount Victoria has to offer.','[[bold:Stage 1: Velodrome to Alexandra Road (0.7km)]][[br]]\r\nStart from the metal barrier on the southeast side of the velodrome. Do a clockwise partial lap of the velodrome then head north through the car park and up the sealed exit road. Turn sharply left and go up past a metal barrier at the steep start of [[track:147]] until you reach and cross Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 2: Alexandra Road to main summit car park (1.1km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn right along [[track:144]] and shadow Alexandra Road for 0.55km until just past a loop road. At that point leave the [[track:144]] (which drops down into the trees) and take the loop road up to the intersection of Alexandra Road and Lookout Road.  Continue around to the left and then the right on the verge of Lookout Road until you reach the main summit car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 3: Main summit car park to grass area (0.9km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn left down the steep end of [[track:229]].  Stay left through a couple of intersections for 0.45km, leaving the [[track:229]] via some single track to briefly follow the [[track:144]] track. Take a shortcut down to the right and follow [[track:231]] north for 0.25km. Veer right at the next Y intersection up [[track:230]] for a 0.1km long steep climb up under the Macrocarpa trees. Then take the very steep rooty right turn up another 0.1km to the top of the open grass field.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 4: Grass area to [[track:145]] (0.4km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn left and descend [[track:144]] across the grass. About 20m into the trees turn right down a single track. Turn left then acute right to the top of an extremely steep ski slope chute.  Plummet down (or go around) the chute, watching out for the step down at the bottom. Continue down some rolling track then, instead of dropping down to the sealed path, turn left up a narrow and rooty track to an open grass area where you join the [[track:145]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 5: [[track:145]] to Grove (1.2km)]][[br]]\r\nFollow [[track:145]] for 0.2km until leaving it and heading up hill from a hairpin corner. Climb up for 0.05km then drop down for almost 0.1km to the right towards Charles Plimmer Park. Climb 0.05km up the grass to follow the cliff edge above Charles Plimmer Park. Head south for 0.8km, crossing the [[track:229]], Dovetail, and then [[track:231]] as you climb up into a circular grove of mature trees close to Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 6: Grove to Alexandra Road (0.9km)]][[br]]\r\nFrom the grove, turn sharply right down an initially steep and tricky piece of single track and continue around to the right for 0.4km until you drop on to [[track:147]]. Turn sharply left on [[track:147]] and head south for 0.5km, climbing back up to Alexandra Road (to the point that was also the end of Stage 1).\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 7: Alexandra Road to Fever Hospital (0.7km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn right down the single track and at the Y-intersection veer right and continue a total of 0.4km to Alexandra Park. Cross Alexandra Park and climb up the middle of the bank opposite. Take the single track up and along the cliff then down a tricky and twisty track, complete with drop off the end of a wooden structure, to exit on to the seal outside the old Fever Hospital â€“ or take the easier path down [[track:144]] to rejoin on the seal.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 8: Fever Hospital to roundabout (0.8km)]][[br]]\r\nDon\'t cross Alexandra Road yet â€“ instead, jump the kerb and head 0.35km south along some single track that runs parallel to Alexandra Road, cross an open field then around to a small parking area off Alexandra Road.  Now cross Alexandra Road and turn right to head south on [[track:144]] for 0.45km, passing through mature trees and across an open field then more trees, to a hairpin bend adjacent to the roundabout at the intersection of Constable Street, Wellington Road, and Crawford Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 9: Roundabout to Velodrome (1.0km)]][[br]]\r\nAt the roundabout fly around the berm then gather enough speed to climb up the steep bank 0.1km opposite â€“ known as the Big Dipper. Continue another 0.15km up through the trees and cross the same field as before (though 10m downhill). Exit the clearing into the trees and continue for 0.3km then take the first left uphill for 0.05km. Turn right at the T-intersection onto [[track:146]] and follow this track for the remaining 0.4km back to where you started next to the velodrome.','Starts and ends at the velodrome.','For further information see [[link:http://pnp.org.nz/mtb/events/2009/NIXC2009Cup-MtVic PNP Cycling Club]] and [[link:http://www.bikenz.org.nz/Resource.aspx?ID=3144 BikeNZ]].','7.448',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' with some advanced bits','2009-01-19 07:30:56',23,'-41.301604','174.789906',14,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:19:23','calc',5),(229,'Lookout Walkway',5,'','Walkway up to the Mount Victoria lookout car park.','From [[track:147]] head up a rooty though fairly wide track that is quite steep in places.\r\n[[para]]\r\nKeep heading up hill and to the north until, after about 0.3km, you emerge into an open grass area. Just before the grass area is an intersection with [[track:230]], which heads off in the opposite direction towards the southeast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn the grassy area, swing around to the right and up a steep section to join [[track:144]] at the point where it veers around to the east towards Palliser Road. [[track:144]] and [[track:229]] coincide for 0.2km, so just continue up the hill towards the southeast. At the next major intersection (which is also the end of [[track:230]]) head up to the left and then sidle around the hill just below Lookout Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.25m from the last grass area you\'ll encounter the final intersection. The left-hand branch continues to Lookout Road via a set of steps (which can be ridden down, if you stay on the left-hand side of the steps), while the right-hand branch goes straight up to the main car park just below the summit.','Branches off [[track:147]] just above Charles Plimmer Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the main lookout car park, with an alternative spur that ends 100m east on Lookout Road.','','1.018',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-18 10:53:17',23,'-41.295704','174.793103',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:29:19','calc',5),(230,'Lookout Scenic',5,'','Scenic route alternative to the [[track:229]].','This is a short, slightly more technical, alternative to part of the [[track:229]]. A branch also connects with the [[track:231]] track to the south.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSince this is a more direct path to the [[track:144]], it is also quite steep - especially the last section up to and alongside an open grass area.','The northern end branches off [[track:229]] just before it emerges into an open grass area. An alternative entry branches off [[track:231]] and then joins the main track half way up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the intersection where [[track:229]] deviates from the [[track:144]].\r\n','','0.302',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-18 11:07:59',23,'-41.295333','174.791805',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:28:52','calc',5),(231,'Mt Vic Summit',5,'','Direct route to the summit of Mount Victoria.','From Pirie Street climb up a wide and mostly easy track. You\'ll cross the [[track:147]] after about 0.1km, but continue up the hill for a further 0.3km.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the marked intersection with the alternative [[track:231]] branch, turn right and head up the hill.  The alternative branch starts on [[track:229]] 0.15m to the north, and also has [[track:230]] veering off about one third of the way along.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce the alternative branches merge follow the signs for about 0.25km up to the intersection of Alexandra Road and Lookout Road, including a very short section where the track coincides with [[track:144]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nCross the road and climb straight up a grassy knob to the pyryimid shaped [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/services/arts/publicart/gallery.php?type=memorial&page=1 Richard Evelyn Byrd Memorial]]. From there, cross the car park and climb up either the steps or the adjacent grass to the summit look out.','The main track starts at a park just off the top of Pirie Street. An alternative entry branches off the [[track:229]] about 0.2km from its [[track:147]] track end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the summit of Mount Victoria.\r\n','','1.064',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-18 11:30:37',23,'-41.297235','174.791569',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:34:59','calc',5),(232,'Goodwin Drive',17,'','Easy climb up from Reynolds Bach Drive to meet [[track:225]] and [[track:226]].','This track provides an easy entry to, or exit from, the northern end of the eastern Hutt hills - certainly much easier than the deeply rutted [[track:225]] track that starts 1.3km to the northeast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom Reynolds Bach Drive to the intersection of [[track:225]] and [[track:226]] is a 70m climb at a moderate 10% average grade.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track\'s name comes from a \"street sign\" at the top, though no other reference to the name has been found.','Turn off the Eastern Hutt Road and go almost 1km up Reynolds Bach Drive. The track starts with a metal barrier set back from the road in a grassy area on a corner.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at the intersection of [[track:225]] and [[track:226]].','Reynolds Bach Drive is the deadend access road for the Silverstream landfill. There are two gates across the road - the top gate, next to the water pumping station, is locked whenever the landfill is closed; the lower gate, next to the railway museum is sometimes open when the landfill is closed but don\'t count on it. If you have a car, then probably best to park it on the flat next to the Eastern Hutt Road and then bike up Reynolds Bach Drive.','0.732',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-29 23:22:56',23,'-41.155111','174.997069',17,2,1,3,23,'2009-04-29 23:22:56','calc',5),(233,'Radome',2,'','Steep descent from near the radar dome to the Waipapa Valley.','Just past the radar dome jump over the metal barrier at a sign-posted 4wd track that deviates off the sealed road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track initially goes up about 20m to a lookout over the deep valley below. It then drops sharply down to the right along what probably used to be a 4wd track but is now more like single track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nApart from a couple of bumps, the track descends down a ridge at around a 20% gradient until it turns across the eastern face of the hill and heads to the valley floor.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe lowest point on the track is where it crosses the Waipapa Stream which meanders along the valley floor - at an altitude that is some 380m lower than the highest point. From there it is a short but steep climb up to meet the northern side of the [[track:234]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the intersection with [[track:234]] the choices are to either turn left and go up the 30% gradient to [[track:39]], or go down to the valley floor (again) then up the not quite so steep but much higher southern part of [[track:234]]. Or if you\'re really keen you could go down to the valley floor then up [[track:236]] to [[track:61]].','Starts 0.2km south of the radar dome, where the sealed road goes around a knob to the right this track continues straight ahead to the left of the knob.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:234]].','Presumably the name Radome is a truncation of \'radar dome\', since the track starts near the Airways Corporation radar dome at the summit of Hawkins Hill.','2.849',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-20 21:03:36',23,'-41.339733','174.726305',14,3,1,1,23,'2009-01-20 21:03:36','calc',5),(234,'Waipapa Loop',2,'','Very steep loop off [[track:39]] to the floor of the Waipapa Valley.','This is a very steep loop off [[track:39]] down to the floor of the Waipapa Stream valley and then back up to [[track:39]]. The track surface is quite rocky and occasionally a bit loose on top but firm underneath.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the bottom of the valley you can either continue around the loop or climb up [[track:236]] to [[track:61]] - and from there either up to [[track:235]] or down to [[track:63]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nOn the northern side of [[track:234]] the [[track:233]] track branches off to the north at a T-intersection less than 0.3km from [[track:39]].','Branches off [[track:39]] 2.5km from the top and then rejoins [[track:39]] a further 0.4km towards [[track:63]].','','1.451',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-24 11:14:56',23,'-41.348859','174.723827',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-01-24 11:14:56','calc',5),(235,'Te Kopahau',2,'','Gravel road along a ridge to the top of Te Kopahau Reserve, overlooking Cook Strait.','This rolling gravel road takes you to a hilltop that offers spectacular views over Cook Strait towards the South Island.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you approach the end there is a Y-intersection. The right-hand branch heads down into Long Gully, which is private property. Take the left-hand branch below a small building and onto a flat area where the track simply ends.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEither return the same way or, if you\'re really keen, backtrack 0.2km and drop down [[track:61]].  Alternatively, return to 0.2km south of the radar dome and head down [[track:233]].','Starts 0.5km along the sealed road past the radar dome, 0.1km before the sealed road ends.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a cliff top overlooking Cook Strait.','','1.782',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-20 20:37:41',23,'-41.336575','174.715619',15,2,1,4,23,'2009-01-20 20:37:41','calc',5),(236,'Waipapa West',2,'','Connection from the bottom of [[track:234]] to [[track:61]].','This is a short and steep connection between [[track:61]] and [[track:234]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nLike most of the tracks in the [[area:2]] area, the track surface is rocky and loose (especially when dry), which can make for a difficult climb due traction issues.  The loose surface can also make for a tricky descent on the steeper sections.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe climb out of Waipapa Stream valley is steep whichever way you go, with the choices being: [[track:236]], [[track:234]], and [[track:233]].','Branches off [[track:61]] almost halfway down and meets [[track:234]] on the valley floor.','','0.845',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-24 11:26:30',23,'-41.348971','174.717915',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-01-24 11:26:30','calc',5),(237,'Cooks Road',15,'','Entry to the [[area:15]] off Bulls Run Road.','From Bulls Run Road the track starts with a bridge over a stream.  You\'ll soon encounter a gate with barbed wire along the top. The [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/how-to-get-there/ Greater Wellington Regional Council]] lists Cooks Road as an official entrance to the [[area:15]], so it is unclear why the barbed wire is there.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnyway, carefully throw the bike over the gate and nip over the fence to the left. Continue along a flatish road, sheltered by the edge of the forest, until reaching another bridge. There is a \"Puketiro Road\" sign attached to this bridge, though it doesn\'t make much sense for Puketiro Road to extend this far south.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust after the bridge the road turns steeply uphill, climbing at a gradient of 15%-20% to where it ends at an intersection with [[track:238]] and Clearys Road.','Starts from 2.1km along Bulls Run Road, off Moonshine Road. The section of Moonshine Road off State Highway 1 is winding and narrow (mostly 1-1.5 lanes), so taking Moonshine Road off State Highway 58 might be a better approach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a Y-intersection with [[track:238]] and Clearys Road.','There is little room to park a car at the start of this track, so if you are driving then it is probably best to park near the motocross track that is 0.25km further along Bull Run Road (though take note of the \"No trespassing\" signs).\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:237]] appears to be a route used by logging trucks, so beware.','1.333',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-25 11:49:53',23,'-41.074887','175.014503',15,3,1,4,23,'2009-09-30 20:47:09','calc',5),(238,'Puketiro Road',15,'','Main forest road from [[track:237]] to the top of [[track:139]].','From [[track:237]] continue climbing up hill at an initial 15-20% gradient. By the time you\'ve travelled for 2km the gradient has subsided to around 10% and at that point the road becomes undulating rather than constantly up.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWander along the ridgeline, noting the numerous side tracks and occasional hints of singletrack. Only a few of the diversions are signposted, that is: [[track:239]], \"Curtis Flat\" (off the apex of a corner next to a recently constructed radio mast), \"Blow Fly Road\" (0.4km from the western end), and \"M.O.T Block\" at the last Y-intersection (heading left, to the southwest).\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you approach the end of the track there is a large sign, at the base of the last hill, that says \"Battle Hill farm forest park\". At the Y-intersection just before the sign, turn right past the faded map board. Less than 0.2km further along is the top of [[track:139]], where it diverges off the road and up to near the summit - from which the views over [[area:13]] and beyond are absolutely stunning.','Eastern end is at an intersection with [[track:237]] and Clearys Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end is at the apex of [[track:139]] (the northern half of which is actually a continuation of Puketiro Road).','[[track:238]] appears to be a route used by logging trucks, so beware.','5.533',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-25 12:06:51',23,'-41.066863','174.991350',14,3,1,4,23,'2009-01-25 12:06:51','calc',5),(239,'Dick\'s Yard',15,'','Short connection between [[track:238]] and another forestry road.','This is a shortcut between [[track:238]] and an unnamed forestry road - that is, if you turn right at the end of this track the forestry road will take you back to [[track:238]] about 0.7k from where you left it.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the track is narrow and seemingly reverting to singletrack, though it is still passable by small 4wd vehicles.\r\n[[para]]\r\nLess then 0.2km from the southern end there is a short and extremely steep 20m drop over the hillside to the forestry road below - looks to be a favourite of the motocross riders.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe tracks ends with a 1m drop down on to a gravel forestry road.','Diverges off [[track:238]] about halfway along, at a signposted Y-intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an unmarked forestry road.','Despite the track\'s name, there is no sign of a \"yard\" as such - though it may have been superseded by the forest plantation.','0.572',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-01-25 11:46:09',23,'-41.066984','174.986351',17,3,1,3,23,'2009-01-25 11:46:09','calc',5),(240,'Tinakori Ridgeline',18,'','Central track along the ridgeline of Tinakori Hill.','There is a short section of sealed road at either end of this track.  The southern entrance is quite steep, though it isn\'t far to the top.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe rest of the track is a generally wide and smooth hard-packed gravel path along the ridgeline.  In a few places there are good views over the city and harbour.','Southern end heads up a sealed road into the trees at around 126 Orangi Kaupapa Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end also heads up a sealed road at the top end of the Weld Street cul-de-sac. It is sign-posted as \"Ridgeline Track\".','','1.615',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-26 20:35:24',122,'-41.270711','174.767075',15,2,1,3,23,'2009-12-20 20:41:15','calc',5),(241,'Huntingdon',18,'','Connection from [[track:240]] to the end of Huntingdon Street.','This is a nice piece of twisty singletrack from the [[track:240]] down to the streets of Wilton.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the track is under dense bush, making for pleasant surroundings where it is easy to forget that you\'re seldom more than 100m from houses.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track, in association with some on the southeastern side of [[area:18]], makes a handy commuting route from Wilton through to the CBD and vice versa.','Eastern end branches off [[track:240]] at a sign-posted intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end is at the end of the Huntingdon Street cul-de-sac turnaround area.','','0.791',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-02-26 21:00:07',122,'-41.271598','174.764757',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-12-20 20:41:36','calc',5),(242,'Karitane Entrance',19,'','Driveway loop that provides the most obvious entrance to the tracks in Truby King Park.','This driveway is included here because it provides the most obvious entrance to the top of the Truby King Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the northern-most point of the driveway, drop down into the trees where there are jumps and tracks being developed by the [[link:http://wgtn.mtbclub.org.nz/ Wellington Mountain Bike Club]] and [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/ Wellington City Council]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust beyond the top of this track, 20m into the trees, there is a sign that says: \"This area is being developed by Wellington Mountain Bike Club with support from the Wellington City Council. Please give way to walkers, check landings are clear before each run and ride to your ability. If you would like to help with this project, please email wgth@mtbclub.org.nz\".','Starts and ends on Manchester Street, under the archway that says \"Karitane\".','For safety reasons proceed around the loop in the clockwise direction. That is, if going up the driveway then take the left-hand branch of the loop.','0.500',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-31 19:55:35',23,'-41.320840','174.788811',17,1,1,5,23,'2009-03-31 19:55:35','calc',5),(243,'Karitane Jump',19,'','A jump track under the trees in Truby King Park.','This is a purpose-built jump track, with a series of dips and jumps along an almost 100m long straight track. The usual direction of travel on the jumps is from north to south. Note that there is a return path on the eastern side of the jump track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOff the southern end of the track there is a narrow, overgrown track that continues into the bush. After 50m it ends in someone\'s back yard, so best not go there.','The northern end is less than 0.1km from the apex of [[track:242]], down a short steep hill.\r\n','The jumps and tracks in this part of Truby King Park are being developed by the [[link:http://www.wmtbc.org.nz/ Wellington Mountain Bike Club]] and [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/ Wellington City Council]].','0.086',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-31 20:11:37',23,'-41.319172','174.788039',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-10-06 12:58:19','calc',5),(244,'Kotinga',19,'','Connecting track from the end of Kotinga Street to the main ridge through Truby King Park.','The Kotinga Street end starts with a short, steep, narrow path that has a broken seal surface. The track soon degrades into a gravel and mud surface, as the gradient becomes more sedate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThen climb up under the pine trees to the central ridgeline, where the track ends.','Starts from the end of Kotinga Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds just above a white metal barrier, at a T-intersection with [[track:335]].','','0.233',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-31 20:24:10',23,'-41.317802','174.788575',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-08-07 20:34:52','calc',5),(245,'A Trail',20,' MTB Only','A Trail is one of the great Whakawerawera trails. ','An awesome little trail that has some short sharp climbs and lots of sweet single track downhill.','From either car park head to the top of Nursery Hill road and head up Katore Road. Just past the Pooh ponds Katore Road splits. Turn left and A trail is approximately 20 meters ahead on the right.','','1.620',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' Grade 4','2009-02-02 20:40:14',59,'-38.171417','176.279197',16,3,3,1,75,'2009-12-14 19:53:09','calc',5),(246,'Be Rude Not Too',20,'','One of the classic tracks in Whaka Forest. A longish mainly downhill single track. If you are a visitor to the area this is a must do.','A longish downhill track with multiple exit possibilities all leading to different tracks.','','','2.500',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' Grade 3','2009-02-04 20:42:28',75,'-38.174000','176.282500',15,3,3,1,75,'2009-02-04 20:42:28','calc',5),(247,'Ball and Chain',20,'','A Short little trail that beats going along the road.','Short and Flat ... thats about it. But it beats riding on the road. :)','','','0.488',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' Grade 1','2009-02-04 20:41:34',75,'-38.185020','176.277270',17,1,3,1,75,'2009-08-13 13:49:27','calc',5),(248,'Billy T',20,'','Billy T','Awesome flowing single track from the top of the park. Worth the long haul getting up there. Signage indicates grade 4 but the track should easily doable by an average rider. There is a step up jump and a drop at the end but these can be easily seen and avoided if desired.\r\n\r\n[[link:http://www.riderotorua.co.nz/trails2.php?catid=2&id=24 More Info]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Billy T Elevation chart]]\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/sites/default/files/tracks.org.nz/billyt.png:Billy T:400:200]]','','','2.045',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' Grade 4','2009-02-04 20:50:33',59,'-38.190704','176.308765',14,3,3,1,75,'2009-12-20 16:08:22','calc',5),(249,'Grant Road',18,'','Short track from Grant Road up to the [[track:251]].','This track provides a convenient and apparently well-used commuting route from the city over to the suburbs around [[area:18]].  \r\n[[para]]\r\nApart from a hairpin bend at the Grant Road end, the track slices diagonally up the hill â€“ meeting the [[track:251]] in an area that was covered with mature pine trees until they were [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/news/display-item.php?id=1777 felled by a storm in 2004]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is quite steep, with a fairly constant gradient that averages 15%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the Scarff Memorial Scout Hall end of the track, there are two alternative routes â€“ one adjacent to the Scout hall itself and the other takes a short cut to the road.','Starts on Grant Road, next to the Scarff Memorial Scout Hall.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with the [[track:251]].','','0.424',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-02 20:22:43',23,'-41.275315','174.770679',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-05 10:02:26','calc',5),(250,'West East Connector',18,'','Short connection from [[track:240]] the to [[track:251]].','From the top, this track has a rolling profile as it drops off the ridgeline.  The last section is particularly steep, with a gradient of more than 20%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track itself is fairly wide - just qualifying as doubletrack.  Most of the track is under mature pine trees, so some of the dips can be a little boggy when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn association with [[track:241]], [[track:240]], [[track:251]], and [[track:249]], this track could form part of a commuting route to/from the city and the suburbs surrounding [[area:18]].','Deviates off [[track:240]] about 0.6km from the northern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMeets the [[track:251]] at an intersection that is sign-posted but otherwise not particularly obvious. [[track:251]] heads into the bush, while the nature flow of the track is straight down/up the hill.','At some point mechanisms will be installed on this track to slow down bikes, given that much of the track is quite steep.','0.452',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-02 21:23:17',122,'-41.271090','174.768662',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-12-20 20:41:49','calc',5),(251,'Northern Walkway',18,'','[[area:18]] section of the [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/walkways-and-tracks/187-explore-wellington-northern-walkway Northern Walkway]].','From the southern end, this track starts with a set of steps and some tight switchbacks.  After that, it curves around the hill and climbs steadily to an intersection where a track heads straight up the hill. Instead of going that way, drop down and around to the right via a wooden structure.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust around the corner is an intersection with the top of [[track:249]], which heads diagonally down the hill. The area around that intersection was covered with mature pine trees until they were [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/news/display-item.php?id=1777 felled by a storm in 2004]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue up the hill at a gradient of almost 15% for another 0.7km, to a sign-posted intersection with the bottom of the [[track:250]].  At that point the [[track:251]] briefly becomes singletrack, heading off into the bushes away from what appears to be the main track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter a short, sharp climb the track then descends over the next 1.3km - gently at first and then increasingly steeply.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFinally, the track ascends over the remaining 0.5km to Weld Street, with the last 0.35km on a partly sealed one-lane road.  A branch off this road goes up to the tennis courts on the ridgeline.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are several benches that offer pleasant surroundings and great views over the city skyline and the harbour.','The southern end is at the top of St. Mary Street, which is a steep, deadend street off Glenmore Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end is next to a green garage at 93 Weld Street, Wadestown - just over 0.1km downhill from the northern end of [[track:240]].  ','This is the only section of the [[link:http://www.feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/walkways-and-tracks/187-explore-wellington-northern-walkway Northern Walkway]] that is open to bikes. At some point mechanisms will be installed on the down hill part of this track to slow down bikes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are lots of tracks that deviate off this one, heading either up or down the hill.  All of them, apart from [[track:249]] and [[track:250]], are closed to bikes.','2.719',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-02 21:08:37',122,'-41.271324','174.771881',15,3,1,2,23,'2009-12-20 20:58:37','calc',5),(252,'Karapoti Challenge',15,'','Short version of an annual race around the [[area:15]]. The course includes a variety of track types and conditions, with challenging hill climbs and fun descents.','[[bold:Stage 1: Karapoti Road (1.7km)]][[br]]\r\nStart on Karapoti Road, 0.2km off Akatarawa Road, at the eastern end of the bridge over the Akatarawa River. Proceed west along Karapoti Road to where the road opens out into a car park at the end.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 2: [[track:191]] (4.3km)]][[br]]\r\nAt the western end of the car park, follow the track that heads up the [[track:191]]. After 0.4km you\'ll need to cross the unbridged Little Akatarawa River - which is rocky and cold, though shallow (except after heavy rain, when it can be deep and fast flowing). From there, the track meanders up the valley, climbing progressively alongside the Akatarawa River West before descending slightly to McGhies Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 3: [[track:192]] (2.0km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn left over the concrete McGhies Bridge, which crosses the Akatarawa River West. Climb over the metal gate and head up the moderately steep gravel road. After a while the road turns down hill, ending in a large clearing at a three-way intersection with [[track:193]] and [[track:194]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 4: [[track:193]] (3.2km)]][[br]]\r\nAt the clearing, turn left up a steep forestry road. After 1.8km of challenging climbing the road reaches the ridgeline. To the left is [[track:195]], but turn right to follow [[track:193]] for a further 1.4km along the rolling hill tops amongst mature pine forest.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 5: [[track:196]] (0.8km)]][[br]]\r\nAt a sign-posted intersection, turn right into [[track:196]]. This forestry road wanders along, gently weaving its way through the pines to the top of [[track:194]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 6: [[track:194]] (2.3km)]][[br]]\r\nAt a T-intersection, turn right down [[track:194]]. The descent is steep and fast, with a bit of rutted cornering to add some technical challenge. The clay surface offers little in the way of grip, other than a thin layer of pine needles, so beware if the track is wet. This Stage ends at the large clearing encountered at the end of Stage 3.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 7: [[track:192]] (2.0km)]][[br]]\r\nFrom here on you\'ll backtrack via the first three stages in reverse.  After a short climb, the descent to McGhies Bridge is fast.  Watch out for loose gravel and potentially vehicles heading up the hill towards you. Remember to stop for the metal gate at the near end of McGhies Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 8: [[track:191]] (4.3km)]][[br]]\r\nAfter a short, gently climb, hoon back down the [[track:191]] - again watching out for other track users (including horses and motor bikes) on this often busy track.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 9: Karapoti Road (1.7km)]][[br]]\r\nFinally, wander back along the access road back to the start/finish line.','Starts and ends on Karapoti Road, next to the bridge over the Akatarawa River.','See the [[link:http://www.karapoti.co.nz/default.asp?PageID=5042 Karapoti website]] for more information about the race.','22.300',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-03 20:38:33',23,'-41.069516','175.078640',13,3,1,4,23,'2009-08-26 17:43:49','user',5),(253,'Summit Road',17,'','Firebreak from [[track:81]] down to the top of Summit Road.','This is a steep firebreak that runs down a ridge between Fairfield and Naenae, from [[track:81]] to the top of Summit Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA typical gradient is in the range 15-20%, though there are some sections with a gradient of 30%+.  Being a firebreak, the surface is exposed to the weather so deep ruts can be expected on the steeper sections.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several sections of track that detour around the most extremely steep parts of the firebreak proper.  Although more moderate than the direct route, these short detours are still quite steep.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way two side tracks drop down secondary ridges on the eastern side of the main ridge (towards Naenae) - both are sign-posted as \"No exit\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn an attempt to keep motorised vehicles out of the Eastern Hutt Hills, the Summit Road end of the track is barricaded by a large steel gate and concrete blocks. Access is permitted for those on foot or mountain bikes - it is possible to squeeze a mountain bike through the gate (or lift it over the gate with some help).','The top joins [[track:81]] just under 0.3km west of the top of [[track:200]], or about 2km north of [[track:76]] along [[track:81]]. There are two alternative entry points off [[track:81]], just 50m apart.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom is at the end of Summit Road, just above Farrelly Grove.','','1.482',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-08 09:33:14',23,'-41.213303','174.943285',15,4,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 13:19:50','calc',5),(254,'Te Whiti',17,'','Firebreak from [[track:162]] down to Te Whiti Park.','This is a steep - in some places extremely steep - firebreak that drops down a ridgeline from the [[track:162]] to Te Whiti Park. Over a length of barely 1.5km the track drops 320m in altitude with only a couple of rests - giving an average gradient of 21%, though some sections are in excess of 30%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout a third of the way down there is a small plateau. Immediately next to the track, on the eastern side, is a pond for fire fighting. To the west is a small clearing leading to the entrance of the \"Konini Saddle Track\" that goes through the Hayward Scenic Reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.2km further down hill is a short section that can be best described as a cliff. Approach with caution, since it is not ridable by mere mortals. Instead, take the short detour to the right (as shown on the map).\r\n[[para]]\r\nRejoin the main firebreak and continue down the hill, trying to not collide with the black and white survey mark pole that is in the middle of the track.  Though that shouldn\'t be difficult because, apart from the cliff detour, the firebreak is wide enough to provide plenty of options regarding choice of line through the ruts and rocks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends with a large steel gate and concrete block barricade, which is easily circumvented.','Starts from a clearing at the top of the third, and final, precipitous stage of [[track:162]], off [[track:81]]. Note that this is towards the northern end of [[track:162]] - there is another firebreak off the southern end of [[track:162]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on the sealed perimeter path around Te Whiti Park, just north of the clubrooms. Follow this path to the south, to exit onto Whites Line East.','This track is on the northern border of Hayward Scenic Reserve. See [[link:http://www.waiwhetu.org Friends of Waiwhetu\'s Hayward Scenic Reserve]] for further information, including a [[link:http://www.waiwhetu.org/tracks.htm map]] of the many walking tracks in the reserve.','1.436',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-15 13:19:15',23,'-41.225522','174.930003',16,4,1,2,23,'2009-03-15 13:19:15','calc',5),(255,'Karapoti Classic',15,'','Gruelling annual race through the [[area:15]].','[[bold:Stage 1: Karapoti Road (1.7km)]][[br]]\r\nStart on Karapoti Road, 0.2km off Akatarawa Road, at the eastern end of the bridge over the Akatarawa River. The actual race starts with a Le Mans style fording of the Akatarawa River, but at any other time you can just cross the bridge. Proceed west along Karapoti Road to where the road opens out into a car park at the end.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 2: [[track:191]] (4.3km)]][[br]]\r\nAt the western end of the car park, follow the track that heads up the [[track:191]]. After 0.4km you\'ll need to cross the unbridged Little Akatarawa River â€“ which is rocky and cold, though shallow (except after heavy rain, when it can be deep and fast flowing). From there, the track meanders up the valley, climbing progressively alongside the Akatarawa River West before descending slightly to [[track:192]] Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 3: [[track:256]] (1.4km)]][[br]]\r\nSail past [[track:192]] Bridge and continue up the valley alongside the Akatarawa River West. This is a more-or-less flat forestry road that ends at a clearing that you\'ll return to after traversing a loop of the [[area:15]] that encompasses almost 34km of steep climbs, difficult technical track, and fast descents.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 4: [[track:280]] (5.1km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn right at the top of [[track:256]] and head northeast to go anti-clockwise around the main loop of the course.  This stage consists of a series of increasingly difficult ascents and descents, ending with a steep drop down to Cedarholm Creek. When you hit the creek, turn right and cycle right up the stream.  As the name suggests, this is just a warm up for the climb that follows.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 5: [[track:281]] (7.5km)]][[br]]\r\nThis is the first of three big climbs.  Actually it is several climbs interspersed with short downhill sections.  The track surface is difficult, being loose when dry and slippery when wet.  After a while you\'ll reach a rolling ridgeline that would provide awesome views except that vegetation has matured and grown too high. You\'ll continue to generally climb.  After descending a bit you\'ll reach a clearing where you need to turn hard left.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 6: [[track:282]] (1.3km)]][[br]]\r\nDrop down this steep and progressively gnarlier technical downhill which culminates in a boulder strewn rock garden.  There are also many drop offs to watch out for.  It ends in a deep gully at a river crossing.  The river is a good place for a rest, in preparation for the hell to come.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 7: [[track:283]] (1.8km)]][[br]]\r\nThe second big climb.  Much of this steep climb is unridable, so expect a fair bit of bike carrying.  The track surface often consists of deep mud, which makes the climb even more difficult.  The good news is that the end of the stage, at a clearing where the track meets Titi Road, represents roughly the halfway mark of the course.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 8: [[track:284]] (5.4km)]][[br]]\r\nContinue climbing to the highest point on the course, near the summit of Mount Titi.  Along the ridgeline the views over the forest and towards Kapiti are simply blocked again by high trees and vegetation.  Then cruise down hill, past the top of Perhams Road, to an intersection with Whakatikei Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 9: [[track:285]] (5.1km)]][[br]]\r\nTurn left into Whakatikei Road, otherwise known as [[track:285]] because it is a fast and almost continuously down hill run to Doper\'s Creek.  Watch out for some tight corners which can be tricky at speed.  As you approach the valley floor, you\'ll pass the eastern end of Norm\'s Crossing (on your right).  About 0.35km later you\'ll meet the point where Rimu Road crosses the Whakatikei River, which is the end of this stage.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 10: [[track:286]] (2.8km)]][[br]]\r\nThis is the third, and final, big climb.  This stage starts from just west of the confluence of Doper\'s Creek and the Whakatikei River.  Head up the hill for a 320m climb that is not as steep as the first two big climbs, but it is more consistently up.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 11: [[track:287]] (4.8km)]][[br]]\r\nTo complete the loop, cruise down the final big descent.  The gradient is initially mild, with some short ascents.  Then the track becomes steep and runs continuously downwards.  At the bottom, cross the Little Akatarawa River to arrive back at the top of [[track:256]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 12: [[track:256]] (1.4km)]][[br]]\r\nReprise this short wander alongside the Akatarawa River West with the knowledge that the worst is behind you.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 13: [[track:191]] (4.3km)]][[br]]\r\nAfter a short, gentle climb, hoon back down the [[track:191]] â€“ again watching out for other track users (including horses and motor bikes) on this often busy track.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 14: Karapoti Road (1.7km)]][[br]]\r\nFinally, wander along the access road back to the start/finish line.','Starts and ends on Karapoti Road, next to the bridge over the Akatarawa River.','See the [[link:http://www.karapoti.co.nz/default.asp?PageID=5042 Karapoti website]] for more information about the race.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThanks to Clive for the GPS data.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe following video covers the course through to the top of Dopers and includes extended Staircase and Big Ring Boulevard footage:\r\n[[media:vimeo:9135838]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Karapoti: elevation chart]]\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/trackfield_graph/graph/251%2C251%2Cfield_track_data/Normal/N::500:150]]','48.600',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-04 08:28:26',226,'-41.023168','175.054436',12,4,3,3,23,'2010-02-14 19:01:01','user',5),(256,'Hukinga Clearing',15,'','Relatively gentle forestry road alongside the Akatarawa River West to a clearing in the Hukinga Forest Block.','From [[track:192]] Bridge this track wanders further into the wilderness alongside the Akatarawa River West.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe clearing where this track ends is the start and the end of the grand loop part of the [[track:255]].','Starts from the northern end of [[track:191]], where it meets [[track:192]] Bridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a clearing at an S-bend in the Akatarawa River West, in the middle of the Hukinga Forest Block.','This track forms part of the [[track:255]].','1.393',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-02 10:58:40',23,'-41.054146','175.066023',15,2,1,3,23,'2009-04-02 10:58:40','calc',5),(257,'Coastal North',21,'','Coastal track north from Whareroa Road car park to The Esplanade.','This is an easy track over rolling sand dunes. There are great views over the beach and northwest towards Kapiti Island.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are several beach access points, plus a couple of secondary routes inland over the dunes towards the [[track:259]] track - though [[track:266]] is the only ridable connecting track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the northern end of this track you can continue along The Esplanade, which is part of the [[link:http://www.kapiticoast.govt.nz/NR/rdonlyres/15805B80-E89A-49DD-AA82-F1CAEE4E4ECE/23280/Cycleguide51104.pdf Kapiti Coast Cycle Route]]. ','Follow Whareroa Road around to the very end. The track heads off towards the north across a small bridge and into the dunes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end of the track is at the southern end of The Esplanade.  There are two small car parking areas - one at the end of the road and the other just inside [[area:21]]. Head up the small hill on the beach side of the second car parking area.','This track is part of [[link:http://www.teararoa.org.nz Te Araroa]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of this track is very exposed, so be prepared for a sand blasting if it is windy.','1.526',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 13:55:41',23,'-40.950214','174.971395',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 13:55:41','calc',5),(258,'Coastal South',21,'','Coastal track south of the Whareroa Road car park.','This easy track meanders though rolling sand dunes alongside Whareroa Beach. There are great views over the beach and northwest towards Kapiti Island.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several beach access points, plus many secondary routes inland over the dunes towards the [[track:260]] track.','The southern end is accessed off Wellington Road. Follow the sealed road around to the left to its northern-most deadend. From the point the track runs parallel to the beach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end starts from a sealed access road that turns off Whareroa Road at the crest of a small hill about 0.25km from the main car parking area. Further along this sealed road there are two additional short connections to the main track (as shown on the map).','This track is part of [[link:http://www.teararoa.org.nz Te Araroa]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of this track is very exposed, so be prepared for a sand blasting if it is windy.','1.530',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 14:44:18',23,'-40.964215','174.965043',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 14:44:18','calc',5),(259,'Inland North',21,'','Inland track north of the Whareroa Road car park.','This track mostly hugs the fenceline between [[area:21]] and Whareroa Farm.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough it is more sheltered than [[track:257]], this track a more hilly. Even though some of the hills are quite sharp, none are more than 20m high. The most interesting hill is just south of [[track:266]], where the track divides into two sides - lots of steps on one side and a horse/bike track of the other side.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are a couple of secondary routes over the dunes to the [[track:257]] track, though [[track:266]] (0.75km from the southern end) is the only easily ridable connecting track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.5km from the southern end, at the obvious apex visible on the map, [[track:267]] heads further inland towards MacKays Crossing.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome 0.2km from the southern end is a 0.1km long \"no stopping\" zone, along the boundary of the local model airplane club. Watch out for low flying aircraft!\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/No-stopping-sign.png:Low flying aircraft:250:283]]','There are four entry points for the northern end of the track:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:at the southern end of The Esplanade]]\r\n[[bullet:off the end of McKenzie Avenue]]\r\n[[bullet:via a fenced accesway between #23 and #25 Rainbow Cresent]]\r\n[[bullet:0.1km from the northern end of [[track:257]].]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end heads inland from the car parking area at the very end of Whareroa Road (directly opposite the southern end of [[track:257]]).','','2.675',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 14:17:13',23,'-40.950312','174.974227',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-08-06 21:00:55','calc',5),(260,'Inland South',21,'','Inland track south of the Whareroa Road car park.','This is an easy meander through the rolling hills of the inland sand dunes to the south of Whareroa Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are many secondary routes over the dunes towards the [[track:258]] track, though most have only a soft sand surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround halfway along the track there are a couple of relatively high vantage points overlooking the dunes, with bench seats conveniently placed for watching the sunset. Nice.','The southern end is accessed off Wellington Road. Follow the sealed road around to the left and then across the loop heading up hill and inland.  The track branches off the sealed road at sign-posted intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end starts from a sealed access road that turns off Whareroa Road at the crest of a small hill about 0.25km from the main car parking area, at a sign that says \"Paekakariki Inland Track\".','','1.710',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 14:58:26',23,'-40.966322','174.966202',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 14:58:26','calc',5),(261,'Wainui Urupa',21,'','Short extension of the [[track:260]] track, past a urupa (Maori burial place).','This is a bumpy grass track that follows a fenceline except for short sections at each end. The climb up from the [[track:265]] end is steep and long - but only relative to the other tracks in [[area:21]], meaning that it is only a few metres high.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs marked on the map, about 0.1km from the southern end the track passes a fenced urupa.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBarely 20m from the intersection with [[track:265]] is the southern end of the [[track:262]].','The northern end branches off [[track:260]], less than 50m from its southern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end meets [[track:265]].','','0.515',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 17:55:35',23,'-40.973880','174.963681',16,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 17:55:35','calc',5),(262,'Whareroa Horse Trail',21,'','Horse trekking trail across the southern part of Whareroa Farm.','This horse trekking trail meanders across open farm land along a sometimes indistinct 4wd farm track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOff to the side of the track, near the Whareroa Road end, is a series of horse jumps and other obstacles.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are markers showing the way, though some are difficult to spot in amongst the rolling hills and long grass. In particular, if heading south there is a point where it is easy to lose the track. At about the 1.2km point there is a farm gate up against a hill, where the track turns to the southeast. About 150m past the gate, watch out for a marker that is just visible through a saddle point in the hill to the south. If you keep heading towards the forested hills in the distance, then you missed the turnoff, so backtrack a bit.','The northern end branches off Whareroa Road about 0.7km seaward from the tram station, or 0.25km in the same direction from the eastern end of the [[track:264]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end meets [[track:265]] at a T-intersection, just 20m from the southern end of [[track:261]].','','1.799',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 18:26:02',23,'-40.970469','174.968562',15,3,1,3,23,'2009-03-13 18:26:02','calc',5),(263,'Surf Club',21,'','Short loop around the Paekakariki Surf Club.','This short loop ducks down to the beach, across the mouth of the Wainui Stream, and then back to the [[area:21]] access road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the southern end of the bridge there are two options: the most obvious track is through very soft sand; the ridable option goes a few metres inland through the bushes.','Just inside the [[area:21]] entrance off Wellington Road, and directly opposite the southern end of [[track:265]], head across the open grass area and then past a \"Beach access\" sign.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEmerges 0.25km north onto the same sealed road.','','0.597',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 16:31:33',23,'-40.974382','174.959893',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 16:31:33','calc',5),(264,'Tram Trek',21,'','Horse trekking path alongside the [[link:http://www.wellingtontrams.org.nz/about.html Kapiti Coast Electric Tramway]].','This is a horse trekking path that more-or-less follows the [[link:http://www.wellingtontrams.org.nz/about.html Kapiti Coast Electric Tramway]] alongside Whareroa Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen heading towards the beach, the track passes through a small stand of trees and runs along the verge of the tram line. The verge disappears 0.1km later, so cross the sealed road and wander another  almost 0.2km to the hill crest. Veer to the north down the single track, which emerges into an open field where the track ends.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt several points along the way there are tram track crossings marked with a small sign like the following:[[br]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/Watch-for-trams.png:Watch for trams:200:195]]','Southern end is on Whareroa Road, about 0.5km west of the tram station - marked with a horse sign and next to a \"No public access sign\" which refers to the two farm roads also at that point.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end meets [[track:259]], in an open area 0.1km from the turnaround area at the very end of Whareroa Road.','','1.343',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 16:03:58',23,'-40.961850','174.972854',15,1,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 16:03:58','calc',5),(265,'Wainui Stream',21,'','Pleasant loop through the bush alongside the Wainui Stream and around the [[link:http://www.paekakarikiholidaypark.co.nz/ Paekakariki Holiday Park]].','A gentle cruise around the [[link:http://www.paekakarikiholidaypark.co.nz/ Paekakariki Holiday Park]] and alongside the Wainui Stream.  A good part of the track is shaded by mature trees - which is particularly pleasant on a hot, sunny day as shade is a rare commodity in [[area:21]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround 50m west of the eastern-most point there are two intersections only 20m apart - one is the southern end of [[track:261]] and the other is the southern end of [[track:262]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhere the track passes the end of Tilley Road there is a large square roof with supports but no walls. Very odd.','Just inside the [[area:21]] entrance off Wellington Road, and directly opposite the southern end of [[track:263]], head along the boundary of the [[link:http://www.paekakarikiholidaypark.co.nz/ Paekakariki Holiday Park]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEmerges 0.15km north onto the same sealed road.','','1.128',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 17:28:33',23,'-40.976115','174.963262',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 17:28:33','calc',5),(266,'Whareroa Pa',21,'','Connection between [[track:259]] and [[track:257]] near the historic site of the Whareroa Pa.','This is the only connection between [[track:259]] and [[track:257]] that is reasonably riding on a mountain bike.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the \"summit\" there is a bench seat conveniently placed for admiring the surrounding sand dunes. The seat is close to being the highest point in the [[area:21]] - at little more than 30m above sea level, it isn\'t much of a hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is narrow and a bit soft in places, but nonetheless provides a useful shortcut between the [[track:259]] and [[track:257]] tracks.','The coastal end is 0.5km from the southern end of the [[track:257]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe inland end is 0.75km from the southern end of the [[track:259]] track, 0.2km north of [[track:267]].','','0.483',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 19:57:41',23,'-40.953265','174.972205',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 19:57:41','calc',5),(267,'Whareroa Stream',21,'','Grassy track alongside the Whareroa Stream.','This track follows the Whareroa Stream as it wanders through the edge of the Whareroa Farm. Along the way you\'ll likely be surrounded by a menagerie of animals, including cows, horses, geese, and [[link:http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/pukeko.html Pukeko]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track appears to be essentially flat, though presumably there is a slight gradient down as the stream flows from south to north.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt a couple of points the track crosses farm roads, with pairs of gates to negotiate.','Northern end branches off [[track:259]] 0.25km northeast of the model airplane club.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is on Whareroa Road, down a gravel road next to the tram station (opposite the Ranger Station).','The farm roads are closed to the public, so stick to the track.','1.948',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-13 20:20:47',23,'-40.962789','174.977660',14,2,1,1,23,'2009-03-13 20:20:47','calc',5),(268,'Grand Loop',1,'','Great sampling of the tracks that the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park has to offer.  This is a popular circuit that conveniently starts and ends at the main car park while including the summit and plenty of sweet single track.','[[bold:Stage 1: [[track:1]] (3.0km, Easy)]][[br]]\r\nStarting from the main car park, this is the primary entry into the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park via an easy climb through the forest.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 2: [[track:2]] (1.4km, Intermediate)]][[br]]\r\nBush clad track that sidles around the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 3: [[track:3]] (1.7km, Intermediate)]][[br]]\r\nA slightly more technically challenging track that drops into a gully and then climbs back out again.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 4: [[track:4]] (2.2km, Intermediate)]][[br]]\r\nStarting from just above pylon 16, this track climbs almost continuously to a few metres below the summit of Makara Peak.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 5: Summit connection (0.2km, Easy)]][[br]]\r\nComplete the last few metres to the summit along the end of [[track:18]] and then part of [[track:51]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 6: [[track:5]] (1.4km, Advanced)]][[br]]\r\nNow for the fun part â€“ let the down hill stages begin. This is the most technically difficult stage of the loop, with a steep and sometimes tricky descent.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 7: [[track:50]] (0.8km, Advanced)]][[br]]\r\nCross the gravel road ([[track:19]]) and continue down hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 8: [[track:6]] (0.2km, Easy)]][[br]]\r\nCross another gravel road ([[track:51]]) and cruise along this short and almost flat connection.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 9: [[track:7]] (0.5km, Intermediate)]][[br]]\r\nWeave down this sweet flowing single track, taking full advantage of the sweeping corners.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 10: [[track:22]] (0.6km, Intermediate)]][[br]]\r\nFinally, drop back down to the main car park â€“ watching out for the concrete slab ramp immediately after a tight left-hand corner past a large tree stump.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/MakaraGrandLoopAltitudev3.png:Makara Peak Grand Loop:492:300]]','Starts and ends at the main car park on South Karori Road.','Refer to the individual track descriptions for further information.','11.206',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (except for Ridgeline and Ridgeline Extension, which are Advanced)','2009-03-13 12:08:50',213,'-41.295220','174.712529',15,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-13 20:56:16','calc',5),(269,'Mount Ken',17,'','Ridgeline connection between the northern and southern segments of [[track:81]].','This tracks rolls along the ridgeline between Moore Valley and the Hutt Valley, passing Mount Ken along the way.  Mount Ken is roughly the northern-most point shown on the map, located about 0.8km from that end of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the road consists of rolling hills, with gradients between 10% and 15%.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust to the west of Mount Ken there is a 0.15km long alternative route that takes a short-cut across a bend in the track, as shown on the map.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor a bit of adrenalin try the [[track:270]], the top of which is located about 0.6km from the western end of this road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSince this is a secondary road the surface is generally a bit rougher than [[track:81]], though that just makes it more interesting.','The western end branches off the southern segment of [[track:81]], about 0.5km north of the communications tower were [[track:201]] branches off [[track:81]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end connects to the northern segment of [[track:81]].','','4.018',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-20 16:28:03',23,'-41.210172','174.977703',14,3,1,3,23,'2010-01-01 13:17:26','calc',5),(270,'Wilkie Firebreak',17,'','Extremely steep firebreak from [[track:269]] down a ridge to Wilkie Cresent in Naenae.','The track starts with a short climb up from [[track:269]] on an S-bend corner.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThen the fun begins.  Overall the firebreak drops 320m in 1.5km, for an average gradient of 21%.  The upper sections are the steepest, with two in particular having gradients of around 40% and 45% respectively.  Combining the steep slope with a tricky surface - deeply rutted in between smooth dirt covered in fine rock marbles - makes for a very challenging descent.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe middle section is relatively gentle, with an average gradient of around 12-15%. Then the last down hill section has a gradient of around 25%, ending with a great berm that sweeps around a sharp corner to the left (though watch out for the bump on the exit).\r\n[[para]]\r\nFollowing that berm, there is a flatish section that ends with a pair of steel gates either side of the empty section where the track finishes.','Branches off [[track:269]], 0.6km north of where [[track:269]] branches off [[track:81]], which is itself almost 0.6km north of the communications tower were [[track:201]] branches off [[track:81]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an empty section between 31 and 37 Wilkie Cresent.','Just after a fire-fighting pond there is another fire break that drops off towards the north (right-hand side when heading down). It appears to be a dead-end, stopping behind the houses on Waddington Drive.','1.869',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-20 11:22:22',23,'-41.208880','174.962640',15,4,1,2,23,'2010-01-01 13:19:30','calc',5),(271,'Rata Reservoir',17,'','Steep access road to a water reservoir above Rata Street in Naenae.','This is a gravel access road to a water reservoir above Rata Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road has an almost constant gradient of 15% as it initially heads straight up a valley and then continues around the hill to a small plateau where the reservoir tank is located.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBehind the reservoir tank is a set of steps â€“ that is the start of the [[track:272]].','Starts with a steel barrier gate at the top of Rata Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a moderately small water reservoir tank, where [[track:272]] starts.','','0.530',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-21 10:45:22',23,'-41.205765','174.969973',17,3,1,4,23,'2010-01-01 13:18:49','calc',5),(272,'Rata Street Loop',17,' (No bikes allowed)','Steep route from [[track:271]] up to [[track:269]].','This track heads more-or-less straight up the hill from the top of [[track:271]] until it meets the [[track:269]] ridgeline.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout halfway up there is an intersection where the loop part of the track branches off to the northwest across a bridge, eventually leading back to Rata Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nParts of the track are poorly designed.  In particular, the section immediately above the bridge intersection is built in a gully that looks like it turns into a creek at times, so the track has been deeply eroded.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track has a steep average gradient of just over 20%, but it is the steps that are the problem from a biking perspective. There are about 100 steps between the bottom of the track and the point where the loop branches off at the bridge â€“ half of the steps are immediately above the reservoir. From the bridge to the top there are a further 50 steps or thereabouts.  In addition, there are several other sections where there could be steps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nConsequently, it is easy to see why this is one of the few tracks in the [[area:17]] where bikes are not allowed â€“ this track simply isn\'t suitable for bikes. However, it would be fairly easy to make this track suitable for bikes, by re-working the sections with steps (most of which are poorly constructed and many could be ridden past now, at least going down).','Starts from behind the water tank at the top of [[track:271]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:269]].','The map currently only shows the section from [[track:271]] up to [[track:269]]. The loop part of the track branches off to the northwest about halfway up and loops around to meet Rata Street some way down the hill.','0.651',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-21 11:18:16',23,'-41.206919','174.973315',16,3,2,1,23,'2010-01-01 13:19:10','calc',5),(273,'Mangaroa Tunnel',16,'','Wide and smooth path through the old Mangaroa rail tunnel.','From the railway-style white picket fence at the western end, climb the easy gravel road and into the forest.  The track then wanders along to the 221m long ex-railway tunnel.  A light is suggested for the tunnel, though not necessary as the other end of the tunnel is always visible.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you emerge from the eastern end of the tunnel, cruise along the remaining 0.2km to where the track ends at a white gate on a corner of the upper car park access road.','The western end is just off Maymorn Road, next to the current rail line and near the western end of the 8.8km long [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rimutaka_Tunnel Rimutaka Rail Tunnel]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end meets the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Tunnel-Gully/ Tunnel Gully Recreational Area]] area access road just below the upper car park, about 0.1km from [[track:278]] and [[track:276]].','For further information see the [[link:http://www.rimutaka-incline-railway.org.nz/route/maymorn-kaitoke.html Rimutaka Incline Railway Heritage Trust]].','1.529',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-30 20:54:19',23,'-41.107489','175.144901',15,2,1,2,23,'2009-10-01 09:16:59','calc',5),(274,'Plateau Ridge',16,'','Forestry road along the Mount Plateau ridgeline.','This track has four distinct sections.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern-most section is initially steep and rutted.  If you want to avoid this section, then instead of going up the first part of [[track:278]], start from the upper car park and take [[track:276]] to the ridgeline, where it intersects with [[track:274]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorth of that intersection, the track is a wide and gentle forestry road for almost a kilometer.  At that point there is a clearing, after which the road becomes single track.  Just after the clearing there\'s a steep descent into, and then climb out of, a small valley.  The track then meets an intersection at the northern-most point shown on the map.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the northern-most intersection, the track that continues straight ahead has a broken hand-written sign that says \"No exit past this point\". From the map it appears that this track goes down the hill to behind houses on Plateau Road. So, take a sharp turn to the left and carefully descend an extremely steep, rutted, and loose rocky section of track that ends at a clearing on the valley floor.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue through the clearing and 0.2km later you\'ll meet the apex of [[track:275]] at a T-intersection.\r\n','Southern end branches off [[track:278]] about 0.75km from the bottom gate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end meets [[track:275]] at its apex.','','2.379',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (Advanced for the northern end)','2009-03-30 20:51:21',23,'-41.106261','175.147390',15,3,1,3,23,'2009-10-18 11:06:42','calc',5),(275,'Maymorn Loop',16,'','Forest road loop to/from [[track:273]], meeting [[track:274]] at the apex of the loop.','This track passes through the Maymorn Block of the [[area:16]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the eastern end, take a short climb into the trees and down a steep track.  Just past the apex, this track meets [[track:274]] in a brief flat section.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track then climbs up through the forest for 0.15km. At that point, the track ahead looks rather overgrown, so instead of going that way diverge to the left up the hillside.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother 0.5km further along, after a brief descent, the track meets an intersection with [[track:273]] running right to left (the tunnel is gently uphill towards the left) and the end of [[track:276]] is directly opposite.','Starts and ends on the [[track:273]] track.  The eastern end is 0.15km west of the tunnel, while the other end is 0.3km further southwest.','','1.188',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-30 20:56:07',23,'-41.105476','175.144215',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-03-30 20:56:07','calc',5),(276,'Mount Climie Firebreak',16,'','Firebreak through the forest near the Mount Climie track.','From the upper car park head west across the grass to the treeline where there is a sign that says \"Climie Firebreak\". Enter the trees, cross a small bridge, and then climb up a tight set of switchbacks. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe remaining climb to an intersection with [[track:274]] is a bit odd. Either side of the track, which is a narrow gravel path running straight up the hill, is a couple of rows of pine trees.  Rather strange.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCross the intersection at the top of the ridge, then cruise down the wide and winding road.  After almost a kilometer you\'ll meet the [[track:273]] track, which runs from left to right, with the tunnel being located 0.45km to the right.  The western end of [[track:275]] heads up the fairly steep hill directly opposite.','Eastern end is just off the upper car park, on the tree line about 50m down hill from the start of [[track:278]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end is at an intersection with [[track:273]] (running left to right) and [[track:275]] (goes up the hill directly opposite).','','1.164',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-30 20:57:24',23,'-41.110173','175.147069',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-03-30 20:57:24','calc',5),(277,'Tunnel Connector',16,'','Short connector from [[track:273]] to [[track:274]] above the tunnel.','This connection from [[track:273]] to [[track:274]] (which passes directly over the tunnel) provides an interesting diversion from the easy tracks in the area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe surface is rough and the track is quite steep â€“ it is, however, very short.','The upper end is almost 0.3km north of the intersection of [[track:276]] and [[track:274]] at a sign that says \"Tunnel Gully via Mangaroa Tunnel\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe lower end meets [[track:273]] at a T-intersection, a few metres west of the tunnel.\r\n','','0.215',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-30 20:46:10',23,'-41.107344','175.147991',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-03-30 20:46:10','calc',5),(278,'Mount Climie',16,'','Steep access road for a cluster of communications towers on and around the summit of Mount Climie.','If you\'re looking for some hill work, then Mount Climie is aptly named. This gravel access road provides an almost relentless grind up 610m of altitude gain over 4.4km, for an average gradient on 14% â€“ though some sections are more like 20%. There are only a couple of brief flatish and slightly down sections to provide relief from the climb. Then, when you think you\'ve reached the top, there is another 50m of climbing to reach Mount Climie itself.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome 0.75km from the start, there is a track that branches off at a sign-posted intersection. That is the southern end of [[track:274]]. A further 0.35km up the hill is one end of the walking-only Tane\'s Track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhile climbing you\'ll get an occasional glimpse through the trees out over the Hutt Valley, giving an impression of the altitude being gained. As you climb up the road you might observe, through your oxygen-derived haze, that the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Ecology-of-Tunnel-Gully/ predominant vegetation changes]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the top, the track rolls along the ridge past several communication towers before a short descent and final climb to the fenced communication tower enclosure at the end of the road.  Walk around the fence for stunning views out over the Hutt and the Wairarapa. Beyond the fence there is a 0.2km section of single track through the moss and snow tussock to a knoll that looks towards the south, including views of Wellington Harbour in the distance. Looking towards the west, Mana Island is visible 30km away through a gap in the hills.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe descent is great fun. At no point is peddling required, as you can roll through the slight up hill bits, though a brake check before starting would be prudent.','Starts from the upper car park of the [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/Tunnel-Gully/ Tunnel Gully Recreational Area]], at a sign-posted white metal gate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a communications tower enclosure at the summit of Mount Climie. Return the same way.','From North Climie there is a route that apparently drops down to the west into the Mangaroa Forest. The initial part of the route is very steep. Note that as of March 2009 there was logging activity in the Mangaroa Forest.','5.797',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-03-22 11:47:43',23,'-41.130702','175.149622',13,3,1,4,23,'2009-09-30 20:44:57','calc',5),(279,'Maupuia Walkway',22,'','Gentle gravel path along the cliff top from Akaroa Drive to Prison Road.','This is a gentle connector that provides a useful way to bypass some of the suburban streets. In addition to a smooth gravel surface, the track offers pleasant views over the harbour.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is an upward gradient from south to north, averaging about 4% before the track eases down a couple of metres at the northern end.','Starts from a small parking area on Akaroa Drive.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a metal barrier at the end of Prision Road.','[[track:871]] is a further section of the Maupuia Walkway, continuing from the Prison Road end of this track down to Shelly Bay Road, via a bunch of steps.','0.843',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-03 09:29:11',23,'-41.305505','174.816577',16,1,1,1,23,'2010-02-24 20:04:26','calc',5),(280,'Warm Up Climb',15,'','A warm up for the big climbs to follow this section of the [[track:255]] course.','The track consists of a series of increasingly difficult ascents and descents, ending with a steep drop down to Cedarholm Creek.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs the name suggests, this is just a warm up for the climb that follows.','Turn right at [[track:256]] and head northeast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at Cedarholm Creek, at the start of [[track:281]].','This track forms part of the [[track:255]] course.','4.879',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-03 20:58:46',23,'-41.034758','175.080528',13,3,1,4,23,'2009-04-03 20:58:46','calc',5),(281,'Deadwood',15,'','The first big climb of the [[track:255]] course.','This track consists of several climbs interspersed with short downhill sections.  After a while you\'ll reach a rolling ridgeline that provides awesome views while continuing to generally climb.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is difficult, being loose when dry and slippery when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter descending a bit you\'ll reach a clearing where the [[track:282]] starts with a turn hard left.','Starts from Ceda