track:23]] and [[track:39]].  Development of this stage has been approved in principle by the [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz Wellington City Council]]. Building of the actual track will be subject to final approval of the proposed route.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:One of the belligerent locals]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/OstrichLongGully.jpg:One of the belligerent locals:415:500]]','Northern end starts from the southern end of [[track:67]], at the entry to Long Gully Station.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end is at the intersection of [[track:23]] and [[track:39]], just below the summit of [[area:2]].','The name \"Barking Emu\" refers to the ostriches at the northern end of the track and the dogs at the Castle which is closer to the southern end. It was found out later that they are ostriches (with only two toes) rather than emus (which have three toes).','2.270',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-03 19:50:35',23,'-41.323588','174.733043',15,3,7,1,23,'2010-01-16 19:47:12','calc',5),(295,'Inconstant Point',10,'','Old farm track that heads up the hill to just south of Inconstant Point, and then down to the [[track:97]] saddle. ','From the [[track:93]] lookout, continue up the hill along a reasonably well defined track through the grass.  The track heads up the ridge through a series of steep hills. Eventually the track evanesces into nothing just before it reaches a farm gate.  The gate marks the boundary of the East Harbour Lakes Block, as indicated by the \"Keep Out\" sign.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the gate, turn sharply downhill and follow an old farm track along the cliff edge to the [[track:97]] saddle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the western cliff top there are great views of the entrance to Wellington harbour.','The northwestern end is immediately next to the stile at the top of [[track:96]], off the saddle point of [[track:97]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southeastern end continues up the hill from the lookout detour of [[track:93]].','This isn\'t an official track of the East Harbour Regional Park, but it is within the boundary and makes for an interesting alternative route to the [[track:97]] saddle point.','1.477',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-12 21:51:23',23,'-41.356018','174.853892',15,3,1,1,23,'2009-04-12 21:51:23','calc',5),(296,'Bothamley',14,'','Gentle wander through Bothamley Park in Cannons Creek.','This is an easy track that runs the length of Bothamley Park.  The western 0.7km is graveled single track, while the remainder is smooth double track road. At the end of the single track section, cross one of several bridges along the track and follow a short bit of asphalt to continue along the unpaved road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are several short linking tracks to adjacent streets.  Of particular note is a short path located next to a concrete bridge over a stream that has a stepped cascade.  The path leads up to [[track:647]]. Beyond the park, behind the shopping centre, is the northern end of the [[track:103]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.5km from the eastern end, under the trees, is a Y-intersection with the southern end of [[track:298]].  A further 0.3km west is a T-intersection with a gravel road, which is the southern end of [[track:297]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the western end there is a sign that says \"Caution.  This area may flood in heavy rain\".','The western end is on Champion Street, less than 0.5km from the motorway.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe eastern end is next to an open grass area on Warspite Avenue.','This track is part of the [[link:http://www.teararoa.org.nz Te Araroa]] walkway.','3.523',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-15 19:20:09',23,'-41.133159','174.862690',14,1,1,2,23,'2009-10-26 19:48:50','calc',5),(297,'Dales Reserve',14,'','Gentle cruise up a pleasant little valley, through bush and scrub.','This is a wide and easy gravel path connecting [[track:296]] with a new subdivision in Ascot Park.  The track has existed for many years, but has been upgraded in association with the subdivision development.  The upgrade includes two new bridges and a well designed path that meanders up a valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern 0.4km has a slight upward gradient, leading to a very moderate climb through the bush to a plateau at the northern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.35km from the southern end there is an exit up to Tararua Close, as shown on the map.  The partially concrete path has a long switchback, producing a moderate gradient that facilitates easy access for bikes.','Southern end is at a T-intersection with [[track:296]], about 0.8km from its eastern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end is next to a small playground on Fiordland Place.','The Google Map aerial photo shows the subdivision in the early stages of development.  As at April 2009 the development is much more advanced, with virtually all sections occupied by new homes.','1.472',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-15 19:18:12',23,'-41.126015','174.871187',15,1,1,1,23,'2009-10-26 19:52:29','calc',5),(298,'Gareth Varley Memorial',14,'','Urban track and skills area named after Gareth Varley.','This track heads up a valley from [[track:296]] Park, passing behind houses that are mostly on Waihemo Street. Much of the track follows a small creek lined with Eucalyptus trees.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt just over the 1km mark the track crosses Warspite Avenue. On the northern side of Warspite Avenue is a large mountain bike sculpture, where the track continues alongside Waitangirua Intermediate School.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround the northern end of the track there is a mountain bike skills development area, though it has fallen into somewhat of a state of disrepair.','The southern end meets [[track:296]] at a Y-intersection about 0.5km from its Warspite Avenue end.  If traveling north, then head around to the left â€“ the short step up straight ahead just leads to an open area behind some houses.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end is next to Ascot Park Reserve, with an accessway to the end of Abbey Way cul-de-sac. Alternatively, jump the fence and cross Ascot Park to meet the bottom of [[track:646]].','This track is named after Gareth Varley, a young mountain biker who was killed crossing a road while representing New Zealand at the 1998 World Mountain Bike Championships in Quebec. Also see [[track:11]] track in the [[area:1]] Mountain Bike Park.','1.664',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-15 19:15:02',23,'-41.124075','174.877324',14,1,1,1,23,'2009-10-26 21:02:19','calc',5),(299,'Boobies',15,'','Jungle rumble down from [[track:284]] to near the bottom of [[track:285]].','This track offers a mixture of conditions, providing challanges aplenty.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe first (top) part is a gentle cruise through the bush. But it soon degenerates into a series of boggy patches â€“ though most have a ridable bypass. The bogs dry up just as the track heads down a ridge and becomes much steeper.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis area of the [[area:15]] is popular with motocross riders, with this track being no exception. Consequently, the middle section of the track degenerates into essentially a continuous rut, occasionally of bike-swallowing proportions. In this middle section, the track surface is a mix of deeply rutted clay and bare rock. Parts of this section are very steep and quite technical. There are also three ancient massive trees fallen across the track â€“ one of which is at chest height, while the others can be ridden under.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe last 1.5km is quite different to the preceeding track.  It has a much more moderate gradient and a firm surface, making for a nice flowing piece of single track â€“ apart from some creek crossings. The first creek crossing is a sharp drop and climb, while the other two are less severe.  The second creek crossing appears out of nowhere, so watch out for it. The third, and final, creek crossing is only 50m from the T-intersection with [[track:285]]. Much of this last section is lined with [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toetoe ToeToe]], which has a tendency to cut any exposed flesh that it gets caught in, like between fingers, so take care to avoid that.','The top (northern) end starts from [[track:284]], 2.8km east of the top of [[track:289]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom (southern) end meets [[track:285]], two-thirds of the way down and about 1.3km north of [[track:301]].','','3.444',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-19 21:19:02',23,'-41.006071','175.026369',14,4,1,1,23,'2009-04-19 21:19:02','calc',5),(300,'Hydro Valley Road',15,'','Gravel road through a pleasant valley and then up to meet [[track:288]] and [[track:284]].','From the intersection with [[track:301]], this road immediately crosses the Whakatikei River via a concrete ford.  Heading north, the road crosses the Whakatikei River a couple more times â€“ each time the river is noticeably smaller as you head up the valley towards the river\'s head waters.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road itself is a typical back-country gravel road. It wanders along the floor of a deep valley, surrounded by electricity transmission towers and high hills.  Towards the northern end, the road climbs up a moderate gradient to the Whakatiki Forest, where it meets several other roads.','Southern end is at a sign-posted intersection with the northwestern end of [[track:301]] and the northern end of Hydro Road. The intersection is also marked with a sign that says \"Hydro Valley\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at an intersection with [[track:288]] and [[track:284]].','','4.006',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-19 12:09:27',23,'-41.009698','175.005341',14,3,1,4,23,'2009-04-19 12:09:27','calc',5),(301,'Norm\'s Crossing',15,'','Gravel road from near the bottom of [[track:285]] to [[track:300]].','From [[track:285]], the initially gravel road drops down to and crosses the Whakatikei River. Expect to get at least wet feet crossing the river, which is quite wide though shallow (at least after a period of dry weather).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road then runs roughly parallel with the river, climbing up a bit and rolls on down to a major intersection as described below.  Along the way, the road surface is a mix of gravel, bare dirt, and exposed bedrock.','Southeastern end meets [[track:285]] at an obvious T-intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthwestern end meets a sign-posted intersection with the southern end of [[track:300]] and the northern end of Hydro Road. The intersection is also marked with a sign that says \"Hydro Valley\".','','1.383',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-04-19 11:55:46',23,'-41.024900','175.020447',16,2,1,4,23,'2009-04-19 11:55:46','calc',5),(302,'Buckley',19,'','Easy path from Buckley Road to Houghton Bay Road.','Starting from a gap in the wooden fence on Buckley Road, the top 0.2km of this track is a sealed path.  The remainder is a mix of grass and gravel that swoops down then flattens out before meeting Houghton Bay Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust before the seal ends [[track:303]] emerges from the bush to the southwest, crossing an exposed concrete pipe to meet this path.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWatch out for the low hanging gray steel chain across the exit to Houghton Bay Road â€“ it can be difficult to see against the gray gravel background.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext to the Houghton Bay Road exit there is a short chute that drops down to the next terrace of Sinclair Park.','The top is on Buckley Road, abour 0.1km from the intersection with Mount Albert Road and Houghton Bay Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom meets Houghton Bay Road in the middle of the series of terraces that form Sinclair Park.','This track is part of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]]. All of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','0.727',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-19 20:59:25',23,'-41.333618','174.785507',16,1,1,2,23,'2009-05-19 20:59:25','calc',5),(303,'Sinclair Park',19,'','Bush clad wander through the reserve above Sinclair Park.','Having branched off [[track:302]] this track wanders up and along a rolling path to a T-intersection. Proceeding straight ahead will soon take you to Buckley Road. More usefully, turn left and weave your way down the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 20m from the T-intersection at the top, [[track:304]] drops down the hillside into the bush.  It rejoins this track further around a ridge to the east.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the bottom of the track is a short section that drops steeply down the hill. Alternatively, there is a somewhat less steep bypass to the south â€“ which makes the climb significantly easier if heading up hill.','Southeastern end is on Houghton Bay Road, at the treeline immediately behind the kid\'s play area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end crosses an exposed concrete pipe to meet [[track:302]] at a T-intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAn alternative entrance/exit is on Buckley Road, 0.8km south of the top of [[track:302]].','This is a popular walking track, so watch out for walkers â€“ especially on the tight corners.','1.412',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-13 19:29:26',23,'-41.335318','174.784842',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-11 11:47:04','calc',5),(304,'Houghton Bay lookout',19,'','Loop off [[track:303]] to a lookout over Houghton Bay.','This short loop track is best done from west to east, as the western half of the track is rather steep. Parts of the track are indistinct as you head down the western hillside, but watch out for the intermittent yellow markers attached to trees and you\'ll be fine.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the middle of this track there is a short no exit branch that ends with a seat and lookout over Houghton Bay. It\'s well worth stopping to admire the inspiring view.','The top (western) end is 20m from a T-intersection on [[track:303]] where a branch goes off to Buckley Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom (eastern) end rejoins [[track:303]] further down the hill.','','0.494',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-13 19:53:59',23,'-41.338822','174.783758',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-05-13 19:53:59','calc',5),(305,'Mt Albert 4x',19,'','4x and slalom race track on Mount Albert.','This is a [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mountain_bike_racing 4x and dual slalom]] mountain bike racing track that weaves down a shallow gully on Mount Albert.  The track includes several jumps, a couple of small step drops, and high bermed corners.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track is used for [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/wellington-and-slalom-updates-t92850.html regular races]], open to riders of all levels.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the bottom of the track, glide up to the saddle point on the left and climb back up the concrete path for another go.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:4x races at 2008 New Zealand Mountain Bike National Championships]][[br]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/2008Nat4x-2.jpg:4x race February 2008:492:426]][[br]]\r\n[[image:http://i443.photobucket.com/albums/qq159/ian314159_pics/2008Nat4x-1.jpg:4x race February 2008:492:506]][[br]]\r\nMore photos: [[link:http://www.flickr.com/photos/vertphoto/sets/72157603925321083/ 2008 4x Nationals]], [[link:http://www.flickr.com/photos/vertphoto/sets/72157613078582860/ Wednesday night races]]','Top (southern) end is on [[track:309]], just off Mount Albert Road. There is a car park 0.15km to the northwest down Mount Albert Road.','The track was originally created as a temporary course for the [[link:http://www.bikenz.org.nz/Resource.aspx?ID=1721 New Zealand Mountain Bike National Championships]], held on 22 February 2008. However a subsequent [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/haveyoursay/e-petitions/ep/details/22 petition]] successfully sought to retain the track after the championships.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs at May 2009, the long term status of the track has yet to decided. In the meantime, the [[link:http://www.wmtbc.org.nz/ Wellington MTB Club]] continues to maintain the course for the benefit of local riders.','0.222',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-15 14:26:52',23,'-41.329167','174.781961',17,3,1,2,23,'2009-10-06 12:58:54','calc',5),(306,'Mt Albert summit',19,'','Short track to the summit of Mount Albert.','This is a short track to the summit of Mount Albert, from which there are nice views over the surrounding area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen going up it is easiest to take the loop to the southeast.  For the return trip take the direct route down a short, steep drop back to your starting point on [[track:309]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe summit has several radio masts, along with a large survey trig.  At the end of the track there is a concrete octagonal structure â€“ possibly a [[link:http://capitaldefence.orconhosting.net.nz/remgon/wgtnrem.htm World War II observation post]]?','Loops off [[track:309]] at the top of its initial climb up from Mount Albert Road.','','0.213',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-15 18:09:46',23,'-41.329439','174.783948',18,2,1,1,23,'2009-05-15 18:09:46','calc',5),(307,'Hornsley',19,'','Grassy swoop around the eastern side of Mt Albert, with a set of steps connecting to Hornsley Road.','This is an alternative to [[track:309]], heading around the eastern side of Mt Albert along a wide, rolling, grassy path.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.15km from the southern end there\'s a steep set of steps that drop down to Hornsley Road.  Although the steps notionally provide access to/from Hornsley Road, they are very unfriendly from a biking perspective.\r\n[[para]]\r\nLess than 0.1km further along the track branches at a Y-intersection: the upper branch goes up to [[track:308]], while the lower branch continues down and around the hill to an open grassy area where the track meets several others.','Southern end branches off [[track:308]], 50m past the water tank.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at a busy intersection with [[track:308]], [[track:309]], and [[track:310]].','','0.800',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-19 20:43:59',23,'-41.327528','174.786118',16,2,1,2,23,'2009-05-19 20:43:59','calc',5),(308,'Mt Albert Ridgeline',19,'','Wide track along the ridgeline of Mount Albert.','The southern end of this track is fairly tame. From the top of the ridgeline there are sweeping views of the surrounding suburbs and towards Lyall Bay, making this a worthwhile diversion from [[track:309]] or [[track:307]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end is more challenging, with a couple of alternative routes.  The western route is wide and fairly steep. At the top of this climb, next to a [[link:http://www.linz.govt.nz/geodetic/geodetic-database/search/index.aspx?nextform=image&image_id=79213&mode=map&sessionid=630428460225401242707749&code=A2LL survey mark]], is a narrow, rutted, and rocky piece of single track that is much steeper and somewhat tricky (especially when wet, as the rocks are quite slippery).\r\n[[para]]\r\nAn alternative exit from the summit is just south of the survey mark, down a spur of [[track:307]].','Southern end branches off [[track:309]], next to a large water tank.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at a busy intersection with [[track:309]], [[track:310]], and [[track:307]].','','0.703',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' with Advanced single track section','2009-05-19 20:50:20',23,'-41.327471','174.785346',16,3,1,2,23,'2009-05-19 20:50:20','calc',5),(309,'Western Slopes',19,'','Part of the Southern Walkway around the western slopes of Mount Albert.','This is the main track through Mount Albert.  From Mount Albert Road it climbs up to a saddle point just below [[track:306]], then sidles around the western slopes of the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn an open grassy clearing there is a shortcut that continues straight ahead down the hill and under the trees to meet [[track:310]].  The clearing also marks the top of [[track:311]] and an advanced section of [[track:312]].  Meanwhile, the main track continues around to the east where, 0.15km later, it meets the upper end of [[track:310]] and other tracks. ','Southern end is on Mount Albert Road, 0.2km northwest of Buckley Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at a busy intersection with [[track:308]] (and its more difficult shortcut), [[track:310]], and [[track:307]].','This track is part of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]]. All of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','0.997',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-20 21:16:26',23,'-41.327278','174.784219',16,2,1,2,23,'2009-09-11 11:48:57','calc',5),(310,'Melrose Park',19,'','Part of the Southern Walkway through Melrose Park.','The southern half of this track wanders under the trees down a rocky and root infested path.  At a hairpin bend, it then descends a set of steps along the southern boundary fence of [[link:http://www.wellingtonzoo.com/ Wellington Zoo]], above the baboon enclosure.  The steps are well spaced and have a gap along the side so that they can be fairly easily ridden down and, if you\'re keen, perhaps also ridden up.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom of the steps is Melrose Park, which is often used for sporting fixtures â€“ especially on the weekend â€“ so you might have to skirt around the edge of the park.','Southern end is at a busy intersection with [[track:308]] (and its more difficult shortcut), [[track:309]], and [[track:307]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the end of Sutherland Crescent, at the entrance to Melrose Park.','This track is part of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]]. All of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','0.648',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-19 20:58:14',23,'-41.324514','174.784745',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-11 11:47:51','calc',5),(311,'Mt Albert Park',19,'','Connection to/from the hockey fields in Mount Albert Park.','This is a fairly steep connection from the Mount Albert Park hockey fields to a busy intersection with several other tracks. The gradient is between 15% and 20%, making for a decent climb.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the mid point of the main track there is a spur that heads north to meet the loop section of [[track:312]].','Eastern end climbs up from the car park of the Mt Albert Park hockey fields.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end is in a clearing at an intersection with [[track:309]] (where its shortcut drops down to meet [[track:310]]), and the top of the advanced section of [[track:312]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the halfway point a spur heads north to meet the loop section of [[track:312]].','','0.479',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-20 21:04:17',23,'-41.325038','174.782894',17,3,1,2,23,'2009-05-20 21:04:17','calc',5),(312,'Newtown Park',19,'','Connection from Southern Walkway to Newtown Park.','This track consists of three distinct parts:\r\n[[bullet:The main track starts from the hairpin bend on [[track:310]] and heads initially east and then north to end near Newtown Park.  About 50m southwest of the [[track:310]] end is a Y-intersection; the left-hand (southern-most) branch is the spur of [[track:311]], while the other branch is the continuation of this track.]]\r\n[[bullet:From the [[track:310]] hairpin an alternative steep and rocky shortcut drops down the zoo\'s fenceline, rejoining the main track after less than 50m.]]\r\n[[bullet:Also meeting the main track just a few metres west of the bottom of the zoo fenceline shortcut is an advanced section of track that drops down from a busy intersection with [[track:309]] and other tracks.  The top of this section is initially tame, but soon turns into a short though extremely steep and technical bit of single track.]]','Northern end is on the access road to Newtown Park, at the eastern end of a low wooden fence.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSoutheastern end is in a clearing at an intersection with [[track:309]] (where its shortcut drops down to meet [[track:310]]), and [[track:311]].','','0.754',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' with Advanced sections.','2009-05-20 21:15:23',23,'-41.323644','174.782524',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-08-07 20:36:41','calc',5),(313,'Pistol',19,'','Short connection from [[track:312]] to the Wellington Pistol Club.','This is a short connecting track that goes from the northern end of Mount Albert Park up to [[track:312]].  The track is quite steep, with a grass and rock surface that doesn\'t provide much grip in the wet.','Eastern end meets [[track:312]] at a T-intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end drops down to the northwestern corner of the Wellington Pistol Club\'s car park.','It is probably best to avoid the area between this track and the [[track:312]] track, as it is immediately behind the firing range of the [[link:http://www.pistolwellington.org.nz/Welcome.html Wellington Pistol Club]].','0.100',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-19 20:52:04',23,'-41.323352','174.781293',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-05-19 20:52:04','calc',5),(314,'Hataitai Zigzag',5,'','Easy alternative to the steep initial section of [[track:147]].','This track provides a nice alternative to the initially steep southern start to the [[track:147]] track.  Instead of heading straight up the hill, this track wanders up through the bush at a relatively gentle gradient.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 1/3 of the way up the track crosses the Hinau Street spur of the [[track:147]] track, which it then rejoins 0.2km later for the final section up to Alexandra Road.','The top meets the spur of [[track:147]] that goes down to Hinau Street, about 0.15km from Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom is on the velodrome exit road, where the main [[track:147]] track heads straight up the hill.  Instead of going up [[track:147]], head 20m north and then alongside the Hataitai electrical sub-station\'s fence.','Built in May 2009 by [[link:http://www.kennett.co.nz/ Simon Kennett]] and others.','0.334',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-22 08:35:50',23,'-41.303510','174.790528',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:24:14','calc',5),(315,'Karori Park Loop',6,'','Circumnavigates Karori Park, with several connections to neighboring streets.','This is a smooth and flat beginner\'s loop around the perimeter of Karori Park.  It is popular with kids on bikes, walkers, and runners.  The track is sufficiently wide to accommodate all users, consisting of two surfaces â€“ the outer surface is asphalt, while the inner surface is hard-packed sand and fine gravel.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several access points to adjacent streets, along with a connection to the bottom of [[track:35]] and the western and eastern extents of [[track:319]].  In the southwest corner there is a bridge that leads to an accessway behind the Terawhiti Bowling Club and then on to Makara Road â€“ this is a popular exit for people on their way back to main car park of [[area:1]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe loop itself is 1.0km long. There is an additional 0.7km of access paths, as shown on the map.','The main access is off Karori Road, though there are several other access points as shown on the map.','The Karori Park facilities were upgraded in 2007, as part of the [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/news/display-item.php?id=2919 Karori Park Upgrade Project]].','1.692',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 17:58:48',23,'-41.286377','174.723805',16,1,1,2,23,'2009-09-01 17:56:38','calc',1),(316,'The Snake',6,'','Sinuous track that weaves its way from [[track:320]] to [[track:319]].','This is a fun little track.  It is a luge-like slalom course that weaves back-and-forth across what used to be a 4wd track.  After rolling down a series of bermed corners, the track heads into the trees via a couple of sinuous flattish switchbacks to emerge onto [[track:319]] at a plateau overlooking Karori Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track was constructed in 2008-09 as part of the [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/karori-park-beginners-trail-project-t86653.html Karori Park Beginners\' Trail Project]].','Starts from the glade, next to the northern end of [[track:319]] and a few metres from [[track:320]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds near the picnic tables overlooking Karori Park, on [[track:319]].','','0.238',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:55:39',23,'-41.283345','174.723140',17,1,1,1,23,'2009-06-07 20:55:39','calc',5),(317,'Downhill extension',6,'','Extension up from the top of [[track:88]].','This is a short, very steep, and not particularly well-formed little track.  It is only ridable in a down hill direction, from east to west.\r\n[[para]]\r\nStarting from [[track:324]], this track could be used as an extension of [[track:88]] â€“ hence the name.  It emerges quite suddenly out of the bush and on to [[track:323]].  From there, turn left and then almost immediately turn right down the start of [[track:88]].','Drops off [[track:324]] about 25m north of the power pole.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on [[track:323]] a few metres west of the top of [[track:88]].','','0.101',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:01:15',23,'-41.281104','174.721225',17,4,1,1,23,'2009-05-26 18:01:15','calc',5),(318,'98 DH shortcut',6,'','Shortcut between sections of the [[track:88]].','At the base of the [[track:88]] steps (which have a bypass on the left), instead of turning sharply left this track continues straight down the hill.  The track surface is steep, consisting of hard-packed dirt with a covering of pine needles, so there is little traction â€“ especially when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at a T-intersection with [[track:88]].  Just before that point, [[track:321]] appears out of no-where, dropping on to this track down the last sweeping banked corner on the right.','Starts at the bottom of the steps on [[track:88]] and rejoins [[track:88]] just before it drops down to meet [[track:35]].','','0.109',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:02:05',23,'-41.282979','174.722418',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-05-26 18:02:05','calc',5),(319,'Karori Park Picnic',6,'','Access to a picnic area overlooking Karori Park.','This is the primary access route to the [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/karori-park-beginners-trail-project-t86653.html Karori Park Beginners\' Trail Project]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom a spur of [[track:315]], the western end of this track climbs up to a small plateau where there are a couple of picnic tables overlooking Karori Park. Just north of the picnic tables there is an easy, wide, and smooth path that heads north towards a glade where you\'ll find the [[track:320]] track along with the top of [[track:316]] (which emerges from the trees near the picnic tables).  Another way to reach the glade is via the more challenging [[track:325]], which climbs up steeply from a 4-way intersection and then drops down an extremely steep bank just east of [[track:320]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nDirectly opposite the end of [[track:316]] is the top end of [[track:339]], which is an easy way up to the plateau.  An interesting way down from the plateau is via a connector that drops down a steep slope to the car park at the northeastern corner of Karori Park.\r\n','Southwestern branch is at the bottom of [[track:35]], where it meets a spur of [[track:315]]. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern end is just a few metres short of [[track:320]], immediately next to the top of [[track:316]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother branch diverges from east of the picnic tables and drops down to the Sunshine Avenue connection to [[track:315]].','','0.379',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-25 17:39:42',23,'-41.283543','174.723381',17,2,1,2,23,'2009-09-01 17:57:38','calc',5),(320,'Karori Pump',6,'','Pump track in a glade behind Karori Park.','This is a short pump track built in a flat glade behind Karori Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA pump track is a continuous loop of turns and bumps built on level ground. The idea is for a mountain bike or BMX rider to complete one or more circuits of the track without pedalling. Instead, forward momentum is created and maintained by pumping the bike up and down the bumps, primarily using the upper body.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPumping is a key riding skill, as demonstrated and explained in this [[link:http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y9cwoQpRUqo video]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track was constructed in 2008-09 as part of the [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/karori-park-beginners-trail-project-t86653.html Karori Park Beginners\' Trail Project]].','Located in a glade behind Karori Park â€“ most easily accessible from [[track:319]], via [[track:339]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nA fun exit is via [[track:316]], at the southern end of the glade.','','0.051',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:53:23',23,'-41.282402','174.723194',18,1,1,1,23,'2009-06-07 20:53:23','calc',5),(321,'Karori Ladder Drop',6,'','Technical track including a couple of expert-level ladder drops.','After a relatively tame start off [[track:88]], this track gets serious with a high ladder drop off a steep dirt bank.  There is a bypass to the right, which is tight and also quite a drop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA bit further along, there is another smaller ladder immediately after a sharp dip â€“ though that one is more of a ramp than a drop.  It is also followed by a steep and slippery dirt bank.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt appears that this is not an \"official\" track, as such, but rather was probably built by locals.  Successfully negotiating the ladders requires some skill, so approach with a healthy combination of courage and caution.','There are a couple of entrances that drop off [[track:88]] 0.12km from its start on [[track:323]]. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends with a drop over a small bank onto [[track:318]] just before it rejoins [[track:88]].','','0.230',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:05:12',23,'-41.282795','174.721769',18,5,1,1,23,'2009-05-26 18:05:12','calc',5),(322,'Karori Park Ridge',6,'','Climb up the ridgeline behind Karori Park.','Around 0.15km from the western end of [[track:32]] there is a clearing that contains a set of signs and three tracks.  On the right-hand side is the top of [[track:35]]; in the middle is the continuation of [[track:32]]; and to the left, heading up a steep hill, is this track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter climbing up the initial steep section of this track, you\'ll emerge into another clearing where this track crosses [[track:32]].  Continue up the rooty and somewhat steep track directly opposite.  Just as the track levels out, a short branch heads off to the left while the main track continues on.  Both branches soon meet [[track:324]].','Diverges off [[track:32]] at the same clearing that marks the top of [[track:35]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nMeets [[track:324]] at a couple of alternative connections at around the highest point of the ridge.','','0.350',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:25:59',23,'-41.280757','174.720490',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 17:58:16','calc',5),(323,'Straight and Narrow',6,'','This is a pair of short connecting tracks â€“ one goes straight up to [[track:324]] while the other is a narrow descent to [[track:35]].','This is a track of two (unequal) halves.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe \'Straight\' section connects several tracks between [[track:35]] and [[track:324]].  From the top of [[track:88]], this track heads straight up a steep hill, with a surface that consists of often wet smooth clay.  The lowest part of this section is often muddy, which makes for much fun when descending from [[track:324]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe \'Narrow\' section is a narrow, steep, and rocky chute that can be quite challenging when wet.  Given the narrowness of the chute, there is little room for error and the rocks are unforgiving.','The \'Straight\' section continues from the point where [[track:35]] takes a sharp turn towards Karori, and heads straight up a steep hill to [[track:324]]. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe \'Narrow\' section drops down a chute off [[track:32]] to join \'Straight\' a few metres from the [[track:35]] intersection.','','0.190',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:33:29',23,'-41.281267','174.720841',18,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 17:59:04','calc',5),(324,'Telegraph Ridge',6,'','Connectione between [[track:32]] and [[track:88]].','The most obvious way to identify this track is by ascending the straight section of [[track:323]], which heads straight up the hill to where there is a power pole on a ridge.  The power pole serves as a prominent landmark for this track and several others nearby.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the power pole, the track heads north along the ridge past [[track:317]] and [[track:322]] (which meets this track at two points), before dropping down to meet [[track:32]] in a clearing.  This part of the track is fairly tame, though the descent to [[track:32]] can be tricky when wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHeading south from the power pole, the track takes a step up and then ends at a large fallen tree.  Steps have been constructed over the tree, though there is no obvious track beyond that point.  Instead, drop down an extremely steep chute that falls off the side of the track.  This section soon meets [[track:88]] via an especially steep and technical few metres of cliff-like track.','Northern end meets Skyline at a saddle point clearing immediately below where [[track:32]] zigzags up a hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end joins [[track:88]] after dropping off the ridge.','','0.340',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','/Advanced','2009-05-25 17:42:52',23,'-41.281124','174.721751',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 17:59:39','calc',5),(325,'Upper Glade',6,'','Climbs up to above the glade and then drops down a dirt bank to [[track:320]].','From a 4-way intersection, this initially wide track heads up the hill at quite a steep gradient.  The climb is short, as the track reaches a plateau and then sidles around the hill under the trees.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs the track progresses it becomes less well defined, soon disappearing entirely.  At that point, you\'ll find yourself quite some way above the glade that contains the [[track:320]].  It is possible to scramble your way further along to a gully which then descends into the glade, though that route isn\'t ridable.\r\n[[para]]\r\nInstead, the quickest exit strategy is straight down a bank that drops into the glade â€“ though on the way down beware of the trees, fallen branches, and extremely slippery dirt surface.','Heads up a hill between branches of [[track:319]], then drops down a steep bank into the glade where [[track:320]] is located.','','0.209',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 20:56:53',23,'-41.283116','174.723596',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 18:00:54','calc',5),(326,'Newtown to Mt Vic',5,'','Wide track that climbs from the colleges in Newtown up to the northwest corner of Alexandra Park.','From the northwest corner of Alexandra Park, this track drops down a rocky path to the Number 3 playing field of [[link:http://www.wellington-college.school.nz Wellington College]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNot far from the top [[track:330]] heads up the bank towards the southwest. Further down, just before the track emerges out onto a sealed driveway, there is a set of wooded steps leading up to the [[track:327]] Observatory.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTo exit from the bottom of this track, follow the sealed road north, west, and then north again along a tree-lined one-way driveway that emerges onto Paterson Street between the Basin Reserve and the Mount Victoria Tunnel.','The top is at the northwestern corner of Alexandra Park. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom is next to Ground Number 3 of [[link:http://www.wellington-college.school.nz Wellington College]].','Near the bottom of the track, under the trees, there is a white bollard towards the southwest side of the track â€“ watch out for the grey chain connected to the bollard and draped across the track, as it may be difficult to see.','0.459',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:11:01',23,'-41.304820','174.784874',17,3,1,2,23,'2009-09-10 20:31:12','calc',5),(327,'Gifford',5,'','Narrow track that runs along the fenceline of the [[link:http://www.was.org.nz/01gifford.html Gifford Observatory]].','From a saddle point intersection with [[track:330]], this track drops down a hill alongside a graffiti-covered corregated fence.  The top half of the track is wide and smooth, while the bottom half is narrow and somewhat more tricky.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the bottom of the track, there is a gate through the fence, leading to the Gifford Observatory.  From there, the rest of the way down to [[track:326]] involves a substantial set of wooden steps.','The top is at a saddle point on [[track:330]]. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom is near the bottom of [[track:326]].','Note that from the top of the steps there appears to be a track that continues down the hill along the fenceline, but it doesn\'t actually seem to go anywhere.','0.255',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:12:31',23,'-41.305400','174.783415',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:23:33','calc',5),(328,'Alexandra Park DH',5,'','Short and steep downhill-only track from the northwest corner of Alexandra Park.','The northwestern corner of Alexandra Park sees the confluence of several tracks, of which this is the least obvious.  In fact, it isn\'t even defined as a track at all, initially.  To reach the track proper, cruise along the western edge of Alexandra Park on the same level as the playing field.  Then dive into the bush at the southwestern corner of the park and wander along until you reach the edge of a cliff that overlooks an open grassy area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter stopping to admire the view, contemplate the steep and rocky surface before proceeding.  The track is narrow, so there is little choice but to head straight down the hill.  Depending on the conditions and the gear you have, this short descent ranges from technically challenging through to insane.  The price of failure is high: there are pickles nearby on both sides, and the jagged rocks are