 bottom end of [[track:328]].','Starts from the end of Owen Street. \r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a sign-posted intersection with [[track:326]].','','0.772',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:13:59',23,'-41.307310','174.784670',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-14 07:23:47','calc',5),(331,'Melbourne',19,'','Steep connection between Mount Albert Road and Melbourne Road.','The top 0.1km of this track is across an open area on a hairpin corner of Mount Albert Road, about 0.3km downhill from the [[track:305]] track.  Cruise down the grassy hill past the end of [[track:332]] to a clearing, then turn sharply left down the sign-posted track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the grassy clearing at the top, this track descends rather steeply for 0.15km through a gap carved in the scrub.  At that point there is a sharp dip in the track, with an off-camber dirt surface that is quite slippery when wet.  After climbing out of the dip, the track continues down to exit onto a quiet section of Melbourne Road.','Descends from Mount Albert Road to Melbourne Road.','','0.444',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-25 17:47:51',23,'-41.329179','174.777873',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-11 11:49:25','calc',5),(332,'Volga',19,'','Gentle wander between [[track:331]], off Mount Albert Road, to Volga Street.','From Volga Street this track forms a short loop connecting two entry points that are only 60m apart.  The northern entrance is the most prominent, located only 0.1km from Mount Albert Road.  The southern entrance looks more like a driveway â€“ which it is â€“ located next to some garages.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the point where the two entrances meet, veer off the loop down a short section of gravel road then take a sharp right turn rather than going down the steps that are straight ahead.  The track then wanders along below Volga Street and Mount Albert Road to meet [[track:331]] in a grassy clearing.','Starts from a short loop off Volga Street in a couple of places. \r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:331]], just below Mount Albert Road.','','0.423',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-25 17:48:33',23,'-41.329300','174.779837',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-11 11:49:50','calc',5),(333,'Southern Truby King',19,'','Section of the Southern Walkway through Truby King Park.','From the eastern side of [[track:242]] this track drops gently down a well-formed gravel path under the trees.  There are a couple of steps down, but nothing significant.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter a short distance, just before a set of steps that go up to the apex of [[track:242]], turn off the well-formed path and down some single track that runs roughly parallel to [[track:333]] though without being quite so steep.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track then converges with, and briefly coincides with, [[track:333]] along a section of gravel road.  After less than 0.1km, this track diverges along a short piece of single track that meets the apex of a sweeping corner where it meets [[track:334]] and the northern end of [[track:333]].','Branches off the eastern side of the loop on [[track:242]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on [[track:334]], just above the steps down to Coromandel Street.','This track is part of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]], though it runs parallel to the nearby [[track:334]] which is confusingly also marked as being part of the Southern Walkway.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAll of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the eastern town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','0.394',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:20:17',23,'-41.317899','174.788017',16,2,1,1,23,'2009-06-10 19:07:02','calc',5),(334,'Coromandel',19,'','Connection to Manchester Street to Coromandel Street, with an alternative connection to Owen Street.','From the Manchester Street end, climb up through the mature pine forest to an open, grassy area.  Swerve around the hill to the right, where there is a short track through the long grass that drops down to a gravel road.  To the west there is a short access road, past the Workingmen\'s Bowling Club, to Owen Street.  The main track continues up the gravel road, initially to the east and then turning northwards.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the highest point on the gravel road, there is an intersection with [[track:333]] and [[track:335]].  Turn left down the sealed path, then zigzag your way down to Coromandel Street â€“ watching out for a couple of short flights of steps mixed in with the sections of steep sloping footpath.','Southern end is on Manchester Street, opposite a spur of [[track:336]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the end of Coromandel Street, at the base of a set of concrete switchback slopes and steps.','This track is part of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]], though it runs parallel to the nearby [[track:333]] which is also confusingly marked as being part of the Southern Walkway.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that all of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the eastern town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','0.727',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:19:38',23,'-41.317931','174.787266',16,2,1,4,23,'2009-06-09 18:14:19','calc',5),(335,'Truby King Midline',19,'','Runs down the midline of Truby King Park.','This track runs down the midline of Truby King Park, forming the backbone from which other tracks radiate.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top section, from the apex of [[track:242]], is a wide and relatively open area under mature pine trees. After dropping down a steep slope, this track coincides for a short way with [[track:333]] along a gravel road. [[track:333]] diverges down a piece of single track and this track continues along the gravel road to the apex of a sweeping corner where it meets [[track:334]] and the northern end of [[track:333]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top of this track, just after dropping off [[track:242]], look to the left (west) and you may see bikes flying through the air along the [[track:243]] track.','Southern end is at the apex of the [[track:242]] loop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end meets [[track:334]] just above the switchbacks and at the northern end of [[track:333]].','','0.391',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-25 17:49:51',23,'-41.317794','174.788017',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-06-10 19:07:40','calc',5),(336,'Wellington Zoo',19,'','Runs along the eastern fenceline of Wellington Zoo, from [[track:310]] to Manchester Street.','This track runs along the eastern boundary fence of [[link:http://www.zoo.wcc.govt.nz/ Wellington Zoo]].  If you peer through the fence, you might get a glimpse of an animal or two.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a large flight of steps at the Melrose Park (southern) end of this track.  The steps reduce the friendliness of the track from a biking perspective, though it is a useful connection between [[track:310]] and [[track:334]] for walking and running.\r\n[[para]]\r\nA spur near the southern end, at the base of the steps, leads to the end of Melrose Crescent.  Another spur near the northern end goes up a few steps to meet Manchester Road diagonally opposite the southern end of [[track:334]].','Southern end drops off the [[track:310]] car park, down a set of many steps.  An alternative entrance is from the end of Melrose Crescent.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end has two alternatives, both on Manchester Street.  One option is down a sealed driveway next to the [[link:http://www.zoo.wcc.govt.nz/net/experience/functions.aspx Archibald Centre]]; while the other branches off up a small hill to end directly opposite the southern end of [[track:334]].','This track part of the [[link:http://feelinggreat.co.nz/facilities-and-venues/mountain-bike-tracks/201-southern-walkway-newtown-to-south-coast Southern Walkway]]. All of the Southern Walkway, which traverses the eastern town belt from Houghton Bay to Oriental Bay, is open to bikes except for the northern-most section from Palliser Road to Oriental Bay.','0.507',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-05-26 18:21:45',23,'-41.321807','174.785947',16,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-11 11:50:18','calc',5),(337,'Conviction',22,'','Two-way track designed primarily as an uphill route connecting with [[track:346]].','This is the main uphill route through the reserve â€“ though this is a two-way track, so watch out for people in either direction.  The track winds its way up the hill, deviating from an old farm track in a couple of places so as to maintain a moderate gradient.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is mostly firm dirt, with some rock armoring in places.  Some sections seem to be prone to being a little boggy, which is to be expected from a new track that is still under development.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout two-thirds of the way up there is a short connection up to a lookout on a ridge.  The views are mainly towards the southwest, in the general direction of the airport.','For the uphill, enter from Bottom (southern) end is on the grassy area at the apex of Darlington Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTop (northern) end is most of the way up the hill, at an intersection with [[track:346]].','These tracks are two way and shared use, for bikes they are primarily intended for climbing as part of a loop with Jail Brake (our DH track). Please do not ride downhill at speed, the corners are not made for it so you will brake heavily and skid.  That is not good.\r\n\r\nAlso, these are dual use tracks, expect walkers and remember to give way to uphill riders and all walkers.  These two tracks were built by mountain bikers but walkers have priority as with all tracks in Wellington unless otherwise designated.  \r\n\r\nAlso, do not shuttle these tracks, big bikes should stick to Jail Brake. ','0.786',123,41,36,124,'','','2009-06-07 19:46:48',88,'-41.299162','174.826931',17,