nsists of a circuit built in an open grassy area just off the [[track:144]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe circuit includes a variety of obstacles designed to build mountain biking skills and confidence. The obstacles include:[[br]]\r\n[[bullet:a pair of offset see-saws (ie. the pivot is offset so that the see-saw always returns to the same position)]]\r\n[[bullet:a surface of artifical tree roots]]\r\n[[bullet:wooden ramps of various slopes]]\r\n[[bullet:slalom poles]]\r\n[[bullet:swing bridge]]\r\n[[bullet:a boardwalk that gets progressively narrower]]\r\n[[bullet:plastic matting, of the type sometimes used to reinforce track surfaces]]\r\n[[bullet:a rock garden.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe circuit is designed to be ridden in an anti-clockwise direction.','Located in a large clearing 0.2km north of the Crawford Road / Wellington Road roundabout.  Both [[track:144]] and the [[track:228]] course pass through the top of the clearing.','','0.169',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 21:24:10',23,'-41.310868','174.789812',17,2,7,1,23,'2009-08-06 20:41:54','calc',5),(341,'The Dipper',5,'','Steep connecting track between [[track:144]] and [[track:231]].','This is an interesting little track that connects [[track:231]] with [[track:144]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nTravelling northwards this track drops quite steeply away from Alexandra Road,  dipping sharply â€“ hence the name â€“ before gently rising to the northern end.  It is possible to gather a lot of speed down the hill, so watch out for other track users.\r\n[[para]]The northernmost 0.1km of this track coincides with a section of [[track:231]] â€“ ending at the point where the branches of [[track:231]] meet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top section (at the Alexandra Road end) has a gravel surface, while the rest of the track is a mixture of dirt, rocks, and tree roots.','Southern end branches off [[track:144]] almost 0.5km north of Mount Alfred along Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end meets [[track:231]] as it climbs quite steeply towards Alexandra Road.','','0.379',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 21:27:26',23,'-41.298460','174.791236',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-06-25 19:39:41','calc',5),(342,'Hobbit\'s Hideaway',5,'','Short piece of track used during the filming of The Lord of the Rings trilogy.','This is a wide and gentle connecting track that would be unremarkable except that it was used during the filming of [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings_film_trilogy The Lord of the Rings trilogy]].  Apparently this was the location where the [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbits  Hobbits]] hid while being chased by [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl  Ringwraiths]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBoth ends of this track are clearly signposted.','Southwestern end meets [[track:147]] 0.2km from Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNortheastern end meets [[track:343]] 0.25km from Alexandra Road and 40m uphill from the top of [[track:344]].','','0.141',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 21:29:24',23,'-41.301024','174.788634',17,2,1,2,23,'2009-06-22 19:37:44','calc',5),(343,'Old Mac',5,'','A relatively long track, by [[area:5]] standards, between [[track:144]] and [[track:229]].','This track cruises generally downwards from Alexandra Road to just above Charles Plimmer Park.  Going the other way, this is a convienient way to get from Majoribanks Street up to the centre of [[area:5]].  Some sections of track are moderately steep, but nothing major.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe surfaces varies considerably along the length of this track. From the top end, the surface is initially firm gravel. Subsequent sections include hard-packed dirt, tree roots, rocks, pine needles, and occasionally mud.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way, this track passes through several intersections. To stay on track, simply follow the helpful little marker signs that were installed in mid-2009.','Southern end is at a busy intersection on the northern side of Mount Alfred.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end meets [[track:229]] just above Charles Plimmer Park.','','0.882',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 21:42:47',23,'-41.299573','174.790571',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:31:46','calc',5),(344,'Rosamund\'s Track',5,'','Short connection between [[track:343]] and [[track:147]].','This is a short and rather steep track between [[track:147]] and [[track:343]].  The track climbs from north to south, along a hard-packed dirt surface that generally has some shallow to moderate ruts due to the steep gradient.  There are also a few exposed tree roots along the way, just to make things interesting.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top (southern end) of the track passes over the [[link:http://www.heritagehelp.co.nz/tunnel.html Hataitai Bus Tunnel]], which runs from Pirie Street to Waitoa Road.','Southern end branches off [[track:343]] 40m north of [[track:342]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at a busy intersection with [[track:231]] and [[track:147]] walkway.','This track is named after [[link:http://www.fourcorners.co.nz/new-zealand/wellington-walker/ Rosamund Averton]], who is well known for her [[link:http://www.livingstreets.org.nz/rosamunds_rambles.htm ramblings]] around the many tracks of the [[region:1]] region.','0.180',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-07 21:35:27',23,'-41.299456','174.789691',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-06-28 21:08:33','calc',5),(345,'Tawa Dirt Park',14,'- Off Duncan Street beside the Tawa train station over bridge.','A dual line BMX - 4X track with 6ft dirt jumps and skills area (under construction)','The 30yo BMX Track has been resurrected with a new project aiming to create a dirt park open for a wide range of riders and skill level.\r\n\r\nAt present the dual line BMX track runs down off Duncan street into a rolling 1/2ft step down followed by a split 1/2ft step up table top into a dual line right hand burm.  Pedaling into the back straight consisting of a 1ft double into a 3ft table top followed by a 4ft split step down table top into a right hand burm.  A couple cranks to finish into a triple set of 1ft doubles and a short 10m push back upto the start.\r\n\r\nThe 6ft dirt jumps are well under way, 2 1/2 complete out of a proposed set of 4 so is definately a project in progress but hope to have them finished when it\'s a little drier.\r\n\r\nThis vision is being overseen by Tawa Off Road Riders Club (TORRC)in conjunction with Wellington City Council (WCC)','Head to Tawa on SH1 or by Train. \r\n\r\nIf driving from the south:  Turn left at the Tawa offramp and follow the Main Road until turning right at the Tawa Street roundabout (BP Station on your right) Head down Tawa street, across the train tracks at Redwood train station then up on to Duncan Street turning left at the Duncan Street roundabout.  Keep heading north until you get to the Tawa Train station on your left.  The dirt park is below you on your left.\r\n\r\nIf driving from the north:  Exit at the Porirua offramp at the Mungavin Interchange, turn right at the interchange and go over the bridge, turn left onto Kenepuru Drive at the Titahi Bay Road/Walton Leigh Avenue/Kenepuru Drive roundabout.  Follow Kenepuru Drive onto Main road Tawa until you turn left at McLennan Street and drive across a short bridge.  Then turn right at the roundabout onto Duncan street and keep heading south untill you get to the Tawa Train station on your right.  The dirt park is below you on your Right.  Good angle parking available.\r\n\r\nIf coming by train:  Jump on a train to get you to Tawa, get off at the Tawa train station and access is off Duncan Street via the Tawa train station overbridge.','The locals are keen to make this a decent dirt park appealing to riders of different skill level and bike preference whether it be BMX, DJ or a full sus park beast.','0.100',0,0,NULL,NULL,'Single level Dirt Park','- Able to be ridden by a beginner (3yo) through to an advanced rider.','2009-06-10 17:37:43',113,'-41.169969','174.827650',18,1,7,2,113,'2009-06-10 17:47:23','user',0),(346,'Bootleg',22,' (Work in progress)','Two-way mostly sidling track that connects Nevay Road with the [[track:870]] DH run.','From Nevay Road head down a short and fairly steep section to the top of [[track:337]]. Be aware of the creek at the intersection with [[track:337]], as the crossing is not bridged.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter crossing the creek, head up towards the right across a bridge â€“ this section of track bypasses the old, and very steep, farm track that continues straight up the hill from the creek.  You\'ll cross this old farm track again further up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter about 0.1km the track turns west and sidles across the hill just within the boundary of the reserve.  After a while the track emerges on to a grassy opening with a view of Evan\'s Bay. Loop around to the left and you will see the entrance to the rest of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis is a 2 way track so expect to see people coming the other way.','The eastern end is on Nevay Road, just up hill of the last bus shelter before the prison.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe western end is to the right of the prison sign on Main Road, just outside where the road to the water tanks is obstructed by several concrete blocks. Head towards the water tanks to find the top of [[track:870]].','These tracks are two way and shared use, for bikes they are primarily intended for climbing as part of a loop with Jail Brake (our DH track). Please do not ride downhill at speed, the corners are not made for it so you will brake heavily and skid. That is not good. Also, these are dual use tracks, expect walkers and remember to give way to uphill riders and all walkers. These two tracks were built by mountain bikers but walkers have priority as with all tracks in Wellington unless otherwise designated. Also, do not shuttle these tracks, big bikes should stick to Jail Brake. ','0.656',22,26,119,115,'','','2009-06-12 15:28:28',88,'-41.297671','174.825976',17,3,1,1,52,'2010-04-18 19:31:41','calc',5),(347,'Massey Memorial',22,'','Bush clad connection from Massey Road up to the Massey Memorial. ','At the bottom end there are a few steps up from the edge of Massey Road.  Thereafter the track is wide with a gentle gradient as it climbs up under the trees to a plateau near of the head of Point Halswell.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe small grounds around the memorial are well tended.  Views over the harbour are spectacular, especially if you climb up the rough tracks to the southeast of the memorial.','Bottom end is on Massey Road, about 0.5km north of the former Shelly Bay Air Force Base. Beware that the steps at the bottom of this track are virtually on the edge of the road. There is a parking area directly opposite the track entrance.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTop is at the southwestern corner of the Massey Memorial.','The [[link:http://www.mch.govt.nz/emblems/monuments/massey.html Massey Memorial]] is a mausoleum for William Ferguson Massey, who was Prime Minister of New Zealand from 1912-1925, and his wife.','0.296',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-13 11:57:58',23,'-41.286514','174.825279',17,2,1,2,52,'2010-02-24 20:00:42','calc',5),(348,'Weir Loop',4,'','Short loop off [[track:34]] to a weir upstream of St. John\'s Pool.','This is a short loop that deviates off [[track:34]] and then rejoins [[track:34]] less than 100m further along.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom near St. John\'s Pool this track heads up the valley alongside the Kaiwharawhara Stream, just downstream from the [[link:http://www.sanctuary.org.nz/ Karori Sanctuary]]. Just as it reaches a weir across the stream, the track turns uphill to rejoin [[track:34]].','Northern end diverges off [[track:34]] a few metres south of St John\'s Pool, just as [[track:34]] starts to climb out of the valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end drops off [[track:34]] 50m before reaching Waiapu Road.','','0.139',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-21 20:53:48',23,'-41.289426','174.753229',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-06-22 20:00:30','calc',5),(349,'Kohekohe Bush',4,'','Short connection between [[track:34]] and Birdwood Steps.','A few metres from the [[track:34]] end of this track there is a small wooden bridge. Painted on the western railing of the bridge is \"Glow worm grotto\", referring to the adjacent mossy rockface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust past the bridge there is a low-hanging tree. On one side of the tree someone has helpfully painted \"Duck\". The other side of the tree says \"M.Y.H!\", presumably meaning \"mind your head\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout halfway along the track there is a faint track that deviates from a concrete stormwater cover. This side track runs behind some houses and ends after little more 0.1km at a gate that says \"Private\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you approach Birdwood Steps, there are a couple of options. The straight track drops sharply down onto Birdwood Steps. The other option zigzags up to a slightly higher place on Birdwood Steps.  Either way, the easiest exit is to go up to Ponsonby Road â€“ the alternative involves descending a lot of steps down to Birdwood Street near Karori Tunnel.','Southern end meets [[track:34]] at a hairpin bend about 0.2km from [[track:34]]\'s western end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is near the top of Birdwood Steps, just off the end of Ponsonby Road.','The unofficial signage at both ends of this track refers to it as the \"Kohekohe Bush Track\", presumably reflecting the [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kohekohe Kohekohe]] trees that are common in the surounding Kaiwharawhara Stream valley.','0.260',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-21 20:58:18',23,'-41.288388','174.752124',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-06-22 20:29:06','calc',5),(350,'42 Traverse',24,'','An entertaining ride on a flowing vehicle track','This ride is a vehicle track from off state highway 47 to Owhango.\r\nDespite being vehicle track it is rutted and gnarled enough for entertain experienced riders. Can be extremely muddy to the point of gumming up gears. The river crossings provide opportunities for un-gumming things and  were ridable but over bottom bracket. It is not recommended to do this track after heavy rains as not being able to cross the river would mean a long uphill ride back. There is a pub at the end of the road in Owhango for a well deserved beer.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:42 Traverse]] Elevation Chart\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/trackfield_graph/graph/267%2C267%2Cfield_track_data/Tracksdotorg/N:42 Traverse Elevation Chart:500:150]]','The starting point is usually at the junction of Kapoors Road and Highway 47. Which on between Turangi and National Park, 18kms from National Park.','It is recommended to take a topomap and gps/compass this is not somewhere you\'d want to get lost.','43.078',NULL,NULL,900,340,'',' with some river crossings. keep an eye on the weather','2009-06-22 22:11:18',59,'-39.039453','175.448227',11,3,1,3,59,'2010-01-14 16:12:01','calc',5),(351,'Te Ranga A Hiwi',5,'','Historical connection between the summits of Mount Victoria and Mount Alfred.','[[link:http://www.jps.auckland.ac.nz/document/Volume_28_1919/Volume_28,_No._109/The_Land_of_Tara_and_they_who_settled_it._Part_VI,_by_Elsdon_Best,_p_1-17#pagebreak_8 Te Ranga-a-Hiwi]] is the Maori name for the hills between Point Jerningham (at the northern tip of Mount Victoria) to the coast between Lyall Bay and Island Bay â€“ that is, Mount Victoria, Mount Alfred, and Mount Albert.  However, the scope of this track seems to be limited to connecting the summit of Mount Victoria with the summit of Mount Alfred.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe northern section of this track, from the Alexandra Road toilet block up to the summit of Mount Victoria, coincides with part of [[track:231]].  Most of the rest of the track coincides with a part of [[track:144]] that is adjacent to Alexandra Road, apart from a couple of short sections â€“ the last of which is the ascent to the summit of Mount Alfred.','The northern end is at the summit of Mount Victoria.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end is at the summit of Mount Alfred.','','1.025',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-25 19:42:20',23,'-41.299653','174.791493',15,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-09 12:56:58','calc',5),(352,'Alexandra Park',5,'','Sidling track from the northwest corner of Alexandra Park to the Alexandra Road saddle.','This is a short connection that sidles around the western side of Mount Alfred, hence bypassing a climbing section of [[track:144]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nLike most of [[area:5]], the track surface includes a few tree roots to contend with on this classic, though short, piece of single track. Much of the track surface is hard-packed dirt, though during winter it can get a bit cut up and turn into mud.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track climbs a few metres as it approaches the Alexandra Road saddle, though nothing of significance.','Southern end is at the northwest corner of Alexandra Park. Of the several tracks at that point, this one heads northeast and is almost flat initially.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is at the Alexandra Road saddle point, marked by an information board and the intersection of several tracks. This track heads southwest and slightly down under the mature pine trees.','','0.330',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-28 10:56:21',23,'-41.303772','174.787749',17,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:22:17','calc',5),(353,'Ellice',5,'','Rooty connection between [[track:147]] and the top of Ellice Street.','Narrow, steep, and root-infested little piece of single track that drops down through the trees from [[track:147]] to the top of Ellice Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of the track isn\'t well defined. From the sign post on [[track:147]], head straight down the hill for a few metres and then turn sharply left down a steep little section. From there the track is more clearly defined, levelling out somewhat as it bumps along over lots of tree roots.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the lower end you\'ll emerge from the trees onto the edge of an open grassy area. At that point there is a gas pumping station and the track surface changes to be a sealed path.  Follow the path and then turn down on to the road that ends at a steel barrier at the top of Ellice Street.','Climbs quite steeply up from the top of Ellice Street which is itself very steep.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a sign-posted intersection with [[track:147]], a few metres after passing the top of [[track:365]].','','0.328',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-28 10:58:43',23,'-41.300951','174.787422',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-07-26 11:18:34','calc',5),(354,'Mt Vic Easy',5,'','An easy loop around the southern half of [[area:5]].','This is a loop that encompasses a representative selection of easy tracks on the southern half of [[area:5]].  The companion [[track:355]] loop, which also starts and ends at the saddle point on Alexandra Road, encompasses a selection of intermediate grade tracks on the northern half of [[area:5]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe loop is well sign-posted, with small markers that show a bike and the word \"Easy\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the map board on the western side of the Alexandra Road saddle point, head across Alexandra Road and down [[track:147]]. At the sealed road, turn right and then proceed around the western side of the velodrome.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOff the southern end of the velodrome, follow [[track:146]] for 0.35km.  Turn left down hill and out into an open grassy area. Skirt around the tree line parallel with Ruahine Street, and then follow the signs back into the trees.\r\n[[para]]\r\nKeep heading south and you\'ll soon emerge into another open grassy area, this time above the [[track:340]]. If you like, drop down to the [[track:340]] for a play â€“ otherwise continue up the gentle slope to meet Alexandra Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTurn sharply north and cruise along the side of Alexandra Road for almost 0.2km, to the point where [[track:144]] and [[track:146]] coincide for 0.1km. At the car parking area, where [[track:144]] and [[track:146]] diverge, continue following [[track:144]] due north for 0.3km until you cross Alexandra Road outside the old fever hospital.\r\n[[para]]\r\nClimb the easier option up the hill outside the old fever hospital.  Skirt around the edge of Alexandra Park to its northwestern corner.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFinally, take the [[track:352]] track around the western side of Mount Alfred to complete the easy loop, finishing back at the Alexandra Road saddle point.','Starts and ends at the saddle point on Alexandra Road.','','2.747',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-28 11:01:54',23,'-41.307342','174.790120',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:21:06','calc',5),(355,'Mt Vic Intermediate',5,'','An intermediate loop around the northern half of [[area:5]].','This is a loop that encompasses a representative selection of intermediate tracks on the northern half of Mt Victoria. The companion [[track:354]] loop, which also starts and ends at the saddle point on Alexandra Road, encompasses a selection of easy grade tracks on the southern half of Mt Victoria.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe loop is well sign-posted, with small markers that show a bike and the word \"Intermediate\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the map board on the western side of the Alexandra Road saddle point, head north for almost 0.4km alongside Alexandra Road on the sections of [[track:144]] and [[track:351]] that coincide.\r\n[[para]]\r\nImmediately after crossing a sealed driveway, deviate away from Alexandra Road down [[track:341]] and [[track:231]] until you meet the [[track:229]]. Turn sharply left (southwest) and drop down the [[track:229]] past Charles Plimmer Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFinally, from the southern end of Charles Plimmer Park, follow the [[track:147]] walkway for 0.8km, ignoring the various side tracks and proceeding straight through several intersections.  After a reasonable climb up, you\'ll arrive back at the Alexandra Road saddle point to complete the loop. ','Starts and ends at the Alexandra Road saddle point.','','1.846',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-28 11:04:03',23,'-41.299234','174.790227',15,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-10 20:21:29','calc',5),(356,'Moke Lake',25,'','Scenic meander along Moke Lake Road near Queenstown.','This is a long ride, involving a fair bit of hill climbing.  You\'ll be rewarded with spectacular scenery, primarily the picturesque Lake Moke and surrounding hills, making the effort worthwhile.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of this track is technically easy, though there are some sections that require bike pushing.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track is a 4wd road, while the eastern quarter is single track.','Western end is on the Glenorchy Queenstown Road, about 6.5km southwest of downtown Queenstown.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end is on McChesney Road, in Arthurs Point, about 5km north of downtown Queenstown.','','21.687',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-30 20:14:55',23,'-45.006807','168.614044',12,3,1,3,23,'2009-07-01 06:27:37','calc',5),(357,'Macetown',26,'','Trek up the Arrow River gorge to [[link:http://www.arrowtown.org/mace.htm historic Macetown]].','Starting from Arrowtown, this track wanders up the Arrow River gorge along the old Macetown Road.  The gradient is generally upwards, climbing around 300m overall, though at a fairly gentle rate.  Along the way the track fords the Arrow River 22 times, so prepare to get wet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMacetown is an old gold mining town, established in the 1860s and abandoned by the 1930s.  The remaining historic buildings have been restored and the site is now managed by [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/otago/macetown/ DOC]].','Start from Butler Park at the end of Buckingham Street, Arrowtown.  Return the same way.','','13.420',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-06-30 20:35:23',23,'-44.902943','168.850250',12,2,1,3,23,'2009-06-30 20:37:54','calc',5),(358,'Piwakawaka',33,' - bicycle okay from Punjab St to top of reservoir','Historic track to Old Porirua Road over reservoir lookout.','There is a large sign on Punjab St for Odell Reserve and Piwakawaka track.  There is a tarsealed track to the reservoir at the top of the hill (gate blocks cars, but okay for bicycles).  There are great views from the lookout to Wellington City and across Ngaio and Khandallah areas, and down into Ngaio gorge.  It is popular spot to view fireworks on 5 November.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track down from the reservoir to Old Porirua Road goes through trees.  There are steps in places but it can be a bit muddy and slippy after rain.  There are a couple of \"unofficial\" side tracks which will take you down to the end of cul-de-sacs in Harbour Lights. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a couple of seats on the way, including one just outside the back lawn of a house with a brilliant view (and no fence between their lawn and the track). \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track emerges on Old Porirua Road just a few metres above the Harbour Lights turn-off.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOn top of Khandallah water reservoir\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2490/3764499291_de93935be1.jpg:Water tank:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nEntrance to Piwakawaka track from Old Porirua Road\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3432/3765296162_dc28a108c6.jpg:Piwakawaka track steps:326:490]]','The start of the track is easy to find off Punjab St in Khandallah.  The other end of the track on Old Porirua Road is easy to miss and there is no parking at that end.','','0.959',51,92,167,126,'','','2009-07-05 20:29:50',122,'-41.257227','174.780807',15,2,2,1,122,'2009-08-03 21:02:53','calc',5),(359,'Wightwicks Field',33,'','Part of Northern walkway joining Crofton Downs to Trelissick Park','This is part of the Northern Walkway and one of many routes through Trelissick Park in Ngaio.  It is of interest because tucked away from view is a small field, quite pleasant for picnics on a summers day (but can be a bit damp in winter).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe tracks have recently been upgraded.  They are wide and easy with good bridges over the Kaiwharawhara stream.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis particular route joins Waikowhai Street to Trelissick Crescent, but from Wightwicks field you also have the choice of following the stream.  If you begin the track at Waikowhai St or Trelissick Crescent there is a large WCC map of the tracks through the park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWightwicks Field\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2602/3765296178_52b67654f1.jpg:Wightwicks Field:490:326]]\r\n','Begin at Waikowhai St, which is about 150 metres from the Crofton Downs railway station (and Mitre10 store) towards Ngaio.  There is a large WCC sign and map at the start of the track.','No bikes allowed in Trelissick Park','0.495',59,33,73,99,'','','2009-07-06 22:52:13',122,'-41.253936','174.770787',16,2,2,2,122,'2009-08-03 21:05:59','calc',5),(360,'Kenya St bridge',33,'','Interesting shortcut that is easy to miss','This is a useful shortcut and interesting diversion if you are doing the Northern Walkway or Trelissick Park tracks.  It is easy to miss.  It links Waikowhai St to Kenya Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a bridge across Korimako Stream (Kaiwharawhara Stream) with nice bush views.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several places of historic interest in the area.  The Kenya St entrance to the bridge is opposite the famous clock tower, and next door is a large pioneer house owned by Colin McDiarmid photographer.  For details of the historic places check out the sign in front of Ngaio Library on Ottawa Road (near the entrance to Cummings Park).\r\n[[para]]\r\nEntrance to Kenya St bridge from Waikowhai Street in Ngaio\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3582/3765296200_73bf076cbd.jpg:Kenya St bridge sign:326:490]]','The Waikowhai St entrance is about 200 m south of Ngaio station.  There is a signpost saying \"Waikowhai St 41 - 45\" and \"Pedestrian access to Kenya St\".  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is no sign on Kenya St, but the entrance is almost directly opposite the famous clock tower at no 25.','','0.150',9,NULL,78,87,'','','2009-07-07 21:25:16',122,'-41.254678','174.770122',16,1,1,5,122,'2009-08-03 21:04:51','calc',5),(361,'Mukamuka',10,'','7 hour tramp from Orongorongo River across Mukamuka South Sadddle to Catchpool','This is the route of the \"Mukamuka Munta\".  It is a serious hike of about 27 km in length.  You will need transport at both ends.  The track is not well marked in places, so you should take proper gear with you if you haven\'t done it before - and tell someone where you are going.  Take food, warm and waterproof clothing, and don\'t attempt this track after heavy rain as the rivers will be high.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can start from either Catchpool end or Orongorongo river bridge.  I will start at the carpark a few hundred metres from Orongorongo station bridge.  Start heading east around Turakirae Head scientific reserve.  This is a wide, gravel, 4WD track which continues along the coast.  It is possible to drive a 4WD right along the coastline, though there is a large rockfall approx. halfway to Mukamuka rivermouth which requires some clambering over and you may temporarily lose the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Mukamuka rivermouth features large areas of green grass.  On the Ocean Beach side of the river is a large memorial (on the ground) for the Mukamuka covenant - check out this historic site.  (It is only another 45 mins or so to Ocean Beach from Mukamuka River, and from there another hour along Onoke Spit to the rivermouth opposite Lake Ferry).\r\n[[para]]\r\nMukamuka river is usually easy to cross, and from here you head up the riverbed - go straight up inland instead of forking to the right.  The river gets smaller and smaller and starts to climb.  It is important to pay attention, as the track leading up to Mukamuka South saddle is marked with a large orange triangle, but if you miss it you could end up forking left up another tributary and getting lost.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nOnce you locate the track it is marked with orange tags, and it climbs steeply up several hundred metres to the South Saddle of Mt Matthews.  At the top there are excellent views, and a good spot for a rest and a bite to eat.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou then follow the track through the bush along the ridge until the junction with the Mt Matthews track.  (There may be a \"South Saddle\" broken sign at this junction).  Up-hill leads to Mt Matthews and a few hundred metres more climbing.  Take the well-formed downhill track down through the bush to the Orongorongo river.  The bush is lovely in this area.  When the track meets the river, turn left and head downstream.  There is a large orange triangle marking the track up to Mt Matthews (look for this if coming from Catchpool).  There is a hut near the river but is privately owned and locked.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 400 metres downstream you have a choice of continuing down the river, or taking a track along the bank.  The bank track is a better choice if the river is high.  The inland track is near the junction leading to the inland Whakanui track, and is marked by a small stream emerging from the bush - it is easy to miss if you are walking down the stream bed so look carefully.  In summer the river can be completely dry at this point.  From here it is about 1 hour downstream until you see the bridge and the inland track leading to catchpool carpark.\r\n[[para]]  \r\nTimes: rough guide 2.5 hours from Orongorongo river to Mukamuka rivermouth; 1 hour up river; 30 mins climb up South Saddle; 1 to 1.5 hours back down to Orongorongo river; 1 hour downriver, and 1 hour from river to Catchpool carpark.  Allow 7 - 8 hours for the trip.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView up Mukamuka valley\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2443/3776814871_1f35386a2f.jpg:Mukamuka valley:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nCoastal track\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2563/3777618652_38b394b6dd.jpg:Coastal track:490:326]]','You will need your own transport with a car at each end.  Park at the top carpark at Catchpool (there are toilet facilities there).  At Orongorongo station there isn\'t parking near the bridge, so use the carpark about 1 km up the road.','Cycling is not permitted, and as there are Kiwis in the area all dogs should be kept on a leash.','29.375',580,520,5,60,'',' - you will get wet feet','2009-07-09 21:05:39',122,'-41.380673','174.961052',12,4,2,1,122,'2009-08-01 21:14:28','calc',5),(362,'Bell Track',33,'','Part of Northern Walkway joining Awarua St to Skyline track','If coming along Skyline walkway from Mt Kaukau, Bell Track is clearly signpost leading downhill to the top of Awarua Street.  If you are doing the Northern Walkway then take this route, which leads through Ngaio (past the Awarua St railway station) and on through Trelissick Park to Wadestown and Tinakori Hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can also use this track from Awarua Street, where it is a 20 minute uphill walk to the Skyline track, where you can either go right to Mt Kaukau, or left to Crofton Downs.','Bell Track is at the top of Awarua St, about 1.5 km from the Awarua St railway station (Johnsonville line).','Bikes are ok on Skyline track, but not allowed down Bell Track (there are steps).','0.726',182,NULL,114,296,'','','2009-07-09 21:32:57',122,'-41.244676','174.759135',15,2,2,1,122,'2009-08-16 13:55:06','calc',5),(363,'Wheeler\'s Way',17,' (Private property â€“ see notes)','Forestry road to the Blue Mountains.','This is a wide and smooth forestry road that wanders along a ridge connecting the Western Hutt Hills with the Blue Mountains.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road, and the surrounding pine plantation, is private property. The land owners do not welcome mountain bikes on to their property.  Please respect their wishes.  Foot traffic is OK â€“ see the contact details below.','Eastern end is at the top of Avro Road, in the Blue Mountains.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end meets the end of [[track:81]], not far from the top of [[track:224]].','This road is on private property.  Before venturing into this area, contact the owners for permission: Guildford Timber Limited, telephone 04-528-3978.','2.591',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-11 13:26:02',23,'-41.174907','175.014524',15,2,2,4,23,'2010-01-01 13:17:51','calc',5),(364,'Avian',17,' (Private property â€“ see notes)','Secondary forestry road in the Blue Mountains.','This is a secondary forestry road that bypasses much of the sealed Avro Road climb/descent through the Blue Mountains.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBoth ends of this road are blocked by a couple of large concrete blocks, in an attempt to keep out vehicle traffic.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road, and the surrounding pine plantation, is private property. The land owners do not welcome mountain bikes on to their property. Please respect their wishes. Foot traffic is OK â€“ see the contact details below.','Western end is at the top of Avro Road in the Blue Mountains, a few metres from the eastern end of [[track:363]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end is at the top of Avian Road.','This road is on private property. Before venturing into this area, contact the owners for permission: Guildford Timber Limited, telephone 04-528-3978.','2.292',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-11 13:28:14',23,'-41.176587','175.026884',15,3,2,3,23,'2010-01-01 13:18:10','calc',5),(365,'Pirie',5,'','Short connector from the [[track:147]] Walkway to the top of Pirie Street, just next to the Hataitai bus tunnel.','This is a short and quite steep connector between [[track:147]] and Pirie Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe Pirie Street end of this track has a few steps. The first set of steps, which end on Pirie Street, drop down between a house and a large green electricial transformer. The second set of steps can be avoided by following the house\'s fenceline for a few metres and then turning up hill to join the main track just above the second set of steps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a couple of faintly defined alternative tracks that run more-or-less parallel to the main track.  They also connect with [[track:353]], near the intersection with [[track:147]]. ','','Southern end deviates off [[track:353]], just a few metres off [[track:147]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is on Pirie Street, close to the western end of the [[link:http://www.heritagehelp.co.nz/tunnel.html Hataitai bus tunnel]].','0.106',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-11 13:40:16',23,'-41.299567','174.788449',17,3,1,1,23,'2009-07-26 11:30:20','calc',5),(366,'Waikanae Estuary',28,'','Easy track around Waikanae river mouth','Wide track suitable for both walking and cycling.  It is a popular area for cycling, and you can follow adjacent tracks up either bank of the Waikanae river.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou need to go on the road between Otaihanga domain and entering the Scientific Reserve.  There is a clearly marked walking/cycling track as you exit Makora Rd and cross Otaihanga Road.  New planting on each side of this track which emerged into an area of vacant sections (Petrel Close, Hana Udy Place).  The roads are quiet and signs do show the Kapiti cycling route.  You enter the Waikanae Estuary Scientific Reserve off Hana Udy Place.  This is a wide 4WD track down to the beach meeting up again with the river.  There are many other tracks through the bird reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is flat across the entire length, and you can cycle across the footbridge.  In summer you can walk across the river under the footbridge - the water isn\'t very deep.','There is a good carpark on the Waikanae side of the estuary at the end of Tutere St, and this is a good place to begin.  Another good spot is Otaihanga domain beside the footbridge across the river, off Makora Rd in Otaihanga.','','3.438',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-12 14:53:09',122,'-40.874876','175.011606',15,1,1,2,122,'2009-07-12 15:06:18','calc',5),(367,'Waimanu Lagoons',28,'','Easy walk around Waikanae lagoons','There is a good carpark at the end of Tutere Street by the river mouth, but there are many points where you can access the lagoons from surrounding streets.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhilst some people come to feed the ducks, the lagoons have good numbers of NZ Scaup, Dabchick, Grey Teal, Shoveller, and Shags.  There is a large fir tree in which Shags roost and breed, and Spoonbill may also sometimes be seen roosting at the top of the tree.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTrack is flat.','By car, park in the carpark at the end of Tutere St.  There are toilets in this carpark.','','1.362',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-12 14:59:00',122,'-40.872377','175.010169',16,1,1,1,122,'2009-07-12 15:05:17','calc',5),(368,'Scientific Reserve',28,'','Walk around and through Waikanae bird reserve','This is a walk along the beach and through some of the tracks through the bird reserve.  Cycling is permitted, but it is easier along the beach on foot.  The tracks through the reserve are fine for cycling.  Many people walk dogs in this area - if you do, note that it is a bird reserve so please don\'t let your dogs eat the birds!\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe route shown is a loop from the north end of the reserve by the river mouth, along the beach, out of the reserve and up Manly St, and then back through the reserve to the main track near Hana Udy Place.  There are many other tracks through the reserve.  The route shown is designed to link up with the adjacent tracks.','If you are driving, good places to park are near the main entrances on Manly Street, or at the end of Takahe Drive.  Beach access is provided by the main track on Manly St near Nuhaka Place.','','3.063',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-12 15:14:10',122,'-40.875168','175.004354',15,1,1,1,122,'2010-03-28 20:04:27','calc',5),(369,'Marsden Track',29,'','Grassed Forest Rd. Detailed map @ http://glenberviemtbiking.zoomshare.com/','Easy going with a little up and down in the middle, can be slippery when wet.','Head through the steel gate on left of the notice board at the HQ\'s, follow the road, Main Rd(Etoru Rd), up to the top of hill, and Marsden is on your left, as per the sign.','','2.441',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-18 14:30:15',126,'-35.651752','174.332986',15,2,1,1,126,'2010-02-13 07:57:32','calc',5),(370,'Flipper',29,'','Long, quick downhill. \r\n','A long quick downhill, dropping off Marsden track. follow the signs on Marsden track.',' Marsden Track.','','0.929',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-18 14:35:35',126,'-35.654053','174.336119',15,3,3,1,126,'2010-03-15 08:29:55','calc',5),(371,'Millworkers Track',30,'','Short cut between Korokoro and Cornish Street','This a short (5 - 10 minute) track with historic significance.  It was made by the woollen mill workers around 1900.  When the mill closed in 1968 the track became overgrown, but was re-discovered and cleared in 2002.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt connects Korokoro with the Cornish Street track into Belmont Regional park.  Note that if walking, there aren\'t any footpaths on Korokoro Road on the descent to SH2, so it is better to follow Singers Rd to Maungaraki Rd and pick up some of the other Korokoro walking tracks.  If you want to do a loop trip it is possible to walk through Korokoro to Tiro Moana road and take the [[track:844]] back down to the stream.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is reasonable but can be a bit wet and slippy in winter.  Bikes can use it - there aren\'t any steps.','Park at [[link:http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=-41.222988,174.860759&spn=0.011427,0.019312&t=h&z=16 Cornish St]] entrance to Belmont Regional Park.  Parking is difficult Rahui Grove, which is a private road but the public walkway is signpost.','','0.343',80,NULL,9,89,'','','2009-07-18 21:38:03',122,'-41.220518','174.861177',17,2,1,1,122,'2010-01-17 19:20:06','calc',5),(372,'Titiro Moana Road',30,'','Walking track to water tower and lookout','Previously private land, the owners provide public access for walkers and dog owners on a track that leads to Puketirotiro lookout.  This section begins on a sealed road then after about 150 metres a sign leads left along a well marked track through grass and shrubs.  After about another 250 metres you either continue left to Puketirotiro lookout, or go right which loops back round onto the sealed road where there is a water tower about 100 metres further on.  You can return on the sealed road back to Titiro Moana Road.','Park on Titiro Moana Road near the private sealed road.','Bikes are not welcome by the landowners.','0.484',51,19,177,228,'','','2009-07-18 22:06:47',122,'-41.209575','174.865201',17,1,2,5,122,'2009-07-23 20:11:55','calc',5),(373,'Puketirotiro',30,'','Short walk to a lookout providing excellent views to Petone and Somes Is','Continuation of the public track over private land from Titiro Road on to the Puketirotiro lookout.  Note that near the house at the sign to Puketirotiro the track going left (which is not signed) is a rough route descending to the Korokoro stream track.  The Puketirotiro lookout is about 200 metres past the house, and has excellent views over Korokoro and Petone, and to Wellington harbour.  It looks down on to nearby Sugarloaf.','Either park at Titiro Moana Road and follow the marked walking route, or park on Maungaraki Road near the track to Sugarloaf and follow the sealed road for about 200 metres.  Puketirotiro lookout is about 100 metres off the sealed private road.','Bikes are not allowed.','0.463',37,8,209,246,'','','2009-07-18 22:22:05',122,'-41.209518','174.866016',17,2,2,1,122,'2009-10-04 21:13:28','calc',5),(374,'Puketirotiro North',30,'','Short track to a viewing point over Korokoro stream valley','An optional track that starts opposite the Puketirotiro lookout track, and leads a short way to a viewing point over Korokoro stream valley looking towards Haywards.  This track is a uneven and a little rough in places.  It isn\'t well marked, and is no exit (return the same way).','The track begins opposite the signed route to Puketirotiro, off the sealed private road at 135 Maungaraki Road (there is public access for walkers).','Cyclists not allowed.','0.156',5,NULL,237,242,'','','2009-07-18 22:31:53',122,'-41.210672','174.869277',16,3,2,1,122,'2009-07-23 20:12:29','calc',5),(375,'Sugarloaf',30,'','Maungaraki Road to Acacia Avenue via Sugarloaf lookout','There are a number of walking tracks through the central bush areas of Korokoro.  Note that in places the tracks are steep and rough and can be slippy in winter.  Tree roots are a nuisance in places.  This route is well marked with signs and maps at each end (Mangaraki Road and at Acacia Avenue), and the view from Sugarloaf is well worth the short climb.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeginning on Maungaraki road, the track goes downhill a short way and then there is signposted t-junction.  Go left and up over Sugarloaf, admiring the view of Somes Is.  Continue down and there are two further t-junctions on the route to Acacia Avenue.  Both are signposted, and both tracks lead down through the bush towards Percy\'s reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTop of Sugarloaf\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3517/3764499261_6bfbb3496b.jpg:Sugarloaf:490:326]]','Park on Maungaraki Road near the private road at #135, and follow the signs to Sugarloaf.','','0.797',29,56,236,180,'','','2009-07-18 22:46:38',122,'-41.210721','174.870350',16,2,2,1,122,'2009-09-26 20:49:26','calc',5),(376,'Corins Climb',30,'','Link through Kohekohe from Barberry Grove to Sugarloaf track','This track leads through the Kohekohe hillsides.  It is uneven and steep in places, and in winter can be muddy and slippy.  At the top end it is signposted off the Sugarloaf track.  Near the bottom there is a clearing, from which tracks lead to Barberry Grove, down to Percy\'s reserve via the waterfall track (this isn\'t signposted, but is a clearly defined track leading downhill), and across the Jagger track (which is extremely steep in places) to George Gee Drive.\r\n[[para]]\r\n(Please note that I didn\'t get good GPS signal through the thick tree cover so the GPS route may not be exact - the track is well marked and signposted at each end, you are unlikely to get lost!)','Begin either from Sugarloaf track, or from the end of Barberry Grove.','','0.554',10,104,195,91,'','','2009-07-18 23:05:11',122,'-41.209284','174.870801',16,3,2,1,122,'2009-07-23 20:10:22','calc',5),(377,'Barberry Grove',30,'','Short flat track linking Barberry Grove to central Korokoro tracks to Percy\'s reserve or Sugarloaf','This is a short track linking Barberry Grove to the clearing in the Kohekohe hillside where tracks lead up to Sugarloaf (Corins Climb) or down to Percy\'s reserve.  There are steps at the Barberry Grove end, but the track is very suitable for dog walkers.','Park at the end of Barberry Grove.','','0.200',7,NULL,108,115,'','','2009-07-18 23:12:51',122,'-41.211915','174.872196',16,1,1,2,122,'2009-07-23 20:11:15','calc',5),(378,'Jagger shortcut',30,'','Links Barberry Grove to George Gee drive','This is a short but very steep track through the Korokoro tree clad hillside.  Beginning from the clearing near Barberry Grove, having either ascended from Percy\'s reserve, or descended from Sugarloaf, the track heads South and climbs steeply uphill.  After about 300 metres there is a t-junction with the Bulldozer track.  Go down to George Gee Drive (about 200 metres) or uphill to Sugarloaf.','Nearest car parking is on George Gee Drive or Barberry Grove.','','0.323',48,16,112,122,'','','2009-07-18 23:28:05',122,'-41.210366','174.873376',16,3,2,1,122,'2009-07-23 20:10:59','calc',5),(379,'Fort Buckley',33,'','Short diversion off main Wadestown street to historic gun site','[[link:http://capitaldefence.orconhosting.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/bukley1.htm Fort Buckley]] was an important gun emplacement during WW II.  The site of the old guns sit above Ngaio Gorge looking out over the harbour.  The site is being upgraded and now has wide, smooth tracks and new plantings.  Well worth a short diversion if you are passing through Wadestown.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that although its only about 50 metres above Ngaio Gorge and the old Hutt Road, there isn\'t any way up from the bottom.  Don\'t try climbing up - if you fall it\'ll hurt!','Access from Barnard St.  There is a seat and a new fence near the path down (but no signage).','','0.141',NULL,28,71,43,'','','2009-07-19 16:42:43',122,'-41.259808','174.786065',17,1,1,1,122,'2009-08-03 21:06:54','calc',5),(380,'Makara Gun Bunkers',14,'','Coastal hill-top walk to gun emplacements with views of South Island','Makara Beach is a popular spot for Wellingtonians on weekends.  There is a cafe at Makara beach and toilets.  The road from Karori to Makara Beach is twisty and windy so take care (60 km/hr speed limit).  Construction of the wind farm is still underway to watch out for large trucks on the road during weekdays.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track sets off along the coastline, around a small headland into a small bay which is popular with fishermen and divers.  After about 800 metres the track divides - up the hill to the gun emplacements.  There is one wind turbine visible nearby along this route.  As you climb to the top of the hills more wind turbines come into view.  The track continues along the hill tops.  On a windy day it can be a bit scary, but there are several tracks to keep to the one which hugs the fenceline.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter about a further kilometre there is a style and you enter the gun emplacement area.  Some of these are now fenced off, but you can wander round this historic site with good views of Cook Strait and the South Island.  It takes about 1 hour from Makara Beach to reach the gun emplacements.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome people walk to the gun emplacements and then back along the same route.  If you want a longer walk (allow 3 hours for the round trip), follow the track inland for a few hundred metres to a t-junction.  To the left is a farm track with a closed gate - this leads to Opau Rd and Quartz Hill, but is private property.  However, you can see one of the wind turbines quite closely from the gate.  Take the downhill track to Opau Bay.  This is a sealed road but is quite steep (be careful if wet).\r\n[[para]]\r\nGun emplacements overlooking Cook Strait\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3475/3764499461_5713a49648.jpg:Gun emplacements:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nWind turbines\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3503/3764499419_42a6c8d309.jpg:Wind turbines at Makara:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nCoastline south of gun emplacements (Opau Bay)\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3507/3764499441_13b531355a.jpg:Opau Bay:490:326]]','Drive to Makara Beach and park in the parking area beside the toilets and cafe.','The inland track is closed for lambing from 1 August to 31 October.','3.544',190,190,0,0,'','','2009-07-19 17:03:45',122,'-41.225538','174.700384',14,2,2,1,122,'2009-07-28 20:47:43','calc',5),(381,'Makara Coastal Track',14,'','Coastal route from Makara Beach to Opau Bay','This completes the loop from the gun emplacements and Opau Bay back to Makara Beach, or provides a nice coastal walk if you don\'t feel like walking uphills.  The track follows the coastline and is rocky and uneven - it is tough going along the pebbly shoreline so although the distance isn\'t great it takes a while (allow 1.5 hours, or 3 hours if you do the round trip with the gun emplacements).  At high tide going around the headlands requires a little rock climbing - it isn\'t dangerous, but take care.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3594/3764499233_a50ed14e14.jpg:Makara Beach coastal walk:490:326]]','Park at Makara Beach and follow the coastal walking route.','Whilst the inland track is closed during lambing season, access is always available to the coastal track.','3.172',NULL,NULL,0,0,'','','2009-07-19 17:11:45',122,'-41.225925','174.707251',14,3,2,1,122,'2009-07-28 20:44:42','calc',5),(382,'Mangaone',28,'','Flat walk through Kaitawa bush following a river through Waikanae back country','Mangaone walkway (previously called Reikorangi track) follows an old bush tramway.  The walk is mostly flat with gentle gradients.  The DOC signs say 3 hours for the 8 km walk.  There are three main sections:\r\n[[para]]\r\n1. Starting at Mangaone south road where this is a big carpark, there is a river crossing (it isn\'t deep but the water is over ankle deep so you\'ll get your feet wet) then a 30 - 45 minute walk through Kaitawa scenic bush reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\n2. Emerging from the bush is a large open grassy area near the river.  A great picnic spot in summer.  This is Te Horo clearing.  The track is well marked across the grassland.\r\n[[para]]\r\n3. At the end of the clearing you join a wide 4WD track leading to Mangaone north road.  There is forest on both sides and the track goes gently uphill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn winter parts of the track can be a bit damp.  The track through Kaitawa reserve has good bridges, but there are a couple of small streams to cross in the clearing.  There are a couple of dwellings at the north end of Te Horo clearing - farm dogs, chickens, and a guy living in an old removals truck (say \"hi!\" as you pass!).\r\n[[para]]\r\nTe Horo Clearing - grassy picnic area near the stream\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2653/3764499191_bd3588f7ba.jpg:Te Horo clearing:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou need to cross this river as you leave the Mangaone South car park\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3548/3764499217_5351d4b0db.jpg:Mangaone stream:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]','The best carpark is on Mangaone south road.  At Waikanae traffic lights take the route inland towards the Akatarawa\'s, turning off to Reikorangi about 7 km down the road.  Passing Reikorangi pottery, a few hundred metres down Ngatiawa Road turn left on the Mangaone South Road and drive to the end and park in the carpark.  There is a river crossing at this end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor Mangaone north, turn inland at Te Horo crossroads 9 km north of Waikanae.  Go past the school and follow the signs to Mangaone walkway along Hautere-Cross Road, then turn right on to Mangaone north road and follow it to the end.  The last 4 km are narrow, windy and unsealed.  There is a small carpark at this end.','Whilst it would be easy to cycle the route, bicycles are not allowed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that you will need transport at both ends, or plan to return along the same route (16 km round trip).  Allow 3-4 hours (DOC sign says 3 hours each way, but this is conservative).','7.081',144,192,106,129,'','','2009-07-25 20:35:24',122,'-40.853553','175.146961',13,2,2,3,122,'2009-07-28 20:42:48','calc',5),(383,'Green Point',14,'','Coastal walk to a prominent green knob south of Porirua','This is a popular walk for anglers and picnickers.  From the carpark near the water treatment plant (ie sewarage works!) head up the track between the concrete blocks and after 20 - 30 metres take a small track on the right leading towards the beach.  There is a narrow but well formed track that descends down to the shore.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track to Green Point leads around the coast.  It isn\'t far but requires some clambering over rocks.  At high tide there are a couple of headlands that aren\'t usually any trouble to go round, but can be clambered over if necessary (there are well marked routes up and over).\r\n[[para]]\r\nGreen point is a good spot for picnics, with a good view of Mana Island. Allow about 40 minutes for the walk.','Turn off Titahi Bay road on to Te Pene Av, 2nd left up Te Puke St, and then 3rd left on to Pikarere St.  Follow this round, and take Moki St on the right near the end of the road (becomes a private road about 0.5 km further on).  200 m down Moki St there is a gate which is open during daylight hours.  You can drive 700 metres down the road and park opposite the water treatment plant.  The gates do close at sunset so if you may be late, park at the top of Moki St and walk down.','Dogs are prohibited (Sheep measles area).','1.375',0,27,27,0,'','','2009-07-25 20:52:41',122,'-41.114570','174.813037',15,2,2,1,122,'2009-07-25 20:53:30','calc',5),(384,'Open Bay',14,'','Coastal walk from Green Point south to the next sandy bay','Continue south along the coast from Green Point.  The track is well marked on the grass just above the gravel and rock.  Open Bay is sandy and a pleasant spot in summer.','From Green Point.','(Tracks leading inland are private property)','0.816',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-07-25 20:56:12',122,'-41.107683','174.823208',14,2,2,1,122,'2009-07-25 20:57:57','calc',5),(385,'Moki St',14,'','Access to water treatment plant from Moki St','Leads to the carpark for Green Point if the gates are closed.  There is also a walkway leading north from the gate which joins up with Stuart Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the gates there are good views of the ocean, Mana Island, and north to Whitireia park.','Turn off Titahi Bay road on to Te Pene Av, 2nd left up Te Puke St, and then 3rd left on to Pikarere St. Follow this round, and take Moki St on the right near the end of the road (becomes a private road about 0.5 km further on).  Park near the gates about 200 metres down Moki St.','','0.714',0,61,89,28,'','','2009-07-25 21:03:43',122,'-41.114053','174.812651',15,1,1,5,122,'2009-07-25 21:04:37','calc',5),(386,'Putangirua Pinnacles',32,'','Walk up a riverbed to see the amazing Pinnacles','There is a choice of loop track up through the bush to a lookout, and then descending down the riverbed at the base of the pinnacles - or you can walk directly up the riverbed (which is quicker).  Although it is a riverbed there isn\'t usually much water around.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe pinnacles are large crumbly rock stalagmite type structures rising tens of metres into the air.  They are left behind as the surrounding area erodes.  It is spookily eerie to wander around them - just take care as bits of rock are constantly falling off.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track shown is the loop track through the bush.  Just before the lookout and descent to the riverbed, there is a t-junction and the track continues up behind the pinnacles joining into a 4WD track (which goes on further to a DOC hut in the bush).  After descending to the riverbed it is a further 15 - 20 minute walk up into the pinnacle area proper if you want to go up.  The riverbed is uneven and stony.  If you want to do the bush track you need to watch for the entry and exit carefully from the riverbed as the entrances quickly get overgrown with bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe DOC sign says to allow 3-4 hours for the loop walk.  You can do the bush loop and back along the riverbed in about 1.5 hours, but allow more time to wander up and around the Pinnacles.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3497/3756814633_2098ec4508.jpg?v=0:Putangirua Pinnacles:490:326]]','Driving only.  Take the road to Lake Ferry from Martinborough and turn off left to Cape Palliser.  The Pinnacles are signpost on the left just before a bridge about 18 km from the turn-off.  (Look out for the cute Burnside Church a few km south of Pirinoa).','Camping is permitted in the Pinnacles carpark area.','3.951',209,209,15,224,'','','2009-07-26 20:41:40',1,'-41.445750','175.232534',15,3,2,1,122,'2009-07-29 01:07:02','calc',5),(387,'Cape Palliser',32,'','Rough and wild coastal route from Cape Palliser to White Rock','Beside the steps to the Cape Palliser lighthouse is a small carpark, and a 4WD track leading north along the coastline.  This is through private land to a DOC reserve (Ngapotiki block).  Public access is allowed provided you stay on the track.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that this area is isolated.  No cellphone coverage.  No phones, no houses.  Nearest settlement is Ngawihi on the road to Cape Palliser.  Be self-sufficient.  (That said, there always seems to be surfers, quad bikers or farmers around!).\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom Cape Palliser carpark the rough 4WD farm track proceeds along the coastline for about 3.5 km, where there is a gate at the entrance to the DOC Ngapotiki reserve.  Walking access only through the reserve - if you did take a bike there is about 1 km of sandy area and a short sharp hill which you\'d be pushing your bike on anyway.  That said, quad bikes and cyclists do follow the road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter descending the short, sharp hill there is a locked gate, and then the flat again as you enter the White Rock bay area.  About 3 km further on there is another locked gate, the DOC entrance from White Rock side to the Ngapotiki block.  If you brave the road across the hills from Martinborough (its a long way) then this is where you would park.  White Rock itself, a \"white rock\" just off the shore, is a couple of km further on, in approximately the middle of the bay.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou should plan to return the same way - it is a long way to put a car at both ends.  The coastal track is uneven and muddy in places, with a few river crossings and large puddles after rain.  It took me 3 hours for a return trip using a bicycle - plan on at least 3 hours each way if walking.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTypical view of coastal track\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2520/3756875561_8071fbbfe7.jpg?v=0:Coastal track:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nEntrance to Ngapotiki block from White Rock end\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3438/3757673654_5d87a97ba0.jpg?v=0:White Rock entrance:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nView of White Rock bay area\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2438/3756875609_ed3dc75016.jpg?v=0:White Rock bay:490:326]]','I suggest using the Cape Palliser carpark.  From Martinborough take the road to Lake Ferry, turning off the Cape Palliser and follow the road to the end (about 70 km from Martinborough).  It is sealed apart from the last few kilometres.  Get supplies (food, drink, pletrol) at Martinborough as there isn\'t much past there.  There is a road to White Rock, but it is a long unsealed road.  ','Stunning place on a good day.  Exposed and desolate on a stormy day.  Make sure you tell someone where you are going.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCycling is not permitted through Ngapotiki block.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter Ngawihi there is the little settlement of Mangatoetoe, and between there and the Cape Palliser lighthouse you will often see Seals on the rocks.','11.777',50,50,0,0,'','','2009-07-26 21:08:13',1,'-41.557922','175.340080',12,4,1,3,122,'2009-07-29 01:06:07','calc',5),(388,'Northern wkway Ngaio',33,'','Northern walkway route from Bell Track through Ngaio','This part of the Northern Walkway is along the road through Ngaio, from Bell Track (descent from Skyline walkway) to Trelissick Park.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nBell Track ends at the top of Awarua Street.  Follow Awarua Street, noting the small stream on the right hand side of the street (whilst descending).  Opposite Awarua Street railway station is a northern walkway sign - turn right here and go through Cummings Park, which comes out beside Ngaio library.  There is a sign displaying historic sites in the area beside the library.  There is a cafe in Ngaio and other shops if you need supplies.\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue through Ngaio to the roundabout, using the pedestrian crossing opposite the tennis courts (beside the steps up to Ngaio railway station) to cross Waikowhai Street, and walk along the left hand side of Waikowhai Street to the Trelissick Park entrance which is just before Crofton Downs railway station and the rail bridge over the road.','Three railway stations (Crofton Downs, Ngaio and Awarua Street) on the Johnsonville line provide easy public access to this route.','','2.077',0,121,184,63,'','','2009-08-01 17:29:45',122,'-41.246708','174.767160',14,2,1,5,122,'2009-08-03 21:05:23','calc',5),(389,'Trelissick park stream',33,'','Stream track through Trelissick Park in Ngaio','The beginning of this track is part of the Northern Walkway.  Starting from the entrance on Waikowhai Street near Crofton Downs railway station, the track descends to Wightwicks Field.  From here the northern walkway route goes up (see [[track:359]]) - instead take the smaller track left which follows Kaiwharawhara stream.  This is a lovely walk.  The track is newer than the Northern walkway route, but joins up beside the bridge leading up to Wadestown.  If you are doing the Northern Walkway I recommend the stream track instead.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track has good bridges, and new areas of planting along the route.  There are some grassy areas suitable for picnics.  There is a short steep sidetrack to view the fish ladder.  Near the end of the track are historic powder magazines, and some tunnels (locked grating) leading into the hills.  There may be some mud in places, but overall the track is an easy walk.  ','Crofton Downs railway station is near the Trelissick Park entrance.  Kaiwharawhara railway station near the Ngaio Gorge end.','Bicycles not allowed in Trelissick Park reserve.','2.457',6,53,63,10,'','','2009-08-01 17:46:55',122,'-41.253678','174.778361',15,2,2,1,122,'2009-08-03 21:04:32','calc',5),(390,'Rangiora Av steps',33,'','Shortcut from Kaiwharawhara to Khandallah','Approximately 400 steps connect Rangiora Av (opposite Placemakers on Hutt Road) to Amritsar Street in Khandallah.  Can be a useful shortcut.  The steps are wider and street-lit at night.  Going down is much easier than going up!  There are good views over Wellington harbour from the top of the steps at the end of Amritsar St.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3260/3776651611_019c22f22e.jpg:Rangiora Avenue steps:326:490]]','There is a bus stop on Hutt Road opposite Placemakers near Rangiora Avenue.  Parking is difficult at the end of Amritsar Street.','','0.164',75,0,33,108,'','','2009-08-01 19:34:20',122,'-41.254952','174.792995',16,1,2,2,122,'2009-08-03 21:03:52','calc',5),(391,'Kaiwhara bridleway',33,'','Good walking track joining Khandallah Nicholson Rd to Ngaio gorge','This is a sealed walking and cycling track from Nicholson Road in Khandallah leading down (with views of Wellington harbour) to a small subdivision at the end of Ngaio gorge.  There are several alternative entrances and exits from the bridleway.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe route below begins on Cameron St on Ngaio gorge - the bridleway proper starts about 250 metres up the road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a new subdivision being built (Cameron St, Hershey Way, Brasch Way) below the bridleway, which may result in additional access points in the future.','There is a bus stop at the bottom of Ngaio gorge, from which it is just a short walk up to the bridleway.','','1.010',110,0,5,115,'','','2009-08-01 19:44:07',122,'-41.252645','174.790120',15,1,1,2,122,'2009-08-03 21:03:18','calc',5),(392,'Winchester St',33,'','Entrance to [[track:391]]','Short track from end of Winchester St at the end of Ngaio gorge, to the bridelway.  If you walk up Winchester St from Ngaio gorge it is a short but steep walk!','There is a bus stop on Ngaio gorge road not far from Cameron Road - it a short walk up Cameron St and Winchester St to the start of the bridleway.','Don\'t attempt to park up Winchester St, park down on Cameron Road or Ngaio Gorge Road.','0.086',7,0,48,55,'','','2009-08-01 19:59:37',122,'-41.256549','174.794991',16,1,1,2,122,'2009-08-03 21:03:33','calc',5),(393,'Hervey Way',33,'','Shortcut from Hervey Way (new subdivision) to Kaiwharawhara via sports ground','This is a rough shortcut through the bush above the sports grounds next to Rangiora Av.  It is a well worn track through the trees, and the footpath at the end of Hervey Way suggests that the path may be more fully developed in the future.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom Hervey Way, continue right to the end of the footpath on the right, the track continues into the trees from the end of the footpath.\r\nFrom the sports ground, the track is marked with a pink dot on a tree at the bottom left of the sports grounds at the top of the steps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt used to be possible to walk up through the trees behind the sports ground and join up with the [[track:391]] but the new subdivision has changed access.  New tracks may be created in the future.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bush above the sports grounds was one of the places where Robert Jones (\"bucket man\" - a well known vagrant to Wellington) slept in a tent prior to his death in 2003.','There is a bus stop on Hutt Road near Rangiora Avenue.','Hershey Way is a new subdivision, building in the area may change access.  The sports grounds are 