l reserve.  There is a large grassy area for walking the dogs, and a track through the bush through a small gully and across a tiny stream.  The track through the bush isn\'t well marked - looks like it has been created by the residents rather than a council project.  If you start the track from Makererua Street the track is easy to follow.\r\n[[para]]\r\nStart of track at base of Heke St steps at end of Makererua Street\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2562/3821803793_91d80e6fa6.jpg:Heke St steps:326:490]]','At the end of Makererua Street there are some steps leading up to Heke St (which is near the intersection with Huntleigh Park Way).  The track leads off to the right from the base of the steps.  From the grassy area of Orleans Reserve there are access ways into the bush in several areas.','The track isn\'t well marked through the bush.','0.242',8,NULL,133,141,'','','2009-08-15 17:32:19',122,'-41.250193','174.767976',16,3,2,1,122,'2009-08-15 17:36:45','calc',5),(551,'SUGGESTED LOOPS',106,' Some tracks are dual use','A series of four loops for the slightly more advanced rider that offers a good mix of the tracks, along with some good excersize.\r\nThis is offered as a suggestion, as it is a favorite set of loops the writer rides with mates on a regular basis.\r\n','{Loop 1}....\r\n[[para]]\r\nRide all the way up the Main Codgers Track to the Pipeline.\r\nLeft into the Pipeline and along to the clearing.\r\nRight up Jacks Track to the top of Firball.\r\nDown Firball back to the clearing.\r\nDown the Drain to Summit Road.\r\nUp Summit Road to Pipalini.\r\nAll the way down Pipalini to the very bottom.\r\n[[para]]\r\n{Loop 2}....\r\n[[para]]\r\nUp Andrews kink.\r\nUp Codgers to Pipeline.\r\nAlong Pipeline to Clearing.\r\nDown Drain.\r\nDown Pig to intersection with Snout.\r\nUp snout to summit.\r\nHard right down Guts back to Pig.\r\nDown Pig to Tusk.\r\nDown Tusk to DC.\r\nDown DC to bottom.\r\n[[para]]\r\n{Loop 3}....\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong Lower Road to Summit road.\r\nUp Summit Road to Crux.\r\nAlong Codgers to Pipeline.\r\nAlong Pipeline to Clearing.\r\nDown start of Upper Fern Loop.\r\nInto Lower Fern loop to bottom.\r\nAcross summit road into Guts.\r\nAlong to snout then left down to Crux.\r\nAll the way down DC to Bottom.\r\n[[para]]\r\n{Loop 4}....\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong Lower Road to Summit Road.\r\nUp Summit Road to Crux.\r\nUp Codgers to Tantragee road.\r\nDown Tantragee Road to start of Gully track.\r\nDown Gully Track.\r\nDown Willow.\r\nBack home along Betsy Eyre.\r\n','','','14.263',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' ','2009-08-15 18:58:40',135,'-41.290677','173.301635',15,4,3,1,135,'2010-01-13 10:11:09','calc',5),(552,'Korokoro Dam',11,'','Pleasant, though fairly demanding, bush walk in the valley feeding the Korokoro dam up to the [[track:100]] track. Walking only.','This track wanders along the bush-clad valley the feeds the Korokoro dam. There are lots of steps and steep sections, hence this is one of the few tracks in the [[area:11]] that is closed to bikes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nGiven that the Korokoro Valley is the main catchment for the dam, it isn\'t surprising that there are several creek crossings along the way. Some, though not all, creek crossings are bridged â€“ one crossing in particular has a newly constructed foot bridge.  Just north of the halfway point there is a section of track that coincides with a creek for a few metres, so expect to get wet and muddy feet after rain.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track has a moderate gradient. But towards the northern end you\'ll encounter a series of steps and steep switchbacks at the head of the valley. Much of the track in this area has a gradient of 40%+, making for an energetic climb or a somewhat tentative descent.  Some of the slopes are so steep that they are difficult to walk down without slipping, even though they have a firm gravel surface.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.4km from the top you\'ll emerge from the bush into more open farm land. The track\'s gradient becomes somewhat flatter, though continues to climb up to meet the [[track:100]] track.','Southern end heads up the Korokoro Valley above the dam â€“ past the \"No cyclists\" sign and wooden barrier.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end branches off [[track:100]], about 0.8km up from its Stratton Street end.','','2.040',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-16 09:21:42',23,'-41.192122','174.881401',15,3,2,1,23,'2009-08-16 11:51:47','calc',5),(553,'Oakleigh East',11,'','Nice bush-clad stroll from Oakleight Street down into the Korokoro valley. Walking only.','From the Oakleigh Street car park this is initially a smooth, wide, and nearly flat track. However, it soon starts dropping down into the Korokoro Valley, getting progressively steeper as it descends. There is a short climb as you near the bottom, followed by the steepest section where the track turns into a series of steep and somewhat roughly hewn steps.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe valley itself is a pleasant setting, complete with gentle streams, mature bush, and plenty of birds for company. It\'s easy to forget that the valley is just a short distance from densely populated Lower Hutt.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom of the valley you\'ll meet the [[track:552]] track. Turning left and wandering (mostly) down the valley will take you to the Korokoro dam after about 0.5km.  Turning right, up the valley, is a fairly demanding climb up to the head of the valley â€“ and then beyond to the [[track:100]] track.','Southern end is on the eastern side of the Oakleigh Street car park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end meets [[track:552]] near the bottom of the Korokoro Valley.','','1.174',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-16 09:37:25',23,'-41.198516','174.878054',16,3,2,1,23,'2009-08-16 11:52:36','calc',5),(554,'Huntleigh Park Way',33,'','Wide tracks through shady native bush','There are a number of wide, well formed tracks through the Huntleigh Park park bush area above the Guide hall in Silverstream Road.  I have only mapped one possible track down, there are a number of tracks but most end up in the same place at the bottom.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2650/3822610302_e470ca3055.jpg:Huntleigh Park Way:490:426]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nI begin the description from the small entrance near 28 Huntleigh Park Avenue.  This is a small no-exit road in the suburbs of Ngaio.  The track is well maintained with proper bridges and steps. About 100 metres into the bush there is a track going uphill to the right.  This exits the bush via a stile (see also the [[track:555]] track) and continues up to Crows Nest.  Continue left/downhill. The track zig-zags a little, but eventually emerges near a small stream near the Girl Guides Huntleigh buildings on Silverstream Road beside an adventure play area.','Walking from Ngaio to Huntleigh Park way, or from the back of Silverstream play area.','Bicycles not permitted.','0.687',NULL,84,179,95,'','','2009-08-16 12:35:48',122,'-41.249629','174.763405',16,2,2,1,122,'2009-08-16 13:10:55','calc',5),(555,'Bulldozer',33,'','Extreme bush-bashing for adventurers only (GPS needed)','There is an easy track leading up from the end of Silverstream road towards the hills, the [[track:32]] track being visible on the hills above.  The track is rough, with gorse on each side, and wet in places after rain.  It seems to be used for bulldozer access to the new subdivisions on the hills in Crofton Downs.  The walk up to the bulldozers is easy, and used by people walking dogs.  The walk so far is fine, and a return along the same track is the way for most walkers.  (I have bush-bashed up to the Skyline track from this point by the bulldozers.  There is a ridge that can be followed, but it is tough going).\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3543/3821803879_3ec6a69287.jpg:Bulldozer:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 600 metres up the track past the old bulldozer in the gorse a track leads up to the right.  This is not a maintained track, but is used by possum baiters and adventurers.  It leads up eventually to the top of the hill overlooking Huntleigh Park way, and there is a good track from the top of the hill up to Crows Nest.  Getting to the top of the hill is not easy.  There are brambles, nettles, gorse and barberry.  There are pink markers in places used by possum baiters, but the track gets lost towards the top of the hill, so make sure you have a GPS with the track or waypoints marked in it.  It is tough, the gorse is high, it will be painful and blood may flow!  Don\'t attempt this track unless you are properly equipped and confident.  The uphill track is fairly easy to begin with, a grassy track amongst the bushes.  As you get higher the gorse is thicker and track harder to distinguish - head for 174.760852,-41.248494 on the GPS, which will bring you to a flat grassy lookout/resting point.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2455/3822610420_cc8ff43d72.jpg:Midway point:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nGood views over Crofton Downs and across to the [[track:32]] walkway.  There is a reasonable track from here further up through more gorse to join with the main track down from Crows Nest at 174.761447,-41.247795.  From here you can go up to [[track:728]], veer left downhill through well defined tracks planned for new subdivisions (exit to Hunleigh Park Way or Heke St), or down right into Huntleigh Park Way bush area - the entrance is over a stile.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2632/3822610498_80333f0361.jpg:Stile:326:490]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough it is possible to do a round trip from Huntleigh Park way, once again I emphasize that this is a very tough walk and only for the experienced tramper who doesn\'t mind pushing through gorse.','End of Silverstream Road, or from Huntleigh Park Way bush.','Should only be attempted by experienced trampers.  Make sure you have a GPS for navigation.','1.617',176,107,103,172,'','','2009-08-16 13:02:18',122,'-41.247805','174.765573',15,5,2,1,122,'2009-12-25 17:12:13','calc',5),(556,'Gilberd Bush',14,'','Gentle Newlands bush track with views to Wellington harbour.','There are well marked entrances to this relatively new and well maintained track in Newlands from Bayswater Place, Fernhaven Grove and Ladbrooke Drive.  The track is wide and mountain bikes are allowed.  The track is slightly below the road set at the top of the bush with some good views of Wellington harbour.  Beginning from Ladbooke Drive (the highest point) the track zig-zags downhill and then follows the hill round with an exit to Bayswater Place after about 500 metres.  Ferhaven Grove is another 500 metres, with a seat and lookout point slightly further downhill from the exit to Fernhaven Grove.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2597/3821804069_45d2878b46.jpg:Ladbrooke Drive entrance:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nView from Fernhaven Knoll\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3452/3822610588_77ba42cac4.jpg:Fernhaven Knoll:490:326]]\r\n','Well marked entrances in Newlands from Ladbrooke Drive, Bayswater Place and Fernhaven Grove.','','1.262',NULL,55,235,180,'','','2009-08-16 13:25:20',23,'-41.223367','174.832939',16,2,1,2,122,'2010-01-25 12:57:55','calc',5),(557,'Redwood Bush',14,'','Pleasant stroll through shady Tawa bush','This is a short, shady walk through Tawa bush-clad hillsides.  Signpost entrances on Brasenose Place, Achilles Close and Peterhouse St.  Starting from the Brasenose play area, the track leads off to the right.  It is a little uneven in places with tree roots on the track, but is otherwise well maintained with wooden bridges and steps.  Archilles Close is about mid-way along (0.5 km), and Peterhouse St exit a further 0.5 km.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2634/3822610740_dfb3a9cdd0.jpg:Redwood Bush:490:326]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 120 metres up the track from Brasenose Place, the main track goes right through the bush.  Another track continue uphill, eventually reaching the [[track:558]].  This is quite a trek uphill and not well marked near the top, but affords some good views of Tawa and Churton Park.','From Brasenose Place, Achilles Close or Peterhouse St in Tawa.','Bicycles not allowed','1.056',18,46,95,75,'','','2009-08-16 13:36:01',122,'-41.178509','174.811127',16,1,2,1,122,'2009-08-16 13:49:03','calc',5),(558,'Airstrip',14,'','Well used but unmarked track from Redwood to near Churton Park airstrip','About 120 metres up the track from Brasenose Place on the [[track:557]] track is a junction.  Continue uphill, across a small style about 150 metres further up (at this point there is also a well formed track that follows the bush-line right - see [[track:729]].  It parallels the [[track:557]] track but higher up the hill, and is for pest management (ie possum trapping).\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you continue up-hill you rise above the bushline and follow the fenceline around to the right with good views over Tawa and Churton Park.  The track climbs uphill to the pine plantation, and through the forest to the top of the hill.  The airstrip is on private land on the other side of the fence to the left.  As you emerge from the forest there is a gate at the top of the hill, and about 50 metres past the gate is a small geodetic survey marker on the hill, which is shown by the short track leading to a dead end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can continue downhill and join up with the [[track:168]] track.  There is well formed route.  From the gate at the top of the hill, the easiest way is to cross the fence and follow the fence-line on the right down past the pine plantation.  There is another fence to cross, and continue following the fenceline beside the pine plantation until your reach the more mature Spicer Forest.  There are two white signs (relating to possum poison) on the fence.  When you cross this fence you will see the well formed track heading through the pine trees, which joins up with the main Spicer Forest track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView from the fenceline\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2694/4229889771_01135cff95.jpg:Fenceline above Tawa:480:320]]','Track from Redwood Bush at the end of Brasenose Place in Tawa.','This track used primarily by possum trappers and is not properly marked so I recommend taking your GPS the first time you attempt it.','1.419',139,NULL,139,278,'','','2009-08-16 13:48:05',122,'-41.176102','174.813552',15,3,2,1,122,'2010-01-23 23:30:19','calc',5),(559,'5km Extension',103,'','Extend your McLeans Island ride with this new 5km section of singletrack','Opened in August \'09 this is a new track through new pine plantings. Like the 10km track, this is fast and winding with well bermed corners and trees, plus has the added advantage of several lumps (for jumping?) and a fun zig-zag section between sand piles.','Entrance and exit is about 8.5km from the start of the 10km loop. You come out of the forest into a new planting area, past the rock garden, then emerge at the waterhole before plunging back into the forest. Hang left instead of right and follow the track into the trees and then out into the open again. It will curve around (anti-clockwise) and you will exit at the waterhole again. This time, hang right to get back onto the track and home again.','There are some \'jumps\' (lumps) but it\'s not a BMX track, and they are easily ridden over while seated, or put in a bit of power and get a bit of air if you still have strength in them at this point.','5.000',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-16 14:33:15',1,'-43.454757','172.482519',15,1,3,1,137,'2009-09-11 16:40:52','user',5),(560,'Haywards',11,'','Convoluted pylon access route between [[track:106]] and the [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Haywards_Electrical_Substation.jpg Haywards substation]].','This is a pylon access road that provides an interesting, though challenging, connection between the [[track:106]] loop and the Haywards substation.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe climb in either direction is steep, though there\'s much more altitude to gain if travelling from east to west as much of the climb at the western end has already been incorporated into the [[track:106]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several side tracks, which are just short accessways to adjacent pylons (of which there are three separate lines).  Most of the diversions are easy to ignore. However, if travelling from west to east you\'ll encounter a fork in the road where it is less obvious which way to go:\r\n[[bullet:The right-hand fork descends steeply to a dead-end. It is just a pylon accessway and best avoided as the climb back up is very steep (ie. up to 25% gradient).]]\r\n[[bullet:The left-hand fork also descends steeply, and looks directly at another pylon 150m away â€“ go down that fork.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter continuing to descend steeply for a while, the track rolls along for almost a kilometre before the final descent to Haywards Hill Road.','Western end branches off [[track:106]] next to a pylon. If travelling around [[track:106]] in a clockwise direction, then look for the [[italic:second]] pylon next to the road and follow the obvious track that initially heads north.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end is on Haywards Hill Road (State Highway 58), directly opposite the Haywards substation. There\'s a nicely groomed section of gravel road that briefly runs parallel to the highway, climbing up a few metres to a steel barrier gate.','','3.717',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-16 19:02:24',23,'-41.149674','174.971867',15,4,1,3,23,'2009-08-16 19:44:26','calc',5),(561,'Bolton Memorial Park',41,'','Direct route from Botanic Gardens to city','In addition to being a stroll past historic sites, starting from the Seddon memorial, past the Robertson\'s Cottage site and graves of notable people from the past, and finally over the Dennis McGrath Bridge to the walkway close to The Terrace - this is the most direct route from Tinakori Road to Wellington city.','Buses stop on Tinakori Road near the main entrance to the Botanic Gardens.  From Bowen Street, walk up the street and take the steps on the left beside the last multi-storey building before the footpath runs out.  Dennis McGrath bridge is behind this building (MED).','Bicycles not permitted','0.739',NULL,26,64,38,'','','2009-08-16 19:54:35',122,'-41.279677','174.773984',15,1,2,5,122,'2009-08-16 20:38:25','calc',5),(562,'Clifton Terrace',41,'','Access to Clifton Terrace carpark from north side of motorway','This is an alternate route from the Botanic Gardens down to Clifton Terrace carpark and The Terrace.  From Seddon Memorial in the botanic gardens, head right down Kinross Street, cross over Bolton Street and about 100 metres down the street just before the bridge take the track on the right which leads along the side of the motorway.  About 100 metres along the track there is a junction - you can go either way.  On the upper route there is the option of exiting to Clifton Terrace.  On the lower route you can take the [[track:472]].\r\nAbout 400 metres along the track there is another exit to Clifton Terrace.  If you continue another 75 metres or so you come to the Clifton Terrace Cable Car stop, and the Clifton Terrace carpark.  50 metres further on you can exit on The Terrace beside the motorway off-ramp.  The hotel opposite has a lift that you can take down to Lambton Quay and Cable Car Lane.','Numerous entry and exit points from Clifton Terrace and Bolton Street (note that there is no access from Aurora Terrace), Clifton Terrace carpark, and The Terrace.','Bicycles are not prohibited, but difficult because there are many steps.','0.834',NULL,35,55,20,'','','2009-08-16 20:08:37',122,'-41.282273','174.774714',16,1,1,2,122,'2009-08-16 20:09:54','calc',5),(563,'Clifton Tce lower',41,'','Alternative lower route on Clifton Terrace','Alternative route on [[track:562]] which you should take for access to [[track:472]].','Clifton Terrace or from Clifton Terrace carpark Woodward Street entrance.','','0.175',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-16 20:13:29',122,'-41.282628','174.772718',16,1,1,2,122,'2009-08-16 20:38:02','calc',5),(564,'Thorndon trail',41,'','Heritage trail walk beside the motorway from Thorndon Quay to Bowen Street','From Bowen Street walk through the carpark beside the government buildings and take the steps at the back of the carpark where the signpost says \"Hill St\".  From there you follow the path with the motorway on one side and large mostly government buildings on the other side.  There are several roads to cross.  At Hawkestone St it pays to walk down the road a short distance to cross the other side of the motorway off-ramp (the majority of cars seem to turn right to go in to Thorndon rather than the city).  Continue along was a small park on the right near Fitzherbert Terrace, under Hobson Street, and finally emerge on Thorndon Quay underneath the motorway.  If you wish to do a return trip, you can join Tinakori Road about 100 metres north up Thorndon Quay.  Katherine Mansfield birthplace is a short distance up Tinakori Road from this junction.','You can join from Bowen St, Hill St, Hawkestone St, May St, Hobson St or Thorndon Quay near Tinakori Road junction.','Bicycles are not prohibited, but note there are steps in many places','1.106',15,37,30,8,'','','2009-08-16 20:29:25',122,'-41.282193','174.775314',14,1,1,2,122,'2009-08-16 20:32:35','calc',5),(565,'Waterfall Track',11,'','Walking track up to a waterfall in a narrow gorge. The walk involves many unbridged creek crossings and clambering over boulders.','This is a wet and rocky walking track up the narrow Dry Creek valley. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is initially smooth and firm, but soon degenerates into a rough bush track. Along the way you\'ll cross the creek about 20 times, including a couple of sections where the track coincides with the creek bed, so expect to get wet feet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you near the end of the track, the valley narrows even more. Eventually the valley turns into a steep-sided ravine, at the head of which is the waterfall after which the track is named. Approaching the waterfall itself involves scrambling over large boulders and leaping over deep pools.','Wander up the valley from the Dry Creek car park. The start of the track is a bit past the (closed) flying fox.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is a deadend, so return the same way.','','0.828',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-24 20:47:19',23,'-41.155555','174.963884',15,4,2,1,23,'2009-09-01 19:54:41','calc',5),(566,'Stream Walk',11,'','Gentle stroll along one of the Korokoro Stream\'s tributaries.','This is a short and very gentle stroll alongside a small stream. The track surface is firm and smooth, while the surrounding bush is pleasant.','Southern end is next to the wool shed.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is in a small clearing, at the southern end of [[track:567]] and opposite the bottom of [[track:102]]\'s steep drop to cross the creek.','','0.280',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-24 20:54:05',23,'-41.176752','174.890960',17,1,2,1,23,'2009-09-01 20:30:32','calc',5),(567,'Upper Stream',11,'','Trek up a narrow valley from the end of Stratton Street, then up a steep climb to meet [[track:143]].','From the southeastern end, wander up the valley along a track that is faintly defined in places.  The track surface is mostly grass, with several unbridged creek crossings along the way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you head up the valley the track gets slowly steeper, and the valley gets progressively narrower. Just as the valley starts to narrow dramatically, the track turns sharply left up a steep hill. The turnoff isn\'t all that obvious â€“ if you see a farm fence crossing the stream ahead, then you\'ve gone too far. Turn back and look for a track that goes straight up a small crease in the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFollow the track up to a saddle point, after which the gradient mellows for the final section to join [[track:143]].','Southeastern end is at the northern end of [[track:566]], at the bottom of [[track:102]]\'s steep drop to cross the creek. Veer around the hill to the left, following the creek upstream.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthwestern end meets [[track:143]] part way down.','','1.324',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-08-24 20:57:12',23,'-41.172662','174.888203',16,3,1,1,23,'2009-09-01 20:47:02','calc',5),(568,'Powles Path',41,'','Historic walk from Seddon Memorial to Bolton St','A historic walk through Bolton memorial cemetery, and also an access way from the Botanic Gardens to Bolton St.','Seddon memorial is a short walk from Lady Norwood rose garden in the Botanic gardens - head north-east along the side of the playing fields (Anderson park).  Easdale St is the first right on Bolton St after the bridge over the motorway, when heading up from The Terrace.','Bicycles not allowed in Bolton St cemetery area.','0.233',18,28,53,43,'','','2009-08-29 22:29:30',122,'-41.280129','174.773405',16,1,2,2,122,'2009-08-29 22:30:09','calc',5),(569,'City to Sea',41,'  (cycling is okay in parts)','13 km walk from Central Wellington to Island Bay on the south coast','This is a long but very interesting walk through parks and reserves from the centre of Wellington to the south coast.  The city council produce a good brochure with a map and information, and suggest 6 hours to do the full walk (3.5 to 4 hours typical).  You can walk it in sections and many variations are possible.  The route shown deviates slightly from the official track in the Hutchison Road to McAlistair Park area, but this does not matter as many variations are possible depending on how much time you have.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe walk begins in Bolton St cemetery near the chapel (Mowbray St / Bolton St corner).  There is information, a map, and look for the City-to-Sea signs and orange arrows along the route.\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3515/3867107114_1a82587bb4.jpg:City-to-Sea:475:449]]\r\nThe path crosses the motorway using Denis McGrath bridge.  Many routes are possible in the botanic gardens, but end up at the cable car.  From there you descend via steps in Rawhiti Terrace to Kelburn Park.  I recommend a short diversion through the [[track:514]] route.\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2540/3867107134_62a15a492e_m.jpg:Cable Car:475:316]]\r\nFollow the route past the University and Boyd Wilson Field, through Aro Park, up Epuni St and Tanera Park to Central Park.  Central Park has recently been upgraded and is now a very pleasant walk.  Several routes through the park are possible but the City-to-Sea walkway is now well marked -  you need to emerge and cross Brooklyn Road opposite Bidwell St.  This takes you in to Prince of Wales Park.  The official route emerges onto Hutchison Road and then in to MacAlister Park.  The route I have plotted emerges on to Connaught Terrace in Vogeltown; it is then a short walk down to the dairy on the corner of Short St/Liardet St, and the official route is picked up again by walking down Finnimore Tce towards the water tank (inside the hill) and in to MacAlistair Park.  The route emerges from MacAlistair Park, crosses Liardet/Britomart St and skirts round the side of Berhampore Golf course.  There may be some muddy patches around here, and the track up from the golf course to Tawatawa Ridge is the steepest part of the walk (seats have been thoughtfully placed along the route).\r\n[[para]]\r\nView from Tawatawa Ridge towards Island Bay\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2666/3866323401_1b88e16f82.jpg:Tawatawa Ridge:475:316]]\r\nThe route through the reserve along Tawatawa Ridge has the best views on the walk.  It is exposed and will be tough going on a windy day, but the views are wonderful.  Look out for the goats in adjacent fields (city council weed control).  The track continues down Frobisher St past the Buddhist Stupa (look out for the gold dome on the left) and in to Oku Street reserve which is undergoing upgrades and tree planting.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOku Reserve trig\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2535/3866323429_b0d08ac097.jpg:Oku Reserve trig:475:316]]\r\nFrom Oku reserve the track descends to Island Bay via Shorland Street.  There is a bus stop at the end of the Parade near Shorland Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAllow 4 - 6 hours for walking the entire route, and note there is considerable up and down probably amounting to around 500 metres climb from end-to-end.','Bolton memorial park is just off The Terrace, a short walk from Wellington railway station and Lambton Quay.  You can park a car on Glenmore St opposite the Botanic Gardens all day at the weekend (City Coupon parking zone during the week).  Island Bay is well served by buses, the walk terminating at the bus stop at the end of the The Parade in Island Bay.','Bicycles are not prohibited in most places along the route, but it is most suitable for walkers (there are steps and bush areas through which cycling would be difficult).','13.341',173,170,8,5,'','','2009-08-29 22:38:14',122,'-41.296381','174.789047',12,2,2,1,122,'2010-01-09 20:20:58','calc',5),(570,'Kapakapanui',28,'','Tough day walk on the edge of the Tararuas','This is a tough 6 - 7 hour circular walk into the Tararuas.  There are excellent views of the Tararua peaks on a clear day (which isn\'t very often).  At the start of the route there are some small streams to cross and you will get your feet wet.  Most people do the walk clockwise, but you can go either way.  There is a hut mid-way up when going clockwise.  It is only at the top that you get a view of the Tararuas, otherwise you are walking in native bush.  There are some very steep parts going up and down.  This walk is for experienced trampers.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView of Mt Hector and Tararua Peaks from Kapakapanui Trig\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3027/3867452870_407fac451b.jpg:Kapakapanui:480:320]]','At Waikanae turn at the traffic lights over the railway and head inland for about 5 km to Reikorangi.  Take the turn-off here to the left and go past the Reikorangi cafe/farm.  This is Ngatiawa Road, and you follow this road right to the end (do not turn off on [[track:382]] South Road).  There is a small carpark at the end of the road.','There may be snow at the top in winter, so be prepared.','11.139',948,948,141,1089,'','','2009-08-29 23:15:45',122,'-40.921685','175.143700',14,4,2,1,122,'2009-08-29 23:28:45','calc',5),(571,'Albermarle',41,'  (possible on bicycle)','Short bush walk beside Kaiwharawhara stream','Part of the Kaiwharawhara stream restoration project, there is a short easy bush walk between Cardinal McKeefry school and the Kindergarten mid-way up Albermarle Road.  The track is well marked, and although there is a city council Kaiwharawhara stream project sign at the bottom, it is otherwise unmarked.  Local residents are still planting trees in the area.','From Ian Galloway park cross the road on the pedestrian crossing opposite Cardinal McKeefry school.  The entrance is just past the school at the bottom of Albermarle Road.','Bicycles are not excluded (there aren\'t any signs \"yet\") and could navigate most of the track - there are just a few steps in the middle.','0.219',30,NULL,120,150,'','','2009-08-30 13:55:34',122,'-41.276605','174.759833',17,2,2,1,122,'2010-01-19 21:39:08','calc',5),(572,'Otari Wilton Bush',7,'','Sanctuary to Sea route through Otari Wilton bush to Karori Cemetery','This route is part of the new Sanctuary-to-Sea route.  It is a wide and flat track from the carpark off Churchill Drive (near Wilton House, popular for wedding receptions)to the entrance to Karori Cemetery on Seaforth Terrace.  The Sanctuary-to-Sea route links to [[track:389]] and to Karori Sanctuary (see [[track:25]]) and the council should complete the route by the end of 2009.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the carpark off Churchill Drive the main picnic area is about 1 km away, where there are toilets, barbecue area, and several trails leading up into the bush.  Continue for another 800 metres following the stream, where there is an exit to Ian Galloway park.  Continue over a bridge and a short climb up to Karori Cemetery.  The Sanctuary-to-Sea route is well marked, along with the SS Penguin and other trails around the cemetery.','There are carparks at Churchill Drive and on Wilton Road for Otari Wilton bush.  Karori Cemetery is a short walk off Karori Road which is well served by buses.  You can drive in to Karori Cemetery at times, but note that the gates do close at sunset.','','2.201',81,NULL,60,141,'','','2009-08-30 14:15:36',122,'-41.270356','174.750295',15,2,2,2,122,'2009-08-30 14:38:23','calc',5),(573,'Karori Cemetery',7,'','Short walk through the middle of Karori cemetery','Karori cemetery is large and there are many pleasant walks between the gravestones.  This route links Seaforth Tce to the bush walks at the back.','There are several entrances to Karori cemetery a short walk from Karori Road which is well served by buses.  ','','1.069',8,NULL,143,151,'','','2009-08-30 14:22:41',122,'-41.271549','174.755402',15,1,1,5,122,'2009-08-30 14:23:32','calc',5),(574,'Blue and Yellow trails',7,'','Follows the Blue and Yellow lower trails in Otari-Wilton bush','These are well formed routes with steps in places, but can be a bit muddy in winter.  Quite popular with runners.  The Blue and Yellow trails lead off the main [[track:572]] track that follows the stream.  These are the lower tracks - the upper tracks are more interesting, include the 800 year old Rimu trees.\r\n[[para]]\r\nStarting from the back of Karori Cemetery the track descends a short distance into the bush, and there is a fork with a track leading up to Johnston Hill.  Continue right over a short steep area with some steps.  Along the blue trail there is a track leading left up the hill for a loop which includes the 800 year old Rimu trees.  This joins back to the lower track near the bridge over the stream at the picnic area.  The lower yellow route begins here, and there is also an upper yellow route.  The lower yellow route joins the main track at the bridge north of the picnic area.','A good access point in the main picnic area below the carpark on Wilton road.  There is an entrance at the back of Karori Cemetery.','Not suitable for bicycles.','1.475',NULL,74,151,77,'','','2009-08-30 14:31:53',122,'-41.271678','174.755788',15,3,2,1,122,'2009-08-30 14:36:57','calc',5),(575,'Featherston Domain',107,'','Walk along the shore of Lake Wairarapa','Featherston Domain is a few km south of Featherston, on the shore of Lake Wairarapa.  It is suitable for walkers, dogs, bicycles, boats, and some 4WD vehicles.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom of South Soldiers Settlement Road there is parking on the right beside the yacht club buildings.  There is a wide 4WD dirt track that heads east along the northern end of the lake.  It terminates at a stream outlet into the lake about 1.9 km from the start (wetland reserve beyond that point).  Return the same way.  About half way along there is narrow bridge over a stream which restricts the traffic to walkers and cyclists from that point on.','From Featherston take highway 53 east towards Martinborough, then turn right into either Murphy\'s Line or South Featherston Road (which is just beyond the 100 km sign, and has a signpost for Featherston Domain).  Turn right again into Lake Domain Road, and then left into South Soldiers Settlement Road which terminates at the domain.','','1.945',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-06 20:49:59',122,'-41.163342','175.309010',14,1,1,3,122,'2009-09-06 20:53:06','calc',5),(576,'Carter Scenic Reserve',107,'','Short walk through Kahikatea','This is a pleasant DOC managed walkway on a reserve outside Carterton.  From the carpark there is a short walk and after 200 metres there is a loop walk going left and right.  There is a boardwalk over swampy areas.  Approx halfway round there is a one-way track leading to Ruamahanga River (approx 20 minutes walk each way).  The Kahikatea walk takes about 15 minutes.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3495/3892343210_40e69c02c9.jpg:Carter Scenic Reserve:480:320]]','From Carterton follow Park Road to the end, turn left into Carters Line and right in to Gladstone Road.  The reserve is signposted approx 3 km along Gladstone Road on the right.  There is a carpark about 500 m down the driveway.','Bicycles not allowed.','1.383',0,10,65,65,'','','2009-09-06 21:03:39',122,'-41.062560','175.600877',15,1,2,2,122,'2009-09-06 21:05:32','calc',5),(577,'Kiriwhakapapa',107,'','Historic mill track at the foot of the Tararua Ranges','This is a lovely bush walk with abundant bird life, and is one of the gateways into the Tararuas (track leads up to a hut from the loop track).  It follows an old mill road, and there is a sign showing the site of a tree nursery from the 1930\'s near the Mikimiki Road end.  I recommend starting at the Kiriwhakapapa end as the carpark and picnic area is much better provisioned that Mikimiki Road.  The track is well formed with bridges, and gentle gradients, but can be a bit muddy in places after rain.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMikimiki track entrance\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2527/3892343182_5209ac79ea.jpg:Mikimiki Road end:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf walking, allow 2 hours each way.  If you don\'t have a car at each end you will need to return the same way.','The best carpark is at the end of Kiriwhakapapa Road, which is about 10 km north of Masterton on SH2.  The last few kilometres of the road are gravel, and narrow in places.  There are two carparks in Mikimiki Road, but there is more gravel and the road is narrower.  Kiriwhakapapa Road end has toilets and a large picnic area.','Suitable for mountain bikes, but you will need to carry bikes down steps in a couple of places.  There are 3 or 4 river crossings, and the track can be muddy after rain.','6.115',269,282,291,308,'','','2009-09-06 21:37:49',122,'-40.820175','175.542641',13,3,1,1,122,'2009-09-06 21:53:43','calc',5),(578,'Loop track',107,'','Shorter loop track walk from Kiriwhakapapa car park','A shorter loop track from the Kiriwhakapapa picnic area.  The walk takes 30 - 45 minutes and is less steep.  There is a track leading up into the Tararuas (Blue Range Hut) from the loop track.','From the Kiriwhakapapa carpark, the start of the loop track is just a few metres from the entrance.','','1.217',27,52,323,298,'','','2009-09-06 21:50:31',122,'-40.813290','175.539122',15,1,1,1,122,'2009-09-06 21:52:22','calc',5),(579,'Castlepoint',107,'','Easy stroll to Castlepoint lighthouse','A pleasant walk on a nice day.  Can be very windy at times, and at high tide it can be dangerous crossing the causeway from the carpark.  On fine sunny days the main danger is the many people walking up to enjoy the view!\r\n[[para]]\r\nCastlepoint Lighthouse\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3501/3892343300_00488ea594.jpg:Castlepoint Lighthouse:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe walk takes about 30 minutes.  If you are more energetic consider doing [[track:580]] as well.','Castlepoint is about 60 km (1 hour drive) east of Masterton.  The route is well signposted and the road is sealed all the way.  Tinui is a pleasant place to stop for afternoon tea and crafts.','Bicycles are not welcome nor practical.\r\nThere are steep cliffs so stay on the walkway.','1.251',50,50,1,1,'','','2009-09-06 21:59:43',122,'-40.905080','176.221991',15,1,2,2,122,'2009-09-06 22:08:56','calc',5),(580,'Deliverance Cove',107,' (bicycle ok part of track)','1 hour loop walk south of Castlepoint Lighthouse','A slightly more energetic walk that Castlepoint Lighthouse.  There is a gentle loop walk from the carpark south round the hill above the bay, with an optional loop (which is unsuitable for bicycles) on to the rocky headland offering great views.  This part of the walk is steeper, and there is no handrail at the top so be careful in windy weather (it is a long way down).  The loop track continues back along the beach to the carpark.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView from headland overlooking Deliverance Cove, back to Castlepoint Lighthouse\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3523/3892343272_3db78dc2e4.jpg:Deliverance Cove:480:320]]','From Castlepoint carpark, the start of the walk is signpost just past the church (St Peters by the Sea).  Castlepoint is 60 km east of Masterton.','','3.768',158,158,1,1,'','','2009-09-06 22:07:55',122,'-40.904820','176.222076',15,2,1,1,122,'2009-09-06 22:10:04','calc',5),(581,'Henley Lake',107,'','Stroll round Henley lake and wetland area in Masterton','The track route shown goes round the main take and the river loop out around the wetland area.  There is a bird observation tower in the middle of the wetland area.  There are other side tracks to explore.  The route shown is about 4 km and takes about an hour.  There is a large map and sign at the Te Ore Ore Road entrance.\r\n[[para]]\r\nHenley Lake Te Ore Ore Road entrance\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3526/3892343246_8f9ef2d281.jpg:Henley Lake:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nOn Henley Lake can be found a range of less common bird life, including Scaup, Grey Teal, Mute Swan, Coot, Black Billed Gull and Black Fronted Dotterel in the wetland area.','There are two main carparks, one on Te Ore Ore Road (road to Castlepoint) and one on Colombo Road, north end of Masterton.','(Sorry, bicycles not permitted in Henley Park)','3.883',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-06 22:15:29',122,'-40.951770','175.680227',15,1,2,2,122,'2009-09-06 22:19:09','calc',5),(582,'Honeycomb Rock',107,'','Coastal walk on the east coast of the Wairarapa to view an interesting rock and seals','(Full track description and route to follow - the track shown is approximate only, not from GPS)\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe start of the walk goes across a few fields to bypass the start of Glenburn station, but joins up again with a flat 4WD track out to Honeycomb rock.  There is one stream crossing.  The rock has seals in winter.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nStart of track at Glenburn station\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2660/3895975020_4a7bebb14c.jpg:Start of walk:480:320]]\r\n','Getting there takes almost as long as doing the walk!  From Carterton take the road to Gladstone, and follow Gladstone Road to the Te Wharau junction.  Follow the signs to Glenburn station, passing through Te Wharau settlement on the way.  Glenburn station is about 60 km from Masterton, and the last 20 km of the road is unsealed.  Allow an hour to drive from Masterton. ','Carterton is the nearest place for petrol, food and drink.  There is nothing at Te Wharau or Glenburn/Flat Point.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is closed for lambing in September and October.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNo shooting and no dogs, but mountain bikes okay.','4.112',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-07 20:03:02',122,'-41.322299','175.819530',13,2,1,3,122,'2009-09-07 20:18:36','calc',5),(583,'Petone',17,'','Easy walk or ride beside Petone beach','There is a good flat walking and cycling track from the western side of the harbour near the motorway, extending the length of the Petone beach to Hikoikoi reserve where you can join up with the [[area:12]].  At the western side you can cross the railway (bridge) and highway (carefully - no bridge, underpass, pedestrian crossing or traffic lights unless you go up to Petone station where there is an overpass) and join up with [[track:99]] and the Belmont Regional Park tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe promenade is a popular spot in summer and can get crowded.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3497/3914388549_45e0aa9c35.jpg:Petone beach:480:320]]','Petone railway station is a few hundred metres north of the beach.  You can join or leave the beach at many points along the length.','','4.047',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Flat','','2009-09-13 20:32:26',122,'-41.223859','174.880028',14,1,1,2,122,'2009-09-13 20:41:27','calc',5),(584,'Split Enz',20,'','Arguably the best flowing single track at Whakarewarewa','Beautiful flowing track almost all downhill. Some good views if you stop so I am told (never been able to stop). \r\n\r\n[[link:http://www.riderotorua.co.nz/trails2.php?catid=2&id=56 More info]]','Go up Moerangi Rd from the bottom of Billy T','','3.000',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Grade 3','2009-09-16 21:55:35',59,'-38.200418','176.300976',15,3,1,1,59,'2009-09-20 19:59:43','user',5),(585,'Pondy',20,'','This combines what officially are Pondy-Downhill, Pondy-New and the tail end of roller coaster. These all connect with out interruption.','Yet more flowing single track. A couple of bridges that are fine as long as you don\'t look down. Short descents followed by short climbs in the rollercoaster section.','','','3.107',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','3','2009-09-17 20:31:24',59,'-38.192121','176.295204',14,3,1,1,59,'2009-09-18 09:12:08','calc',5),(586,'Little Red Riding Huck',20,'','Flowing track with lots of medium sized jumps. All can be rolled over. ','This is a continuation of Huckleberry Hound (to be added). There are about 40 jumping opportunities along this track. Crosses \"corners\" track several times on route. Ends at the pump track.','','','1.438',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','3','2009-09-17 20:53:22',59,'-38.182204','176.299732',15,3,1,1,59,'2009-12-17 20:34:23','calc',5),(587,'Botanic Garden',41,'','Stroll round the perimeter of the botanic gardens','There are many paths through the Wellington botanic gardens (see [[track:693]], [[track:694]], [[track:692]], [[track:691]]), along with sculptures, cable cars, rose gardens, tea houses, Carter observatory, Treehouse visitor centre and other attractions.  This particular route goes around the perimeter of the gardens starting from the Boundary entrance at the southern end.  There are many other entrances - the main one is off Glenmore Street not far from Bowen Street corner.  The other main entrances are on Salamanca Road, and at the end of Upland Road where the cable car terminates.','From the city walk up Bowen Street or Bolton Street, or take the [[link:http://www.wellingtoncablecar.co.nz/ cable car]] from Lambton Quay.','Bicycles not allowed in the gardens, which can be very crowded on sunny weekends.','2.568',69,69,97,97,'','','2009-09-19 22:25:29',122,'-41.282709','174.765937',16,1,2,2,122,'2009-11-28 21:42:01','calc',5),(588,'Edmund Lomas Park',12,'','East bank: Spur from Birchville Bridge alongside the Hutt River, from Birchville Bridge to the Edmund Lomas Park.','This is a mostly gentle cruise alongside the Hutt River. There is one more difficult section where the track dips down into a small gully, involving a steep climb (in both directions) and tight corners with sharp drop off the side.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt one point, just east of the small gully, the track appears to pass through the back yard of a house.  Just head straight for the [[area:12]] sign on the opposite side of the lawn and you should be OK.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPart of the track is a firm gravel path, though with a series of poorly designed sharp drains making things a little awkward. The rest of the track is dirt and/or grass, suggesting that it isn\'t quite finished yet (as at September 2009).\r\n[[para]]\r\nNext section of the [[area:12]]:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:126]] on the opposite bank]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:125]] to the south]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:127]] to the southwest across the bridge]]','Western end is at the Birchville Bridge â€“ head along the gravel driveway then veer off along the singletrack.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end is on Edmund Lomas Grove, after passing through Edmund Lomas Park.','','0.826',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-20 09:11:31',23,'-41.090689','175.102715',16,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-01 14:26:35','calc',5),(589,'Foxton Beach',108,'','Easy cycling trail from Foxton township to Foxton Beach following a proper cycling track.','This track begins beside the Primary School (corner of Duncan St in Foxton) just off SH1.  It is a straight walk or ride down to Foxton Beach and along the sea-front to the trees near the camping ground.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFoxton Beach is well known for water activities, and is also one of the best spots in NZ for observing migratory wading birds.  There is a viewing platform along the promenade and expect to see a few keen enthusiasts with binoculars or telescope.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe main cycleway follows the highway (80 km/hr area) for about 2 km between Foxton and Foxton Beach, but is well off the road so is quite safe for young rider.\r\n[[para]]\r\nStarting from the pine trees near the motor camp in Foxton beach, there is a fairly new well defined track along the promenade and past the wharf and boat club.  You then go through a small playground, then turn right and head up the footpath for about 750 metres for the start of the cycle track proper.  This terminates at Foxton Beach Road turns into Lady\'s Mile at Foxton township.  Go right and visit the windmill.  For variation on return, approx. midway between Foxton and Foxton Beach there is fork in the road to the right - if you head down Palmer Road you will enter Foxton Beach at the back of the town.  Turn left along Nash Parade and you will end up back at the pine trees near the camping ground.  Note that this alternative route is along the road so take care as there are lots of fast moving 4WD vehicles.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2434/3936822536_1c910bd6e9.jpg:Foxton Beach:480:320]]','By car - either park just off the main street (eg near the old Woolpack factory on Duncan St) in Foxton and ride down Ladys Mile/Foxton Beach Road.  Or park beside the trees on Pinewood Road near the motor camp near the birdwatching information sign.','','5.586',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-20 20:57:01',122,'-40.466017','175.250473',13,2,1,1,122,'2009-09-20 21:04:34','calc',5),(590,'Otaki River',28,'','Flat riverbank walk from Otaki bridge to the sea','There is a large carpark immediately on the left as you cross the Otaki bridge (heading north) beside the quarry entrance, and from here the Highway-to-Sea walkway is signpost.  It skirts the quarry, and there are numerous warning signs about avoiding heavy vehicles and rock crushing equipment.  The track is always open, but best to do it after noon on Saturday or on Sunday (when no equipment is operating).  There are several possible routes - the green triangles follow the top of the stopbank, but there is a wide metal road on the inland side, and rougher tracks on the river side so some variety is possible if making a return trip (watch for vehicles on the gravel road).  There is a carpark near the Otaki rivermouth off Kapiti Lane at Otaki Beach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe walkway sign says 2 hours return walk.  Allow 30 - 45 minutes if cycling.  You may also want to check out the [[track:591]] walk.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2493/3936042431_3367ee8391.jpg:Otaki river walk:320:480]]','By car to Otaki.','','3.675',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-20 21:14:14',122,'-40.755710','175.138378',13,2,1,3,122,'2009-09-21 20:00:22','calc',5),(591,'Chrystalls Bend',28,'','Inland riverbank walk from Otaki bridge with pleasant picnic spot at end','Park in the same carpark as for the [[track:590]] walk beside the quarry on the left as you cross the bridge going north.  However, the Chrystalls Bend walk follows the riverbank inland, going underneath the highway and upstream for about 2 km.  It is shorter and more interesting than the Highway-to-Sea walk, and at the end there is a large pond with picnic tables.  The track is still being formed and may be muddy in places where heavy equipment has been working, but there are some excellent bridges and tree planting along the route.  The track is marked with green triangles, but it is easy to stray onto the gravel road - this may be okay at weekends but watch out for heavy vehicles.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSign says 1 hour return walking, but I\'d allow 1.5 hours.  About 30 minutes return cycling (as track is uneven in places).\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3530/3936822654_91d6ec7a31.jpg:Start of Chrystalls Bend walk:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nPicnic area\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2636/3936042447_5f202e3487.jpg:Chrystalls Bend picnic area:480:320]]','By car, park beside Otaki bridge.','Due to heavy vehicles working nearby, this walk is only open:  Mon-Fri 5pm to dusk; Sat noon to dusk; Sun dawn to dusk.','2.773',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-20 21:22:38',122,'-40.765136','175.145416',14,2,1,1,122,'2009-09-20 21:28:34','calc',5),(592,'Te Ara Piko',14,'','Part of the track that will one day go round the Pauatahanui inlet','An easy track extending from the eastern end Motukaraka Point.  Unfortunately it terminates before reaching Pauatahanui, and continuing along the road is not recommended (no footpath).  It also does not currently join the [[track:292]].  However, it is a pleasant walk and one day the track will extend right around the inlet.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track builders are doing a professional job, with sturdy bridges and engraved marking posts.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2429/3933947564_902c20e763.jpg:Te Ara Piko bridge:480:320]]','By car, drive to Motukaraka Point which is on Grays road halfway between Mana and Pauatahanui.','','0.732',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-20 21:38:22',122,'-41.091125','174.896679',14,1,1,2,122,'2009-09-20 21:41:09','calc',5),(593,'Pauatahanui wetlands',14,'','Walking tracks through wetlands to bird hides','The main entrance is just off Paekakariki Hill Road at the small settlement of Pauatahanui just a few metres from the Lighthouse cinema.  Opposite is a nice church which is worth a look round.  About 200 metres down the gravel driveway is small carpark and some information.  The track begins at the end of the carpark going in two directions - left takes you about 700 metres to a bird hide, and right also goes for about 700 metres past one hide and then either to another bird hide or an exit on to Grays Road.  (If you cross the road you can do the [[track:594]] track to more bird hides.\r\n[[para]]\