bed through Galbraiths Gully','This part of Galbraiths Gully is a \"route\" rather than a track, and is quite difficult in places.  Good shoes are required.  The water is generally only a few cm deep.  The track up to Maungaraki Road is known as the Zig Zag track, and emerges beside a childcare centre where the signpost says \"Huggans Hollow\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you continue down to Korokoro road you have two choices - the Dry Loop track or the wet foot track.  The wet foot track is a \"route\" following the stream bed.  It is fairly flat and whilst you may get your feet wet there isn\'t usually much water, but you should have good shoes on.  The dry loop track is a steep climb, you won\'t get wet feet, and you are rewarded with some good views of Wellington harbour at the top.  The choice is yours!','Park beside the playground on the corner of Te Whiti Grove and London Road, or park in the commuter carpark at the bottom of Korokoro Road and walk up Galbraiths gully.','','0.507',30,24,118,124,'','','2009-09-26 20:30:06',122,'-41.216386','174.871273',16,3,2,1,122,'2009-10-04 20:47:39','calc',5),(611,'Galbraiths Gully',30,'','Bush walk through original bush on excellent track','This was one of the first bush tracks cut up the hillside by early settlers.  The bush on the left on the way down is still original.  There is a sign near the top by Maungaraki Road providing some information on the walk and Galbraiths Gully.  The track is sealed with steps (and a slope in most places allowing bicycle access), and has streetlights at night.  For residents this track provides access to Petone railway station.','Short walk up from Petone railway station, or park in the commuter carpark area at the bottom of Korokoro road and walk up.','','0.410',NULL,92,117,25,'','','2009-09-26 20:38:28',122,'-41.217371','174.871745',16,1,1,5,122,'2009-09-26 20:39:29','calc',5),(612,'Southern walkway',41,' (bicycle only in some sections)','11 km walk from Oriental Parade over Mt Victoria to Island Bay','The Southern Walkway (Te Ranga a Hiwi) is a well signposted walk which can be done from end-to-end, or in sections.  Beginning from Oriental Parade the walk starts near the eastern end of the bay and climbs steeply (but on sealed paths and steps in many places) up to Mt Victoria, optionally going past the lookout on the top (peak is about 196 metres asl).  The climb up from Oriental Parade is for walkers only, but there are plenty of mountain biking routes on [[area:5]].  There is a famous spot about mid-way along Mt Victoria where a scene from Lord of the Rings was filmed - it is signposted at 41deg18\'9.94\"S, 174deg 47\'20.52\"E.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3480/3957739682_108e900b6e.jpg:Mt Victoria lookout:320:480]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter about 1 hours walk the track crosses the highway near the Mt Victoria tunnel and continues into Newtown and Kilbernie, past the Truby King Park (Karitane Products), Wellington zoo, through Melrose Park and up on to Mt Albert.  There are many side tracks along this stretch of the walk but the track is now well signposted - if you do wander from the main track it is easy to rejoin it again.  For mountain biking tracks in this area see [[area:19]].\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2652/3956961061_0fffc5a9c4.jpg:Southern walkway:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nAfter crossing Houghton Bay road the track descends through Sinclair Park to The Esplanade, and the last kilometre continues right along the coastline of Taputeranga marine reserve to Island Bay.  There is a bus stop at the corner of Reef St and The Parade, and there are also shops here if you require refreshment.','Park in Oriental Parade or walk round from Courtenay Place bus station.  There is a bus terminus at the end of Island Bay where the walk starts/finishes.','','10.714',546,538,4,12,'','','2009-09-26 20:43:17',122,'-41.300508','174.790764',12,2,1,2,122,'2009-09-27 16:35:31','calc',5),(613,'North Face',1,' (Under construction)','New track down from the summit of [[area:1]].\r\n[[br]]\r\nUnder construction. For more information, see the [[link:http://makarapeak.org/northface North Face Blog]].','The North Face track is an intermediate route down from the summit of [[area:1]], providing an alternative to the road ([[track:51]]) and the more difficult [[track:5]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBy design this is a busy track, with lots of undulations, swerves, wriggles, grade reversals, corners, and 14 switchbacks (including six in a funnel-shaped valley). All of these features have been carefully constructed to give the track great flow.  Straight lines are antithetical.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track traverses the northeast face of Makara Peak, which is remarkably sheltered from the weather. Currently almost all of the area is covered in dense gorse and barberry, interspersed with occasional natives.  The track was designed to carefully avoid as many of the existing natives as possible, while opening up a large tract of scrub land that was previously inaccessible.  This access will enable planting of more native flora and provide opportunities for additional possum bait lines.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nWith an end-to-end altitude drop of 105m, the average gradient is 6.5%. The maximum sustained gradient is 10%, though occasional short sections are steeper.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFor most of its length this track runs parallel to [[track:5]].  At a couple of points the two tracks are within a few metres of each other, making possible connections between them.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEven before construction started, plans were hatched to extend both ends of this track, to provide better integration with adjacent tracks. Specifically:\r\n[[bullet:200m long connection from part way down [[track:12]] to the top of North Face. This will also provide access to the top of [[track:14]] and [[track:49]].]]\r\n[[bullet:A continuation down through a grassy clearing visible in the map, then joining the [[track:19]] at a lower point.]]\r\n[[bullet:350m long connection from the continuation above to near the picnic tables on [[track:50]]. This section was [[link:http://makarapeak.org/northface?mode=PostView&bmi=261718 mostly piloted]] on 28 December 2009 and [[link:http://makarapeak.org/northface?mode=PostView&bmi=290475 the rest]] was piloted on 13 February 2010.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:vimeo:11072997]]','Top is just below the summit of Makara Peak, on [[track:51]], next to the top of [[track:14]] and [[track:49]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is on the [[track:19]], just over a 20m hill from the intersection of [[track:5]] and [[track:50]].','This track is one-way only, down from the summit (ie. northwest to southeast).\r\n[[para]]\r\nExploration of the area began in October 2008, with an initial look to see if it would be possible to build this track. Piloting began in earnest in March 2009, and the [[link:http://wellington.govt.nz WCC]] gave approval to build the track after doing a walk-through of the pilot track on 25 September 2009. Construction of the track was remarkably fast, with the entire length being rideable from the first week of March 2010. With 35 work parties in just over four months, more than 1500 person-hours of volunteer work went into building this track.','1.541',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-09-27 13:35:43',177,'-41.290383','174.711435',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-21 06:27:54','calc',5),(614,'River Track',111,'','Medium track. Good warm up for the longer tracks. Stream crossing near the finish means you end up with wet feet.','Leave the carpark at the base of the dam. Take the left fork around the vehicle gate. Up the road and take the right fork further down the road. There is a small sign indicating the track. Then up the track to you take the left fork.\r\n\r\nThis is a short track with some technical parts. Easy for an experienced rider. \r\n\r\nNear the end of the single track you need to ford the stream. You could try riding it.\r\n\r\nOnce across the stream it is 100m to the r