matangi Beach).  Walk back to Foxton Beach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that there is no marking for the track from Cousins Avenue that emerges from the sand dunes to the beach.  It can be hard to find if you haven\'t been there before.  There is a building visible near the beach about 100 metres south of the track.','By car, drive through Foxton Beach and take a right on to Nash Parade and drive to the end.  Turn left in to Cousins Avenue west and park at the end of the road (about 250 metres from the turnoff).','','3.310',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'(track is essentially flat apart from minor humps on the sand dunes)','','2009-10-03 20:39:27',122,'-40.454915','175.247383',13,2,1,3,122,'2009-10-03 20:48:32','calc',5),(633,'Moutoa Reserve',108,'','Riverbank walk to recreation area (mainly for fishermen)','This is a DOC recreation reserve signpost off Whirokino Road a few kilometres south of Foxton.  There are two gates (which should be closed after passing through) and the track is also usable by 4WD vehicles.  The reserve is about 1 km down the track, and you can walk either down the 4WD track or along the top of the stopbank (which affords a view of the river).  Flax planting is underway at the reserve, which would be a pleasant picnic or fishing spot in summer.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3484/3975881829_a0a0f2ea74.jpg:Moutoa Reserve:480:320]]','Driving south from Foxton, turn left on to Whirokino Road which is immediately before the bridge over Foxton River on SH1 (this is the bridge over the river, which is a little further south than the longer bridge over the floodway).  Watch for a gate on the right-hand side about 2 km east along Whirokino Road - there is a DOC sign on the gate.','','1.288',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'(Flat)','','2009-10-03 20:57:36',122,'-40.526163','175.294676',15,2,1,3,122,'2009-10-03 20:59:13','calc',5),(634,'Waikanae Riverbank',28,'','Easy walking or cycling route along Waikanae river bank','There is a well formed track each side of the Waikanae river between SH1 and the sea.  There are many entry and exit points.  The track shown in a loop starting on the north bank near SH1 (you can gain entry either from SH1, or park in Karu Crescent which is safer and quieter, and use one of two accessways from the street).  There are many access points to the river which is quite shallow and safe for splashing around in during the summer.  Approx. 2 km from SH1 is a new bridge Te Arawai.  A further 3 km towards the sea is Otaihanga domain and another good footbridge across the river.  At either bridge you can cross the river and continue back to SH1 on the other side of the river.  There are several gates to pass through on the northern side, and an area of private land (ok provided you stay on the path).  The track varies from single, double to 4WD and sealed - in general it is well kept, flat and wide.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTe Arawai bridge over Waikanae River\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3441/3976644322_8e30073cc5.jpg:Te Arawai bridge:320:480]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is about 5 km from SH1 to Otaihanga domain bridge.  The round trip of 10 km is about 45 minutes on a bicycle but allow 2.5 if walking.','There are many points to begin or end the walkway.  To get off SH1, I recommend either driving down Te Moana Road and then left to the end of Tutere St and parking in the domain beside the lagoons by the sea, or turning off on to Te Moana Road from SH1 at the traffic lights and parking on Karu Crescent (or nearby) and then starting the trail.  The other good parking area is Otaihanga domain off Makora Road on the southern side of the river.  There are toilets at Otaihanga domain and beside the Waimanu lagoons.','This route is part of the [[link:http://www.teararoa.org.nz/ Te Araroa]] walkway.\r\n[[para]]\r\nCyclists give way to pedestrians.  Expect a lot of walkers, joggers, pushchairs, dogs and horses on the track at weekends!\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a narrow footpath on the bridge across the river on State Highway 1.  I recommend getting off your bicycle and walking it across the bridge.  This is no safe cycle track or other off-road route.','9.575',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'(Flat track)','','2009-10-03 21:13:55',122,'-40.872377','175.033836',13,1,1,3,122,'2009-10-03 21:22:07','calc',5),(635,'Bracken St',17,'','Riverbank track opposite Shandon Golf course','A wide track between the creek beside the Shandon golf course and state houses.  It provides an alternative route to the [[area:12]] through the golf course.  Starting from entrance on Bracken Street which is just before the entrance to Memorial Park, the track leads south towards the sea.  Approximately mid-way there is an exit to Tennyson St, and further on there are two exits around the state houses to Heretaunga St.  The track finally exits near the end of Jackson St in the industrial area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nConsider this an alternative route for variation if doing the [[track:132]] track of [[area:12]].','There is a carpark at the end of Bracken St near the entrance to Memorial Park.  The southern end is walking distance from Petone along Jackson St, and from Hikoikoi reserve.','','1.167',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-04 20:01:22',122,'-41.225409','174.903374',14,1,1,3,122,'2009-10-04 20:21:51','calc',5),(636,'Shandon golf course',17,'','Riverbank track along edge of Shandon golf course','This is an easy track marking a return route along the other side of the riverbank from the [[track:635]] track.  It does go through the golf course (like the [[track:132]]) so you need to respect the golfers and watch out for stray golf balls.  It is only in the northern part of the route that it is necessary to cross a green to exit to Memorial Park.  This track should only be walked - if you are cycling please stick to the [[track:132]] route on the [[area:12]].','There is parking at the end of Bracken St near the entrance to Memorial Park.  It is also walking distance from Petone along Jackson St, or from Hikiokio Reserve.','Consider this an alternative track for variation if doing the [[track:132]] of the [[area:12]].','1.789',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-04 20:16:42',122,'-41.227862','174.898739',14,1,2,1,122,'2009-10-04 20:19:32','calc',5),(637,'Dry Foot Loop',30,'','A rough track through Korokoro bush clad hillsides','This track completes the link from [[track:610]] to Korokoro Road.  There are two routes - the dry foot track and the wet foot track.  The two routes are signpost a little north of the good [[track:611]] walk, and at the signpost to Maungaraki Road up the Zig Zag track about mid-way through the bush. \r\n[[para]]\r\nDry foot track - a very steep climb up the ridge.  The track is rough in places but wide at the top with some good views over Wellington harbour.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWet foot track - this follows the stream bed.  It is fairly flat, and there isn\'t much water but you do need good shoes and the track is very rough in places.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBoth tracks would be very hard to cycle.','There is parking in the commuter car park at the bottom of Korokoro Road.  It is also a short walk from Petone station (there is a pedestrian overpass over SH2).','The streambed \"wet foot\" track is designated a \"route\".\r\n[[para]]\r\n(Some difficulty exactly marking the tracks with a GPS as reception is bad in the gully.  The stream-bed \"route\" isn\'t well marked but as it follows the stream you shouldn\'t get lost.  There are clear signposts at junctions.)','0.632',83,83,27,27,'','','2009-10-04 20:37:22',122,'-41.216968','174.870608',16,3,2,1,122,'2009-10-04 20:41:29','calc',5),(638,'O\'Donahoos',30,'','Good bush track from Akatea Road to Sugarloaf','Of the three tracks down the bush clad hillsides from Sugarloaf (O\'Donahoos, [[track:608]] and [[track:376]]) this is the easiest and best formed track.  Near the top you can go right to [[track:375]] or exit to the top of Maungaraki Road and continue with [[track:373]] if you wish.','Parking is a little tricky on the