ct 11 2009',5,'','This is a map of the long course for PNP club race on Sun Oct 11 2009.\r\nFull course description is \r\n[[link:http://www.pnp.org.nz/mtb/events/2009/MTBSeries2009/Round%203%20Mt%20Vic here]]:','This course is similar to the NI XC Cup 2009. The differences are as follows in order from the velodrome:\r\n[[para]]\r\n1. Go up new Kennett bros track after leaving velodrome (at least after the first lap)[[br]]\r\n2. Go into the forest on the left instead of going straight ahead up the hill.[[br]]\r\n3. After arriving in the clearing go left into the trees instead of right and double back up the hill to the entrance to the ski chute.[[br]]\r\n4. Go down the new steep track in the park at the top of Marjorybanks, across the park and double back to rejoin last years route.[[br]]\r\n5. At the top of the climb by the wooden seat do the first downhill before the seat not the one after it.[[br]]\r\n6. When you come out at Alexandra park instead of crossing the field, follow the track down to the right and then take the first left, then walk.... yes walk! up the rocky downhill section.[[br]]\r\n7. After you cross the park with the new mini skills area, take the right in to the trees as usual but then take your first right to follow new rooty section.[[br]]\r\n8. At the T junction after the next climb instead of going right, go left back up to Alexandra road. Go up the knoll and right at the top, down the rooty descent.[[br]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nHeight graph (starts on alexandra rd opp bowling club now from velodrome)\r\n [[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/trackfield_graph/graph/63%2C63%2Cfield_track_data/Normal/N:PNP Height Graph:500:100]].','','','7.566',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-06 22:12:25',59,'-41.300381','174.791458',14,3,1,1,59,'2009-10-07 07:52:54','calc',8),(643,'Eastern Walkway',22,'','One of the WCC Explore Wellington walkways across the eastern peninsula','The Eastern walkway extends between Seatoun and Tarakena Bay.  The route shown begins at Tarakena Bay (car park for Ataturk memorial), heads north along the well signposted Eastern Walkway route across the hills to Pass of Branda, then down into Seatoun and back along the coast around Point Dorset and then follows the shoreline around Breaker Bay, Eve Bay, Flax Bay, Reef Bay, Palmer Bay, past the Wahine Memorial Park and back tothe carpark at Ataturk memorial.  The walk is about 4 km in each direction, allow 2.5 to 3 hours if walking.  Cycling is not allowed across the Eastern walkway, but you can cycle along the coast road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe route includes several entry exit points - Bury Grove, Sidlaw Street, Signallers Grove and there are two entrances on Beacon Hill Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe walkway is well maintained with wooden steps in many places, but some spots can get muddy after heavy rain.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPoint Dorset\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2454/4018919722_229626f892.jpg:Point Dorset:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nHole in rock on Breaker Bay side of Point Dorset\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2593/4018919672_04539e326c.jpg:Hole in rock:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nLittle Blue Penguins come ashore at night around the Eastern Bays.\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2668/4018919656_aa550e1754.jpg:Blue Penguin sign:480:320]]\r\n','There are a number of entry and exit points as noted above, but the best car parks are at Ataturk memorial (Tarakena Bay near Wahine Memorial Park) or in Seatoun around Hector St.','Bicycles not allowed on Eastern walkway over hills (but okay on coast road)','9.246',120,120,2,2,'','','2009-10-17 21:03:27',122,'-41.329260','174.820204',14,2,2,2,122,'2009-10-17 21:08:44','calc',0),(644,'Conclusion Walkway',14,'','Rolls along a suburban cliff-top with stunning views over Papakowhai, Porirua Harbour and towards Whitireia.','The southern half of this dirt track runs parallel to Conclusion Street, presumedly leading to the track\'s name.  In any case, this track provides a welcome escape from the sprawl of the surrounding suburbia.\r\n[[para]]\r\nParts of this track are very steep, as it rolls along the top of a cliff.  The effort is worthwhile, as the views are impressive â€“ looking northwest over Papakowhai and across Porirua Harbour towards Whitireia Park (the [[track:171]] track is visible along the edge of the harbour).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is quite varied, ranging from bare rock and soft dirt, to concrete steps at the northern end, and a large wooden structure that spans a gully near the northern end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are several exits up or down to nearby streets, including an impressive set of ramps and steps down to Eskdale Road. Just before the track drops down a large set of steps to Livet Place, there is an exit up to Doncaster Terrace â€“ directly across the grassy area at the top is the northern end of the [[track:645]].','Southern end is on Whitford Brown Avenue, though there is the option of starting on Conclusion Street and dropping down an open grassy area between houses.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is in Livet Place, though access off the end of Doncaster Terrace is more bike friendly.','','1.838',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (bordering on Intermediate)','2009-10-26 19:29:14',23,'-41.115961','174.870436',15,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-07 11:41:52','calc',5),(645,'Ascot Park Walkway',14,'','Roller-coaster paved path through the Wild Thyme Reserve.','This is a smooth concrete path that wanders along the top of the pleasant bush-clad Wild Thyme Reserve.  The path swoops up and down along a hillside, making for a roller-coaster ride â€“ some parts of which are quite steep.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the southern end, just before the concrete path turns straight up the hill, there is a sharp corner from which the much rougher [[track:646]] heads down to Ascot Park.','Northern end is off a small grass area at the end of Doncaster Terrace. It is tucked around a corner, so isn\'t visible from the road â€“ just wander down the grass and the track will become obvious as it heads into the trees to the east.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is at the intersection of Sombrero View, Almora View and Doncaster Terrace.','In July 2009 the Porirua City Council, in association with [[link:http://www.projectcrimson.org.nz/home/page.aspx Project Crimson]], planted 750 northern rata trees in the Wild Thyme Reserve adjacent to this track.','0.523',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-26 19:34:10',23,'-41.113204','174.873708',17,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-07 10:26:39','calc',5),(646,'Ascot Park Access',14,'','Rugged and steep access between [[track:645]] and Ascot Park.','This is a shortcut from the [[track:645]] to Ascot Park via a rough-cut bulldozer track. The views over Pauatahanui Inlet are quite nice, though it would be best to stop when admiring the views as the track surface is rugged and loose.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe descent down to Ascot Park is very steep and rutted, with large rocks and vegetation debris aplenty.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom Ascot Park there is a short climb up to a steel barrier arm at the Conclusion Street end of the track.','Northern end deviates off [[track:645]], just before the concrete path turns straight up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end is on Conclusion Street, above Ascot Park.','','0.478',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-26 19:36:47',23,'-41.115807','174.875768',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-07 10:42:57','calc',5),(647,'Cannons Creek Park',14,'','Open field connection between [[track:296]] and [[track:103]].','','','','0.920',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-26 19:39:29',23,'-41.137377','174.866338',15,2,1,1,23,'2009-10-26 19:40:39','calc',5),(648,'Otatara Pa',114,'','Historic Maori Pa site with nice views over Napier area','Pleasant hillside walk around a once important fortified Maori Pa.  From the large carpark there is a gentle climb up a wide 4WD path onto the grassy hillsides which provide good views over Hawke\'s Bay.  There are several lookout points.  Approx. halfway round there is a signpost with an optional exit over farmland to Churchill Drive.  The loop track continues down to the carpark.  Allow 1 to 1.5 hours for the walk.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOtatara Pa entrance\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2573/4046013004_ca49d33837.jpg:Otatara Pa entrance:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nView of Pa from opposite hillside\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2638/4046012938_17dfa60c5f.jpg:Otatara Pa:480:320]]','Drive south through Taradale on Gloucester Road towards SH50.  At the bridge (Waiohiki Road) continue straight (don\'t go over the bridge) and the carpark is on the right about 50 metres further on.  It is well signpost.','Bicycles not allowed.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a number of electric fences to cross - in most cases the wires are insulated at the style, but take care.','2.162',118,118,12,12,'','','2009-10-26 20:56:24',122,'-39.547421','176.832204',16,2,2,2,122,'2009-10-26 20:57:49','calc',5),(649,'Ahuriri Estuary',114,'','Circuit round estuary in Napier','There are several places to enter the walkway which does a circuit round the Estuary.  There is a good carpark with toilets in Humber Street off SH2.  From there there is a wide flat track leading clockwise round the Estuary, up onto the bridge beside the rail bridge to cross the estuary, and then back down across the estuary on wooden walkways to cross the wetland areas (bicycles not permitted in this area).  Allow about an hour to walk the circuit.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3532/4045269055_74d1288472.jpg:Ahuriri Estuary:480:320]]','Off SH2 going north out of Napier.  Good carpark in Humber St, or park in the marked areas on Pandora Road.  There is no access from the Main North Road (Highway 2B) on the western side of the estuary.','Bicycles allowed on certain parts of the track - should be used through wetland area as this is a bird sanctuary.','3.907',4,4,1,1,'','','2009-10-26 21:08:43',122,'-39.483740','176.883488',15,2,2,2,122,'2009-10-26 21:10:28','calc',5),(650,'Ngaruroro Wetlands',114,'','Short walk round wetland reserve','This is a short track round a newly developed wetland.  Bicycles not permitted, but there are many nearby cycle tracks between the main highway and the shore and along the river stopbands (which hopefully will be added in the near future).  There is one bird hide about 1/3rd of the way round the wetland from the main gate.  Return the same way, or exit and cross highway and return by the beach.','Going south from Napier, turn left into the gates at Waitangi and drive towards the river, then back under the road and rail bridges and park near the gate by the electric fences.  You can walk through the gate and up onto the rise which does a semicircle around the wetland.','','0.673',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-26 21:15:37',122,'-39.563469','176.920073',16,2,2,1,122,'2009-10-26 21:18:48','calc',5),(651,'Tumanako Loop',114,'','Short loop in Boundary Stream Mainland Island reserve','This is the gentlest track in the reserve and suitable for most people.  Boundary Stream is a mainland island reserve where predators are being eradicated to encourage native species to thrive.  The bird-song in the area is as close to pre-human population of NZ as you will find anywhere.  There are Kiwi in the bush areas (which you may hear in the night).  The loop track is well marked.  There are views through the bush over the cliffs mid-way round - it is easy to forget that the area is over 700 metres above sea level.  The signage says 1 hour walk, but should take no more than 30 - 45 minutes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBoundary Stream\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2529/4046013122_abffe7133b.jpg:Boundary Stream carpark:480:320]]','Boundary Stream reserve is about 60 km north of Napier.  Take SH2 north out of Napier and continue around the coast to Wairoa (don\'t take SH5 to Taupo).  At Lake Tutira there is a store, take the left (Matahorua Road) and continue to the signpost at Pohokura Road (Matahorua road continues right to Shine Falls).  Go up Pohokura Road, a short distance along the seal runs out and the last 12 km are unsealed.  Along the way you will pass Opouahi Reserve and Bellbird Bush.  There is a wide carpark at Boundary Stream reserve.','Cycles not permitted in the bird reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are rough toilets just off the car park (opposite side to Tumanako walk).  There is no freshwater or other facilites beyond the Tutira store, so be prepared and self-sufficient.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that this is a Kiwi area so take car if travelling through after dark.','1.610',29,37,727,727,'','','2009-10-26 21:33:39',122,'-39.122470','176.808300',13,1,2,1,122,'2009-10-26 22:32:52','calc',5),(652,'Kamahi Loop',114,'','Longer loop walk at Boundary Stream Mainland Island reserve','This is a longer loop walk off the [[track:651]].  It is slightly more difficult than the Tumanako Loop, but easily completed by most people in about 1.5 hours.  The bush walk is lovely, with some excellent views from a lookout point on the cliffs, and the track back to the carpark follows a stream (which turns in to Shine Falls a short distance away).  Although the track is near the cliff edges, the bush provides a safe barrier and nowhere does it feel unsafe.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout mid-way round the track to Shine Falls is sign-posted.  This track is marked as suitable for experienced trampers only, and is best completed with transport at each end.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView from lookout about 800 metres asl\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2468/4045269139_28160103a8.jpg:Cliff view:480:320]]','Follow the directions given for [[track:651]].  The track begins about 200 metres from the carpark on the right-hand part of Tumanako Loop.','Bicycles not allowed in the bird reserve.','3.943',0,151,706,706,'','','2009-10-26 21:44:50',122,'-39.122337','176.808815',13,2,2,1,122,'2009-10-26 22:33:26','calc',5),(653,'Bell Rock',114,'','Breathtaking views over Hawkes Bay high country from about 1,000 metres','This is reasonably energetic 3 hour loop walk through bush and then across the farmland peaks to a rocky cliff-top - it is then that you realise you are at 1000 metres!  This is one of my favourite NZ walks - on a good day.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe start of the walk is signpost a few kilometres further up Pohokura Road from Boundary Stream ([[track:651]]).  This isn\'t much of a carpark, enough for about 2 cars to pull over from the unsealed road.  The track then leads up through bush for about 2 km, then emerges over a style into farmland.  The track is marked with DOC green poles with yellow ring at the top, and roughly follows 4WD tracks across the farmland.  The poles do not follow the tracks exactly, taking a more direct route.  In white out conditions (cloud is attracted to the peak) it can be difficult to spot the next pole - however, the 4WD tracks head in the same direction.  Bell Rock is about 2 km further along, terminating at the cliff edge.  There are no safety rails so take care near the cliff edge (as my Mother says ... \"if you fall down I\'m not climbing down to get you\").  There are wonderful views from this point providing it is a clear day.\r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way following the DOC green/yellow poles.  At the signpost to Pohokura Road you can continue straight ahead along the 4WD track.  There are no poles along this route, but it is a well marked 4WD route with deep ruts in places.  The track re-enters the bush reserve through a gate, and continues down along the side of the bush and exits through farmland about 700 metres further up Pohokura Road.  This entrance is harder to find from Pohokura Road - on the gate is a sign \"Scenic Reserve Firearms and Camping Prohibited\".\r\n[[para]]\r\nBell Rock\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3506/4045269219_2fd2f7438d.jpg:Bell Rock:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nTrack across hill tops\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2488/4045269175_3cdd85e392.jpg:Hill top track:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nBell Rock track northern entrance\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3480/4045269289_578727b81c.jpg:Bell Rock track:480:320]]','Follow the directions to Boundary Stream research [[track:651]].  Bell Rock is a few kilometres north of Boundary Stream, about 60 km from Napier.  Allow an hour if driving.','The sign says cycling not permitted.  However, I have seen organised cycle trips using the 4WD tracks (not the bush route through bird reserve) so it may be worth enquiring with DOC for a permit.','6.524',274,274,762,762,'','','2009-10-26 22:02:23',122,'-39.113413','176.817226',13,3,2,3,122,'2009-10-26 22:06:48','calc',5),(654,'Bellbird Bush',114,'','Short loop walk through pleasant native bush','This is a short bush walk, allow about 15 minutes.  However, there is a longer (2 hour) Spooners Hill walk (route not yet shown - but it exits at 39deg 7\'44.82S, 176deg 48\'49.46E).  As the name suggests, the area abounds with native birds including Bellbird, Tui, Rifleman, Tomtit and native Pigeon.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBellbird bush sign\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2498/4046013366_4e0c085ed7.jpg:Bellbird bush:480:320]]\r\n','Bellbird bush is signposted on the left a few kilometres before arriving at Boundary Stream reserve (see directions on [[track:651]]).  Park beside the entrance.  The Spooners Hill loop track exit is a few kilometres south on Pohokura Road beside the entrance to Opouahi Station).','The track is a little rough and muddy in places, but generally suitable for all.','0.347',3,9,767,767,'','','2009-10-26 22:18:33',122,'-39.111615','176.809244',14,1,2,2,122,'2009-10-26 22:21:05','calc',5),(655,'Opouahi Reserve',114,'','Loop walk round lake beside Pan Pac Kiwi creche','A predator proof fence is used to protect Kiwis, and there is a pleasant bush walk round the lake.  Note that the track shown is approximate (GPS track to be added in the future).  The entrance is along the route to Boundary Stream [[track:651]].  Allow about 1 hour for the loop walk.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOpouahi Scenic Reserve sign\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2624/4045269407_99870a9bea.jpg:Opouahi entrance:480:320]]','Follow the directions to [[track:651]].  The entrance is on the right driving up the road, a few kilometres from the Shine Falls sign.  There is a large carpark area at the front.','Walkers only.  The entrance is through special predator proof gates.','1.706',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-26 22:25:25',122,'-39.124600','176.821175',13,2,2,1,122,'2009-10-26 22:31:52','calc',5),(656,'White Pine Bush',114,'','Gentle loop walk and picnic area popular with families','From the large carpark there are toilets and picnic facilites, and then a couple of walking options.  The short loop walk shown here is a sealed track suitable for all ages.  At the far end there is another loop walk (unsealed, slightly rougher track).  Across the road there is another track leading to [[track:657]] (about 1.5 hours one way).\r\n\r\n','Carpark is off SH2 about 20 km north of Napier on the road to Wairoa.','Walkers only on the sealed pathway.','0.546',7,7,208,208,'','','2009-10-26 22:40:35',122,'-39.300764','176.889582',14,1,2,2,122,'2009-10-26 22:51:03','calc',5),(657,'Tangoio Falls',114,'','Several walking options to view waterfalls','From the carpark off SH2, there is a 40 minute return walk to the lower waterfall, or a further 15 minutes to a lookout view the larger Tangoio Falls.  From the lookout there is a track to [[track:656]], about 1.5 hours one way.  The track is good but can be muddy in places after rain.  The route shown leads from the car park to the lower and upper falls - the track to White Pine Bush isn\'t shown yet.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2599/4045269457_4683b783b6.jpg:Lower Falls:320:480]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nTangoio Falls\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2473/4045269515_d9dc0e9de5.jpg:Tangoio Falls:480:320]]\r\n','On the right-hand side driving north on SH2, about 15 km north of Napier on the road to Wairoa.','','1.715',106,NULL,20,126,'','','2009-10-26 22:44:55',122,'-39.301163','176.885977',14,2,2,1,122,'2009-10-26 22:50:39','calc',5),(658,'Altar Boy',29,'','A new track under-construction.','','','','0.947',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','   Grade 5','2009-10-27 20:10:21',126,'-35.654263','174.334960',15,4,3,1,126,'2010-03-25 14:48:06','calc',5),(659,'Hydrabad',108,'','Short beach walk along Waitarere shoreline to remnants of the Hydrabad','The Hydrabad was built in 1865 in Scotland.  Whilst bound for Adelaide on 24 June 1878 it came ashore on Waitarere Beach in a bad storm.  This was a deliberate attempt by the captain for the safety of passengers and crew, and there was no loss of life.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe wreck is advertised in Waitarere Beach, and it is a pleasant walk along the shore.  It is about 1.8 km from the end of Waitarere Beach Road, or you can drive down Rua Avenue and access the beach from Hydrabad Avenue.  From here it is about 800 m to the wreck.  Don\'t expect anything great - in fact, it is quite hard to find!  Look out for a post with 30 km/hr and \"Total Fire Ban\".  The wreck is near this post - some rust iron hull can be seen poking out of the sand.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3482/4060453582_de7f919336.jpg:Wreck of Hydrabad:480:320]]','Either park at the end of Waitarere Beach Road beside the surf club, or drive down to the end of Rua Ave and access the beach from there.','Please keep to tracks when walking over the sand dunes to the shore, to preserve the fragile coastal environment.','0.851',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-31 20:50:21',122,'-40.550983','175.200777',14,1,1,6,122,'2009-10-31 20:52:33','calc',5),(660,'Waitarere Forest RD12',108,'','Main route from Waitarere Beach township to Foxton Estuary through Waitarere Forest','Vehicles are not permitted in Waitarere Forest (without a permit), but pedestrians and cyclists are welcome provided they take care.  There are logging trucks operating but you are unlikely to come across any at the weekend - just watch out for large farm vehicles at the Waitarere end of the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe forest is criss-crossed with tracks.  The route shown here is the main route from Waitarere Beach Road through to Foxton Estuary.  It is a wide gravel road in good condition.  The many side roads vary in degree of roughness, but this track is good.  The road is labelled \"RD12\". Some other roads are marked, but I strongly recommend taking a GPS (signal is good even within the forest) as it is easy to get lost.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is a long straight road.  If you are cycling try some side roads if you are bored - they will offer more of a challenge!  Cyclists allow 30 - 45 minutes, if walking allow about 2 hours.  It is about 10 km each way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nForest entrance on Waitarere Beach road\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2587/4059710267_c63fa53363.jpg:Waitarere forest entrance:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nForest track\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2487/4059710227_92fa5c99d4.jpg:Forest track:480:320]]','Park at the forest entrance on Waitarere Beach Road.  Not vehicles allowed in the forest.','No facilities within the forest.  There is a 4 Square store about 200 metres further down Waitarere Beach Road if you need supplies.','9.872',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-31 21:01:04',122,'-40.517714','175.220947',12,2,1,4,122,'2009-10-31 21:03:49','calc',5),(661,'Waitarere RD42',108,'','Loop route in Waitarere Forest','Loop route off main route RD12 in Waitarere Forest.  Good 4WD tracks, just a little rough in places when logging operations have been operating in the vicinity.  Take a GPS and do not rely on road signs within the forest (there are a few, but it isn\'t a reliable means of finding your way).','Off RD12 in Waitarere Forest.','','3.289',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-31 21:06:46',122,'-40.503619','175.243607',12,2,1,3,122,'2009-10-31 21:09:09','calc',5),(662,'Oturoa Road',108,'','Alternative access route to Waitarere Forest','This track provides an alternate route for access to Waitarere Forest.  Access is via a farm track off Oturoa Road, which is off SH1 near Foxton Bridge.  Pedestrians and cyclists are welcome in the forest, other vehicles are not, and the farm track access to the forest is shared with farm vehicles who take precedence.  There is a locked gate to cross into the forest, but once in there you are unlikely to come across any vehicles on the weekend (there are logging operations underway in the forest so take care, especially on week days).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe forest has many tracks, the route shown provides access from Oturoa Road to the edge of Foxton River.  You can continue down the road to join up with other forest tracks already mapped.  I recommend taking a GPS as only a few of the forest roads have signs (GPS reception is good within the forest).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe forestry roads and long - cycling is more practical than walking.  Allow about 1.5 hours walking one-way for the route shown.','Turn off SH1 about 1 km South of the Foxton Bridge on to Oturoa Road.  About 1.5 km down the road there is a sharp left turn.  Park here on the verge (there isn\'t room for many cars), and begin walking down the farm track towards the forest.  The locked gate and forest entrance is about 1 km down this road.','','5.945',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-31 21:17:30',122,'-40.499442','175.214767',12,2,1,4,122,'2009-10-31 21:19:41','calc',5),(663,'Oturua loop',108,'','Alternative route from Oturoa Road access to Waitarere Forest','An alternate track through Waitarere forest from [[track:662]].  Continue down this track if you wish to join up to [[track:660]].  There are many roads within Waitarere Forest but I recommend taking a GPS with you as it is easy to get lost and not all roads are signposted.','See direction on [[track:662]].','','3.014',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-10-31 21:23:04',122,'-40.506751','175.252533',12,2,1,4,122,'2009-10-31 2