 Titahi Bay','Mana Island is much smaller than its northern neighbour Kapiti Island.  From the landing area on the south-eastern part of the island there are well maintained walking tracks.  If you go take the Tirohanga track north you pass the toilet and historic woolshed, and then there is a short steep climb about 100 metres to the flat grassy top of the island.  The well mown track continues to the north western corner of the island where there is a trig on the historic site of the old lighthouse.  Returning along the western side you pass the location of the concrete Gannet colony (concrete gannets since removed).  You can then take the coastal track back to the landing area, or follow the southern island loop, which joins the Tirohanga track back down to the landing area.  There is a small wetland loop track behind the DOC buildings near the landing area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAllow 1.5 to 2 hours for a leisurely walk, and look out for the \"Lizard Lounge\" boxes (there is one by the lighthouse trig).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe island is an important DOC wildlife sanctuary, with a small breeding population of Shore Plover, Takahe, and Yellow-Crowned parakeet.  Visitors are allowed on the island between 8 am and 5 pm, and expect to be met by DOC staff.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTrig and site of old lighthouse\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2747/4165074665_1d194a0dc4.jpg:Trig:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nHistoric woolshed dating back to 1834\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4004/4165833228_85bcffe43d.jpg:Historic woolshed:480:320]]','There is no scheduled ferry service to Mana Island.  The Wellington DOC office (phone (04)-384 7770) can provide a list of yachts that may be chartered, or you can try [[link:http://www.sailmanaisland.co.nz/ Mana Island Sailing Adventures]] (skipper Michael Peters).  6 - 8 people are needed to charter a boat, and another option is to catch a ride with a fishing party.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother option is [[link:http://www.manaisland.org.nz/ The Friends of Mana Island]] (FOMI). You can contact Brian Paget at (04) 802 4345 or mobile 021-523-444.  These trips are guided and can take up to 30 people.','As it is a scientific reserve there are no dogs allowed, no overnight camping, and bags should be checked for vermin upon arrival.','6.645',120,120,2,2,'','','2009-12-07 21:12:18',122,'-41.086726','174.782352',14,2,2,2,122,'2009-12-08 20:14:52','calc',5),(711,'Bethunes Gully Track',122,'','A short track with some obstacles and bridges.','[[bold:Obstacle at Bethunes Gully]]\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/sites/default/files/bethunes.jpg::400:300]]\r\n','Go to Bethunes Gully at the head of North East Valley. ','','1.529',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-12-07 23:40:30',59,'-45.829637','170.551372',15,3,1,1,59,'2009-12-20 16:51:53','calc',5),(712,'Higgle d piggle d',29,'','A technical trail, grade 5. Not yet open.','','','','0.491',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-12-14 12:06:46',126,'-35.657349','174.345303',16,6,3,1,126,'2010-01-18 19:47:48','calc',5),(713,'The Tickler',20,'','Connects end of [[track:245]] to start of [[track:246]].','Crosses creek goes through a gully.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[media:youtube:rMMJhv0BplE]]\r\nVideo credit: Andrew Francis','','','1.152',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-12-14 19:49:05',23,'-38.169789','176.286256',15,3,1,1,59,'2010-02-04 22:12:31','calc',5),(714,'Sidewinder',20,'','An outback track connecting direct road to windy road and Hill Road (via lentil link)','A pretty un-remarkable track by Whakarewarewa standards, looks like it hasn\'t seen some love from the track maintenance people for a while. A little overgrown but far from impassable.','Carry along direct road past the top of hot cross bun','','0.661',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-12-14 20:07:32',59,'-38.171678','176.306148',15,3,1,1,59,'2009-12-14 20:09:10','calc',5),(715,'Lentil Link',20,'','Connects end of Sidewinder to Hill Road','Somewhat unremarkable','','','0.457',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2009-12-14 20:16:56',59,'-