oderately graded slopes.\r\n[[para]]\r\nJust 40m from the top there is the entrance to a tunnel that provided an outlet for the water reservoir that is located on the other side of the ridge. The tunnel was hewn out of solid rock. At the top, look directly opposite the intersection with [[track:159]] to see the old water supply dam and pump for the defunct Onslow County Borough. There is a short and rather precarious track down to the reservoir.','Bottom is at the end of Truscott Avenue. Head across the open grassy area to the western corner of the park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of this track meets [[track:159]] at a sign-posted T-intersection.','There is plenty of parking at the end of Truscott Avenue.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track is sign-posted as \"Circular Track\".  A circuit that goes up this track, along 0.5km of [[track:159]] and then down [[track:780]] makes for a good walk â€“ or do the circuit in the reverse order for a more strenuous workout.','0.734',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-03 09:11:59',23,'-41.227176','174.788918',16,3,2,1,23,'2010-01-03 10:32:59','calc',5),(780,'Truscott South',14,'','Southern section of a steep walking track through Johnsonville Park between Truscott Avenue and [[track:159]].','This is a steep walking track through Johnsonville Park between Truscott Avenue and [[track:159]].  Along the way there are many flights of stairs â€“ about 500 steps in total.  For most of the way the gradient averages around 25%, though the bottom 0.2km is more gentle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of the track is quite narrow and in places it is not well formed.  In particular, at around the halfway point the track passes under a bunch of old pine trees that have lots of exposed roots running down the steep slope, making for a precarious section.  In addition, many of the steps are awkward, being either designed for pixie feet or degraded by wear.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNear the bottom end, the track passes through a damp valley that is full of moss-covered rocks.  It then runs below some houses that are on the Johnsonville side of the disjointed John Sims Drive, before emerging on to a driveway and then out on to Truscott Avenue.','Bottom is at the end of Truscott Avenue. Head up the driveway towards 67 Truscott Avenue, off the parking area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of this track meets [[track:159]] at a sign-posted T-intersection.','There is plenty of parking at the end of Truscott Avenue.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track is sign-posted as \"Circular Track\".  A circuit that goes up [[track:779]], along 0.5km of [[track:159]] and then down this track makes for a good walk â€“ or do the circuit in the reverse order, heading up this track first, for a more strenuous workout.','0.780',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-03 09:13:21',23,'-41.229645','174.788961',16,3,2,1,23,'2010-01-03 10:54:24','calc',5),(781,'Canaan Downs loop',34,'','This is a very scenic and fun recreational ride that suits a variety of riders. While the main track is recreational in grade, there are lots of side loops, ramps, drops and logrides to keep more advanced riders happy too. About 1.5 - 2 hours of riding that does require a little bit of fitnss and endurance at times.','The Abel Tasman National Park encompasses this area, and the surroundings are picturesque and stunning with awesom veiws, native bush, caves and sink holes.\r\nIf making the venture this far in, its well worth the short walk down to Harwoods Hole.\r\nThe ride starts with a climb up to the start of the Rameka Track which branches off to the left, then carries on through a slightly rougher section to Wainui Saddle. Here the track breaks away to the right and follows the contour of the valley around and down through some clever creek crossings and fun flowy track. Eventually there is another climb to the top of the hill and a fun decent back to the road, and then back around to the carpark.','Drive to the top of the Takaka Hill road, looking for a road off to the north and signage for Canaan Road, and Harwoods Hole.\r\nFollow this 11km gravel road to its very end where you will find a carpark with toilets. This is the start of the loop.\r\nThis is also the start of the Rameka Track, and its a good ride to ride the loop, then do the Rameka. This does require organising a pickup and return at the bottom.','','16.199',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-03 21:28:40',135,'-40.951024','172.890001',13,3,3,1,135,'2010-01-07 23:51:29','calc',5),(782,'Gibbs Hill',34,'','Open only during the winter months 1 May to 1 October\r\n','Abel Tasman National Parkâ€™s Gibbâ€™s Hill Track this week becomes the first Nelson national park track that can be mountain biked with mountain bikers able to ride it for 5 months from Friday, 1 May.\r\n\r\nMountain biking is being trialled during the winter visitor season, 1 May to 1 October, over 2 years on the track that runs across the park between Totaranui and Wainui Bay. Monitoring will take place to determine whether or not mountain biking should be allowed to continue on the track beyond the 2-year trial period. \r\n\r\nThe move follows a change to General Policy for National Parks which now allows mountain biking in national parks on routes specified in national park management plans. Mountain biking provisions were included in a new Abel Tasman National Park Management Plan that came into effect late last year.\r\n\r\nDOC Golden Bay Area Manager John Mason said mountain bikers could just ride the 10-km Gibbs Hill Track or make a 23-km round trip by also cycling on roads between Wainui and Totaranui.  \r\n\r\nâ€œWe hope mountain bikers will enjoy this first riding opportunity in Abel Tasman National Park. \r\n\r\nâ€œMountain biking is only permitted in the off-peak winter season when fewer people are walking the track. Mountain bikers need to adhere to the mountain bikersâ€™ code which includes requirement to show respect and consideration to walkers. \r\n\r\nâ€œMonitoring during the trial period will assess mountain biking impacts including environmental effects and any impacts on other peopleâ€™s use and enjoyment of the track. If the impacts are found to be minimal and acceptable then mountain biking will be allowed to continue on the track.â€\r\n\r\nThe Department is also reminding mountain bikers that biking is not allowed on the Heaphy Track and other Kahurangi National Park tracks.\r\n\r\nâ€œMountain biking is illegal on the Heaphy Track and elsewhere in Kahurangi National Park under park bylaws now in place. People can be prosecuted under the bylaws for mountain biking in the national park.\r\n\r\nâ€œOptions for mountain biking in Kahurangi National Park are presently being considered in a partial review of the parkâ€™s management plan. What mountain biking can take place in the park wonâ€™t be established until the review is completed and a new reviewed management plan is in place specifying the mountain bike access allowed. \r\n\r\nâ€œThe public will have the chance to comment on proposals for mountain biking in the park when a draft reviewed management plan is released for public submissions, expected to be before the middle of this year. Public submissions will be taken into account in preparing a final draft reviewed plan for consideration by the Nelson/Marlborough Conservation Board and then the New Zealand Conservation Authority.â€\r\n\r\nAdditional information\r\nGibbs Hill Track can be cycled in either direction. It is graded as an intermediate-level mountain biking track. No more than eight riders are allowed in a group. Mountain biking is not allowed on other tracks in the area.\r\n\r\nMountain biking is also now allowed year-round on a short section of another Abel Tasman National Park track. The Moa Park Track can be cycled, between the turnoff on the Rameka Track â€“ which is legal road and currently used for mountain biking â€“ and the Wainui Track turnoff. This section of track links with a mountain bike track being developed in the adjoining Canaan Downs Scenic Reserve, providing a round trip. \r\n\r\nThe current Kahurangi National Park Management Plan came into effect in 2001. Under the General Policy for National Parks in place at the time, mountain bikes were categorised as vehicles which were prohibited in national parks except on formed roads.\r\n','','','10.569',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-03 21:34:11',135,'-40.817358','172.977744',12,3,1,1,135,'2010-01-03 21:34:34','calc',5),(783,'Bridge to Nowhere',129,'','Classic trek through the Whanganui National Park, including the \"Bridge to Nowhere\".','[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Bridge to Nowhere]]\r\n[[image:http://farm1.static.flickr.com/187/383614792_6fe422fb19.jpg:Bridge to Nowhere:500:375]] \r\n\r\nThis track was done as part of a package (through the Bridge to Nowhere Lodge) that included accommodation in Raetihi on Friday night, shuttle to the start of the track, jet boat from the end of track to the lodge, dinner, bed and breakfast at the Bridge To Nowhere Lodge, 3+ hour canoe ride down Whanganui River to the pickup point, jet boat ferrying bikes to pickup point and shuttle back to Raetihi.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track starts (going anticlockwise) with a long but comfortable middle ring climb to an undulating section before reaching the main summit (about 660m) a bit before Â½ way.  After that there is a steep descent to the river (this is cut up be quad bikes and has some difficult bits such as ruts that are both difficult to avoid and too deep/narrow to pedal through).  Once down on the relative flat by the river (Mangapurua Stream) there is a long sidle along the river flats with the only difficult bits being a couple of narrow tracks across cliff faces (best not to loiter under these), the odd stream crossing/washout and quite few swing bridges that it is not recommended to ride across.  The Bridge 2 Nowhere just appears in front of you as you round a corner and if you want pictures from the side angle, take them from the other side of the bridge (or go bush bashing/climbing).  After the bridge it is a short somewhat overly groomed track town to the Whanganui River and the jet boat landing.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you progress along the track it generally goes from 4wd track to quad bike track to single track and is pretty much all 4wd track up to the main summit.  If a bush is not sufficient, there is a toilet about 2/3 way along the track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you want, you can get canoes left for you at the landing and they are big enough for two people plus two bikes  - depends of how much you value keeping you bike should you not be a capable canoeist.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThis ride is not recommended during wet weather but if you are booked and it looks like it might rain, do it anyway if you can.  The ground/mud is very abrasive, being especially hard on brake pads and the drive train.  The track itself is not particularly difficult except for the section from the top down to the river which, when wet, turned into a slippery rutted clay stream bed.  Even in the dry there would be a few minor bits where pushing would be advised as it is a long way to go get medical help.  \r\n [[para]]\r\nOverall this track it easier than the 42nd traverse in terms of the required stamina but is more technically demanding, especially if wet.  The scenery is spectacular, even in the wet, and this would have to be a must do (and must do again) ride for any cross country type mountain biker of medium or better fitness.  You could easily do this ride over a few days as there are ample very pleasant looking spots for tenting if you are prepared to carry one.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Bridge to Nowhere]] Elevation Chart\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/trackfield_graph/graph/260%2C260%2Cfield_track_data/Tracksdotorg/N:Bridge to Nowhere Elevation Chart:500:150]]','Drive to Raetihi, sign in at the motor camp, go to pub (or Cossie Club).  On return, drive to Ohakune, go to cafe with friends, drive home with big grin.','Parts of the track are in the process of being modified, as this track is to be part of the [[link:http://www.tourism.govt.nz/Our-Work/New-Zealand-Cycle-Trail-Project/New-Zealand-Cycle-Trail-Quick-Start-Tracks/Quick-Start-Track-5-Mountain-to-the-Sea/ New Zealand Cycle Trail Project]].','35.616',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-07 13:43:02',59,'-39.221615','175.063705',11,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-12 16:35:07','calc',5),(784,'629',105,'','Named after the hill it is on, \"629\" which just so happens to be 629m high! By coincidence, the round trip climb and drop is 6.29km!\r\nExpert / Extreem level track with lots of log rides and jumps.\r\nRequires a bit of a slog to get to the top, but well worth the effort.\r\nFast becoming a favorate amongst the madmen!','This is an expert level track with lots of Log rides and Drop Off\'s.\r\nThere are plenty of \"Chicken Lanes\" for those not quite up to the challenge, and working their way up to being able to conquer the beast.\r\nAt this stage the only access is a 600m climb to the top which can be done in one of two ways','Ride out of Nelson up the Maitai Valley Road. You need to ride up past the camp, onto the gravel road where the seal ends, and over the bridge just up from there. A further km up the road is another bridge. If you look to the right just before this bridge you will se the exit point of the track. Carry on up the road to the point where you see the waterpipe over the river like a rainbow, go around the next sweeping bend and along to the next picnic spot. Here you will need to cross the river. At this point its a case of taking all the roads / tracks / firebreaks that go UP.\r\nAt the very summit of the hill where the track goes into the bush, you should find the track entrance.\r\n','','6.291',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-07 23:37:31',135,'-41.297267','173.350670',14,5,3,1,135,'2010-01-07 23:42:55','calc',5),(785,'Mount Alfred',5,'','Short downhill connection from near the summit of Mount Alfred down to the [[track:352]] track.','This track is fairly typical of the connecting tracks that are all over [[area:5]].  It is short, steep, infested with exposed tree roots (very slippery when wet), and has a surface consisting of pine needles and soft dirt. The track is also narrow and tight, making for a technical challenge to ride cleanly.','Starts almost directly opposite the part of [[track:144]] that skirts around the eastern side of Mount Alfred.  As you reach the brow of the hill, turn right onto [[track:351]] for a few metres and then sharply left down the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMerges with [[track:352]], at around its mid-point.','This track was constructed in late 2009/early 2010. It will be used as part of the [[link:http://www.bikenz.org.nz/Article.aspx?ID=4774 BikeNZ MTB National XC Mountain Bike Championships]] to be held on 27 February 2010.\r\n','0.113',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-09 12:53:43',23,'-41.303641','174.788005',18,3,1,1,23,'2010-01-09 13:18:58','calc',5),(786,'Badminton Hall',5,'','Technically interesting connection through the trees just above the [[link:http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-2427-0-0-0&sID=21167 Wellington Badminton Association]] hall. ','From the southeastern end this track drops off [[track:354]] down through the trees into a little valley. Part way down, the track crosses a small (usually dry) creek via an artificial rock garden consisting mainly of broken chunks of concrete. A little further along there is a concrete step down, followed by a deeply rutted corner.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track then climbs slightly, around a hairpin bend and a neat keyhole corner, before rejoining [[track:354]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are plenty of exposed tree roots and short, sharp slopes that look like they would be especially slippery when wet.','Southwestern end is on [[track:354]], less than 0.1km north of the clearing that contains the [[track:340]]. This intersection with [[track:354]] is marked by a pink inverted V painted on a small tree.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNortheastern end rejoins [[track:354]] just as the easy course enters the trees just above the badminton hall.','','0.213',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-09 13:23:12',23,'-41.310238','174.789629',18,4,1,1,23,'2010-01-09 13:59:17','calc',5),(787,'Brooklyn Walkway',41,'','Main route through Central Park','Central Park has recently been upgraded by Wellington City Council and now feels refreshed.  Brooklyn walkway is the \"red\" route by the map, from the main gates at the bottom of Brooklyn Hill up past the tennis courts and emerges opposite the Malaysian High Commission on the corner of Brooklyn Road and Washington Av.  Walking uphill is a small climb, but the gradient is easy.','There is a bus stop on Brooklyn Road near both ends of this walk.','','0.604',NULL,58,101,159,'','','2010-01-09 19:45:38',122,'-41.299927','174.767976',16,1,2,5,122,'2010-01-09 20:02:49','calc',5),(788,'Ohiro Road track',41,'','Track through Central Park near Ohiro Road','Starting from the top of Central Park at the intersection of Brooklyn Road and Ohiro Road, this track winds downhill in parallel with Ohiro Road until you reach a historic bridge over Moturoa Stream.  At this point you can take the Moturoa Stream track down to the main gates, or the Caretakers Path back up to Ohiro Road.  The route shown takes the Caretakers track from the bridge back up to Ohiro Road.','There is a bus stop at the top of Brooklyn Hill near the start of the route.','Good track but parts can be slippy after rain.','0.614',NULL,73,169,96,'','','2010-01-09 19:54:15',122,'-41.299863','174.767761',16,2,2,2,122,'2010-01-09 19:57:26','calc',5),(789,'Moturoa Stream',41,'','New stream track through the centre gully of Central Park','Recently upgraded with a number of new wooden bridges criss-crossing the Moturoa Stream.  This goes through the centre of Central Park, with track leading off both sides to adjacent tracks ([[track:787]] [[track:788]]).','Begin at the main Central Park gates at the bottom of Brooklyn Hill.  There is a bus stop near the entrance, or it is just a short walk up from the top of Willis St.','','0.541',51,NULL,65,116,'','','2010-01-09 20:36:03',122,'-41.299669','174.767160',16,2,2,1,122,'2010-01-09 20:36:54','calc',5),(790,'Woodmancote Lookout',33,'','Short walk to lookout over Khandallah above Woodmancote swimming pool','Short walk up the hill behind the swimming pool at the end of Woodmancote Road.  There is a seat at the top and views across Khandallah to the harbour.  It is a short climb but the 5 - 10 minute walk is suitable for all.','There is a carpark at the end of Woodmancote Road beside the bowling club and Cafe de Parc.','','0.298',34,NULL,161,195,'','','2010-01-10 14:04:49',122,'-41.238222','174.785314',15,1,2,1,122,'2010-01-10 14:05:45','calc',5),(791,'Sirsi alt',33,'','Marked as an alternative route to Mt Kaukau from Woodmancote Road','This track leave from behind the Woodmancote Road swimming pool and provides an alternate route to Mt Kaukau from the main Northern Walkway route.  This route is a little rougher but still relatively easy to walk.  It joins up with [[track:161]] and then on up to Mt Kaukau.  \r\n','There is a good carpark at the end of Woodmancote Road.  The closest train station is Box Hill on the Johnsonville line.','Mountain bikes are not specifically prohibited but would be difficult on this track as there are steps in several places.','0.743',171,NULL,175,346,'','','2010-01-10 14:20:52',122,'-41.238157','174.785228',15,3,2,1,122,'2010-01-10 14:22:00','calc',5),(792,'Simla Crescent',33,'','Main northern walkway route from Simla Crescent to Mt Kaukau','The track involves a bit of a climb (nearly 300 metres) but is well rewarded with a good view from the lookout near the Mt Kaukau tv transmitter.  It can be blustery up there on a windy day, but the track is wide and has steps and a few seats for resting.  The council is also in the process of upgrading the walk so it is even easier for residents to enjoy the wonderful views from the top!  Allow 30 minutes each way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSeat halfway up Simla Crescent route\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4047/4260555083_4b24894e9b.jpg:Simla Crescent:480:320]]','The start is signposted about 300 metres up Simla Crescent from the Simla Crescent train station.','Mountain bikes not allowed on this route.','1.510',296,NULL,125,421,'','','2010-01-10 14:33:16',122,'-41.238480','174.786472',15,2,2,2,122,'2010-01-10 15:31:50','calc',5),(793,'Clark Street',33,'','Walking tracks in Khandallah Reserve between Simla Crescent and Clark St','The route shows two routes between [[track:792]] and Clark St, which is halfway to Woodmancote Road.  There is a signposted entry/exit point at Clark Street.  These linking track provide a good loop walk - from Woodmancote Road to Mt Kaukau, back down Simla Crescent track and then along Clark St track back to Woodmancote Road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThese tracks are not as well formed as the main Simla Crescent and Woodmancote Road tracks to/from Mt Kaukau, and there can be the odd wet patch after rain.','Nearest railway station is Simla Crescent on the Johnsonville line.','(GPS a bit patchy in the bushy hillside so the tracks may not be spot on)','0.667',71,NULL,138,209,'','','2010-01-10 14:43:00',122,'-41.238867','174.785957',15,2,2,1,122,'2010-01-10 15:24:52','calc',5),(794,'Woodmancote Road',33,'','Link track between Simla Crescent, Clark St and Woodmancote Road in Khandallah Reserve','Fairly easy bush walk, though track is a little rougher than the main [[track:792]] and [[track:795]] walkway tracks to Mt Kaukau, and there can be wet spots after rain.  The route shown include the link to Clark St.  All routes are well signposted at junctions.','Nearest train stations are Simla Crescent or Box Hill on the Johnsonville rail line.','','0.542',NULL,62,248,186,'','','2010-01-10 14:53:47',122,'-41.238996','174.786687',15,2,2,1,122,'2010-01-10 15:16:07','calc',5),(795,'Woodmancote Northern',33,'','Main northern walkway route from Woodmancote St to Mt Kaukau','Requires a bit of a climb but this does not put off families of all ages walking up to enjoy the views from Mt Kaukau.  There are many steps on this route and they are now in good condition (but can be a little muddy in places after lots of rain).  The lower [[track:792]] does not have so many steps (but requires the same climb).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track joins into the [[track:792]] track on the way up to Mt Kaukau.  All junctions are well signposted.','Nearest railway station is Box Hill on the Johnsonville line which will get you to Woodmancote Road.  If driving, there is a carpark at the end of Woodmancote Road near the swimming pool','Bicycles not permitted on this route.','0.636',176,NULL,190,366,'','','2010-01-10 15:04:09',122,'-41.238254','174.784241',15,2,2,1,122,'2010-01-10 15:35:49','calc',5),(796,'Summit alt',33,'','Alternate route to Mt Kaukau summit in Khandallah reserve','This track links the main [[track:795]] to the [[track:791]] route.  It is a little rougher than the main tracks, but still suitable for families completing a loop walk from Woodmancote Road.','Nearest railway station is Box Hill on the Johnsonville line.  There is a carpark at the end of Woodmancote Road.','','0.562',93,NULL,184,277,'','','2010-01-10 15:14:51',122,'-41.238544','174.786215',15,3,2,1,122,'2010-01-10 15:16:54','calc',5),(797,'Pipeline',106,'','Main Access to the upper tracks','This track follows alongside the main waterpipe for Nelson City.\r\nThe track is an access track to get you to the top tracks in the park.\r\n','Ride up the main Codgers Trail almost to the top, and you will come to the large water pipe. At this point a trail switches back to the left and follows the pipe... this is the Pipeline track.\r\nWatch you don\'t overpower going around the corner, the gravel there is unforgiving!\r\nBeware of the roots once through the gate!','','0.802',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-10 16:27:03',135,'-41.292608','173.304244',16,2,1,