]\r\nThe top 0.25km undulates along just below a ridge line.  If descending off [[track:156]], watch out for a rather indistinct Y-intersection 50m northeast of a pond â€“ take the branch that heads down the hill towards Cannons Creek, which is visible in the distance.','Northern end is on Warspite Avenue, 50m east of the top end of [[track:296]] and on the opposite side of the road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSouthern end meets [[track:156]] at a saddle point in the hills. This track heads northeast, initially running almost parallel with the transmission pylons that run along the ridge line.','This track forms part of the mountain bike section of the [[link:http://www.poriruagrandtraverse.co.nz/default.asp?PageID=11606 Porirua Grand Traverse]].','2.014',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-17 17:12:27',23,'-41.142693','174.877625',14,3,1,2,23,'2010-01-17 18:18:39','calc',5),(844,'Stream Link',30,'','Steep route linking the Puketirotiro lookout track to Korokoro stream','There are few linkages between the Korokoro stream [[track:99]] and the walking tracks in the hills of Korokoro.  This track does just that - branching off the Puketirotiro lookout track and going down through the bush to emerge beside a bridge on the Cornish Street track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis is a route!  It is not a well formed track.  There are no steps and no hand-rails.  It is steep and slippery after wet weather (tree roots are a menace).  You will get pricked with chest high gorse and you will need to grasp hold of the trees to avoid sliding down the steep bank.  It is a clearly formed track so you won\'t lose your way, but this is not for family outings.  It falls into the category of possum hunter trails.  It is a marked route on the map published by the city council, but it is tough going.  Wear long trousers and gloves and take your time.  It is actually easier going up than down (except for the 180 metre climb!).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track isn\'t marked at either end.  The photos below show the entrance points.  The easiest way is to start at the top.  From Titiro Moana Road walk up the marked route towards [[track:373]] lookout.  As you pass the house there is a sign on the track with arrows showing Tiro Moana Road and Puketirotiro Lookout \"up the hill\".  Take the rough track behind the sign that leads south towards the Korokoro stream.  It gets rough from this point.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is much harder to find the track leading uphill from Korokoro stream.  See photo below.  The track goes uphill from beside a bridge - there is no other indication or signpost.  There are a few markers along the track so once you\'ve found it you shouldn\'t lose the trail.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track is only about 600 metres long, but is a 180 metre climb/descent, and you should allow 20 - 30 minutes to complete it.  Whilst there is a potential to do a loop walk from Tiro Moana Road to Puketirotiro lookout, down to Korokoro stream and Cornish Stream, back up [[track:371]] and then through Korokoro streets back to Tiro Moana Road, it is quite a long round trip.\r\n[[para]]\r\nStart of track from Puketirotiro lookout track\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2748/4281059802_aa6fc35a7b.jpg:Puketirotiro start:480:360]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nTrack start from bridge over Korokoro stream from Cornish Street\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4062/4281059800_1eda573dd2.jpg:Stream start:480:360]]','Either park at [[track:99]] and walk in, or park on Tiro Moana Road in Korokoro and start on the [[track:373]] lookout walk.','Don\'t even think about attempting to cycle this.','0.585',182,NULL,32,214,'','','2010-01-17 17:46:35',122,'-41.209526','174.864471',16,4,2,1,122,'2010-01-17 19:18:24','calc',5),(845,'Nydia Bay',130,'','Technically challenging singletrack with wonderful scenary. 5 to 10 hours to ride from West to East. \r\n\r\nThe distance is less than 30km and you descend about 1150m and climb about 750m. Don\'t be deceived by the numbers, it is a big day out. \r\n\r\nThis is one of my favourite rides in New Zealand. Highly recommended as long as you have the technical skills and fitness to enjoy it!','There is a large shuttle required to get from one end of this track to the other. Well worth bribing or paying someone to drop you off and pick you up!\r\n\r\nStart from Opouri Saddle and finish at Kaiuma Bay.\r\n\r\nRide description, write up and photos over on my blog http://mountainbikingzane.wordpress.com/2010/01/14/nydia-bay-boxing-day/','To get to the start, drive from Havelock towards Nelson. Take the French Pass turn off and turn right over the bridge to head towards Duncan Bay. Stop at Opouri Saddle and look for the track heading from the saddle down to Duncan Bay.\r\n\r\nTo get to end, driving from Havelock, go past the Trout Hotel at Canvastown. There is a right hand turn over a single lane bridge over the Pelorus river which will get you onto Kaiuma Bay Rd. Drive the many windy km to almost the end of the road. There is a small one lane bridge over a river in farmland which is close to where the track comes out.','[[bold:Nydia Bay]] Elevation Chart\r\n[[image:http://www.gamma.net.nz/trackfield_graph/graph/320%2C320%2Cfield_track_data/Tracksdotorg/N:Nydia Bay Elevation Chart:500:150]]','27.620',750,1150,500,0,'','  Many technical sections','2010-01-17 20:43:26',246,'-41.176823','173.784052',8,5,1,1,138,'2010-04-21 14:03:47','calc',5),(846,'Hidden Valley ',102,'','nice wee XC connector from bottom of Vic Park to the Old Skool Bowenvale Downhill.','From bottom of Victoria Park, after the \'washout\' drop (Hospital Corner), hang a right at the gate, across the stream, and zig and zag your way up through scrub and pines into tussock land under the pylons and connect to the \'Old Skool\' Bowenvale Downhill track.','Bottom of Bowenvale Valley, bottom of Victoria Park','','0.579',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-18 12:02:36',206,'-43.583375','172.653580',13,3,3,1,206,'2010-01-18 12:05:13','calc',5),(847,'Military Road',41,' (no bikes due to