scent from the summit of Boulder Hill, along a rough farm track and across open paddock. For much of its length the track is ill-defined, though the orange markers provide sufficient guidance.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 3: [[track:134]] (2.41km)]][[br]]\r\nNear the end of [[track:135]] there is a short climb up to [[track:134]], which then continues climbing to a major intersection near the gas station.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 4: [[track:158]] (0.68km)]][[br]]\r\nContinue straight ahead from [[track:134]] past the gas station and around the hill, then jump the fence just before the road heads down hill and cross the airstrip.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 5: [[track:111]] (0.64km)]][[br]]\r\nFrom the airstrip briefly dip down into a valley and up to another major intersection.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 6: [[track:112]] (0.95km)]][[br]]\r\nHead up the steep grassy track to the west (away from, rather than past, the bunker), over a hill and then skirt around the base of Round Knob.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 7: [[track:152]] (4.55km)]][[br]]\r\nFrom Round Knob, jump a couple of stiles and then head southwest along a series of rolling hill tops, valleys, and saddle points.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 8: [[track:100]] (0.29km)]][[br]]\r\nGo through a large wooden gate and up the last section of the [[track:100]] track, to a smaller gate that is 20m south of the actual trig.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 9: [[track:151]] (2.69km)]][[br]]\r\nProceed down the very steep and, in places, quite rough track that descends from Belmont Trig to the base of Horokiwi Valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 10: [[track:150]] (0.78km)]][[br]]\r\nFrom the clearing known as Baked Beans Bend, follow a wet and wild track down the valley, including many unbridged creek crossings.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[bold:Stage 11: [[track:99]] (3.01km)]][[br]]\r\nFrom a large \"Belmont Trig\" sign carved into a fallen tree, head down this mild valley to finally emerge at the end of Cornish Street.\r\n','The track starts from [[area:11]]\'s Dry Creek entrance, off State Highway 2. From the car park climb up the short zig-zag track next to the information board, and then turn right up the 4x4 road.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track ends at the end of Cornish Street, Petone.','Puke Ariki was created in 2005 with the intention of it becoming a \"signature track\" for the [[area:11]]. [[link:http://www.gw.govt.nz/assets/council-reports/Report_PDFs/2005_177_1_Report.pdf Naming the track]] involved wide community consultation by the Greater Wellington Regional Council.','22.036',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' (sections range from Easy to Advanced)','2010-01-20 19:29:19',23,'-41.182530','174.905090',12,4,1,1,23,'2010-01-20 19:40:36','calc',5),(850,'Pearls ',29,'','Escape trail from end of Lovers Lane when river is in flood. Under-Construction.','Escape trail from end of Lovers Lane when river is in flood. Under-Construction.','At end of Lovers Lane turn left, before you get to bridge. If you have done Gup Gup then return back across bridge on Lovers Lane and follow Pearls Trail to Main Rd.','','2.470',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-22 16:37:54',126,'-35.639511','174.337921',14,3,3,1,126,'2010-03-15 08:28:59','calc',5),(851,'Highbury Fling',3,' (Under construction)','Gentle connection between [[track:25]], just above George Denton Park, and Ashton Fitchett Drive.','This two-way, dual-use, track is part of a plan to enhance bike access through Polhill Reserve (the other part is [[track:839]]).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track broadly follows the contours around the top of Polhill Reserve, producing an overall gentle gradient up from the northern end though with some somewhat steeper undulations along the way.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 0.2km from the northern end the track crosses [[track:55]]. At around the halfway point there is a side track that goes to a lookout.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track is under mature forest, providing a sense of isolation even though the track would have spectacular views