461/4296403463_7862099f7c.jpg:Charles Duncan sign:480:360]]','The entrance is beside 2B Fyvie Avenue, which is near the intersection with Main Road.','(Thanks to Danger Mouse for information about this reserve)','0.468',21,21,37,37,'','','2010-01-23 19:06:15',122,'-41.159658','174.824624',15,1,1,1,122,'2010-01-23 23:17:42','calc',5),(854,'Fyvie Av steps',14,' (many steps)','Steps providing a shortcut between Main Road, Fyvie Avenue and Deveron Place','This shortcut begins on the main road between Tawa and Linden opposite McLellan Street (there is a pedestrian crossing if you need to cross the road).  The steps lead up to Fyvie Ave.  After crossing the road the steps continue up a few metres to the right, and emerge on a small cul-de-sac Deveron Place which is off Victory Crescent.','Walking distance from Tawa shops and general Tawa/Linden area.','','0.274',62,NULL,20,82,'','','2010-01-23 19:12:42',122,'-41.160595','174.819560',15,1,2,2,122,'2010-01-23 23:34:18','calc',5),(855,'Ohariu extension',14,'','Wide track to nowhere','This is a short track off the main [[track:168]] route.  It doesn\'t lead anywhere (gate to private property), but clearly would be the road if Ohariu Valley Road is ever joined up to Broken Hill Road.  It is wide, and provides a short but interesting diversion from the main Spicer Forest trail.  From the Spicer Forest track this route leads downhill through a reasonably gentle gradient and out of the forest.','Obvious junction off the [[track:168]] route.','','0.366',NULL,50,214,164,'','','2010-01-23 19:24:40',122,'-41.170934','174.812350',15,2,1,3,122,'2010-01-23 23:35:02','calc',5),(856,'The Valley Track',14,'','Entry to Seton Nossiter Park off Mark Avenue.','From the car park off Mark Avenue head down a steep gravel path to the 4WD road that runs down a valley to a picnic area at the heart of Seton Nossiter Park. The northern end of the valley, against the motorway embankment, forms part of a flood control scheme for the Porirua Stream.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are several stream crossings along the way, via small bridges or fords. One of the stream crossings has a set of solid stepping stones, while a weir just past the bottom of [[track:858]] consists of loose stones that provide precarious footing.\r\n[[para]]\r\nPart of the valley is a designated dog exercise area, where dogs are permitted to be off the leash.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the picnic area there are three other tracks:\r\n[[bullet:[[track:857]] heads up a hill out of the valley]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:167]] wanders up a connecting valley below Woodridge]]\r\n[[bullet:[[track:858]] does a circuit that starts 0.45km along [[track:167]] and ends on the grass mound between the picnic area and the stone weir.]]','Northwest end is at a car park off Mark Avenue.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSoutheast end is in a valley on the boundary of Seton Nossiter Park.','Beyond the stone weir there is a rough track that continues up a valley towards the northeast. The valley is jam-packed with blackberry and the unformed, informal, and presumably dead-end track appears to be used as a possum bait line.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSee [[link:http://www.grenadavillage.org.nz/The%20Grenada%20Village%20Community/Seton%20Nossiter%20Park/seton_nossiter_park.aspx Grenada Village]] for more information about Seton Nossiter Park.','1.028',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-25 08:47:28',23,'-41.211835','174.820354',16,2,1,1,23,'2010-01-25 13:26:14','calc',5),(857,'Bushland Grove',14,'','Access to Seton Nossiter Park off Bushland Grove.','This is a short connection from Bushland Grove down into the heart of Seton Nossiter Park.  The top third is a steep and narrow path, while the rest is a 4WD road.','The northern end is in the picnic area, at the intersection of [[track:856]] and [[track:167]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe southern end is on Bushland Grove.','See [[link:http://www.grenadavillage.org.nz/The%20Grenada%20Village%20Community/Seton%20Nossiter%20Park/seton_nossiter_park.aspx Grenada Village]] for more information about Seton Nossiter Park.','0.358',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-25 08:49:08',23,'-41.213715','174.822146',17,3,1,2,23,'2010-01-25 13:57:38','calc',5),(858,'The Top Paddock',14,'','Tramping track around the upper reaches of Seton Nossiter Park.','From the [[track:167]] intersection, cross the bridge and then embark on a very steep and occasionally slick tramping track that heads straight up a narrow valley. As you approach the top of the hill there is a set of crude switchbacks which are almost as steep and slippery as the rest of the climb up from the valley.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bush line the track emerges out into a grass and gorse paddock. Shortly thereafter you\'re faced with a triangle cut into the grass â€“ this is the three-way intersection shown on the map. The eastern branch is a dead-end. The western end heads down a steep gully and the ridge to the bottom of the valley, where it meets [[track:856]].','The southern branch is on [[track:167]], about 0.45km from the picnic area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe western branch is on a grassy mound between the picnic area and the loose stone weir on [[track:856]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is also a dead-end eastern branch, which ends at the boundary of the [[link:http://www.woodridge.co.nz/about.html Woodridge development]]. At the end of White Pine Avenue (0.12km from the end of this track) there is a large sign that says \"Keep Out! Private property\".','See [[link:http://www.grenadavillage.org.nz/The%20Grenada%20Village%20Community/Seton%20Nossiter%20Park/seton_nossiter_park.aspx Grenada Village]] for more information about Seton Nossiter Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the intersection with [[track:167]] there\'s a laminated paper sign that says \"Gully Gut Buster\".','0.615',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-01-25 08:51:27',23,'-41.213570','174.825203',17,4,2,1,23,'2010-01-25 14:10:59','calc',5),(859,'Jungle Scout Return',8,'','Short track that returns from [[track:74]] to the open area at the end of Waiu Street.','This track is intended to be a short return leg from [[track:80]] for those who don\'t want to continue up the hill on [[track:74]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track wanders along under the trees more-or-less parallel with [[track:80]]. From the [[track:74]] end the gradient is generally down hill at a fairly gentle gradient, though with a few little dips and swerves to make things interesting.','Western end is on [[track:74]] less than 0.1km up from the end of [[track:80]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEastern end meets [[track:80]] less than 40m from the start/end of the [[track:176]].','','0.370',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-02-06 11:08:34',23,'-41.250076','174.924692',17,2,1,1,23,'2010-03-27 20:47:33','calc',5),(860,'Last Sun',11,'','Seriously hard-core downhill track featuring a variety of jumps, gaps, drops, chutes, rocks and tree roots.','This is a raw downhill track, with serious features that demand real skill and commitment (or at least the bravado of youth). Much of the track is lined on either side by tape that says \"DANGER KEEP OUT\". The tape is intended to delineate the track, though it could equally be referring to the track itself.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe top of the track is unmarked and hence not especially obvious. If the drop off the side of [[track:111]] is too intimidating, then proceed no further â€“ the top is far from being the most difficult section.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you proceed down the steep â€“ and sometimes extremely steep â€“ hillside along the edge of the forest block, you\'ll encounter a variety of obstacles (otherwise known as features). The features include:\r\n[[bullet:Jumps: ramps and/or bumps that are designed for getting a bit, or possibly a lot, of air. Some, though not all, can be rolled over.]]\r\n[[bullet:Gaps: similar to jumps, though generally can\'t be rolled over so they need to be taken at speed.]]\r\n[[bullet:Drops: there are several drops, some utilising the terrain and others created artificially by filling behind logs placed across 