each Lake Wairarapa near the remains of a wooden hide (no shelter possible).  \r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is possible to walk along the grassy bank beside the lake for about 1 km towards Featherston.  It is pleasant on a sunny day, but the area is exposed and it can be awful on a windy and wet day.  The lake itself is shallow and boggy.\r\n[[para]]\r\nGravel road leading towards lake shore\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2723/4362192812_c1b2cbdef8.jpg:Oporua floodway:480:320]]','Travelling from Featherston towards Marinborough, turn right off SH53 on to Kahutara Road (signposted to Lake Ferry). There is no longer any sign for Oporua floodway when driving south.  About 18 km down Kahatura Road look for a pair of flood gates (usually locked open) before the road takes a dip.  There is another pair of flood gates about a few hundred metres south (with a sign for Oporua floodway visible if you are travelling north) near Parera Road.  Beside the northern set of gates there is a gravel road leading on to the top of the stop bank and first of the 7 gates (the gravel road does a \"Y\" as it emerges from the top of the stop bank, with two entry/exit points on to Kahatura Road.','4WD, farm vehicles and stock also share the road.','3.817',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-02-14 19:45:12',122,'-41.241545','175.262489',13,1,1,3,122,'2010-02-16 22:24:43','calc',5),(867,'Deb\'s Track',131,'','Narrow downhill track','A fun downhill through recently felled pines. Can be very dusty and loose when dry.','','','1.950',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' Grade 3','2010-02-14 19:45:42',59,'-38.636417','176.061745',15,3,1,1,59,'2010-02-14 19:47:00','calc',5),(868,'Son of Buzzard',131,'','Branches off Buzzard','','','','0.379',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',' Grade 3','2010-02-14 20:01:23',59,'-38.639953','176.070532',17,3,1,1,59,'2010-02-14 20:19:59','calc',5),(869,'Cave Bay',2,'','Continuation of southern coastline track from [[track:175]]','The 4WD coastline track continues from [[track:175]] west towards Cable Bay.  The track gets rougher making cycling more difficult - it may be easier to stow the bike behind a bush and walk.  The area is still popular with 4WD vehicles, mainly fishermen, and on a fine weekend you are unlikely to be alone even in this remote spot.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is the occasional stream crossing on the coastal track, but the water is rarely more than a few centimetres deep.\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can follow the coastline all the way to Cable Bay, where you must then go inland.  However, I have only mapped a few kilometres further from Karori Rock, finishing about 12.5 km from the carpark in Owhiro Bay parade.  Beyond this point it will be easier to progress on foot.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4021/4371586771_aef2fcff3e.jpg:Coastal track east of Karori Rock:480:320]]','Park in the carpark at the end of Owhiro Bay parade and walk or cycle from there.','Watch out for 4WD vehicles.','2.008',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-02-20 19:14:18',122,'-41.324619','174.669743',13,3,1,4,122,'2010-02-20 19:17:09','calc',5),(870,'Jail Brake',22,'  : Not suitable for walkers','Downhill-only track with a steep gradient, jumps, and big bermed corners.','This is a steep downhill track that flows down a narrow valley on the western side of the Maupuia Reserve.  It is designed for 5-6 inch trail bikes but can be ridden on a hard-tail or a 8 inch DH rig.  It can be shuttled easily with sealed road access at both the top and bottom. If you do shuttle it please stick to this track and do not ride down Bootleg / Conviction.\r\n[[para]] \r\nAlong the way there are several jumps and various other features including rock drops.  The top third and the bottom third of the track are largely complete (although tweaking continues).  The middle section is to be built but is able to be ridden as an old-school (read: temporary) straight line descent.  This section will progressively be replaced with the final line during 2010.  \r\n[[para]] \r\nAll jumps can be rolled and there are easy lines around drops.  Some jumps do may still require some commitment to negotiate successfully. About 2/3rds of the way down there is a substantial rock drop.  Riders should take the easy line to the left until they have checked it out.\r\n[[para]] \r\nThe design goal of this track is that a competent cross country rider will be able to have a lot of fun on the track while more advanced riders will be able to shred it. \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe entire track is under regenerating bush, providing a sense of splendid isolation â€“ until the track suddenly emerges back into civilisation on Miramar North Road.','Top is on the water tank access road, about 100m beyond the concrete blocks off Main Road (where [[track:346]] ends).  Look for the last large pine tree on the left, just before the access road opens out into a broad paved area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is on Miramar North Road, between a bus shelter and a small building designated as the \"Miramar North Water Pump Station\", opposite the northwest corner of Centennial Park.  Wander along Darlington Road to find the bottom of [[track:337]].','Under construction.  See the Miramar Track Project discussion on [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/miramar-track-project-t91605.html Vorb]] or [[link:http://www.facebook.com/pages/Miramar-Track-Project/220242049761 Facebook]] for details of track building sessions. We build most Sundays @ 10am on Jail Brake.  As of February 2010 parts of the track have been completed.  The rest has a temporary line that can be ridden but the track is still very much a work in progress.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track shown on the map is a bit rough, for a couple of reasons:\r\n[[bullet:Parts of the track are likely to change as construction proceeds, and]] \r\n[[bullet:GPS reception in the area is poor, due to the track being in a valley on the southerly side of a steep hill.]]','0.587',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','  : Considered an \'expert\' track on XC scale; \'intermediate\' for DH tracks','2010-02-24 19:38:02',88,'-41.300443','174.824538',16,5,3,1,23,'2010-04-18 19:52:26','calc',5),(871,'Maupuia Steps',22,'','Foot-only continuation of the [[track:279]], with over 200 steps between Prison Road and Shelly Bay Road.','This track connects Prison Road and Shelly Bay Road via a series of more than 200 steps interspersed with sections of single track.  Many of the steps are somewhat awkward, either requiring a large stride or sloping away when walking down hill.  There\'s also a section of track near the bottom that appears to be almost permanently wet from water runoff coming down the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough much of the track is under tree cover, there are several places where gaps in the foliage provide stunning views over the harbour towards Hataitai and Roseneath.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom of the track emerges rather abruptly onto the edge of Shelly Bay Road, so watch out for traffic.','The top is at the end of Prison Road, at the northern end of the gentle section of [[track:279]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe bottom is on Shelly Bay Road, about 0.7km south of the former Shelly Bay Air Force Base â€“ which was decommissioned in 1995 and [[link:http://www.airforce.mil.nz/operations/airforce-news/103/shelly-bay.htm returned to Iwi in 2009]].','Strictly speaking this track is part of the [[track:279]].  However, it is identified separately here due to it having a completely different character to the gentle cliff-top meander that forms the remainder of the walkway.','0.365',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-02-24 19:42:26',23,'-41.301842','174.819126',17,3,2,1,23,'2010-02-24 19:44:53','calc',5),(872,'Nevay Road Walkway',22,'','Short connection between Darlington Road and Nevay Road.','This is a short connection between Darlington Road and Nevay Road.  The Darlington Road end starts out going up a one-lane driveway, before turning into the bush and heading up a steep gravel path.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of the track in under mature tree cover, which provides a pleasant spot of shade on a hot day.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn addition to a steep gradient there\'s a bunch of steps along the way â€“ about 70 in all, of which 2/3 are at the top and the other 1/3 are at the bottom.','Bottom is on Darlington Road, about 60m from the bottom of [[track:337]].  Head up the narrow sealed road to the end, and then up some steps that go up the hill.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTop is next to 149 Nevay Road, about 0.4km down hill from the eastern end of [[track:346]].','Although there\'re no signs explicitly restricting bike access, the steep gradient and numerous steps make this track generally unsuited to bikes.','0.272',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-02-24 19:47:02',23,'-41.301217','174.828068',17,3,2,1,23,'2010-02-24 19:48:45','calc',5),(873,'Rameka Project  Great Expectations',34,'','MTB Track developed on the Rameka Project \"Carbon Sink\" land','This great addition to the Rameka Experience has been built by the volunteers and helpers of the Rameka Project in conjunction with the Golden Bay MTB Club.\r\nThis is the start of a planned network of trails in the area.\r\nIn short the Rameka Project is a \"Carbon Sink\" project to help get our world back into the shape it should be!\r\nSo... with that in mind.\r\nIt may be worth noting that people living, or based in Golden Bay often park beside the big Totara at the bottom of the Rameka Gorge (4 km out of Takaka) and ride up the Rameka Creek Road and then down Great Expectations. Others do the same and ride up to Canaan Downs and back  doing the entire Rameka Track both ways!\r\nBoth are greener options than using shuttles to and from the top!\r\n\r\n\r\n','The best way to ride this is as a side diversion of the Rameka Track from the top of Canaan Downs. \r\nWhen you get down out of the forest and start your way down the road, follow the road down behind the castle to the point where it splits. Carry on down the rameka road a little bit forther and look to your left for the Project Rameka Sign.\r\nAlternatively you can access it directly from the Rameka Road as noted above.','Join the Rameka Project and make a donation to this worthy cause!\r\nYou can find the website at:\r\nhttp://projectrameka.carbonsink.org.nz/\r\n\r\n','2.109',0,100,440,340,' Cruisy and flowy down ','','2010-02-27 23:24:13',135,'-40.907229','172.848989',15,3,3,1,135,'2010-03-02 21:21:10','calc',5),(874,'Ulva Island',132,'','Gentle walk amongst pristine island sanctuary','Ulva Island (Te Wharawhara) is an important island sanctuary, providing a habitat for some rare NZ birds and some great bush walks.  A water taxi leaves from Golden Bay on Stewart Island ($20 return) for the 5 minute trip to Post Office Bay on the island.  Pick up the Ulva Island leaflet ($2) at the wharf and set off round the island - allow 2 hours for a leisurely round trip.  All tracks are well sign-posted.  The track is gravel so you don\'t need special shoes: sand-shoes are fine.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAs you leave the wharf there is a track leading off to the left to Flagstaff hill where you get a view over the water to Stewart Island.  Continue along the track to the golden sandy beach of Sydney Cove, where there is a small shelter and a rope swing.  Go along the sand and re-join the track inland for a few hundred metres to a junction.  From here you can walk either clockwise or anti-clockwise.  The route shown goes clockwise to Boulder Beach, then back inland to West End Beach, and then back to the junction and back to the wharf.\r\n[[para]]\r\nLook out for Weka\'s, especially on the beaches.  There are small flocks of Brown Creeper and the very rare Yellowhead in the canopy.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNote that the track only covers part of Ulva Island - the rest of the island is not accessible.\r\n[[para]]\r\nUlva Island ferry terminal at Golden Bay\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2694/4397208855_620c861889.jpg:Ulva ferry terminal:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nSydney Cove on Ulva Island\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4048/4397974748_7c72761a7b.jpg:Sydney Cove:480:320]]','The $20 water taxi service leaves from Golden Bay (15 mins walk from the centre of Oban) at 9 am, 12 noon and 4 pm, returning and 12 noon, 4 pm and 6 pm daily (weather permitting).  It isn\'t necessary to book, but the boat only takes 9 people and it can be popular.  You can also hire a water taxi for travel at any time, or join a guided tour of the island.','There is no food or drinking water on the island.  Make sure you are fully self-sufficient.  There are toilets near the wharf and in Sydney Cove.  There is a shelter by the wharf and in Sydney Cove (a few minutes walk from the wharf).','4.383',37,37,1,1,'','','2010-02-28 21:30:42',122,'-46.928550','168.123994',15,2,2,2,122,'2010-03-01 22:05:25','calc',5),(875,'Ackers Point',132,'','Coastal walk to historic lighthouse','Starting from the centre of Oban, this route follows the coastline east along the road through Lonnekers Beach and least Bay to Harrold Bay where there is one of NZ\'s oldest houses (built by Lewis Acker in 1835).  Here the road ends and you follow a good gravel walking track along the headland up to the lighthouse where there are great views over the bay.  In late summer the attraction is Sooty Shearwaters (Muttonbirds) which return to their burrows in the hillsides at dusk, and Penguins can also sometimes be seen returning to shore.\r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn the same way.  Allow 2 - 3 hours for the return trip.','From Elgin Terrace in Oban (the main road along Halfmoon bay) take the road east along the coast.','(Do not venture off the track on the headland, as there are underground burrows which may cave in).','3.525',33,NULL,1,34,'','','2010-02-28 21:44:44',122,'-46.906770','168.132191',13,2,2,3,122,'2010-02-28 21:48:21','calc',5),(876,'Deep Bay',132,'','A round trip combining several short tracks within easy walking distance of Oban township','This route combines several short walks starting and ending from central Oban township.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeginning from the waterfront on Elgin Terrace, walk up Ayr Street, turn right into Dundee Street and about 100 metres on the left the Fuschia Walk is signposted.  This is a short walk through native bush, which emerges at the bottom end of Traill Park sports field.  The Raroa walk continues from the other side of this park, but instead take a diversion by walking up Golden Bay Road and turning left in to Leonard St.  About 200 metres up Leonard St is a short pathway to Observation Rock where you can get good views over Golden Bay to Ulva Island.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn down Leonard St, cross Golden Bay Road and enter Traill Park.  The Raroa walk is signposted from the far corner of the field.  This is another walk through native bush to Watercress Bay/Thule Road.  When you emerge on Thule Road walk back towards Oban, and after about 400 metres on the right the Deep Bay walk is signposted.  This is about 2 km long coastal walk through bush.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen you emerge at Petersons Hill Road you can return to Oban, or continue down Deep Bay Road towards the coast to visit Reverend Wohlers monument which is about 1 km away.  The last part of this walk is across private land, but is well signposted and has styles to cross the fence.  The stone cross is on the hill overlooking the coast and there are views over Ringaringa beach.  Return to Petersons Hill Road and follow it back in to the centre of Oban.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlthough there is some walking on roads, there are few cars on Stewart Island.  The bush walks are good gravel paths with steps, which are not muddy and special footwear is not required.  Allow about 3 hours for the round trip.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOban beach front\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2718/4397974772_285a2caecd.jpg:Oban beach front:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nView of Iona Island from Observation Rock\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4019/4397974834_9a73527b6b.jpg:Iona Island:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nReverend Wohlers monument\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4040/4397209021_94403dc4fc.jpg:Wohlers monument:480:320]]','Walking from the centre of Oban.','Bicycles ok on the roads but not on the bush walks (Fuschia, Raroa, Deep Bay).','6.905',77,77,1,1,'','','2010-03-01 20:49:13',122,'-46.904131','168.141718',14,2,2,2,122,'2010-03-01 22:10:48','calc',5),(877,'Horseshoe Bay',132,'','Coastal walks north of Oban township taking you to the start of the Rakiura track','This route combines several longer walks from Oban township.  You could do the walks separately, but combined they make a nice 5 - 6 hour day walk (about 16 km) return trip from Oban.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the centre of Oban, walk north out of the town on Horseshoe Bay Road, or take a short diversion on Kamahi Road for some hill views of Oban with the option of going down to Bathing Beach.  Descend past Mill Creek (a quick diversion to Halfmoon Bay cemetery is worth a look here) to Butterfield Beach and continue until you read Braggs Bay Road on the right.  Go up Braggs Bay Road, and drop in to Moturau Moana native gardens about 200 metres up the road on the left.  There is a balcony in the gardens with views back over the bay to Oban.\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinue along Braggs Bay Road and past Bragg Beach, noting the lovely golden sands in Stewart Island.  The road ends and the Horseshoe Point track is signposted.  Just a short distance from the start of the track is a historic cemetery on the right, and a little further on a trig.  About 1.5 km along the coastal track the path descends to the golden sands of Dead Man Beach, then ascends again and a further kilometre takes you to Horseshoe Point where there is small trig and good views over Horseshoe Bay.  Continue along the coastal track to Horseshoe Bay and follow the road or walk along the sandy beach.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 1.5 km around Horseshoe Bay take Lee Bay Road on the left and follow this road to the end.  You may encounter traffic on the road as this is the route for trampers doing the Rakiura track.  There is a carpark at the end of the road and maps marking the start of the track.  Start the Rakiura track for about 1 km to Little River, where there is an inland route up to Garden Mound, 162 metre climb.  There is a trig at the top which is now covered by trees, but about 100 metres from the trig is a seat and a view across the Stewart Island bush back to Oban.  The descent from Garden Mound to Lee Bay Road is very muddy (even in dry weather), and good shoes or tramping boots are required on this part of the track.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nReturn to Oban along Lee Bay Road, Horseshoe Bay and Horseshoe Bay Road (inland road, instead of the Horseshoe Point track).  Look out for a seat, old ringer telephone and yellow pages along the road!\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can hire cycles in Oban and ride to Lee Bay Road, but cycling is not permitted on Horseshoe Point or Garden Mound tracks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView of Oban from Moturau Moana native gardens\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4049/4397209079_f8430df661.jpg:View of Oban:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nCoastline near Dead Man beach\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4067/4397209127_fd5d87bc43.jpg:Coastline near Dead Man beach:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nHorseshoe Bay\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2757/4397209165_b21fc54cd3.jpg:Horseshoe Bay:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nStart of Rakiura walkway\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2775/4397975058_c20f1bfbc1.jpg:Rakiura walkway anchor:480:320]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nCoastline at start of Rakiura walkway\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4022/4397975104_23ae9fd722.jpg:Coastline of Rakiura walkway:480:320]]','From the centre of Oban.','There are no shops outside Oban, so take food, drinking water and other supplies before leaving.  There is no public transport, but you can arrange transport to Lee Bay Road if, for example, you just want to do the Garden Mound walk.','15.838',162,162,1,1,'','','2010-03-01 21:21:15',122,'-46.886360','168.138885',13,2,2,2,122,'2010-03-01 22:09:34','user',5),(878,'Fern Gully',132,'','Easy bush walk inland from Oban township','From the centre of Oban walk inland along the Main Road and take the right-hand fork of Kaipipi Road about 1 km inland (the left hand road goes to the airstrip).  You will go past the heliport.  Continue along the road until it ends.  At this point the Fern Gully track continues for about 1.5 km following a stream in the bush.  It terminates at a small clearing with a seat and could be a pleasant spot for a picnic.  Return along the same route\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the end of Kaipipi Road the left hand 4WD track is the track to Ryan\'s Creek and Kaipipi Bay.  The part of the track marked on the map below marks the portion to the junction of the Ryan\'s Creek and Kaipipi Bay tracks.  (The Kaipipi Bay track becomes the 2 - 3 day 36 km Rakiura track which loops round inland and joins up back at Lee Bay Road (see [[track:877]]).  \r\n[[para]]\r\nAllow 1.5 hours for the round trip.','Walking distance from Oban township.','Parts of the Fern Gully track can be muddy, and some of the bridges are nothing more than a plank across the river with a hand-rail on one side only.','3.715',70,NULL,1,71,'','','2010-03-01 21:39:21',122,'-46.910875','168.123264',13,2,2,2,122,'2010-03-01 21:40:19','calc',5),(879,'Barton\'s Bush',17,'','Gentle wander through one of the last remaining stands of native bush in the Hutt Valley.','Barton\'s Bush is part of the Trentham Memorial Park.  It is the remnants of the native forest that once largely filled the upper Hutt Valley, consisting now mainly of mature [[link:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beilschmiedia_tawa Tawa]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe tracks through the bush are wide and essentially flat, apart from a couple of small dips (which are fun to swoop down and then up the other side). Presumably in an attempt to protect the bush, the tracks are lined on both sides with a chicken wire fence â€“ providing somewhat of an artificial feel to an otherwise pleasantly shady spot.\r\n','There are four entrances, as shown on the map, accessible from the sealed paths that go around most of the bush (except for the northern side, between Holdsworth Avenue and the northwest entrance).  That is:\r\n[[bullet:Just off the end of Holdsworth Avenue, next to the steel barrier gate.]]\r\n[[bullet:A playground off Brentwood Street. The track from the playground goes through a small satellite stand of bush and is initially not well formed. However, it soon crosses a sealed path and then enters the main stand of bush.]]\r\n[[bullet:Southwest entrance, next to the cricket pitch.]]\r\n[[bullet:Northwest entrance, just over a flood stop bank from the [[track:122]] section of the [[area:12]].]]','','1.091',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-03-07 20:14:55',23,'-41.130646','175.029105',16,1,1,2,23,'2010-03-07 20:39:39','calc',5),(880,'The Portal',41,' Not advisable to walk down with ipod :)','A nasty brute with drops and gap jumps. Some have ride around options. Many do not.\r\n\r\nBest leave your fully rigid hard-tail at home for this one.','This is a DH track with steep slippery corners, man made structures, ramps, drops gap jumps and roots aplenty.\r\n\r\nIf breaking both wrists sounds like a fun Saturday then this track is for you.\r\n\r\nI don\'t know the actual name of this track. Please feel free to update this file if you do.','The trailhead is at the top of Connaught Terrace in Brooklyn.\r\n\r\nThe entry looks like a driveway next to the main sealed track through Prince of Wales Park. Walk to the back of the grassy knoll and look for the gap in the bush. If you can\'t ride the first two corners it\'s not a good idea to continue.','This may not be a legal track, but the WCC track access policy permits riding in Prince of Wales Park and this track has been there for a long time. Because it is hard to find conflict with walkers and other users is minimal.','0.933',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-03-15 21:33:45',1,'-41.309107','174.771827',17,5,1,1,92,'2010-03-16 15:19:49','calc',5),(881,'Smokin\'',1,' (Under construction)','Weaving track through a mellow valley under mature forest.','This track is a continuation of a project to build an easier route down from the summit of [[area:1]].  The first, and main, part of that plan to be constructed was the [[track:613]] track â€“ which was opened in early 2010.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of this track is under mature forest, though the [[track:73]] end is through a variety of prickly plants including the ubiquitous gorse and barberry along with the more unusual (for this area) stinging nettle.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are four sweeping switchbacks that wind down a fairly mellow valley, following by a run out of the valley that is parallel with [[track:50]] for the last 50m or so.','Start is on the [[track:19]].  Currently this appears to be in the middle of nowhere, but the plan is that it will continue on from an as-yet unpiloted track that connects from the bottom of [[track:613]]. In the meantime, cruise down 0.16km of the [[track:19]] from the bottom of [[track:613]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at the top of [[track:73]], next to the picnic tables at the intersection with [[track:50]].','Under construction.  See the [[link:http://makarapeak.org/northface North Face blog]] for reports on progress.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track\'s name is derived from the haul of exotic plants that Wellington City Council have occasionally removed from the valley.','0.348',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-03-15 22:11:14',23,'-41.292717','174.716526',18,3,1,1,92,'2010-03-21 11:23:51','calc',5),(882,'Prince',41,'','Main trunk line through Prince of Wales Park from Salisbury Terrace to Connaught Terrace in Brooklyn.\r\n\r\nA good connector to the top of The Portal. ','Also known as Heart Attack Track.\r\n\r\nSteep in some sections when climbing up to Brooklyn.','The entrance to Prince of Wales Park from the Connaught Terrace end is on a fairly obvious sealed path heading into the reserve. \r\n\r\nThe city entrance is just past the soccer field. Head towards the Scottish Harrier Club and turn right on the sealed path.','','0.606',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-03-15 22:15:23',92,'-41.308592','174.771141',17,1,1,1,92,'2010-03-16 22:52:00','calc',5),(883,'Forsyth',2,'','Short connection between Forsyth Grove and the Polhill wind turbine access road.','Most of this track has a grass surface, apart from a short section of concrete path at the bottom.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe upper section winds through bush and is quite steep initially.  It then mellows somewhat before reaching a flight of 34 steps near the bottom.','Top is on the Polhill wind turbine access road, on a corner just over 0.5km up from Ashton Fitchett Drive and 0.1km down from the intersection of [[track:24]] and [[track:25]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is at the end of Forsyth Grove.','','0.147',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-03-20 09:20:55',23,'-41.305704','174.749447',18,3,1,1,23,'2010-03-24 14:23:45','calc',5),(884,'Whakanui',9,'','Bush walk in the Orongorongo range','This is a popular easy day walk for trampers from Hine Rd or Sunny Grove in Homedale (on the coast road just south of Wainuiomata) to the Orongorongo River Catchpool recreation area.  This track is better maintained and easier to walk than the [[track:886]] track.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the carpark at the end of Hine St the track starts a slow, steady climb uphill from about 100 m to 550 metres.  The track initially follows Sunny Grove, and you can also begin the walk at the end of Sunny Grove.  After about 3 km you reach 550 metres and the \"hairpin bend\".  There is a sign here, go left for Whakanui track and right for the [[track:886]] track.  The Whakanui track follows the ridge line at around 560 metres.  The ridgeline is in the middle of the Orongorongo\'s, and has pretty bush outlook each side.  The track is in good condition.  In the last 2 km the track descends quickly from the ridgeline to the Orongorongo river beside a small creek.  If you are doing the Mt Matthews track then you cross the river (often a trickle) and the Matthews track is marked on the far side with an orange triangle about 200 metres upstream.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe sign at Hine St says 4 hours - allow at least 3 hours to walk one way from Hine St to the Orongorongo River.  The highest point on the track is about 640 metres, the ridgeline around 560 metres.\r\n[[para]]\r\nView back to Wainui from Whakanui track\r\n[[image:http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2782/4450202772_c153b7b919.jpg:View over Wainui:480:360]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nOrongorongo river near Whakanui track entrance\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4027/4450202848_a750a82545.jpg:Orongorongo river:480:360]]','Park in the carpark at the end of Hine St and follow the large sign beside the carpark.  Alternatively, park in the top carpark at Catchpool recreation area and walk up the Big Bend track to the start of the Whakanui track beside the Orongorongo river.','This is a Kiwi area - dogs are not welcome.  Keep them on a leash, or preferably leave them at home.  Sometimes Kiwis do wander around during the day and dogs like eating them.  There are at least 14 pairs of Brown Kiwi in the area.','8.969',589,472,51,168,'','','2010-03-21 21:04:29',122,'-41.299992','174.958649',12,3,2,2,122,'2010-03-21 21:34:03','calc',5),(885,'Big Bend track',9,'','Follows the Orongorongo River in the Catchpool recreation area','This track follows the Orongorongo river upstream from the bridge where the main track from the Catchpool carpark meets the river.  It is normally a pleasant walk along the riverbank above the river, and is the better route after rain when the river is high.  It is generally an easy walk, but is currently overgrown in a few area (check trip reports).  There are huts along the river bank.  Allow an hour for the walk.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWhen the water levels are low it is slightly quicker to walk along the riverbed.','From the top carpark in Catchpool recreation area, take the main track to the river and then continue along the track upstream.','Keep dogs on a leash to avoid a messy encounter with Kiwis.','3.537',32,NULL,152,184,'','','2010-03-21 21:13:53',122,'-41.293543','174.989548',12,2,2,1,122,'2010-03-21 21:16:54','calc',5),(886,'McKerrow',9,'','Orongorongo range ridgeline tramp','This track follows the ridgeline closest to the coast in the Orongorongo range.  The track is not as well maintained as the [[track:884]], and affords only occasional views through the trees to Wellington.  There isn\'t a defined \"Mt McKerrow\" peak - there is a junction with a few signs (Clay Ridge track leading back down to Catchpool valley) in the bush.  Whilst not a long walk, it is difficult as there are many tree roots and muddy areas.  The ridgeline is around 650 metres asl.  There is a marked track leading down to the Boys Brigade camp about midway between McKerrow and Sunny Grove.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAllow 3-4 hours to walk from Orongorongo river to Hine Rd/Sunny Grove.  At each end the track climbs quickly to around 550 metres, then follows the ridge.  The highest point on the track is around 670 metres, and the ridgeline is about 100 metres higher than on [[track:884]].  Follow the [[track:884]] track back to Hine Rd.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4062/4449428331_e3167dfc00.jpg:Trees on McKerrow ridgeline:360:480]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you want to do a round trip, I suggest starting at Catchpool carpark, walking in to the Orongorongo river, up the [[track:885]], left up [[track:884]] to the hairpin bend and then back along McKerrow (and down the Clay Ridge track back to Catchpool).  If you start at Hine Rd you ascend and descend twice, whereas if you start at Catchpool the hairpin bend joining Whakanui to McKerrow track is at 550 metres asl.','Begin either at Hine Rd in Homedale, or from the end of the Catchpool track beside the Orongorongo river.  From Hine Rd carpark, follow the signs to Whakanui track, and at the hairpin bend about 3 km (you will have ascended to around 500 metres) there is vertical sign showing McKerrow track to the right (the wide [[track:884]] continue to the left).  From Catchpool upper carpark, after walking about 1 hour just before the track descends to the Orongorongo river the McKerrow track is marked with a vertical sign on the left of the track.  ','Dogs not welcome.  There are North Island Brown Kiwi in the area, which occasionally come out during the day.  Dogs should be kept on a leash, or preferably left at home.','6.974',489,122,184,551,'','','2010-03-21 21:30:10',122,'-41.302571','174.969635',12,3,2,1,122,'2010-03-21 21:37:03','calc',5),(887,'Link Track',8,' (Under construction)','Short connection between [[track:78]] and [[track:176]].','This is a busy little connecting track between [[track:78]] and [[track:176]].  There are plenty of bumps and wriggles to keep you busy, even though the track is only short.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe purpose of this track is two-fold:\r\n[[bullet:link [[track:78]] with the rest of the [[area:8]], and]]\r\n[[bullet:ultimately open up the next valley to the northeast for building more tracks.]]','Top is just over 0.5km from the bottom of [[track:78]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom meets the eastern side of the [[track:176]].','As of March 2010 the track is still under construction and is simply called \"Link Track\" (though the name is likely to change).\r\n','0.330',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-03-27 21:03:47',23,'-41.247850','174.929236',17,3,1,1,23,'2010-03-27 21:25:35','calc',5),(888,'Nikau Palm Reserve',28,'','Native bush walk near Lindale','Nikau Palm reserve is a pleasant shady bush walk.  The track is well marked with steps, rising from the carpark up the hill with a few seats and a picnic table at the top (you can continue up-hill to join the track at the end of [[track:889]]), then descending again to the carpark.  There are numerous palm fronds from the trees which may lie over the track, especially near the bottom.  The reserve has a nice slightly unkept feeling.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is a very short gravel path from one side of the loop walk to the other.  The stepped path up through the bush and back will take about half an hour.','If you are driving south it is easy - turn off SH1 at the Lindale turnoff (north of Paraparaumu) and the reserve is on your left with a car park before the road swing round underneath SH1.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you are driving north also take the Lindale turnoff north of Paraparaumu, but follow the sign at the roundabout to Nikau Valley, then take the first left which is a short road that appears to be heading toward the southern exit from SH1, but turns into the Nikau Reserve carpark.','','1.143',121,121,12,12,'','','2010-03-28 20:13:18',122,'-40.909750','175.023816',16,2,2,1,122,'2010-03-28 20:27:20','calc',5),(889,'Anlaby Road',28,'','Hilltop walk above Nikau Valley with coastal views','This is a good 4WD track starting at the end of Anlaby Road in Nikau Valley.  It goes across the hilltops with views of Lindale and Paraparaumu beside new sections in Nikau Valley.  It descends to Nikau Palm Road.  There are no signs at the start or end of the walkway, but the track is well used by local residents and the track joins in to [[track:888]] beside the picnic table which is outside the bush with a view to the coast.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf walking or cycling you can do a round trip by continuing right along Nikau Palm Road, left again in the Maui Pomare Road, and then back up Anlaby Road.','Drive to the end of Anlaby Road in Nikau Valley (it is now sealed to the end), or you can park off the road on a corner on Nikau Palm Road about 400 metres from the junction with Maui Pomare Road and walk up-hill.','','1.096',NULL,58,161,103,'','','2010-03-28 20:22:20',122,'-40.910042','175.025296',15,1,1,3,122,'2010-03-28 20:26:27','calc',5),(890,'Seymour',17,'','Connection between Seymour Grove and the eastern edge of Maidstone Park.','From the top, this track starts as an easy and wide grass path between houses off Seymour Grove.  The character soon changes, becoming a steep and winding track up and then down a steep ridge.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track surface is mostly firm, though there are some rough and rocky sections with plenty of exposed tree roots.','Top is next to 12 Seymour Grove.\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is at the eastern edge of Maidstone Park, less than 20m from the bottom of [[track:892]]\'s lower loop.','Although bikes are not prohibited, this track isn\'t really suitable for bikes since there are about 85 steps along the way.','0.586',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-03 11:09:23',23,'-41.125465','175.080507',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-03 11:29:57','calc',5),(891,'Maidstone Ridgeline',17,'','Rumble along the ridge above Maidstone Park.','This track provides access to the top of [[track:894]]. There\'s a vehicle turnaround area at the eastern end of this track, perfect for shuttling bikes up to near the top of the ridge.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom the drop-off point cruise up the gravel road, around the rim of a wall next to a water reservoir, and then up to the Brett Latimer Lookout.  After that, the track is mostly downhill to a sharp right-hand corner â€“ the road continues down the hill, but the main event is the start of [[track:894]] which is immediately behind a picnic table on the outside of the corner.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMost of this track follows the gravel road that runs along the ridge overlooking Maidstone Park. However, there are a few deviations that have been specifically built for bikes.  These deviations include jumps and drops, providing a warm up for [[track:894]].','Eastern end is at the top of an extension road off the end of Seymour Grove.  There\'s room to turn around a vehicle that could be, say, running shuttles.\r\n[[para]]\r\nWestern end drops sharply down the hill parallel with the top section of [[track:894]].','','0.690',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-03 11:11:53',23,'-41.129813','175.079080',16,3,1,2,23,'2010-04-03 13:17:16','calc',5),(892,'Maidstone East',17,'','Tramping track from the eastern side of Maidstone Park.','This track consists of three parts:\r\n[[bullet:The lower loop, which starts and ends on the edge of Maidstone Park. The loop is about 0.50km long, and climbs steeply up the hill and then drops steeply down a ridge on the other side of a narrow valley.]]\r\n[[bullet:A 0.25km long connection up to an extension of Seymour Grove.]]\r\n[[bullet:A 0.20km long connection over to the mid-point of [[track:893]].]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nMuch of this track is very steep and rocky, with lots and steps and plenty of exposed tree roots â€“ making for a generally rough surface.','The highest, and eastern-most, point is on an extension to Seymour Grove, opposite a car parking area.  Where Seymour Grove ends at a turning area, head up the road extension and take the right-hand alternative for 0.15km.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe lower loop ends on the eastern edge of Maidstone Park, less than 20m from the bottom of [[track:890]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAnother branch heads up a fairly steep hill to connect with [[track:893]].','Although bikes are not prohibited, this track isn\'t really suitable for bikes since there are about 250 steps along the way.','0.903',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-03 11:13:23',23,'-41.127599','175.079461',17,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-03 13:07:52','calc',5),(893,'Maidstone West',17,'','Walking track from the western side of Maidstone Park.','This track meanders up a fairly steep ridge to the top of the hill overlooking Maidstone Park. The track surface is mostly firm gravel, through it is a bit rough in places.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt about the halfway point there\'s an intersection with [[track:892]]. Just below this intersection there\'s a picnic table and, a few metres further down the hill, a bench seat conveniently placed to admire the view over Maidstone Park.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you\'re looking to do a few runs down [[track:894]], but don;t have a shuttle, then this is the most direct way to get from the bottom to the top of [[track:894]]. However, this track has lots of steps and a steep gradient, so expect a fair bit of pushing your bike up the hill.','Bottom in on Maidstone Park, next to the bottom of [[track:894]] and 50m south of the PÃ©tanque piste.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTop meets [[track:891]] about 50m from the top of [[track:894]].','Although bikes are not prohibited, this track isn\'t really suitable for bikes since there are more than 80 steps along the way.','0.696',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-03 11:14:47',23,'-41.129054','175.077041',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-04-03 13:03:03','calc',5),(894,'Maidstone DH',17,' (Under construction)','Downhill MTB track from [[track:891]] to Maidstone Park.','This is a purpose-built downhill track, complete with: jumps, tabletops, drops, gaps, chutes, big berms, and wooden structures.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track builders have focussed on making it a skill based track for everyone to develop the skill needed for downhill racing.  Therefore, there are nana lines around all things nasty and most jumps are rollable.  Nonetheless, this is a steep and gnarly track, with substantial jumps and drops â€“ tackle it with due care.\r\n[[para]]\r\nSome of the features have adopted names, like: Top jump, Mini Double, Ladda Splat, The triple t (which is a table top that has 3 different sized jumps on it), Wild Drop, and The Rockstar.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTowards the bottom there\'s an extremely steep chute that takes a direct path straight down the hill. The main track takes a much longer zigzag path, crossing the chute along the way and rejoining just before a wooden drop on to the grass park area.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the bottom, after cruising along a flat section adjacent to the forest edge, there are two alternative paths:\r\n[[bullet:The left-hand path goes up and then down a wooden ramp.]]\r\n[[bullet:The right-hand path drops off the end of a wooden structure.]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe main track, excluding the extremely steep chute shortcut, is 1.10km long, having dropped about 90m from the top of the ridge.','Top is on [[track:891]], behind a picnic table about 50m up from the top of [[track:893]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nBottom is next to the PÃ©tanque piste, near the bottom of [[track:893]].','As of early 2010 this track is being re-constructed after the top section was messed up by logging in mid-2008.  For updates on the construction process, see [[link:http://www.vorb.org.nz/latest-news-maidstone-downhill-rebuild-t105018.html Latest news on Maidstone Downhill rebuild]].','1.131',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-03 11:16:31',23,'-41.129151','175.075786',16,4,3,1,23,'2010-04-03 13:32:25','calc',5),(895,'Howard',134,'','Climb from the top of Howard Road up to the [[track:82]] track that runs along the main ridge between Eastbourne and Wainuiomata.','This is a pleasant, though somewhat steep, track through native bush. The track surface is firm, being graveled all the way â€“ though the gravel is a little loose and hence slippery on some of the steeper sections.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnd-to-end this track gains around 120m of altitude, with a few flatish and short downhill sections in between.  At the top you can either return the same way, continue along the [[track:82]] track, or do a loop including [[track:896]] and [[track:897]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlong the way there are a couple of lookouts offering spectacular views over the harbour. The first is almost 0.5km up from the bottom and only 10m off the main track.  The second is less than 0.1km from the top and just a short walk along a flatish section of track. Oddly, the upper lookout doesn\'t have a seat.','Starts at the end of Howard Road, next to a pair of large water tanks.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at a T-intersection with [[track:82]], 0.6km from Wainuiomata Road.','There is little room for car parking in the turnaround area at the top of Howard Road.  A better option for parking would be Ngaumatau Road, where there is a large paved area at the top of [[track:897]].  From there to the bottom of [[track:895]] is just a short walk (0.35km) along the road, though there is no footpath.','1.310',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-11 08:45:17',23,'-41.249128','174.915969',16,3,2,1,23,'2010-04-11 09:59:54','calc',5),(896,'Cheviot',134,'','Steep connection between the end of Cheviot Road and [[track:895]] (just below the [[track:82]] track).','This is a steep  walking track through mature bush.  Most of the track is under tree cover, which offers plenty of shade on a sunny day.  However, there are occasional glimpses of the outside world â€“ in particular, about 0.3km from the top the track offers great views of Lowry Bay from a short section of track that is in the open.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track\'s surface is graveled, which provide a firm base but in some places there\'s the risk of sliding down the track due to the steep gradient (especially when descending).\r\n[[para]]\r\nImmediately before the bottom end of the track, at the intersection with [[track:897]], there are three pipes which are somewhat unexpected given the location.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAt the top, it is another 0.25km up from the intersection with [[track:895]] to an intersection with [[track:82]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is possible to include this track in a loop that also encompasses [[track:895]] and [[track:897]].','Starts at the end of Cheviot Road, where there is a bit of room for car parking.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection near the top of [[track:895]].','','1.255',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-11 08:49:00',23,'-41.250225','174.917128',16,3,2,1,23,'2010-04-11 10:07:23','calc',5),(897,'Ngaumatau',134,'','Short, though rather steep, connection between the bottom of [[track:896]] and Ngaumatau Road.','This walking track features several zig zags as it winds its way up a rather steep bit of hill. The track surface is firm gravel, though beware that even so some parts are slippery due to the steepness.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAround the bottom of this track, at the intersection with [[track:896]], there are three pipes which are somewhat unexpected given the location.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIt is possible to include this track in a loop that also encompasses [[track:895]] and [[track:896]].','Starts at Ngaumatau Road, where there is a sizable paved area suitable for car parking.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds at an intersection with [[track:896]], just a few metres from the end of Cheviot Road.','','0.491',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-11 08:51:07',23,'-41.252311','174.912477',16,3,2,1,23,'2010-04-11 10:06:28','calc',5),(898,'Carterton Mountain Bike Park',107,'','Stage One (2Loop)of the Carterton Mountain Bike Park is complete.\r\n','There are two loop tracks (both beginners) and a few beginners obstacles.[[br]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere is easy going \'outer\' loop track with a slightly\r\ntighter \'inner\' loop . The trail is on lightly contoured\r\nland between Dalefield Rd and Kaipaitangata Stream,\r\neast of the Water Tank. There are some humps\r\nand hollows, a few bridges and some nicely bermed corners.\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\nIn time this trail will link up to the planned trails on the\r\nother side of Dalefield Rd on Mt Dick & across the Kaipaitangata stream, then it will be a\r\nnice little trail to do some warm up laps before heading\r\nto the hills','At the south end of Carterton head along Dalefield. The park is on your right, and is signposted at the park.\r\n(Map shows Kaipaitanga Rd, it is NOW Dalefeild Rd, Start to end.)','The Carterton Mountain Bike Park was featured in the Wairarapa News on 10 March 2010: [[link:http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/local/wairarapa-news/3429729/Mountain-bike-park-dream-is-achieved Mountain bike park dream is achieved]].','2.100',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Flat','','2010-04-12 18:05:20',151,'-41.003545','175.452905',15,1,1,1,232,'2010-05-11 09:29:45','user',0),(899,'Field Hut',28,'','Popular track introducing walkers to the Tararua ranges','Field Hut lies near the bushline, approximately 6 km from Otaki Forks.  From the carpark, go down to the river and cross the swing bridge.  Field Hut is signposted - you head up the hill instead of left (Waitawaewae) or right (Arcus loop walk).  The track up the hill has recently been upgraded, and whilst you ascend quickly to 500 metres it is a wide gravel track.  The track enters the bush and continues to Field Hut at around 850 metres.  The walk is a constant climb but the gradient is reasonable - there is relatively flat section for a while at around 600 metres, but expect 2 hours of continual ascent).  Although the sign says 3 - 4 hours from Otaki Forks, most trampers do it in 2 - 2.5 hours.  You don\'t need tramping boots if you are just going to Field Hut and back (good running shoes are fine).\r\n[[para]]\r\nField Hut has 20 bunks and you can stay overnight, but note it is quite popular at weekends and you probably won\'t be alone.  It is heated.  If you are staying overnight you need to pay DOC fees for [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-stay/backcountry-huts-by-region/wellington/kapiti/field-hut/ Field Hut]] (usually 1 or 2 tickets for huts in the Tararuas).  \r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you are doing a day walk, have lunch and then return to Otaki Forks.  30 minutes further up is Table Top at 1000 metres, which can be a good spot for playing in snow in winter.  You can continue to [[track:900]], which is part of the Southern Crossing route, and is about 2 hours from Field Hut.\r\n[[para]]\r\nOtaki Forks\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4047/4530607084_d76f74ffae.jpg:Otaki Forks:480:360]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nField Hut\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4067/4529973959_7034908ebf.jpg:Field Hut:480:360]]','Otaki Gorge Road is signposted inland immediately before the bridge into Otaki on SH1 (southern end).  Follow the road to the end.  There are a couple of sections of gravel road and the road is narrow in a couple of places near the end.  There are several carparks - for day walkers and overnight long-term parking.','There is an intentions book at the caretakers house, which you should sign.  Make sure you are properly prepared for tramping in the Tararuas - food and drink, warm waterproof clothing, and your intentions are known to other people.','6.371',781,NULL,95,876,'','','2010-04-18 20:16:49',122,'-40.912994','175.265923',12,3,2,1,122,'2010-04-18 21:04:43','calc',5),(900,'Kime Hut',28,'','Part of the Southern Crossing across the Tararua ranges','This track continues the Southern Crossing from Otaki Forks via [[track:899]] towards the Wairarapa.  Whilst the route up to [[track:899]] was reasonable gentle, if you are continuing on to Kime Hut (and beyond) you need proper tramping boots and equipment.  The reward is superb views on a fine day.\r\n[[para]]\r\nFrom [[track:899]] continue on upwards for about 30 minutes where you emerge on Table Top at about 1000 metres.  This is a relatively flat area with good track and boardwalks across boggy areas of tundra.  You are now above the bush level and in the open, and when it snows in winter this can be a fun place!  Midway along Table Top is a junction and signpost to Penn Creek.  This return route to Otaki Forks is a \"route\" only, there are slips on the route and walking through Otaki River - DOC advises against using Penn Creek track (unless you are an experienced tramper).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track now continues to ascend first up Dennan.  There is a relatively flat stretch of track at around 1200 metres, and then the ascent continues up to Hut Mound at about 1400 metres.  You will pass the signposted junction to Maungahuka Hut which is up the central ranges, and at the top of Hut Mound is a signpost down to Kime Hut which is a few minutes below the top of the mound.  Allow 2 hours for the walk from Field Hut to Kime Hut, and be prepared for a 550 metre ascent.  The Maungahuka junction is about 1 hour past the Penn Creek junction.  \r\n[[para]]\r\nWhilst it can be pleasant on this track in summer, in winter the area is often covered in snow and ice and proper tramping gear is required.  The track is very well marked with stones and poles in the higher places.  However, even experienced trampers can run in to trouble in winter ([[link:http://www.stuff.co.nz/2594033/ Seddington]]) so take care.\r\n[[para]]\r\nIf you are staying overnight at [[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-stay/backcountry-huts-by-region/wellington/kapiti/kime-hut/ Kime Hut]] note that the hut has no heating, so it can be VERY cold in winter, and even in summer!  It has 20 bunks, and requires 1 DOC hut ticket.\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[track:901]] is about 1 hour further on.\r\n[[para]]\r\nTable Top, 1000 m\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4007/4529974017_18a50ed844.jpg:Table Top:480:360]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nView north from Hut Mound to Dennan and Table Top\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4035/4529974203_2ac460e685.jpg:Dennan:480:360]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nKime Hut, 1400 m\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4067/4530606934_53d9a7d0bd.jpg:Kime Hut:480:360]]','Continue the Southern Crossing route from [[track:899]] from Otaki Forks.','','4.730',540,20,860,1400,'','','2010-04-18 20:48:58',122,'-40.916626','175.247726',12,3,2,1,122,'2010-04-18 21:05:44','calc',5),(901,'Mt Hector',28,'','Southern Crossing tramp to one of the highest points in the southern Tararuas','This is a continuation of the [[track:899]] and [[track:900]] tracks, part of the Southern Crossing from Otaki Forks to Kaitoki or the Wairarapa.\r\n[[para]]\r\nContinuing from [[track:900]], the track ascends Field Peak (about 1460 metres) before dropping to about 1360 metres before ascending again to Mt Hector at 1529 metres.  At the top there is a memorial cross for the trampers who lost their lives in the second world war.  There are also magnificent views (on a clear day) over Wellington, the Wairarapa and the Tararua ranges.  On a clear day it is possible to see Mt Ruapehu, Mt Egmont, and the Kaikoura ranges in the South Island.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe area is high and very exposed, so make sure you are properly prepared at any time of the year.  In winter there is a good chance that the area will be covered in snow.  However, the track is well used and well marked.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMemorial Cross on top of Mt Hector\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4069/4529974145_9716e446c5.jpg:Mt Hector:360:480]]\r\n[[para]]\r\nBeehives and Dress Circle south of Mt Hector\r\n[[image:http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4059/4530607166_4d03e952c6.jpg:Dress Circle:480:360]]\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\nYou can read Mt Hector in 45 - 60 minutes from Kime Hut.  The Southern Crossing track continues to Alpha Hut which is several hours further along past the Beehives and along the Dress Circle.  From Otaki Forks you can expect to reach Mt Hector in about 5 hours if you are fit.','Continuation of [[track:899]] and [[track:900]] tracks from Otaki Forks.','Tramping through these ranges in the Tararuas requires proper preparation and gear.  Make sure your intentions are logged with someone who knows were you are going.','1.641',169,116,1400,1529,'','','2010-04-18 21:01:08',122,'-40.923111','175.228500',12,3,2,1,122,'2010-04-18 21:02:08','calc',5),(902,'Kill Devil',135,'','An up-and-back ride which take you up to 980m above Cobb Valley and to the historic Riordans Hut. An awesome adventure ride if you make an overnight stop at the hut.\r\n\r\n[[para]][[image:http://lh4.ggpht.com/_h7SxYMhNm70/S4V5OzijwgI/AAAAAAAAEyk/hH-rLdaQlVQ/s720/11210%20IMG_3025%20exp%20b.jpg:hut:400:266]]','A pretty gruelling ascent, but an absolute blast coming back down the 57 technical rocky switchbacks.\r\n\r\n[[para]][[image:http://lh4.ggpht.com/_h7SxYMhNm70/S4V5aI5yk8I/AAAAAAAAEzI/I-oOL28K860/s800/11580%20CSC_1261%20b.JPG:down:400:266]]\r\n\r\n[[para]]A 10/10 ride in my books, if you stay the night in the hut with a roaring fire.\r\n\r\n[[para]][[image:http://lh4.ggpht.com/_h7SxYMhNm70/S4V5K-k3EdI/AAAAAAAAEyY/MI-sZh8OOjk/s800/10960%20CSC_1229%20cropped%20b.jpg:fire:400:266]]\r\n\r\n[[para]]From the Kennett Bros rev7 book:\r\n\r\n[[para]]p194, 3 stars\r\nGrade 5-, 4-8hrs, 24km return\r\n(return same way)\r\n\r\n[[para]]\"This tough ride has fantastic scenery, and countless technical challenges, with 57 switchbacks packed into a 700m climb.\"\r\n\r\n[[para]][[image:http://img541.imageshack.us/img541/1547/elevationprofile400.png:profile:400:229]]\r\n\r\n[[para]]\r\n[[link:http://www.nelsonmountainbikeclub.org.nz/stories/storyReader$795 Nelson MTB Club writeup]][[br]]\r\n[[link:http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-stay/backcountry-huts-by-region/nelson-marlborough/golden-bay/riordons-hut/ DOC Riordans Hut description]]','The start is at the end of gravel Uruwhenua Rd, which is off the main SH60.','There is next to no water supply up to the hut, but in the bush next to the hut is some sort of natural spring.','11.200',1112,400,130,850,'Figures are for ride up only','','2010-04-21 09:53:35',246,'-41.026535','172.765503',13,4,1,1,246,'2010-04-21 11:25:50','calc',5),(903,'Wakamarina',116,' (Logging access road is closed to vehicles during weekdays.)','A great ride across the Richmond Range. Native forest, technical downhill, some serious altitude, a hut to stay the night... this one has it all.','Bit of a slog up the gravel logging road, but once into the bush at 600m its nice singletrack through native forest up to Fosters Clearing and Fosters Hut at 1100m.[[para]]\r\n\r\n[[image:http://d3.tramper.co.nz/files/objectversions/2430/P3020076.JPG:hut:400:]][[para]]\r\n\r\n[[link:http://doc.org.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-stay/backcountry-huts-by-region/nelson-marlborough/south-marlborough/fosters-hut/ DOC Fosters Hut]][[para]]\r\n\r\nThe track then wanders about up high for a bit, before heading straight down some fun steep tracks under lush forest canopy. A bit hard to navigate, so watch out for those orange markers.[[para]]\r\n\r\nEnd up on Wakamarina Rd, which take you down to Canvastown, which has a pub and not a lot else. Lots of good old goldmining history and relics in the area.[[para]]\r\n\r\nFrom Kennett Bros book:[[br]]\r\np220, 4 stars!![[br]]\r\nGrade 3 or 5-, 2 or 5 hrs, 20 or 35km[[br]]\r\nTwo options:[[br]]\r\nA fun trip to the tops and back, or the full hardcore crossing of the Richmond Range from Onamalutu to Canvastown.[[para]]\r\n\r\n[[image:http://img718.imageshack.us/img718/1547/elevationprofile400.png:profile:400:]]','Logging road (Kiwi Rd) starts at the end of Onamalutu Rd and continues up to a carpark at 600m elevation. During weekdays, the logging road is open to vehicles, so you can drive up to the carpark. Otherwise, do it properly and ride up from the bottom. ','The route on the map below starts at the end of Onamalutu Rd.','24.596',1812,1865,170,110,'','','2010-04-21 14:24:08',246,'-41.428055','173.633080',12,4,1,1,246,'2010-04-21 14:38:29','calc',5),(904,'Secret Valley',14,'','5 minute walk near Pukerua Bay railway station','If you have cause to stop in Pukerua Bay this short walk is worth checking out.  The Secret Valley is signposted at the end of Takutai Road near the entrance to Pukerua railway station.  The short bush walk follows the Waimapihi Stream.  There are some interesting sculptures along the way.  The track is well formed with bridges over the stream, and there are several entry/exit points along the route to Takutai Road.  The track exits at the end of Takutai Road near SH1.  Suitable for all ages, and should not take more than 5 - 10 minutes to walk.','Driving south in to Pukerua Bay, turn left on to Takutai Road just before the footbridge across SH1.  Drive up to the end of Takutai Road and park near the railway station.','','0.261',NULL,12,78,66,'','','2010-04-24 19:25:03',122,'-41.036328','174.886669',17,1,2,1,122,'2010-04-24 19:26:44','calc',5),(905,'Maungakotukutuku Rd',15,'','Continuation of Maungakotukutuku Road through the forest towards Nikau Valley','This track is the continuation of Maungakotukutuku Road from the point where the road ends for normal vehicles just before a couple of stream crossings.  4WD vehicles, motor bikes and quad bikes continue from this point, but if you are not in a 4WD vehicle you can park at the turning circle and walk or cycle from this point following the 4WD road through the forest.  It is not possible to go all the way to Nikau Valley (where it joins up with Mahaki Road) as there are currently forestry operations and the Nikau Valley end crossing private land. However, you can go about 2 km north along Mangakotukutuku Road and there are other forestry track leading off the main road to explore.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe road ends abruptly where there is a logging operation currently in progress.','From Paraparaumu drive south down Valley Road and then left on to Maungakotukutuku Road.  Continue to the very end of Maungakotukutuku Road, which is about 4 km from the [[track:289]] carpark.  The end of the road is identified by arriving at a stream crossing.  There is a turning circle where you can park the car.\r\n[[para]]\r\nI don\'t believe there is any public access from Mahaki Road in Nikau Valley.','Watch out for motor vehicles along the track - motor bikes, 4WD vehicles, quad bikes.','3.494',NULL,33,162,129,'','','2010-04-24 19:39:47',122,'-40.939582','175.030746',13,2,1,3,122,'2010-04-24 19:44:09','calc',5),(906,'Tawatawa',19,'','Well-formed undulating light intermediate single track through bush and pine trees.','This is a well-formed, undulating track around the upper part of Tawatawa Reserve. The track passes through bush and pine trees as it climbs up to a ridge overlooking the reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEither return the same way, or return back to the lower reserve via [[track:907]].  Alternatively, take a detour around the [[track:908]] loop.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAbout 2/3 of the way down (going anti-clockwise) it pays to watch your speed as there is a right hand corner with a tree waiting to shoulder tap you on the inside and not much track on the outside to recover in before doing some tree hugging.  However, when not going too fast, this corner is easy to negotiate.','Starts in Tawatawa Reserve, just off Murchison Street.  There is a carpark nearby, at the entrance to Tawatawa Reserve.\r\n[[para]]\r\nEnds on the ridge overlooking the reserve, next to a small water tank.','In 2008-09 Wellington City Council redeveloped the former landfill site off Murchison Street and renamed it Tawatawa Reserve. Prior to the [[link:http://www.wellington.govt.nz/projects/ongoing/prestonsgully.html restoration project]] the area was known as Preston\'s Gully.\r\n[[para]]\r\nMakes a good night ride in conjunction with the [[track:908]] loop.','1.436',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-25 10:12:35',200,'-41.332418','174.766560',16,3,1,1,23,'2010-05-03 14:58:01','calc',5),(907,'Frobisher',19,'','Shingle and grass access road up to the water tank overlooking Tawatawa Reserve.','Gentle 4wd climb to a ridge between Tawatawa Reserve and the Manawa Karioi Ecological Restoration Project.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThere are a couple of short links to the [[track:908]] loop, which would make a nice detour.  The top of the [[track:906]] track is behind the water tank, heading down to Tawatawa Reserve â€“ ending just over 0.3km from the bottom of this track, along Murchison Street.','Southern end is off Frobisher Street, next to the intersection with Murchison Street.\r\n[[para]]\r\nNorthern end is next to a small water tank on a ridge overlooking Tawatawa Reserve.','','0.648',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-25 10:14:30',200,'-41.334335','174.765658',16,1,1,3,23,'2010-05-03 15:06:47','calc',5),(908,'Manawa Karioi',19,'','Loop around the outside of the Manawa Karioi Ecological Restoration Project.','This is an easy grassy track that does a loop goes round the outside of the [[link:http://www.mk.org.nz/ Manawa Karioi Ecological Restoration Project]] (a community project with the objective of restoring native plants and animals to Island Bay\'s coastal hills at Tapu Te Ranga Marae).\r\n[[para]]\r\nThe track can be done in either direction.  Around the highest point, near the southwestern corner of the loop, there is a short link through to [[track:907]] and hence [[track:906]].','Take the sealed drive up from end of Danube Street to the entrance and signboard.  The loop starts and ends there.\r\n[[para]]\r\nAlternatively, there is a short link to [[track:907]] near the southwestern corner of the loop.','Together with [[track:906]] and [[track:909]] makes a good night ride starting from Island Bay shops. ','2.109',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-25 10:16:17',200,'-41.331999','174.765487',16,2,1,2,23,'2010-05-03 14:59:53','calc',5),(909,'Tawatawa East',19,'','Track from Eastern side of Tawatawa Reserve to get to Manawa Karioi loop','Short section of track up from Tawatawa Reserve to Frobisher.  A bit more technical and steeper than [[track:906]] but can still ride it in both directions.  Very tight corner near the top. \r\n','From Murchison St, [[track:907]] or from top of [[track:908]] loop.','In 2008-09 Wellington City Council redeveloped the former landfill site off Murchison Street and renamed it Tawatawa Reserve. Prior to the restoration project the area was known as Preston\'s Gully. \r\n\r\n','0.406',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-04-26 20:57:34',200,'-41.334287','174.763963',17,3,1,1,200,'2010-05-03 15:05:22','calc',5),(910,'PushBike',14,'  - WCC reserve, GWRC ward and private property.','Do you live in the Northern Suburbs and are sick of driving [or riding] for hours just to get to a decent track?  Your problem is solved.','It\'s taken me a year but she\'s got everything from a challenging uphill and single track loop to a full on free ride & DH line into a bit of trials stuff to finish.\r\n\r\n\r\n###  No track is ever finished so be sure you scope the track before you hit anything  ###\r\n\r\n\r\nI\'ve noted expert here because although you don\'t need to have lungs like air balloons to bike to the top [you are allowed to just push up] and you definately don\'t need balls of steel to hit the track gap and drop off [you can just ride around]...  To be honest both of these traits would help you immensely.  This track really will suit riders with a chameleon for a bike [something like a Stinky or Reign XO] if you want to do it all and enjoy it.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPS.  BE VERY AWARE OF HORSES.  YOU CAN BE SHARING THE TRACK AT ANYTIME WITH ADJACENT PROPERTY OWNERS.  AS ALWAYS, IF YOU GET OFFSIDE WITH THE LOCALS THE TRACK WILL GET SHUT DOWN SO BE EXTRA NICE, STOP & GET OUT OF THEIR WAY WHEN YOU HEAR THEM COMING.  THEY HAVE RIGHT OF WAY AT ALL TIMES!','One hard to get to entry point.  Make your way to Tawa then find Collins Ave.  Drive to Wilf Mexted Reserve beside the old Brick works at the end of Collins Ave just before the road turns into Woodman Drive.  Park up on the grass verge on the right [heaps of room]\r\n  \r\n\r\nEnter the reserve by foot via the lefthand side of the Reserve info board.  Aprox 3-4m in look up over your left shoulder to find an overgrown steep track winding up towards the old brick works.  Once in the clearing at the top follow the gravel road 150m north to the back [east side] of the buildings.  On your right there is an overgrown entry to the old farms\' 4WD track with a gate and a possum bait warning notice.  Follow the winding 4WD track up [remember to breathe]\r\n\r\n\r\nYou will come to a fork in the track that leads up to your right or across the hill to the south west.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe track to the south west will take you around the the south side of the hill and also splits into two.  take the right hand track [high line] and you will come to a clearing of long grass.  Head out to your right to find a gap in the trees and head down the windy track untill you hit a 4WD track heading north.  The left track [low side] will continue around the south side of the hill then come to the Rangatira St properties fence line.  Both will bring you out above the Rangatira St property\'s [be considerate of the horses in their paddocks] Continue north along the fence line until you are back on the track cut in the tree line [it just follows on from the fence line so just keep going till it turns back into a track]\r\n\r\n\r\nBack at the 1st fork in the track...  If you head straight up the hill to your right this will take you up to the summit.  The wide tunnel like top trail takes you to a gate in the old top fence line, from there you can switch to freeride mode and find a trail down that suits your skill level.  \r\n\r\n\r\nRule of thumb is if you\'re more an XC than a DH then follow the 4WD track down and you\'ll easily be safe.  If you\'re up for a challege then I\'d encourage you to have a look at the options.  All trails lead to the bottom of the hill overlooking the Rangatira St properties.  If you keep heading north you\'ll find it hard to get lost or loop back on your self.\r\n\r\n\r\nOnce above the Rangatira St properties follow the fenceline track north into a 90 degree burm with a ski jump at the top.  This chute will take you down a steepish run off into a chicane between trees at speed into a pellet ride [not big enough to call it a wall ride] Best to just ride down this one the first time to see what\'s required of you, nothing too hard just better to see it before you do it.\r\n\r\n\r\nOnce around the little pellet ride you\'ll have a cruisey finish down through another chicane into a couple pellet gap jumps and out on to an access road.  Head straight at the other pellet jump between the trees and this will take you in to the trials stuff or you can follow the access road all the way to Ribbonwood Tce in Ranui Heights if you wish [BEWARE OF ARCHERY CLUB MEMBERS - ARROWS HURT... A LOT]\r\n\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve gone as far north as you want to turn around and head back up the track [I suggest you ride back up the 4wd track as you\'ll be pushing up the freeride tracks but a good way to learn the trails]\r\n\r\n\r\nAlternatively if you know a real good sort, have them meet you in Ribbonwood Tce and you can drive home from there together [orrrh]','Ride time:  If you\'re real bike fit and can handle yourself in the air then an easy 25mins from Collins Ave to Ribbonwood Tce [no loops just straight through] Then 35mins back up and over to where you started.\r\n\r\nIf you push up from Collins Ave and toddle down to the Rangatira St properties then push back up and roll back down to Collins Ave then you\'ll need to think about putting aside a good hour and 30mins.\r\n\r\nI guarantee the first time you go in there, time will loose all meaning :D  \r\n\r\nEnjoy but respect the trails please.  Try not to skid them up or route the burms...  It\'s taken me a crap tonne of time and effort to build so I\'m not wanting to have to do a stack load of maintenance to keep it running for you.\r\n\r\nGood riding.','6.000',200,225,100,75,'It\'s technically a mountain...','  - 3km up 3km down','2010-05-05 22:31:55',113,'-41.156492','174.844966',15,5,1,1,113,'2010-05-05 22:35:53','user',0),(911,'Wetland Westside',8,' (Under construction)','Gentle meander through the forest on the western side of the wetland.','For a gentle meander through the forest, this is the place to be.  The track is busy, with lots of twists and turns. The terrain is more-or-less flat, making this track suitable for anyway looking for an easy introduction to mountain biking.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis track is currently under construction. The map shows Stage 4, though stages 1 to 3 have yet to be built. See [[link:http://www.facebook.com/pages/Wainuiomata-Lower-Hutt-New-Zealand/Wainuiomata-Trail-Project/211059460782 Wainuiomata Trail Project on Facebook]] for details of when building is taking place.','Starts and ends on the [[track:176]].\r\n[[para]]\r\nStage 4 starts opposite the start of [[track:738]]. Head into the area that used to be a pump track and veer around to the right to find the start of the benching.','One-way, from the [[track:77]] end.','0.312',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-05-08 13:33:08',23,'-41.247283','174.926097',18,2,1,1,23,'2010-05-08 14:14:57','calc',5),(912,'Kowhai Park',108,'','Family park in Levin near Lake Horowhenua','This park is being developed and is a pleasant spot just outside Levin town centre near the lake.  There aren\'t really any tracks in the open park, the track below roughly goes around the perimeter.  ','Drive down Queen St West towards the lake, and there is parking on the left just before the sharp 90 degree turn right to the lake domain.  ','Note that this is a popular spot for walking dogs.','0.837',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-05-09 21:57:17',122,'-40.612568','175.265257',16,1,1,6,122,'2010-05-09 22:00:18','calc',5),(913,'Otaki River Sth bank',28,'','River bank anglers access track to beach','This is an anglers access track along the south bank of Otaki river from SH1 to the beach.  On the south side of the bridge there is a sign clearly stating anglers access, and a style over the fence.  There are several locked gates to pass through - walkers can cross easily but cyclists will need to lift the bicycle over the gate or fence.  The first locked gate is about 1.8 km from the bridge, and the second locked gate a further 1 km.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis is a 4WD track, grassy in places, which turns to stones and gravel as you approach the beach.  The track passes several bachs near the beach end and diverges into several disparate tracks leading to the river mouth.\r\n[[para]]\r\nThis can be a popular spot for fishermen and other water activities, so watch out for vehicles especially near the beach.','Parking is easiest on the south side of the bridge on the inland side, where there are toilets and a rest area.  Rather than crossing SH1 it is possible to walk under the bridge to the start of the track.','','4.314',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','2010-05-09 22:08:02',122,'-40.760001','175.137520',13,2,1,3,122,'2010-05-09 22:10:11','calc',5);
